  ('PC-INF-B4-8', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Archaeological evidence shows that the first settlements at the site date to approximately 3,000 BCE. The settlement was abandoned suddenly around 1,200 BCE — grain stores were left full, tools were found mid-task, and cooking fires had not been extinguished. No bodies were found in the ruins."

What can be reasonably inferred from the evidence described?', '["The settlement was destroyed by a volcanic eruption that killed all residents.","The inhabitants left abruptly and likely survived to resettle elsewhere.","The settlement was abandoned because the grain supply ran out.","Disease wiped out the population, leaving no one to extinguish the fires."]'::jsonb, 1, 'Full grain stores and tools mid-task indicate the departure was sudden, not planned. The absence of bodies suggests the people left rather than died in place. A volcanic eruption or disease would likely leave victims. Grain supply was clearly not the reason (stores were full).', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-B4-8'),
  ('PC-INF-B4-9', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"A new field manual requires squad leaders to document the reason for any deviation from the standard patrol formation. Within one month, the number of undocumented deviations dropped by 90 percent, but the number of formally documented deviations actually increased by 40 percent."

What can be inferred from these statistics?', '["The patrol route itself was changed 40 percent more often after the manual was issued.","Squad leaders began to comply with the documentation requirement, making previously hidden deviations visible.","Deviations decreased because the new patrol routes were safer.","The 40 percent increase indicates that discipline worsened after the manual was issued."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The near-elimination of undocumented deviations alongside a rise in documented ones suggests that deviations were occurring before — just unrecorded. The requirement brought them into the official record, not that more deviations were happening. The wording about ''discipline worsening'' misreads more documentation as more rule-breaking.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-B4-9'),
  ('PC-INF-B4-10', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The treaty required both nations to reduce their stockpiles by 30 percent within five years. Nation A submitted its reduction plan on the first day. Nation B requested four extensions over three years and had completed only 8 percent of its reduction by the deadline."

What can be inferred about Nation B''s commitment to the treaty terms?', '["Nation B strongly supports the treaty but lacked the technical capacity to comply.","Nation B''s pattern of delays and minimal compliance suggests it is not fully committed to the treaty.","Nation B reduced its stockpile by more than required once the extensions were granted.","Both nations treated the deadline as optional."]'::jsonb, 1, 'Four extension requests and only 8% completion against a 30% requirement strongly suggests reluctance or unwillingness, not merely technical difficulty. Nation A''s prompt action makes the treaty''s feasibility clear. Choice C contradicts the 8% figure. Choice D is not supported — Nation A complied.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-B4-10'),
  ('PC-INF-B4-11', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"A company that manufactured industrial components for 80 years announced in its final quarterly report that it was profitable. Two weeks later, it declared bankruptcy. Investigators later found that the company had been shifting expenses to subsidiaries it owned, making the parent company''s balance sheet appear healthy while debt accumulated elsewhere in the corporate structure."

What can be inferred from this passage?', '["The company''s auditors had approved its financial practices as legal and accurate.","The bankruptcy was caused by a sudden market downturn that followed the report.","The profitable quarterly report was misleading because it concealed debt that existed at the corporate level.","The subsidiaries were unrelated businesses that happened to fail at the same time."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The scheme involved moving debt to subsidiaries so the parent looked profitable. The investigators'' finding directly implies the report misrepresented the company''s true financial condition. Auditor approval is not stated. A sudden market downturn contradicts the structural debt explanation. The subsidiaries were owned by the company, not unrelated.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-B4-11'),
  ('PC-INF-B4-12', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"A cognitive study found that participants who were told they were being observed performed routine tasks more carefully but produced less creative output. A follow-up study removed the observer and found that creative output increased while error rates on routine tasks rose slightly."

What can be inferred from the two studies taken together?', '["Observation is harmful and should be eliminated from all performance evaluations.","Creative workers should never be monitored.","Observation appears to enhance accuracy on routine tasks but may inhibit creative thinking.","The follow-up study invalidates the results of the first study."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The two studies together show a trade-off: observation increases routine accuracy but suppresses creativity; removing observation reverses both effects. Neither study is invalidated — they are complementary. Choices A and B draw absolute policy conclusions the data do not support.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-B4-12'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-1', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Eating breakfast every morning gives your body the energy it needs to start the day. Students who eat breakfast tend to perform better in class and stay focused longer than those who skip it. Make it a habit to eat something in the morning, even if it is small."

The author''s purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["describe the history of breakfast as a cultural practice","encourage readers to eat breakfast regularly","compare different types of breakfast foods","report the results of a scientific study"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The closing imperative says it plainly: "Make it a habit to eat something in the morning, even if it is small." Combined with the benefits framing, the passage is a soft pitch, not neutral exposition. Choice B captures that persuasive purpose. Choice A invents a cultural-history angle that never appears. Choice C invents a comparison among breakfast foods the passage does not make. Choice D treats the unsourced student claim as a formal study report, which the passage does not present as research findings. Only B fits the directive tone.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-1'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The base library is open Monday through Friday from 0800 to 2000 and on Saturdays from 0900 to 1700. It is closed on Sundays and federal holidays. Soldiers must present their military ID to check out materials."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["argue that libraries are important resources for soldiers","persuade soldiers to use the library more often","provide factual information about library hours and access requirements","compare the base library to civilian public libraries"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Every sentence delivers a fact: hours of operation, closure days, and the ID requirement. No language praises the library, urges use, or weighs alternatives. Choice C captures that neutral, informational purpose. Choice A invents an argumentative stance the passage never takes. Choice B invents persuasion that the matter-of-fact language does not carry. Choice D invents a comparison to civilian libraries that never appears. The passage reads like a posted notice, and only C describes that purpose accurately.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-2'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-3', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Every spring, the river flooded the lower fields, and every spring the farmers rebuilt their fences, replanted their seeds, and returned to work. They did not complain — or if they did, they complained only to one another, quietly, and then went back to the fields."

The author''s tone toward the farmers can best be described as:', '["critical of their failure to prevent the flooding","admiring of their quiet resilience","indifferent to their annual struggles","sympathetic but pessimistic about their future"]'::jsonb, 1, '''Did not complain'' and returning to work each year without fanfare conveys quiet strength. The author''s choice to note their stoicism — and to present it without irony — signals admiration. No criticism, indifference, or pessimism is present in the tone.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-3'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-4', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The city council has approved, for the third time in five years, a measure to study whether a downtown parking garage is needed. Meanwhile, the parking shortage continues, three businesses have closed citing customer difficulty parking, and the mayor has announced another task force. Progress, apparently, is on schedule."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["supportive of the council''s methodical approach","sarcastically critical of the lack of action","neutral and informational","alarmed by the economic impact on local businesses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The closer gives it away: "Progress, apparently, is on schedule." That line, placed after three studies, three closures, and yet another task force, is mock-praise. Choice B names that sarcasm. Choice A reverses the attitude. Choice C ignores the loaded "apparently" and the deliberate juxtaposition of inaction with mock progress. Choice D names a near-but-distinct attitude, since the author''s focus is the council''s pattern of avoidance rather than alarm over business impact specifically. The business closures function as evidence for the critique, not as the emotional center.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-4'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-5', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Letters from soldiers to their families during World War I reveal an almost universal silence on the worst of what they experienced. The mud, the cold, and the artillery were mentioned; the dead faces of friends were not. They wrote about food, about home, about small jokes — anything to protect the people they loved from what could not be unseen."

The author''s tone toward the soldiers can best be described as:', '["critical of the soldiers for hiding the truth from their families","analytical and detached","somber and deeply respectful","nostalgic for the simplicity of wartime letters"]'::jsonb, 2, '''Anything to protect the people they loved from what could not be unseen'' frames the soldiers'' silence as an act of love, not deception. The gravity of ''what could not be unseen'' adds solemnity. The tone is respectful and somber, not analytical or nostalgic.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-5'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"A growing body of research suggests that multitasking — far from being a productivity technique — reduces performance on all tasks attempted simultaneously. The brain does not truly parallel-process complex activities; it rapidly switches attention between them, with a switching cost paid each time. Those who believe they are efficient multitaskers are often, according to the data, among the worst performers on divided-attention tests."

The author''s primary purpose is to:', '["celebrate the ability of skilled professionals to multitask effectively","describe the history of research on human attention","challenge the belief that multitasking is an effective productivity strategy","compare multitasking across different professions"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage opens by saying multitasking is "far from being a productivity technique" and closes with the ironic finding that self-described efficient multitaskers "are often, according to the data, among the worst performers." Both moves push against a common belief. Choice C captures that. Choice A reverses the stance. Choice B invents a history-of-research framing the passage does not adopt. Choice D invents cross-profession comparison that never appears. Only C reflects the corrective, myth-busting purpose the passage actually pursues.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-6'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-7', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The space between words is where a good editor works. A manuscript arrives fat with adjectives, brimming with throat-clearing introductions, padded with every idea the writer was afraid to leave out. The editor''s gift is not addition but subtraction — the courage to remove what the writer loved but the reader does not need."

The author''s attitude toward the act of editing is best described as:', '["skeptical that most editors have the necessary skills","reverential — viewing good editing as a rare and meaningful craft","critical of writers who overwrite their manuscripts","neutral, presenting editing as a technical process"]'::jsonb, 1, '''The editor''s gift'' and ''the courage to remove'' frame editing as a special ability — a gift requiring bravery. This elevated treatment signals reverence, not skepticism or neutrality. The passage describes writer habits sympathetically (''every idea the writer was afraid to leave out''), not critically.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-7'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-8', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The glacier that covered this valley 12,000 years ago left behind the hills to the north, the flat plain to the south, and the scattering of boulders that farmers have been removing from their fields ever since. Ice, it turns out, is not merely weather. Given enough time and weight, it becomes geology."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["alarmed by the ongoing effects of ancient glaciation","wryly reflective, finding meaning in the slow scale of geological time","strictly scientific and data-driven","mournful about the disappearance of glaciers"]'::jsonb, 1, '''It turns out'' and the observation that ice ''becomes geology'' are quiet, reflective moments — the author finds something worth remarking on in the long view of time. This is contemplative, slightly wry, not alarmed or data-driven. Glacial disappearance is not the subject.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-8'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-9', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee report ran to 847 pages. It was released on a Friday afternoon in December, with no press conference scheduled. The executive summary was 4 pages. The findings were labeled ''preliminary.'' Six months later, a follow-up was promised."

The author''s implied attitude toward the committee''s handling of the report is:', '["supportive — a 847-page report demonstrates thoroughness","critical — the details suggest the report was released to minimize public attention","neutral — the author is simply presenting facts without judgment","hopeful — the follow-up report may address unresolved questions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Friday afternoon December releases, no press conference, ''preliminary'' findings, and a delayed follow-up are classic bureaucratic tactics for burying unwanted information. The author selects these details deliberately to imply criticism without stating it. A neutral author would not stack these signals.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-9'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-10', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The soldier who does not think about the mission — who moves on instinct, reflex, and training alone — is often called battle-hardened. We praise him for it. We decorate him for it. And then, when the war ends and he cannot stop moving on instinct, we call it a disorder and wonder why the training does not switch off when the war does."

The author''s primary purpose is to:', '["argue that soldiers should not be given combat training","criticize soldiers for seeking recognition through combat","highlight a contradiction in how society values and then pathologizes combat instincts","propose a new approach to treating veterans with post-traumatic stress"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage traces one cycle: we train the response, reward the response, then diagnose the same response as a disorder. The author''s purpose is to expose this contradiction, not to argue against training or propose clinical solutions. ''We praise him'' and ''we call it a disorder'' shows the critical symmetry is the point.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-10'),
  ('PC-ATP-B4-11', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"There is something both useful and troubling about the word ''closure.'' Useful, because it gives people permission to move forward after loss. Troubling, because it implies that grief has a terminal state — that the missing weight of a person eventually becomes light enough to carry without noticing. People who have lost someone they love report, almost universally, that they do not stop missing them. They simply learn to carry the weight differently."

The author''s tone toward the concept of ''closure'' is best described as:', '["firmly opposed — the author believes the word should be abandoned","fully supportive — closure is essential for healthy grieving","nuanced — the author acknowledges its usefulness while questioning its implied finality","clinical and detached, reporting grief research without personal interpretation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author calls closure ''both useful and troubling,'' then unpacks both halves. This is not opposition or support — it is a nuanced critique that preserves the word''s value while questioning its misleading implication of completeness. The lyrical ending (''carry the weight differently'') rules out clinical detachment.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-B4-11'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which organelle is known as the powerhouse of the cell because it produces most of the cell''s energy?', '["Nucleus","Ribosome","Mitochondria","Vacuole"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mitochondria run cellular respiration, converting glucose and oxygen into ATP, the energy currency cells spend on every active process. Muscle cells and neurons pack in extra mitochondria because they burn through ATP fast. The nucleus stores DNA and directs gene expression, but it does not generate energy. Ribosomes are the protein-assembly stations that read mRNA and link amino acids. Vacuoles store water, food, or waste, especially in plant cells. Confusing the nucleus with mitochondria is the most common slip since both are major organelles students hear about first.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-1'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which gas do plants release as a byproduct of photosynthesis?', '["Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen","Oxygen","Hydrogen"]'::jsonb, 2, 'During photosynthesis the plant splits water molecules to harvest electrons, and the leftover oxygen is released through stomata. That is why forests and ocean phytoplankton drive Earth''s oxygen supply. Carbon dioxide is the opposite: plants pull it in as a raw material and lock its carbon into glucose, so they consume it rather than release it. Nitrogen is the dominant gas in the atmosphere but plants cannot use it directly from the air, so it is not part of photosynthesis. Hydrogen ends up bound inside glucose, not released as gas.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-2'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'The primary role of the cell membrane is to:', '["Produce proteins for the cell","Control what enters and exits the cell","Store genetic information","Convert sunlight into energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer studded with proteins that acts as a selective gate, letting some substances pass freely (small nonpolar molecules), pumping others in or out actively (ions, glucose), and blocking the rest. Protein production happens at ribosomes attached to rough ER or floating in cytoplasm, not at the membrane. Genetic information lives in the nucleus in eukaryotes or in the nucleoid region in bacteria. Converting sunlight to energy is the chloroplast''s job, found only in plants and algae. The membrane is gatekeeper, not factory.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-3'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'In an ecosystem, which organisms are the primary producers?', '["Herbivores","Carnivores","Decomposers","Plants and algae"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Primary producers capture energy from sunlight (or chemicals at deep-sea vents) and turn it into stored chemical energy, building the base of every food web. Plants, algae, and photosynthetic bacteria do this. Herbivores like deer or grasshoppers are primary consumers because they eat producers. Carnivores eat other animals and sit higher in the chain. Decomposers like fungi and bacteria recycle dead matter into nutrients, which is essential but not the same as producing energy from sunlight. The distinction is whether the organism makes food or eats food.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-4'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Which blood component is primarily responsible for fighting bacterial infections?', '["Red blood cells","Platelets","White blood cells","Plasma"]'::jsonb, 2, 'White blood cells, also called leukocytes, are the immune system''s frontline. Neutrophils swallow bacteria, lymphocytes produce antibodies and kill infected cells, and macrophages clean up debris. Red blood cells carry oxygen and have no role in fighting infection. Platelets are cell fragments that plug wounds and start clotting cascades. Plasma is the straw-colored liquid that carries everything else, including antibodies the white cells produce, but plasma itself is the transport medium rather than the attacker. White cell count rises during infection, which is why doctors order a CBC to check it.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-5'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'A food chain reads: grass → grasshopper → frog → hawk. If the frog population is removed, what is the most likely short-term result?', '["Hawks will increase in number","Grasshoppers will increase in number","Grass will decrease","Hawks will switch to eating grasshoppers directly and maintain balance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Remove the predator and the prey explodes. With frogs gone, grasshoppers face no consistent predator at their trophic level, so their numbers surge in the short term. Hawks lose a major food source and would decline, not increase. Grass would also decline as more grasshoppers eat it, but that secondary effect lags behind the grasshopper boom itself, making the grasshopper increase the more immediate result. Hawks switching directly to grasshoppers ignores that food chains are not infinitely flexible and that adapting prey preferences takes time and may not maintain population balance.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-7'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'Osmosis is best defined as:', '["The active transport of glucose across a membrane","The movement of water from low solute concentration to high solute concentration across a semipermeable membrane","The diffusion of oxygen from lungs into the bloodstream","The breakdown of food in the digestive tract"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Osmosis is the passive movement of water through a semipermeable membrane from an area of lower solute concentration to an area of higher solute concentration. It does not require energy and moves water, not solutes.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-8'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 3, 'Which organ system is responsible for removing gaseous waste (carbon dioxide) from the body?', '["Digestive system","Urinary system","Respiratory system","Circulatory system"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The respiratory system handles gas exchange in the alveoli of the lungs, where oxygen diffuses into the blood and carbon dioxide diffuses out and gets exhaled. The circulatory system transports CO₂ from tissues to the lungs but does not actually remove it from the body, which is a common slip because blood is involved in both transport and removal. The urinary system removes liquid nitrogen waste as urine. The digestive system removes undigested solid waste as feces. Match the waste type to the system: gas to lungs, liquid to kidneys, solid to intestines.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-9'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'A plant cell placed in a highly concentrated salt solution will most likely:', '["Swell and burst as water rushes in","Remain unchanged because the cell wall prevents movement","Shrink as water moves out through osmosis","Absorb the salt ions and increase in size"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The salt solution has a higher solute concentration than the cell''s interior. By osmosis, water moves from the cell (lower solute) into the solution (higher solute), causing the cell to shrink (plasmolyze). The cell wall limits swelling, not shrinking.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-10'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'Mitosis results in:', '["Two genetically identical daughter cells, each with the same chromosome number as the parent","Four daughter cells, each with half the parent''s chromosome number","One parent cell that doubles its DNA but does not divide","Two cells with different genetic makeup due to chromosome shuffling"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Mitosis produces two genetically identical cells that each carry the same number of chromosomes as the original cell, used for growth and repair. Meiosis (not mitosis) produces four cells with half the chromosome count for sexual reproduction.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-11'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 4, 'Which process do decomposers like fungi and bacteria perform that is essential to the nutrient cycle?', '["Photosynthesis, converting CO₂ to glucose","Nitrogen fixation, converting N₂ gas to ammonia","Decomposition, breaking organic matter into inorganic nutrients","Transpiration, releasing water vapor from leaves"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Decomposition is the breakdown of dead organisms and waste into simpler inorganic molecules like CO₂, ammonia, and mineral ions that return to soil, water, and air. Without it, carbon and nitrogen would stay locked in corpses and dead leaves and ecosystems would starve. Photosynthesis is what plants and algae do, not fungi. Nitrogen fixation is a narrow process performed by specific bacteria (Rhizobium, cyanobacteria) on N₂ gas, not the general decomposer role. Transpiration is water loss from plant leaves, completely separate from nutrient cycling driven by decomposers.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-12'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-13', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 5, 'A recessive genetic trait will be expressed in an individual when:', '["The individual carries at least one dominant allele","The individual is heterozygous (one dominant, one recessive allele)","The individual inherits two recessive alleles, one from each parent","The trait skips a generation before appearing"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Recessive traits are masked when a dominant allele is present. Expression requires two copies of the recessive allele (homozygous recessive). Heterozygous individuals carry the trait but do not express it; ''skipping a generation'' describes the pattern, not the cause.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-13'),
  ('GS-LS-B5-14', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 5, 'During aerobic cellular respiration, where in the cell does the Krebs cycle take place?', '["In the cytoplasm","In the nucleus","In the mitochondrial matrix","On the outer mitochondrial membrane"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The Krebs cycle (citric acid cycle) occurs in the mitochondrial matrix, the innermost compartment. Glycolysis happens in the cytoplasm. The electron transport chain is located on the inner mitochondrial membrane, not in the matrix itself.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.life-science::GS-LS-B5-14'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which state of matter has a definite volume but no definite shape?', '["Solid","Liquid","Gas","Plasma"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Liquids hold a fixed volume because their molecules stay close together, but they flow to take the shape of whatever container holds them. Pour a liter of water into a tall cylinder or a flat tray, and it remains a liter while changing outline. Solids lock in both shape and volume because their molecules are fixed in place. Gases expand to fill the entire container, so they lack both a fixed shape and a fixed volume. Plasma is ionized gas found in stars and neon signs; like ordinary gas, it conforms to no fixed shape or volume.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-1'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which of the following is a chemical change?', '["Ice melting into water","Cutting a piece of paper","Iron rusting","Sugar dissolving in water"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Rusting is iron combining with oxygen to form a new compound, iron oxide, with different color, hardness, and chemical properties. New substance means chemical change. Ice melting is a physical change because the H₂O molecules are identical before and after, just rearranged from rigid crystal to flowing liquid. Cutting paper changes shape, not composition. Sugar dissolving spreads sucrose molecules through water but does not transform them; evaporate the water and the sugar returns unchanged. The test is whether a brand-new substance with new chemistry has appeared.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-2'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'On the periodic table, elements in the same column (group) share similar properties primarily because they have the same:', '["Atomic mass","Number of protons","Number of neutrons","Number of valence electrons"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Valence electrons are the outermost shell electrons that participate in chemical bonding, and elements in the same group share the same valence count. That is why all Group 1 alkali metals react violently with water and all Group 18 noble gases barely react at all. Atomic mass increases steadily down a group, so it cannot be the cause. Proton count defines the element itself and is unique to each element, never shared. Neutron count varies among isotopes even within a single element and has no bearing on chemical behavior, only on stability and mass.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-3'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'What happens to the pressure of a gas inside a sealed container when the temperature increases, assuming volume stays constant?', '["Pressure decreases","Pressure stays the same","Pressure increases","The gas liquefies"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Heating a gas speeds up its molecules. They hit the container walls harder and more often, which is exactly what pressure measures. With volume fixed, pressure rises in direct proportion to absolute temperature; double the Kelvin temperature and pressure doubles. This is Gay-Lussac''s Law. A sealed aerosol can in a hot car can rupture for this reason. The gas does not liquefy from heating; liquefaction usually requires cooling or compressing. Pressure cannot stay the same because faster molecules cannot avoid more forceful collisions when the walls do not move.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-4'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'In a chemical reaction, the substances that are present before the reaction begins are called:', '["Products","Reactants","Catalysts","Compounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Reactants are the starting materials that get consumed and rearranged during a reaction, written on the left side of the arrow. Products are what comes out on the right side, so swapping the two reverses the equation. Catalysts speed up reactions by lowering activation energy but are not consumed and are not counted among reactants or products; they often appear above the arrow. Compound describes a category of substance, not a reaction role; both reactants and products can be compounds or elements. The arrow direction is the visual cue: left equals reactant, right equals product.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-5'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'A substance has a pH of 2. Which statement best describes this substance?', '["It is strongly basic and will feel slippery","It is weakly acidic and slightly corrosive","It is strongly acidic with high hydrogen ion concentration","It is neutral and safe to drink in any quantity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A pH of 2 is strongly acidic, only one step away from battery acid at pH 1 and well below the neutral mark at 7. Because pH is logarithmic, pH 2 has 100,000 times more hydrogen ions than neutral water. Calling it weakly acidic underestimates the danger; lemon juice sits around pH 2 and is still capable of dissolving tooth enamel. Strongly basic substances feel slippery and have high pH above 12, not low pH. Neutral substances sit at 7, not 2, and nothing at pH 2 is universally safe to drink in unlimited amounts.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-6'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'When a substance undergoes sublimation, it transitions directly from:', '["Liquid to gas","Solid to liquid","Solid to gas","Gas to liquid"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sublimation skips the liquid phase, going straight from solid to gas. Dry ice (solid CO₂) is the textbook example because at room pressure it cannot exist as a liquid, so it simply turns into CO₂ gas. Solid air fresheners and mothballs also sublime slowly. Liquid to gas is evaporation or boiling, not sublimation. Solid to liquid is plain melting. Gas to liquid is condensation, the reverse of evaporation. The reverse of sublimation, gas straight to solid, is called deposition, which is how frost forms on a cold windshield without dew first.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-7'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 3, 'Which type of chemical bond results from the transfer of electrons from one atom to another?', '["Covalent bond","Hydrogen bond","Ionic bond","Metallic bond"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ionic bonds form when one atom hands off electrons to another, creating a positively charged cation and a negatively charged anion. The opposite charges attract and lock the ions in place, as in sodium chloride where sodium gives up an electron to chlorine. Covalent bonds work differently, with atoms sharing electron pairs rather than transferring them, common in water and methane. Hydrogen bonds are weak attractions between polar molecules, like the ones holding water''s strands together, not full bonds. Metallic bonds let electrons flow freely through a lattice of metal atoms, giving conductivity.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-8'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'A catalyst speeds up a chemical reaction primarily by:', '["Increasing the temperature of the reactants","Providing energy to break all molecular bonds","Lowering the activation energy required for the reaction","Increasing the concentration of products"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Catalysts provide an alternative reaction pathway with lower activation energy, allowing more reactant molecules to have sufficient energy to react. A catalyst is not consumed and does not change the energy of reactants or products.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-9'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'In a neutralization reaction, an acid and a base react to form:', '["Another acid with different strength","Salt and water","Carbon dioxide and oxygen","A metal oxide"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An acid donates H⁺ ions, a base donates OH⁻ ions, and when they meet the ions combine to form H₂O while the leftover spectator ions pair up as a salt. Hydrochloric acid plus sodium hydroxide gives sodium chloride and water: HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H₂O. The pH moves toward 7. Producing another acid would mean the reaction never neutralized anything. Carbon dioxide and oxygen come out of combustion or photosynthesis, not acid-base neutralization. Metal oxides form when metals burn or corrode with oxygen and have nothing to do with mixing an acid and a base.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-10'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 4, 'Which of the following correctly identifies the number of moles in 44 grams of CO₂? (C = 12 g/mol, O = 16 g/mol)', '["0.5 moles","1 mole","2 moles","44 moles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Molar mass of CO₂ is 12 (one carbon) plus 2 times 16 (two oxygens), which equals 44 g/mol. Moles equals mass divided by molar mass, so 44 grams divided by 44 g/mol gives exactly 1 mole. The 2-mole answer comes from doubling because there are two oxygens, but the formula already accounts for that in the molar mass. The 0.5-mole answer halves correctly only if the substance were O₂ or someone forgot the carbon. The 44-mole answer mistakes grams for moles entirely and ignores the conversion.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-11'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 5, 'In the balanced equation 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, how many moles of water are produced from 3 moles of H₂ and excess O₂?', '["1.5 moles","2 moles","3 moles","6 moles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Read the coefficients: 2 moles of H₂ produce 2 moles of H₂O, a 1 to 1 ratio. So 3 moles of hydrogen produce 3 moles of water when oxygen is plentiful. Dividing 3 by 2 to get 1.5 misreads the ratio by treating the 2 in front of H₂ as a divisor rather than recognizing it pairs evenly with the 2 in front of H₂O. Doubling to 6 mistakenly multiplies by 2. Answering 2 moles ignores that the limiting reactant is H₂ and that excess O₂ means hydrogen sets the cap.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-12'),
  ('GS-PS-B5-13', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 5, 'Which of the following best explains why noble gases (Group 18) rarely form chemical bonds with other elements?', '["They have very high atomic masses that prevent bonding","They have complete outer electron shells with no tendency to gain or lose electrons","They are radioactive and unstable at normal temperatures","Their electrons orbit so quickly that other atoms cannot bond to them"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Noble gases have full valence electron shells (8 electrons, or 2 for helium), giving them maximum stability. With no need to gain, lose, or share electrons, they have virtually no chemical reactivity. Their stability is electronic, not related to mass or speed.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physical-science::GS-PS-B5-13'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'The layer of Earth that we live on, which makes up the surface and outer crust, is called the:', '["Mantle","Core","Lithosphere","Asthenosphere"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The lithosphere is the rigid outer shell of Earth, including the crust and the cool uppermost portion of the mantle, and it is the layer broken into tectonic plates that carry continents and oceans. The mantle as a whole sits below the lithosphere and is much hotter and more deformable. The core is the metallic center, an outer liquid layer and an inner solid layer of mostly iron and nickel. The asthenosphere is the partly molten zone right beneath the lithosphere where plates ride and convection occurs. We live on top of the lithosphere.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-1'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What causes the seasons on Earth?', '["Earth''s varying distance from the Sun as it orbits","The tilt of Earth''s axis relative to its orbital plane","Changes in the Sun''s energy output throughout the year","The Moon blocking different amounts of sunlight"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Earth''s axis is tilted approximately 23.5° relative to its orbit. This tilt causes one hemisphere to receive more direct sunlight during part of the year (summer) and less during another (winter). Earth''s distance from the Sun varies only slightly and is not the primary cause.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-2'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Metamorphic rock is formed when existing rock is subjected to:', '["Rapid cooling of magma at the surface","The compaction of layers of sediment over time","High heat and pressure deep within Earth","Erosion by wind and water"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Metamorphic rock starts as another rock (igneous, sedimentary, or even older metamorphic) and gets reshaped by intense heat and pressure deep underground without fully melting. Limestone becomes marble, shale becomes slate, sandstone becomes quartzite. Rapid cooling of magma at the surface produces extrusive igneous rocks like basalt, not metamorphic. Compaction of sediment layers makes sedimentary rocks like shale and sandstone. Erosion by wind and water is the breakdown step that creates sediment in the first place; it does not form rock by itself. The key word is transformed, not melted, not crushed, not weathered.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-3'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'The water cycle step in which water vapor cools and changes into liquid water droplets to form clouds is called:', '["Evaporation","Condensation","Precipitation","Transpiration"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Condensation is the phase change from gas back to liquid. As warm moist air rises and cools, vapor molecules slow down enough to stick together as tiny droplets around dust or salt particles, forming clouds and fog. Evaporation is the opposite direction, liquid turning to vapor when surface water absorbs heat. Precipitation comes after condensation, when droplets grow heavy enough to fall as rain, snow, or hail. Transpiration is plant-driven evaporation through leaf stomata; it adds moisture to the air but is not the cloud-forming step. Cooling vapor equals condensation.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-4'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'Which atmospheric layer, positioned just above the stratosphere, is where meteors typically burn up upon entering Earth''s atmosphere?', '["Troposphere","Stratosphere","Mesosphere","Thermosphere"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mesosphere extends from roughly 50 to 80 km up, sitting directly above the stratosphere. The air there is thin but dense enough that friction with incoming meteoroids generates the heat that produces shooting stars. The troposphere is the bottom weather layer and is too low to see most meteor burns. The stratosphere holds the ozone layer but is below where meteors flame. The thermosphere is the next layer up, where the ISS orbits and auroras glow, and although it is hot, the air is too thin to ignite meteors efficiently.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-5'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'According to the rock cycle, which process can convert igneous rock into sedimentary rock?', '["Melting followed by rapid cooling","Heat and pressure deep underground","Weathering, erosion, and compaction of the rock fragments","Volcanic uplift pushing the rock to the surface"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An igneous rock at the surface is exposed to weather. Rain, wind, ice, and biological activity break it into fragments, which rivers and gravity carry to lower ground. Layers pile up, get buried, and compact and cement into sedimentary rock through lithification. Melting and rapid cooling would just produce another igneous rock, not sedimentary. Heat and pressure deep underground transform existing rocks into metamorphic rocks like slate or marble. Volcanic uplift moves rock around but does not by itself change what type of rock it is. The route to sedimentary always passes through sediment.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-6'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 3, 'At which location would a hurricane most likely begin to weaken significantly?', '["Over warm tropical ocean water","When moving toward the equator","After making landfall or moving over cooler water","When it absorbs a nearby low-pressure system"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hurricanes are heat engines fed by evaporation from ocean water warmer than about 26°C. Cut off that energy source and the storm dies. Moving over land removes the moisture supply and adds frictional drag, so storms decay quickly inland. Moving over cooler water has the same effect of starving the convection. Warm tropical ocean water is what fuels hurricanes, so it strengthens rather than weakens them. Hurricanes do not move toward the equator (they curve poleward due to Coriolis steering). Absorbing a low-pressure system can actually feed energy in, not drain it.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-7'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'Which type of plate boundary is associated with the formation of most of Earth''s major mountain ranges?', '["Divergent boundary, where plates move apart","Transform boundary, where plates slide past each other","Convergent boundary, where plates collide and compress","Subduction boundary, where oceanic plates sink under oceanic plates"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Major mountain ranges form where plates collide. The Himalayas rose from India ramming Eurasia, and the Alps rose from Africa pushing into Europe. Collision compresses and folds the crust upward over millions of years. Divergent boundaries pull apart and form rift valleys and mid-ocean ridges, not tall continental mountain belts. Transform boundaries grind past each other and produce earthquakes along faults like the San Andreas, not big ranges. Oceanic-on-oceanic subduction creates island arcs like Japan, which are mountainous but not the world''s major continental ranges. The biggest mountains come from continental crash.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-8'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'As altitude increases in the troposphere, air temperature generally:', '["Increases at a steady rate","Remains constant","Decreases","Increases then decreases"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Within the troposphere, temperature drops about 6.5°C for every 1,000 meters of climb, known as the environmental lapse rate. That is why mountaintops carry snow while valleys stay green and why airliner cabins need heating at cruise altitude. The pattern flips in the stratosphere right above, where ozone absorbs UV and warms the air with altitude. A constant temperature would describe the isothermal tropopause boundary, not the bulk troposphere. Increase then decrease describes the overall atmospheric profile across all layers, not the troposphere alone. Inside the troposphere the direction is simple: up means cooler.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-9'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 4, 'A star''s color is most directly related to its:', '["Size","Distance from Earth","Surface temperature","Age in the stellar lifecycle"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A star''s color is determined by its surface temperature: blue-white stars are hottest, yellow stars (like our Sun) are mid-range, and red stars are coolest. Distance affects apparent brightness, not color. Age and size influence temperature but are not the direct cause of color.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-10'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-11', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 5, 'Which phenomenon best explains why oceanic crust is generally younger than continental crust?', '["Oceanic crust forms faster due to more volcanic activity on land","Continental crust is recycled through subduction more rapidly","Oceanic crust is continuously created at mid-ocean ridges and destroyed at subduction zones","Tidal forces from the Moon preferentially age continental crust"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Oceanic crust is born at mid-ocean ridges where magma rises and solidifies, spreads outward like a conveyor belt, and is eventually pulled back into the mantle at deep-sea trenches. The full cycle takes about 200 million years, which is young in geological terms. Continental crust is less dense, so it floats and resists being subducted, accumulating ages up to 4 billion years. Saying continents recycle faster reverses the truth. Oceanic crust does not form on land. The Moon''s tides influence the oceans and slow Earth''s rotation but do not selectively age continental rock.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-11'),
  ('GS-ES-B5-12', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 5, 'During a lunar eclipse, the Moon appears reddish because:', '["The Moon reflects red light from nearby stars","Earth''s atmosphere scatters shorter wavelengths and refracts red light onto the Moon","The Moon''s own iron-rich surface reflects at a red wavelength","Sunlight heats the Moon''s surface, causing it to glow red"]'::jsonb, 1, 'During a lunar eclipse, Earth''s atmosphere acts like a lens: it scatters away blue wavelengths but bends (refracts) longer red and orange wavelengths into Earth''s shadow, illuminating the Moon with a reddish glow, the same physics that makes sunsets red.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.earth-space-science::GS-ES-B5-12'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-1', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Which type of energy does a moving car possess?', '["Chemical energy","Potential energy","Kinetic energy","Nuclear energy"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic energy is the energy of motion, calculated as one-half mass times velocity squared. Any object moving has it: a rolling car, a thrown football, flowing river water. Chemical energy is stored in molecular bonds, like the gasoline in the tank before combustion, but once the engine burns it the energy converts and the car''s motion now carries kinetic energy. Potential energy is positional, like the same car parked at the top of a hill before it rolls. Nuclear energy comes from atomic nuclei in reactors or stars and has nothing to do with a normal car in motion.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-1'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-2', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'A wedge is a type of simple machine. The primary mechanical purpose of a wedge is to:', '["Change the direction of a force along a rope","Multiply rotational force through gears","Convert a downward force into an outward splitting force","Store energy that can be released later"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A wedge is essentially a moving inclined plane that takes a single push along its blunt end and redirects that force outward along its sloped faces, prying or splitting material apart. Axes, chisels, knives, and splitting mauls all work this way. Changing direction along a rope describes a pulley. Multiplying rotational force through gears describes a wheel-and-axle system or gear train, not a wedge. Storing energy describes a spring or capacitor, not a wedge, which simply redirects force during contact. The signature move of a wedge is conversion of one push into two outward separations.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-2'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-3', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'When you stretch a rubber band and hold it motionless, it has:', '["Kinetic energy only","No energy because it is not moving","Elastic potential energy","Thermal energy from being stretched"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Stretching a rubber band stores elastic potential energy, energy due to deformation. When released, this potential energy converts to kinetic energy. Thermal energy might increase slightly, but the dominant stored energy is elastic potential.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-3'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-4', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'Newton''s Second Law states that force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). If the net force on an object doubles while its mass stays the same, its acceleration will:', '["Stay the same","Double","Quadruple","Decrease by half"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rearrange F = ma to a = F/m. With mass held constant, acceleration scales directly with net force, so doubling force doubles acceleration. Quadrupling would only happen if force quadrupled or if mass were also halved. Decreasing by half would require mass to double (a is inversely proportional to mass at fixed F), but mass is fixed here. Staying the same is only true if force is unchanged. The mental shortcut: in F = ma, if one side doubles and one variable is held, the remaining variable must move in lockstep to keep the equation balanced.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-4'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-5', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'A first-class lever has the fulcrum between the effort and the load. Which of the following is an example of a first-class lever?', '["A wheelbarrow","A pair of scissors","A baseball bat","A bottle opener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Scissors place the pivot pin between your hand on the handles (effort) and the material being cut at the blades (load), which is the defining setup of a first-class lever. Seesaws and crowbars work the same way. A wheelbarrow is a second-class lever because the load (cargo) sits between the fulcrum (wheel) and the effort (hands lifting handles). A baseball bat is a third-class lever because the effort (hand near the knob) sits between the fulcrum (other hand or shoulder) and the load (the ball at the barrel). A bottle opener is also second-class.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-5'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-6', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'If a 10-kg object is lifted 5 meters, how much gravitational potential energy does it gain? (Use g = 10 m/s²)', '["15 joules","50 joules","500 joules","5,000 joules"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Gravitational potential energy equals mass times g times height: 10 kg times 10 m/s² times 5 m equals 500 joules. The 50-joule answer drops the g factor and just multiplies mass by height, a common slip when students think of weight as a single number. The 15-joule answer adds the values instead of multiplying. The 5,000-joule answer adds an extra factor of 10, perhaps by using g = 100 by mistake. Keep the formula PE = mgh in mind and plug in carefully; each piece must be there and in the right units.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-6'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-7', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 3, 'Friction always acts in what direction relative to an object''s motion?', '["Perpendicular to motion","In the same direction as motion","Opposite to the direction of motion","Downward due to gravity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Friction is a resistive force that always points opposite to the direction of motion (or the tendency to move). Slide a box right and friction pushes left; brakes work because friction between pads and rotor opposes the wheel''s spin. Acting in the same direction as motion would describe a propelling force, not friction, which would mean friction speeds objects up instead of slowing them. Perpendicular to motion describes the normal force, the support force from a surface. Downward describes gravity, which is unrelated to friction''s direction. Friction always pushes back against whatever motion is happening.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-7'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-8', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 4, 'A 4-kg block slides down a frictionless ramp and reaches the bottom with a speed of 6 m/s. What is its kinetic energy at the bottom?', '["24 joules","48 joules","72 joules","144 joules"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic energy equals one-half mass times velocity squared: 0.5 times 4 kg times 6² equals 0.5 times 4 times 36, which equals 72 joules. The 144-joule answer forgets the one-half factor and just multiplies 4 times 36. The 48-joule answer uses 6 instead of 6², dropping the velocity-squared term entirely. The 24-joule answer halves 48, compounding two errors. The KE formula has three pieces (½, mass, velocity squared); skip any one and the answer drifts to a distractor. Always square the velocity before multiplying by mass and half.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-8'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-9', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 4, 'What is the mechanical advantage of a lever when the effort arm is 3 meters and the load arm is 1 meter?', '["0.33","1","3","4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mechanical advantage of a lever equals the effort arm length divided by the load arm length: 3 divided by 1 equals 3. This means a force applied at the effort end can lift a load three times heavier. The 0.33 answer inverts the ratio (load divided by effort) and would describe a lever working against you, useful only for speed or distance multiplication. The MA of 1 implies the arms are equal, like a balance scale, which they are not here. The MA of 4 would require the effort arm to be 4 times the load arm, not 3. Always: effort length over load length.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-9'),
  ('GS-PM-B5-10', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 5, 'A 2-kg ball is dropped from 20 meters above the ground. At 10 meters height (halfway down), ignoring air resistance, what is its approximate kinetic energy? (g = 10 m/s²)', '["100 joules","200 joules","300 joules","400 joules"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Initial PE at 20 m = mgh = 2 × 10 × 20 = 400 J. At 10 m, remaining PE = 2 × 10 × 10 = 200 J. By conservation of energy, KE gained = 400 − 200 = 200 J. You do not need to calculate velocity separately.', true, 'trusted', 'gs.physics-mechanics::GS-PM-B5-10'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'According to Ohm''s Law, if the voltage across a resistor is 10 volts and the resistance is 5 ohms, the current through the resistor is:', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","2 amperes","50 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ohm''s Law: I = V / R = 10 V / 5 Ω = 2 A. Current is 2 amperes. Choice A (0.5 A) inverts the formula and divides R by V (5 / 10). Choice B (1 A) subtracts instead of dividing (10 minus 5, halved by some misstep) or applies a guessed ratio. Choice D (50 A) multiplies V by R, treating Ohm''s Law as if voltage times resistance produces current. The formula is strictly division: voltage over resistance equals current.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-1'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'Electrical power in a circuit is calculated using the formula P = IV. If a device draws 3 amperes from a 12-volt source, its power consumption is:', '["4 watts","9 watts","15 watts","36 watts"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Power formula: P = I × V = 3 A × 12 V = 36 W. The device consumes 36 watts. Choice A (4 W) divides V by I (12 / 3), confusing the power formula with Ohm''s Law for resistance. Choice B (9 W) squares current (3²) and ignores voltage. Choice C (15 W) adds the two values (12 + 3) instead of multiplying. Power in a DC circuit is always the product of voltage and current, never the sum or quotient of those quantities.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-2'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'Using P = I²R, what power is dissipated by a 4-ohm resistor carrying 5 amperes?', '["20 watts","40 watts","80 watts","100 watts"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Use P = I²R. Square the current first: 5² = 25. Then multiply by resistance: 25 × 4 = 100 W. The resistor dissipates 100 watts. Choice A (20 W) computes I × R (5 × 4) and forgets to square. Choice B (40 W) doubles I × R or applies 2 × I × R, which is not a power formula. Choice C (80 W) doubles the I × R result. Squaring current is essential because power grows with the square of current, not linearly.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-4'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'Four resistors of 10 ohms each are connected in series. What is the total resistance of the circuit?', '["2.5 ohms","10 ohms","40 ohms","1,000 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Series resistors add directly: Rt = 10 + 10 + 10 + 10 = 40 Ω. Total resistance is 40 ohms. Choice A (2.5 Ω) misapplies the parallel formula, computing 10 / 4 instead of 10 × 4. Choice B (10 Ω) leaves resistance unchanged, ignoring that each added resistor stacks more opposition in the single current path. Choice D (1,000 Ω) multiplies the resistors (10 × 10 × 10) instead of summing them. In series, the values stack additively because current crosses each in sequence.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-5'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'A 100-watt appliance runs on 200 volts. Using P = V²/R, what is its resistance?', '["2 ohms","50 ohms","400 ohms","20,000 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Rearrange P = V² / R to R = V² / P. Square voltage: 200² = 40,000. Divide by power: 40,000 / 100 = 400 Ω. Resistance is 400 ohms. Choice A (2 Ω) divides V by P (200 / 100) and skips squaring entirely. Choice C (50 Ω) divides P by an arbitrary factor or computes V / (2P). Choice D (20,000 Ω) divides V² by 2 instead of P, or otherwise mishandles the divisor. The V² term is non-negotiable when the formula uses V² / R.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-6'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 3, 'Three resistors, 2 ohms, 3 ohms, and 5 ohms, are connected in series to a 20-volt battery. What is the current in the circuit?', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","2 amperes","4 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add series resistances: Rt = 2 + 3 + 5 = 10 Ω. Apply Ohm''s Law: I = V / Rt = 20 V / 10 Ω = 2 A. Current is 2 amperes. Choice A (0.5 A) divides Rt by V (10 / 20) and inverts the formula. Choice B (1 A) uses only part of the resistance or divides by 20 instead of 10. Choice D (4 A) uses only the 5-ohm resistor (20 / 5), forgetting that current sees the full series stack, not one component.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-7'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'A 24-volt source powers three identical resistors connected in parallel. If each resistor is 12 ohms, what is the total current drawn from the source?', '["0.67 amperes","2 amperes","4 amperes","6 amperes"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Each parallel branch sees the full 24 V. Branch current = 24 / 12 = 2 A. With three identical branches, total current = 3 × 2 = 6 A. Cross-check: parallel resistance = 12 / 3 = 4 Ω; total I = 24 / 4 = 6 A. Choice A (0.67 A) divides voltage by series total (24 / 36) as if the resistors were in series. Choice B (2 A) reports only one branch. Choice C (4 A) reports only two branches or uses parallel resistance as branch current.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-8'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'A 10-ohm resistor and a 15-ohm resistor are connected in parallel. What is the combined resistance? (Express your answer as a fraction or decimal.)', '["25 ohms","12.5 ohms","6 ohms","5 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, '1/R = 1/10 + 1/15 = 3/30 + 2/30 = 5/30 = 1/6, so R = 6 ohms. Adding resistances (25) is the series formula. Averaging (12.5) is not a valid circuit rule. In parallel, result is always less than the smallest individual resistor (10 ohms).', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-9'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 5, 'A series circuit with a 30-volt source contains two resistors: R₁ = 6 ohms and R₂ = 4 ohms. What is the voltage drop across R₁?', '["6 volts","12 volts","18 volts","24 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total resistance = 6 + 4 = 10 Ω. Circuit current = 30 V / 10 Ω = 3 A. Voltage across R1 = I × R1 = 3 × 6 = 18 V. By the voltage divider rule, R1 takes 6/10 = 60% of source voltage, and 60% of 30 V is 18 V. Choice A (6 V) reports the resistance value as if it were a voltage. Choice B (12 V) gives the drop across R2 instead. Choice D (24 V) inverts the ratio and assigns R1 80% of the source.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-10'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 5, 'A device with 50 ohms of resistance must dissipate exactly 200 watts. What supply voltage is required?', '["10 volts","50 volts","100 volts","4 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use P = V² / R, so V² = P × R = 200 × 50 = 10,000, and V = √10,000 = 100 V. Cross-check with two-step path: I = √(P/R) = √4 = 2 A, then V = IR = 2 × 50 = 100 V. Choice A (10 V) takes √(P) and ignores R, or divides incorrectly. Choice B (50 V) reports the resistance value. Choice D (4 V) divides P by 50 to get 4 and stops, skipping the square root step that the V² relationship requires.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-11'),
  ('EI-OL-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 4, 'If resistance in a circuit doubles while voltage stays constant, what happens to the current?', '["It doubles","It remains the same","It is cut in half","It increases by the square of the resistance"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ohm''s Law: I = V / R. With V constant and R doubled, new current = V / (2R), which is half the original. Current is cut in half. Choice A (doubles) assumes a direct relationship, but current is inversely proportional to resistance, not directly. Choice B (stays the same) ignores the formula entirely. Choice D (squares the resistance) confuses Ohm''s Law with the I²R power expression. Only one variable changed here, and the inverse relationship between I and R settles the result.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.ohms-law-power::EI-OL-B5-12'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a parallel circuit, the voltage across each branch compared to the source voltage is:', '["Less than the source voltage","Equal to the source voltage","Greater than the source voltage","Divided equally among branches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In a parallel circuit, every branch connects directly to the same two source nodes, so each branch sees the full source voltage. That is the defining property. Choice A (less than source) describes a series component, where voltage divides across each resistor. Choice C (greater than source) violates energy conservation; no passive component creates voltage. Choice D (divided equally among branches) confuses parallel voltage behavior with current behavior, where current does split among branches according to each branch''s resistance, but voltage stays equal across all branches.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-1'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a series circuit, the current through each component is:', '["Different for each component based on its resistance","The same throughout the entire circuit","Zero if any component has high resistance","Split between components based on their resistance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A series circuit has one path for current, so the same current passes through every component. Voltage divides across them based on resistance, but current does not. Choice A (different per component) confuses current with voltage; voltage varies in series, current does not. Choice C (zero with one high resistor) is wrong because high resistance reduces current but does not stop it unless the component is fully open. Choice D (splits among components) describes parallel behavior, where multiple paths share the total current.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-2'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'Three light bulbs are connected in parallel to a battery. One bulb burns out (open circuit). What happens to the other two bulbs?', '["They also go out because the circuit is broken","They dim slightly because total resistance decreases","They continue to glow normally","They burn brighter because they now draw more current"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each bulb in a parallel circuit has its own independent loop from source to source. When one bulb opens, only that branch breaks; the other branches still see the full source voltage and full branch current. The remaining bulbs glow normally. Choice A (all go out) describes series behavior. Choice B (dim slightly) gets the direction wrong; if anything, total resistance rises and total current falls, but per-branch voltage and current do not change. Choice D (burn brighter) confuses branches with a series voltage redistribution that does not happen here.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-3'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'A series circuit with a 9-volt battery and two resistors (3 ohms and 6 ohms) carries a current of 1 ampere. What is the voltage drop across the 6-ohm resistor?', '["1.5 volts","3 volts","6 volts","9 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'V = I × R = 1 × 6 = 6 volts across the 6-ohm resistor. The 3-ohm resistor drops 3 volts, and 3 + 6 = 9 V confirms Kirchhoff''s Voltage Law. Using the full 9 volts across one resistor is a common error.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-4'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'Adding more resistors in parallel to an existing circuit will:', '["Increase total resistance and decrease total current","Decrease total resistance and increase total current","Have no effect on total current from the source","Decrease voltage at the source"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adding parallel resistors means 1/Rt = 1/R1 + 1/R2 + 1/R3 + ..., and each new term increases the right side, which lowers Rt. With source voltage fixed, I = V / Rt rises. Choice A reverses the direction; parallel branches do not raise resistance, they lower it. Choice C ignores Ohm''s Law; total current must respond when total resistance shifts. Choice D confuses load behavior with source behavior; an ideal source holds voltage constant, and even a real source''s voltage drop would be a secondary effect, not the primary outcome.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-5'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'In a series circuit, adding a resistor will:', '["Decrease total resistance and increase current","Increase total resistance and decrease current","Keep current the same because voltage adjusts","Only affect the components after it in the circuit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Series resistances add: Rt = R1 + R2 + R3 + ... So a new series resistor raises total resistance. By Ohm''s Law I = V / Rt, with V constant, higher Rt means lower current through the entire loop. Choice A reverses the direction; series additions cannot lower resistance. Choice C invokes a self-adjusting voltage that the source does not perform. Choice D claims only downstream components feel the change, but a series loop carries one current value everywhere; every component upstream or downstream sees the same reduced current.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-6'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 3, 'Kirchhoff''s Current Law states that the total current entering a junction in a circuit equals the total current leaving it. This law applies to which circuit type as a core analysis tool?', '["Series circuits only","Open circuits only","Parallel and combination circuits","Only DC battery circuits"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kirchhoff''s Current Law operates at junctions where current splits or merges. Pure series circuits have no junctions; the same current flows through every component, so KCL is trivially true and offers no analytical leverage. Parallel and combination circuits are where KCL earns its keep, balancing inflow against outflow at each node. Choice A picks the one topology where KCL is unnecessary. Choice B (open circuits) carries no current at all. Choice D (DC battery only) invents a restriction; KCL holds for AC and DC alike.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-7'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A circuit has two branches in parallel: Branch A draws 4 amperes and Branch B draws 2 amperes. The source voltage is 12 volts. What is the resistance of Branch B?', '["2 ohms","4 ohms","6 ohms","24 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In parallel, each branch sees 12 volts. R_B = V/I_B = 12/2 = 6 ohms. Do not add the branch currents before calculating resistance, each branch is analyzed independently with the full source voltage.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-8'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A switch is placed in the main line of a parallel circuit (before the branches split). If this switch is opened, what happens?', '["Only the first branch loses power","All branches lose power simultaneously","Branches alternate between on and off","The branch with the highest resistance loses power first"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A switch in the main line sits before the current splits into parallel branches. Opening it breaks the only path connecting all branches to the source, so every branch loses power at once. This is exactly how a main breaker cuts a whole panel. Choice A (only first branch) describes a switch placed inside one branch, not the main line. Choice C (alternating on/off) describes oscillator behavior, not a static switch. Choice D (highest-resistance branch first) invents a sequencing rule that does not exist in DC circuit analysis.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-9'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 4, 'A combination circuit has a 2-ohm resistor in series with a parallel combination of a 4-ohm and 4-ohm resistor. What is the total circuit resistance?', '["10 ohms","6 ohms","4 ohms","2 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First combine the parallel pair: 4 Ω || 4 Ω = 4 / 2 = 2 Ω. Then add the series 2 Ω: Rt = 2 + 2 = 4 Ω. Total circuit resistance is 4 ohms. Choice A (10 Ω) adds all three values as if everything were in series. Choice B (6 Ω) leaves the 4-ohm pair uncombined or sums 2 + 4 once. Choice D (2 Ω) reports only the parallel combination and forgets the series 2-ohm resistor. Combination circuits demand reducing parallel sections first, then summing what remains.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-10'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 5, 'In a series circuit with a 48-volt source and three resistors (R₁ = 8 Ω, R₂ = 4 Ω, R₃ = 4 Ω), what percentage of the source voltage appears across R₁?', '["25%","33%","50%","75%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Series total: Rt = 8 + 4 + 4 = 16 Ω. Current = 48 / 16 = 3 A. Voltage across R1 = 3 × 8 = 24 V. Percentage = 24 / 48 = 50%. Voltage-divider shortcut: R1 is 8/16 = 50% of total resistance, so it takes 50% of source voltage. Choice A (25%) treats R1 as one of four equal parts. Choice B (33%) divides by component count (3) instead of resistance share. Choice D (75%) inverts the ratio, giving R1 the share that belongs to R2 and R3 combined.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-11'),
  ('EI-CT-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 5, 'Two batteries, each 6 volts with internal resistance of 1 ohm, are connected in series and power a 10-ohm external load. What is the current through the load?', '["0.5 amperes","1 ampere","1.2 amperes","2 amperes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total voltage = 6 + 6 = 12 V. Total resistance = 1 + 1 + 10 = 12 Ω (internal resistances add in series). Current = 12/12 = 1 ampere. Ignoring internal resistance gives 12/10 = 1.2 A, a common error on multi-battery problems.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.circuit-types::EI-CT-B5-12'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A capacitor in an electrical circuit primarily functions to:', '["Amplify the voltage in the circuit","Allow current to flow in one direction only","Store electrical energy in an electric field","Convert AC to DC"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A capacitor stores energy in an electric field between two conductive plates separated by an insulator (dielectric). It charges when voltage is applied and releases that energy when the circuit demands. A diode, not a capacitor, allows one-directional current flow.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-1'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A resistor is used in an electrical circuit mainly to:', '["Store charge for later use","Limit the amount of current flowing through a component","Convert AC voltage to DC voltage","Step up or step down voltage levels"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Resistors oppose current flow, with opposition measured in ohms. Ohm''s Law (I = V / R) shows directly how a resistor sets the current for a given voltage, which is how engineers limit current to protect LEDs, transistors, and other sensitive parts. Choice A (store charge) describes a capacitor, which holds energy in an electric field. Choice C (AC to DC) describes a rectifier built from diodes. Choice D (step voltage) describes a transformer, which uses electromagnetic induction to change AC voltage levels.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-2'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'An inductor stores energy in a:', '["Chemical battery cell","Magnetic field","Electric field between plates","Mechanical flywheel"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An inductor is a coil of wire. Current through the coil creates a magnetic field, and energy is stored in that field. When current changes, the collapsing or rising field induces a back-EMF that opposes the change. Choice A (chemical cell) describes a battery, where energy is locked in chemical bonds. Choice C (electric field between plates) describes a capacitor, the inductor''s complement, which stores energy in an electric field across a dielectric. Choice D (mechanical flywheel) stores kinetic energy and is not an electrical component at all.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-3'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'Which device is used to step up or step down alternating current voltage levels in power distribution systems?', '["Rectifier","Transistor","Transformer","Capacitor"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A transformer uses electromagnetic induction between primary and secondary coils to step AC voltage up or down according to the turns ratio. Power grids step voltage up to hundreds of thousands of volts for low-loss transmission, then step it back down for delivery. Choice A (rectifier) converts AC to DC and does not change AC voltage levels. Choice B (transistor) amplifies or switches signals, mostly in DC and small-signal contexts. Choice D (capacitor) filters and stores charge but cannot transform voltage levels in a sustained AC distribution system.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-4'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'A light-emitting diode (LED) converts electrical energy primarily into:', '["Heat and mechanical energy equally","Light energy with minimal heat","Chemical energy stored in a capacitor","Alternating current from direct current"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LEDs convert electrical energy into light through electroluminescence in a semiconductor junction. They are far more efficient than incandescent bulbs, which waste most energy as heat. LEDs do not convert AC to DC or store chemical energy.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-5'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'A transistor can be used as an electronic switch because it can:', '["Block all current from flowing in either direction","Store charge and release it on command","Control a large output current with a small input (base) current","Convert AC to DC by allowing current in one direction only"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In a bipolar junction transistor, a small base current controls a much larger collector-to-emitter current. Zero base current leaves the transistor off (open switch); enough base current saturates it on (closed switch). That gain is what makes amplifiers and digital logic possible. Choice A describes an open circuit or insulator, not a switching device. Choice B describes a capacitor''s storage behavior, not a transistor''s gain. Choice D describes a diode''s one-way conduction. Transistors do more than diode action; they amplify.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-6'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 3, 'Which component would most likely be used to filter out high-frequency noise from a DC power supply while allowing the steady DC current to pass?', '["A resistor in series","A capacitor in parallel with the load","A diode in reverse bias","An additional battery"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capacitors pass AC (and AC noise) but block steady DC. Placing one in parallel with the load creates a low-impedance path for high-frequency noise to bypass the load while the desired DC current continues through. This is called decoupling or bypass capacitor usage.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-7'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'A transformer has 200 turns on its primary and 50 turns on its secondary. If the primary carries 1 ampere, what is the secondary current (assuming 100% efficiency)?', '["0.25 amperes","1 ampere","4 amperes","10 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An ideal transformer conserves power: Vp × Ip = Vs × Is. The turns ratio Np / Ns = 200 / 50 = 4, so this is a step-down transformer for voltage and a step-up for current. Is = Ip × (Np / Ns) = 1 × 4 = 4 A. Choice A (0.25 A) inverts the ratio (50 / 200), which gives the secondary voltage scale, not the current. Choice B (1 A) assumes current is unchanged, ignoring the inverse relationship. Choice D (10 A) uses an invented multiplier rather than the actual turns ratio.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-8'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'A Zener diode is connected in reverse bias in a circuit. Its primary application is to:', '["Block all current completely in that branch","Amplify voltage to a higher level","Regulate voltage by maintaining a constant voltage drop","Convert AC to DC in a rectifier bridge"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A Zener diode is engineered to break down at a precise reverse voltage and then hold that voltage steady across itself, even as current through it varies. That clamp action makes it ideal as a voltage reference or regulator. Choice A (block all current) describes a non-conducting open. Choice B (amplify voltage) describes a transistor or op-amp, not a passive diode. Choice D (AC-to-DC bridge) describes standard rectifier diodes; Zener diodes are used specifically for regulation, not for steering AC into DC pulses.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-9'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 4, 'Which effect describes how an inductor resists changes in current by generating a back-EMF (electromotive force)?', '["Capacitance","Self-inductance","Dielectric effect","Zener breakdown"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Self-inductance is the property by which a coil''s own changing current induces a voltage in itself, and that induced voltage opposes the change (Lenz''s Law applied to Faraday''s Law). It is measured in henries. Choice A (capacitance) opposes voltage changes by storing charge, not by generating back-EMF. Choice C (dielectric effect) describes how an insulator between capacitor plates increases capacitance, unrelated to current opposition. Choice D (Zener breakdown) describes a diode entering reverse conduction at a fixed voltage, not an inductor''s reaction to changing current.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-10'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 5, 'A full-wave bridge rectifier using four diodes converts AC to pulsating DC. Compared to a half-wave rectifier (one diode), the bridge rectifier:', '["Doubles the output voltage","Uses both halves of the AC cycle, producing smoother DC output at twice the frequency","Reverses the polarity of the DC output","Requires a transformer, whereas the half-wave rectifier does not"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A half-wave rectifier passes only one half-cycle of the AC input, wasting the other half. The bridge rectifier flips the negative half-cycle to positive using a diode arrangement, utilizing both halves. The output pulsates at twice the AC frequency and is smoother (easier to filter). Voltage is not doubled.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-11'),
  ('EI-CD-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 5, 'In a radio receiver circuit, an LC (inductor-capacitor) tank circuit is used primarily to:', '["Amplify received signals across all frequencies equally","Convert radio waves into alternating current","Select a specific resonant frequency and filter out others","Step down the antenna voltage before processing"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An LC tank circuit resonates at a specific frequency f = 1/(2π√LC), creating high impedance at that frequency and low impedance at others. Adjusting L or C (tuning) selects a desired station. The circuit is a tunable bandpass filter, not an amplifier or antenna converter.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.components-devices::EI-CD-B5-12'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-1', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which of the following materials is the best electrical insulator?', '["Aluminum","Graphite","Silver","Ceramic"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Ceramic has extremely high resistivity and is the standard insulator on overhead power-line standoffs and inside spark plugs. Choice A (aluminum) is a common conductor used in transmission lines and wiring. Choice B (graphite) is a form of carbon that conducts well enough to be used in motor brushes and electrodes. Choice C (silver) has the highest electrical conductivity of any metal at room temperature. Three of the four options conduct readily, which is the giveaway that the lone insulator is the answer.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-1'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-2', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Electrical wiring is typically covered in a plastic jacket primarily because plastic is:', '["A good conductor that improves current flow","Flexible, cheap, and an effective insulator","A semiconductor that limits dangerous voltage spikes","A material that cools the wire during use"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Plastic (PVC and similar polymers) insulates by preventing current from escaping the conductor and causing short circuits or shock hazards. Its flexibility and low cost make it ideal for wire jacketing. Plastic does not conduct or regulate electricity.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-2'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-3', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Gold is used in some high-quality electrical connectors despite its high cost because:', '["Gold has higher conductivity than any other metal","Gold is non-corrosive and maintains low contact resistance over time","Gold''s weight improves mechanical connection strength","Gold stores electrical charge better than copper"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gold does not oxidize in air, so gold-plated contacts keep a low, stable contact resistance for years. That matters more than raw conductivity in connector design, where surface chemistry dominates over time. Choice A (highest conductivity) is wrong; silver and copper both conduct better than gold. Choice C (weight) has no electrical relevance; mechanical force comes from spring contacts, not metal mass. Choice D (stores charge) confuses connector metal with a capacitor; conductors do not store charge in any useful sense in a connector.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-3'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-4', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'When the temperature of most metals increases, their electrical resistance:', '["Decreases because the electrons move faster","Stays the same regardless of temperature","Increases because atomic vibrations impede electron flow","Drops to zero because the metal becomes a superconductor"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In most metals, higher temperature means more vigorous atomic vibration, which causes more electron-lattice collisions. More collisions mean more resistance. That positive temperature coefficient is what lets PTC thermistors and incandescent filaments self-limit. Choice A (decreases) gets the direction wrong; faster electrons do not overcome the increased scattering. Choice B (unchanged) ignores temperature dependence that is well measured for copper, aluminum, and tungsten. Choice D (superconductivity) only occurs in specific materials cooled well below room temperature, not from ordinary heating.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-4'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-5', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'Silicon is classified as a semiconductor because its conductivity:', '["Is equal to that of copper at all temperatures","Can be precisely controlled by temperature, light, or the addition of impurities (doping)","Is zero until voltage exceeds a fixed threshold","Depends only on the current direction, like a diode"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Silicon''s conductivity is tunable. Doping with phosphorus adds free electrons (n-type), doping with boron adds holes (p-type), heating excites carriers across the band gap, and light injects photogenerated carriers. That control is the entire basis for transistors, diodes, solar cells, and integrated circuits. Choice A (equals copper) overstates pure silicon''s conductivity by many orders of magnitude. Choice C (fixed threshold) describes a Zener-like behavior, not the broad tunability of silicon. Choice D (direction-dependent) describes a diode junction, not bulk silicon material.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-5'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-6', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'The dielectric in a capacitor is an insulating material placed between the plates. Its primary purpose is to:', '["Allow electrons to tunnel between the plates and store charge","Increase the capacitance by allowing a stronger electric field to build up","Convert stored energy into heat for circuit protection","Conduct alternating current while blocking direct current"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The dielectric material has a high permittivity that allows the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage, increasing capacitance (C = ε × A/d). The insulator prevents electrons from crossing between plates; charge is stored in the electric field, not by electron transfer.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-6'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-7', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 3, 'An electrical wire''s resistance depends on which of the following properties?', '["Only the length of the wire","Length, cross-sectional area, and material resistivity","Cross-sectional area and the voltage applied","The current passing through it at any given moment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Wire resistance R = ρ × L / A, where ρ is material resistivity, L is length, and A is cross-sectional area. Longer, thinner wire of more resistive material has higher resistance. Applied voltage and current are results of resistance, not causes of it.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-7'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-8', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Two copper wires are identical in length. Wire A has twice the cross-sectional area of Wire B. How does the resistance of Wire A compare to Wire B?', '["Wire A has twice the resistance of Wire B","Wire A has the same resistance as Wire B","Wire A has half the resistance of Wire B","Wire A has four times the resistance of Wire B"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Resistance follows R = ρL / A. With L and ρ constant and A_A = 2 × A_B, R_A = ρL / (2 × A_B) = R_B / 2. Doubling cross-sectional area halves the resistance, because a thicker wire offers more parallel paths for electrons. Choice A (double) gets the direction backward; more area lowers resistance, not raises it. Choice B (same) ignores that area appears in the resistance formula at all. Choice D (four times) treats area as if it appeared squared in R = ρL/A, which it does not.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-8'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-9', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Which statement correctly explains why copper is preferred over iron for electrical wiring despite iron being more abundant?', '["Copper has a lower melting point, making it easier to form into wire","Copper has much lower resistivity than iron, meaning less energy is lost as heat","Copper is magnetic, which helps carry alternating current","Iron corrodes rapidly in air, and copper does not oxidize at all"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Copper''s resistivity (~1.68 μΩ·cm) is about six times lower than iron''s (~10 μΩ·cm), so copper wire wastes far less energy as heat. This efficiency advantage outweighs the cost difference. Copper does oxidize slightly but forms a stable, low-resistance patina; iron rusts severely.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-9'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-10', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 5, 'A 10-meter copper wire has a resistance of 0.2 ohms. If the wire is replaced with a 20-meter wire of the same material and the same cross-sectional area, what is the new resistance?', '["0.1 ohms","0.2 ohms","0.4 ohms","0.8 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'R = ρL / A is linear in length. Doubling L from 10 m to 20 m while holding A and material constant doubles the resistance: 2 × 0.2 = 0.4 Ω. Choice A (0.1 Ω) halves resistance, which would happen if length were halved instead of doubled. Choice B (0.2 Ω) leaves resistance unchanged, ignoring the length dependence entirely. Choice D (0.8 Ω) quadruples resistance, treating length as if it appeared squared in the formula, when in fact only the cross-section can change resistance non-linearly through area.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-10'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-11', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 5, 'N-type semiconductor material is created by doping silicon with an element that has more valence electrons than silicon. Which of the following dopants creates an n-type semiconductor?', '["Boron (3 valence electrons)","Aluminum (3 valence electrons)","Phosphorus (5 valence electrons)","Carbon (4 valence electrons)"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Silicon has 4 valence electrons. Phosphorus has 5, so each phosphorus atom contributes one extra electron not needed for covalent bonding. That free electron becomes a mobile negative charge carrier, producing n-type silicon. Choice A (boron, 3 valence) creates p-type silicon by introducing holes. Choice B (aluminum, 3 valence) also creates p-type material. Choice D (carbon, 4 valence) matches silicon''s valence count exactly, so it contributes neither extra electrons nor holes and would not produce useful doping for n-type or p-type behavior.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-11'),
  ('EI-CI-B5-12', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 4, 'Which of the following most accurately describes why distilled water is a poor conductor while seawater conducts electricity well?', '["Seawater contains more hydrogen, which improves conductivity","Distilled water has no dissolved ions, while seawater''s dissolved salts provide free ions that carry charge","Distilled water molecules resist current because of their polarity","The pressure of the ocean compresses seawater, increasing conductivity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Liquid conduction depends on free charge carriers. Distilled water has almost no dissolved ions, so it has very few mobile charges and conducts poorly. Seawater holds dissolved NaCl, MgCl₂, and other salts that dissociate into Na⁺, Cl⁻, and Mg²⁺ ions, which carry charge freely. Choice A (more hydrogen) is wrong; both waters share the same H₂O molecules. Choice C blames water''s polarity, but polarity alone does not block conduction. Choice D invokes pressure, which has a negligible effect on conductivity compared with ion concentration.', true, 'trusted', 'ei.conductors-insulators::EI-CI-B5-12'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which hand tool is used to tighten or loosen nuts and bolts and has an opening that can be adjusted to fit different fastener sizes?', '["Adjustable wrench","Needle-nose pliers","Cold chisel","Ball-peen hammer"]'::jsonb, 0, 'An adjustable wrench, often called a crescent wrench, has a thumbwheel that slides one jaw in and out so a single tool fits a range of hex nuts and bolts. Needle-nose pliers are for gripping small wires and parts in tight spots and will round the corners of any fastener you try to drive with them. A cold chisel is a striking tool for cutting metal, not for fasteners. A ball-peen hammer is used to shape metal and strike punches. Only the adjustable wrench is designed to set its opening to a fastener size.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-1'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'A mechanic needs to grip a round pipe firmly while cutting threads onto it. Which tool is designed specifically to hold cylindrical workpieces without slipping?', '["Slip-joint pliers","Pipe wrench","Box-end wrench","Offset screwdriver"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A pipe wrench has hardened, toothed jaws set at an angle so that pulling on the handle drives the teeth deeper into the round pipe, locking the grip tighter the harder you pull. Slip-joint pliers can hold a pipe but the jaws will rotate around the work under any real torque. A box-end wrench is shaped to wrap a six- or twelve-point hex fastener and will not grip a smooth cylinder at all. An offset screwdriver is for turning screws in cramped spots. Only the pipe wrench is built for round stock.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-2'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A torque wrench is used instead of a standard socket wrench when:', '["you need to reach fasteners in deep recesses","tightening fasteners to a precise torque specification is required","the fastener head is stripped and will not grip","you are working in a tight space and need a ratcheting motion"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A torque wrench has a calibrated mechanism that signals or limits at a preset value, letting you tighten a fastener to the exact specification a manufacturer calls out for head bolts, lug nuts, or connecting rods. Reaching deep recesses is what a socket extension solves, not a torque wrench. A stripped fastener head needs an extractor or vise grips, not torque measurement. Tight-space ratcheting is offered by any ratchet handle, including non-torque ones. The defining feature is the calibrated measurement, not the reach or the ratcheting.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-3'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'What is the primary purpose of a center punch when working with metal?', '["To scribe a straight line across the workpiece","To mark a starting point so a drill bit does not wander","To remove burrs from a drilled hole","To cut a hole in sheet metal without a drill"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A center punch is struck with a hammer to dimple the metal at the spot where a hole will be drilled, and that dimple cups the drill point so the bit starts where you intended instead of wandering across the surface. Scribing a straight line is the job of a scriber or a square. Removing burrs from a drilled hole is what a deburring tool or countersink does. Cutting a hole in sheet metal without a drill calls for a hole punch or knockout, not a center punch. Center punches mark, they do not cut or scribe.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-4'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A technician selects a drill bit with a twist-style cutting flute and a 118-degree included angle tip. This bit is best suited for drilling:', '["concrete and masonry","general-purpose holes in steel or aluminum","glass and ceramic tile","large-diameter holes in wood only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A standard high-speed steel twist bit with a 118-degree tip is the everyday bit for drilling steel, aluminum, and brass, and it is what comes in a typical mechanic''s index. Concrete and masonry require a carbide-tipped masonry bit driven by a hammer drill, because HSS cannot cut stone. Glass and ceramic tile need a spear-point or diamond bit and very slow speed to avoid cracking. Wood-only large-diameter holes are the territory of spade bits, Forstner bits, or hole saws. The 118-degree point geometry is the giveaway for general metal work.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-5'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A vise-grip (locking pliers) differs from standard slip-joint pliers in that a vise-grip:', '["can be used as a wrench on hex fasteners only","locks onto a workpiece and maintains clamping force without the user squeezing","is used exclusively for cutting wire","adjusts automatically to the size of the fastener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Locking pliers, often called Vise-Grips, use an over-center toggle linkage that snaps the jaws shut and holds them there without any hand pressure, freeing both of your hands and applying steady clamping force. Slip-joint pliers and channel locks need a constant squeeze to hold anything. The pliers are not limited to hex fasteners and can grip almost any shape. Wire cutting is a feature of dedicated cutters or a small notch on some pliers, not the defining feature here. They do not auto-adjust to fastener size; the user sets the jaw with a thumbscrew.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-6'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A combination square is primarily used to:', '["apply torque to hex fasteners in tight spaces","measure and mark 90-degree and 45-degree angles on a workpiece","hold a workpiece in place during cutting","thread bolts onto nuts in hard-to-reach locations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A combination square consists of a rule and a sliding head that provides both 90-degree and 45-degree reference angles. It is used to mark cut lines, check squareness, and verify miters. It does not apply torque or hold workpieces.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-7'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 3, 'A snap-ring pliers set includes two types of tips. One type spreads a ring outward to remove an external snap ring; the other type squeezes a ring inward to remove an internal snap ring. Why must the correct type be used?', '["Using the wrong type will damage the pliers'' handles","Using the wrong type moves the ring in the wrong direction and can launch it unexpectedly or distort it","Both types are interchangeable; choice depends only on ring size","The wrong type will strip the threading on the fastener"]'::jsonb, 1, 'External snap rings are compressed to fit into a shaft groove; internal rings are expanded to fit inside a bore groove. Using expanding pliers on an external ring, or compressing pliers on an internal ring, pushes the ring the wrong way, risking sudden release and possible injury or ring damage.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-8'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'A mechanic describes a tool as having a T-shaped handle, with a square drive that accepts interchangeable sockets, and a ratcheting pawl that allows rotation in one direction without removing the tool from the fastener. What tool is being described?', '["Breaker bar","Speed handle","Ratchet wrench","Flex-head torque wrench"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A ratchet wrench has a reversible ratcheting mechanism that lets the user turn the handle back without moving the fastener, then apply torque again on the next forward stroke. A breaker bar provides high torque but does not ratchet; a speed handle spins freely but also lacks a ratchet pawl.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-9'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'When measuring a shaft''s outside diameter, a technician reads a micrometer thimble scale and finds the sleeve reading is 0.350 inches and the thimble adds 0.012 inches. What is the total measured diameter?', '["0.338 inches","0.350 inches","0.362 inches","0.412 inches"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A micrometer reading combines the barrel (sleeve) measurement and the thimble graduation. Total = 0.350 + 0.012 = 0.362 inches. Subtracting instead of adding (0.350 − 0.012 = 0.338) is a common error; the thimble always adds to the sleeve reading.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-10'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 4, 'A technician wants to cut an external thread onto a steel rod so a nut can be threaded onto it. Which hand tool accomplishes this?', '["Tap","Die","Reamer","Broach"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A die cuts external threads onto a rod or bolt. A tap cuts internal threads inside a hole (to accept a bolt). A reamer smooths and sizes a drilled hole to a precise diameter but does not cut threads.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-11'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 5, 'A star-pattern torque sequence is specified when installing a cylinder head. Why is this sequence used instead of tightening bolts in order from one end to the other?', '["To finish faster by tightening the center bolts last","To distribute clamping load evenly and prevent the gasket from warping or sealing unevenly","Because cylinder head bolts are left-hand threaded on alternating positions","To allow the bolts to be re-tightened after the engine warms up"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A star or criss-cross pattern pulls the cylinder head down against the gasket from the center outward in stepped increments, so clamping load builds evenly across every bolt and the gasket compresses uniformly. Tightening end-to-end pulls one side down first, which can warp the head or pinch the gasket and leak. Finishing faster is not the point of the sequence. Head bolts are not left-hand threaded on alternating positions. Retorquing after warm-up is required on some older engines but is a separate step, not the reason for the pattern itself.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-12'),
  ('AS-HT-B6-13', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 5, 'A feeler gauge (thickness gauge) is used to check the valve clearance in an engine. The technician inserts two blades: a 0.006-inch blade slides with slight drag; a 0.007-inch blade will not enter the gap. What does this tell the technician?', '["The clearance is exactly 0.006 inches","The clearance is between 0.006 and 0.007 inches","The clearance is less than 0.006 inches","The clearance is greater than 0.007 inches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A feeler gauge works by go/no-go logic. The 0.006-inch blade fits (gap is at least 0.006 in), but the 0.007-inch blade does not fit (gap is less than 0.007 in). Therefore the clearance lies between 0.006 and 0.007 inches.', true, 'trusted', 'as.hand-tools::AS-HT-B6-13'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'In a four-stroke gasoline engine, which stroke draws the air-fuel mixture into the cylinder?', '["Compression stroke","Power stroke","Intake stroke","Exhaust stroke"]'::jsonb, 2, 'On the intake stroke, the piston travels down the cylinder while the intake valve is open, and the resulting vacuum pulls the air-fuel charge into the combustion chamber. The compression stroke comes next, with both valves closed and the piston moving up to squeeze that charge. The power stroke is when the spark fires and the burning mixture drives the piston back down. The exhaust stroke is the piston moving up with the exhaust valve open to push spent gases out. The order is intake, compression, power, exhaust.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-1'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'The purpose of a vehicle''s clutch in a manual transmission is to:', '["regulate engine idle speed","temporarily disconnect the engine from the transmission to allow gear changes","convert the alternator''s output to DC current","control the flow of coolant to the engine block"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pressing the clutch pedal pulls the pressure plate away from the friction disc, breaking the link between the engine flywheel and the transmission input shaft so you can move the gear lever without grinding gears against engine speed. Engine idle speed is held by the idle air control or throttle body, not by the clutch. Alternator output is rectified by diodes inside the alternator itself, never by the drivetrain. Coolant flow is gated by the thermostat. Each wrong answer points at a different system unrelated to torque interruption.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-2'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'What is the function of a vehicle''s differential?', '["It filters fuel before it reaches the injectors","It allows the drive wheels to rotate at different speeds when turning","It regulates the voltage output of the charging system","It compresses refrigerant in the air conditioning system"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When a car rounds a corner, the outer drive wheel travels a longer arc than the inner wheel and has to spin faster, and the differential''s bevel gears let the two axles turn at different rates while still splitting engine torque between them. Filtering fuel is the fuel filter''s job. Regulating charging voltage is done by the voltage regulator inside the alternator. Compressing refrigerant is the air-conditioning compressor''s role. The differential lives in the drive axle, not in the fuel, charging, or HVAC systems.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-3'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'A vehicle''s battery provides current to start the engine. Once the engine is running, which component keeps the battery charged?', '["Starter motor","Distributor","Alternator","Voltage regulator only"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Once the engine is running, the alternator is belt-driven off the crankshaft and produces the current that recharges the battery and runs every electrical load on the car. The starter motor only spins while the key is in the start position to crank the engine over; after that it disengages. The distributor, on engines that have one, routes spark to plugs and does not generate current. The voltage regulator alone controls how much output the alternator makes, but it does not produce current by itself. The alternator is the generator in this system.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-4'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'Disc brakes use calipers and rotors. When the brake pedal is pressed, what converts pedal force into hydraulic pressure that actuates the calipers?', '["The brake booster","The master cylinder","The proportioning valve","The ABS modulator"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The master cylinder is a hydraulic pump tied directly to the brake pedal pushrod. When you press the pedal, a piston inside pushes brake fluid through the steel lines, and that pressure pushes the caliper pistons out against the pads. The brake booster only multiplies the foot force you put into the pedal using engine vacuum; it does not generate hydraulic pressure on its own. The proportioning valve balances front-to-rear pressure, downstream of the master cylinder. The ABS modulator pulses the brakes during a skid but does not create the base pressure.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-5'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'Engine oil pressure drops to near zero while the engine is running at highway speed. The FIRST action should be to:', '["Continue driving to the nearest service station","Shut off the engine immediately to prevent catastrophic bearing damage","Add oil while the engine is running","Rev the engine to increase oil pump speed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Engine oil pressure is what keeps a film of oil between the crankshaft and the bearing surfaces. If pressure drops to near zero, the bearings run dry and metal-on-metal contact spins or seizes them in seconds. Shutting the engine off immediately is the only way to save the engine. Driving on to the next station finishes the damage. Adding oil to a running engine is dangerous near hot moving parts and may not even solve the problem if the issue is the pump or a leak. Revving makes the wear faster, not slower.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-6'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 3, 'An automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of a clutch. The torque converter:', '["mechanically locks the engine to the transmission at all times","uses hydraulic fluid to transfer and multiply torque between engine and transmission","shifts gears by means of a centrifugal governor","replaces the differential in front-wheel-drive vehicles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A torque converter is a sealed fluid coupling. Engine torque spins a pump impeller that throws transmission fluid against a turbine connected to the transmission input shaft, and a stator in the middle redirects fluid flow to multiply torque at low speeds. It does not lock the engine to the transmission solidly except when an internal lockup clutch engages at cruise. Centrifugal governors selected shift points on old automatics but do not transfer torque. The differential is a separate gearset farther down the drivetrain. The torque converter replaces the clutch with fluid, not gears.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-7'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A vehicle''s temperature gauge climbs into the red zone. Steam is seen coming from under the hood. The MOST likely cause is:', '["A low transmission fluid level","A burst radiator hose or failed thermostat causing coolant loss","An overcharged battery","A stuck-open EGR valve"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Steam and a rising temperature gauge together indicate coolant is escaping and the engine is no longer being cooled. The most common culprits are a burst hose, blown head gasket, or failed thermostat that traps coolant in the block. Low transmission fluid causes shifting problems, not overheating steam.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-8'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A fuel-injected engine uses an oxygen sensor (O2 sensor) in the exhaust stream. The engine control module (ECM) uses the O2 sensor signal to:', '["determine ignition timing advance based on knock","adjust the fuel injector pulse width to maintain the proper air-fuel ratio","regulate alternator output voltage","control cooling fan speed based on engine temperature"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The oxygen sensor reads how much unburned oxygen is left in the exhaust, which tells the ECM whether the mixture entering the cylinders was rich or lean. The ECM then trims injector pulse width up or down on the next cycle to hold the air-fuel ratio near 14.7 to 1 for catalyst efficiency. Knock-based timing advance comes from the knock sensor, not the O2 sensor. Alternator voltage is governed by the voltage regulator. Cooling fan speed is driven by coolant temperature sensor input. Each wrong answer pairs a different sensor with its own control loop.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-9'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 4, 'A front-wheel-drive vehicle clicks loudly when turning at low speed but is quiet when driving straight. The most likely cause is:', '["A worn constant-velocity (CV) joint","Low power-steering fluid","A cracked brake rotor","A loose exhaust heat shield"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A constant-velocity joint lets a front drive axle send power through the steering angle as the wheel turns and the suspension moves. When the rubber boot tears, grease escapes, dirt gets in, and the joint''s internal balls and races wear, producing a sharp clicking that is loudest on tight, slow turns and quiet when going straight. Low power steering fluid causes a whining or moaning during steering effort, not a click. A cracked brake rotor produces a pulse or grind under braking, not on turns. A loose heat shield rattles with engine RPM, regardless of steering input.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-10'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 5, 'A technician notices that the engine temperature rises quickly to normal then a short time later climbs well above normal, cools slightly, then rises again in a repeating cycle. The MOST likely cause is:', '["A clogged catalytic converter","A thermostat that is stuck partially open, cycling the engine through warm-cool oscillations","A blown head gasket allowing combustion gases into the cooling system","A faulty coolant temperature sensor sending erratic signals to the ECM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A blown head gasket allows combustion gases (under high pressure) to enter the cooling system. These gases displace coolant, form pockets that reduce cooling efficiency, and can cause the temperature to cycle as coolant is intermittently lost and returned. A stuck thermostat causes persistent overheating or chronic under-temperature, not cycling. A faulty sensor changes gauge readings but not actual temperature.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-11'),
  ('AS-VS-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 5, 'An engine knocks heavily under load but the knock nearly disappears at idle. This is most consistent with:', '["A cracked flywheel","Pre-ignition (detonation) caused by low-octane fuel or advanced timing","A broken engine mount","An air leak in the intake manifold"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Detonation, also called spark knock or ping, happens when cylinder pressure and heat are high enough that part of the air-fuel charge ignites on its own before the spark plug fires, slamming a shock wave into the piston. Heavy load is exactly when pressure and temperature peak, which is why the knock fades at idle. Common causes are gasoline with octane below what the engine needs, carbon deposits glowing hot in the chamber, or timing advanced too far. A cracked flywheel makes a noise tied to RPM, not load. A broken motor mount thumps on shifts. An intake leak shows up as a lean miss and rough idle, the opposite load pattern.', true, 'trusted', 'as.vehicle-systems::AS-VS-B6-12'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'When working in a shop where gasoline or solvent vapors may be present, adequate ventilation is required primarily to:', '["keep tools at the correct operating temperature","prevent accumulation of flammable vapors that could ignite","ensure that paint dries faster","reduce humidity that causes rust on tools"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gasoline and most solvent vapors are denser than air, so they pool at floor level in a closed shop and can build up to a concentration that ignites from a spark, a pilot light, or a piece of running equipment. Moving air through the space keeps the concentration below the lower explosive limit. Tool operating temperature is not driven by shop ventilation. Paint drying is a side benefit on some jobs but not the safety reason for the rule. Rust prevention is about humidity control, which is a different problem with a different solution. Ventilation is fundamentally about explosion and fire prevention.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-1'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'A small Class B fire breaks out in the shop. Class B fires involve flammable liquids such as gasoline or oil. Which type of extinguisher is appropriate?', '["Water extinguisher","Class A dry extinguisher","CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher rated for Class B","Any available extinguisher regardless of rating"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Class B fires involve flammable liquids like gasoline, oil, and solvents, and the right answer is a CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher rated for Class B. CO2 smothers the fire by displacing oxygen, and dry chemical interrupts the chemical chain reaction. Water spreads burning liquid because the fuel floats on top of the water and rides the splash. A Class A only extinguisher, designed for wood and paper, will not safely handle a fuel fire. Grabbing any extinguisher regardless of rating risks making the situation worse. Match the extinguisher class to the fuel class.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-2'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'Lockout/tagout (LOTO) procedures are required before performing maintenance on a machine. The PRIMARY purpose of LOTO is to:', '["document the maintenance procedure for quality records","prevent the machine from being energized while a worker is inside or working on it","notify supervisors that the equipment is being serviced","ensure tools are returned to their correct storage locations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lockout/tagout puts a physical lock on the energy isolation point, a breaker, valve, or disconnect, so the equipment cannot be powered up while a worker has hands or body inside it. The lock and tag stay there until the worker who applied them removes them. Documenting maintenance is a paperwork goal, not a safety control. Notifying supervisors is communication, not energy isolation. Returning tools to storage is housekeeping. Only physical lockout actually prevents the startup that injures or kills the technician.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-3'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A shop worker spills a small amount of motor oil on the floor. The safest IMMEDIATE action is to:', '["Mark the spill with a cone and clean it up at the end of the shift","Spread sawdust or absorbent material and clean it up promptly","Wipe it with a rag and place the rag in an open trash can","Pour water over the spill to dilute it"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An oil puddle is a slip hazard the instant it hits the floor, so the safest move is to spread oil-absorbent material or sawdust, sweep it up, and dispose of it properly right away. Marking the spill with a cone and waiting until end of shift leaves a fall hazard live for hours. Wiping with a rag and tossing it in an open trash can risks spontaneous combustion as the oil oxidizes inside a pile of paper trash. Pouring water spreads the oil and does not remove it, and the floor stays slick. Immediate absorbent cleanup is the standard.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-4'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'A worker is grinding metal and is producing sparks and metal fragments. Besides eye protection, what additional PPE should be worn?', '["Latex examination gloves and a dust mask","Face shield over safety glasses, leather gloves, and hearing protection","Safety glasses only, sparks are not hazardous at short range","Chemical-splash goggles and a rubber apron"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Grinding throws hot sparks, sharp metal fragments, and abrasive grit, and the wheel screams loud enough to damage hearing on a long job, so the worker needs a face shield over safety glasses for the face, leather gloves for hot edges, and hearing protection for the noise. Latex exam gloves and a paper dust mask offer no impact, heat, or noise protection. Safety glasses alone leave the rest of the face exposed to flying debris and slag. Chemical-splash goggles and a rubber apron are dressed for solvent or acid work, not for incandescent sparks that would burn through rubber.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-5'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'Before lifting a vehicle with a floor jack to work underneath it, you MUST also:', '["Remove the wheels first to reduce vehicle weight","Place jack stands under the vehicle''s frame or pinch-weld points to support it","Set the parking brake and leave the floor jack as the only support","Run the engine for 10 minutes to warm the oil before working"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A hydraulic floor jack lifts the vehicle, but a seal can leak or a valve can release, and the jack can drop. Jack stands are rigid steel supports that mechanically hold the load while you work, so you place them under the frame rails or pinch welds before crawling under. Removing the wheels does not address the falling-vehicle hazard. The parking brake on its own, with the jack as sole support, ignores the failure mode that kills people. Warming up the oil is unrelated to whether the car is safely supported. Always pair the jack with stands before going underneath.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-6'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 3, 'Oily rags used for wiping up solvent or paint should be stored in a:', '["Cardboard box kept away from windows","Sealed metal container approved for flammable waste","Plastic bin lined with a trash bag","Open drum to allow vapors to escape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Oils and many solvents react slowly with oxygen and give off heat, and rags piled together insulate that heat until they reach the ignition point on their own, a process called spontaneous combustion. A sealed metal can starves any fire of oxygen and contains the heat away from the rest of the shop. Cardboard burns through in minutes once a fire starts inside it. Plastic bins soften and melt and do not contain a fire at all. An open drum lets vapors escape into the air and feeds any spark that finds them. Metal, sealed, and approved is the standard.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-7'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'A worker is about to use a bench grinder and notices that the grinding wheel has a small crack running from the center outward. The correct action is to:', '["Run it at low speed only to avoid spreading the crack","Replace the wheel immediately; a cracked wheel can shatter at high RPM","Apply epoxy to the crack and allow it to cure before use","Use the wheel on the side face rather than the rim to avoid the crack"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A cracked abrasive wheel can explode at operating RPM, sending fragments outward with great force. Any crack, chip, or damage is grounds for immediate replacement. Running it at lower speed or using the side face does not eliminate the risk of sudden catastrophic failure.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-8'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'Which class of fire involves energized electrical equipment?', '["Class A","Class B","Class C","Class D"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Class C fires involve energized electrical equipment such as panels, motors, or wiring, and the rule is to use a non-conductive extinguisher like CO2 or dry chemical so you do not get shocked through the stream. Class A is ordinary combustibles like wood, paper, and cloth. Class B is flammable liquids such as gasoline, oil, and solvents. Class D is combustible metals like magnesium and sodium. Memorizing the letter-to-fuel mapping is the only way to choose the right extinguisher quickly under stress.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-9'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 4, 'Before entering a large tank or enclosed space for maintenance work, a technician should first:', '["Enter quickly and complete the task before vapors build up","Test the atmosphere for oxygen level and toxic or flammable vapors","Bring a lit lamp inside to check for visibility","Seal any ventilation openings to keep temperature stable"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A tank or other confined space can hold an oxygen-deficient atmosphere, leftover toxic vapors, or flammable residues, and you cannot see or smell most of those hazards. A calibrated four-gas meter has to test oxygen, combustibles, and toxic gases before anyone goes in. Entering quickly to beat the buildup ignores that the hazardous atmosphere may already be there. A lit lamp inside an unknown atmosphere is an ignition source. Sealing ventilation makes the atmosphere worse, not safer. Test, ventilate, and only then enter, with a permit.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-10'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 5, 'A shop receives a drum of a new cleaning solvent. The Safety Data Sheet (SDS) lists an IDLH (Immediately Dangerous to Life and Health) concentration of 100 ppm. This value means that:', '["100 ppm is the safe, permissible exposure limit for an 8-hour shift","at 100 ppm, a worker without a respirator faces conditions from which escape may be impaired or irreversible harm may occur","100 ppm is the concentration at which the solvent becomes flammable","100 ppm must be measured monthly to comply with OSHA standards"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IDLH is the concentration at which a worker who loses respiratory protection has roughly thirty minutes to get out before symptoms keep them from escaping or before irreversible health damage sets in. It is an emergency-planning value used to pick respirator type for entry or rescue work. The permissible exposure limit, PEL, is the much lower routine-exposure ceiling for an eight-hour shift, so the safe-shift answer is wrong. IDLH says nothing directly about flammability, which is set by the lower explosive limit. The monthly-monitoring rule is invented; OSHA monitoring frequency depends on the specific substance.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-11'),
  ('AS-SS-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 5, 'A shop policy requires that all rotating machinery guards be in place before the machine is started. A supervisor removes a guard temporarily for an adjustment and then leaves without replacing it. The correct action for the next technician who needs to use the machine is to:', '["Use the machine quickly and then replace the guard afterward","Report the missing guard and refuse to operate the machine until the guard is reinstalled","Operate the machine while holding the guard in place manually","Tape cardboard over the exposed area as a temporary barrier"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Machine guards keep hands and clothing out of rotating gears, belts, and pinch points, and they are a primary engineering control required before the machine runs. The right move is to stop, report the missing guard, and refuse to operate until it is replaced. Running it briefly without the guard exposes the worker for exactly the time the hazard is loose. Holding the guard by hand puts the holding hand inside the danger zone. Cardboard taped over the opening is not a guard, will not stop a rotating part, and can be pulled in. The line is clear: no guard, no operation.', true, 'trusted', 'as.shop-safety::AS-SS-B6-12'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-1', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'Coolant reservoir level is checked and found to be below the MIN mark while the engine is cold. What is the correct action?', '["Add the correct antifreeze-water mixture to bring the level to the MIN-MAX range","Drain and replace all coolant regardless of level","Add straight water only so coolant does not become too concentrated","The reservoir level is irrelevant; check only the radiator cap"]'::jsonb, 0, 'On a modern engine the overflow reservoir is where you check and add coolant when the engine is cold, and the right top-up is the manufacturer-specified antifreeze and water mix, typically a 50/50 blend, to keep both freeze and boil protection intact. Draining and replacing all the coolant is a full service, not a level correction. Adding straight water dilutes the antifreeze and weakens corrosion inhibitors. The radiator cap is not a service point for level on systems built around a reservoir, and opening a hot cap is a burn risk anyway. Add the correct mix, to the correct mark, when cold.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-1'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-2', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'The low-oil pressure warning light illuminates while idling at a stoplight. The engine sounds normal. The driver should FIRST:', '["Rev the engine to 3,000 RPM to build oil pressure","Turn off the engine, check the oil level, and add oil if needed before restarting","Continue driving, oil pressure lights are often faulty","Add transmission fluid to the engine to restore pressure quickly"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A low oil pressure warning at idle can mean the level is genuinely low, the pump or bearings are failing, or the sensor itself is bad, and you cannot tell which one without stopping. Shutting the engine off protects the bearings from oil starvation, then a dipstick check shows whether oil is needed before restart. Revving the engine pushes more oil only at the cost of more wear if pressure really is gone. Driving on because the light might be faulty is exactly the gamble that destroys engines. Transmission fluid is not engine oil and will damage seals and clutches that do not belong in an engine.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-2'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-3', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A technician checks the brake fluid and finds it is dark brown and appears contaminated. The correct service action is to:', '["Top off with fresh fluid to dilute the contamination","Flush the brake system and fill with fresh fluid of the correct DOT specification","Add a brake fluid conditioner and continue use","No action needed, brake fluid darkens naturally and remains effective"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Brake fluid is hygroscopic, meaning it pulls moisture out of the air over time, and that water lowers the boiling point and corrodes calipers, lines, and the master cylinder from the inside. Dark brown fluid is contaminated and needs to be flushed completely from each wheel and refilled with fresh fluid matching the vehicle''s DOT specification. Topping off only mixes new fluid with bad and leaves the contamination in place. Brake fluid conditioners are not a recognized service for this and cannot undo moisture absorption. The claim that dark fluid is normal and effective is simply wrong; brake fluid should be light amber.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-3'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-4', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A driver notices the engine hesitates and stumbles when accelerating from a stop. A mechanic inspects and finds the air filter is completely clogged with dirt. Why would a clogged air filter cause this symptom?', '["The filter restricts airflow, creating an excessively rich fuel mixture that makes the engine stumble under load","The filter blocks cooling airflow to the radiator","A clogged filter increases intake air temperature, advancing ignition timing","The filter restricts oil return to the crankcase"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The engine needs a precise air-fuel ratio. A severely clogged air filter restricts incoming air, causing the mixture to become too rich (too much fuel relative to air). Under load the engine stumbles because combustion is incomplete. At idle, the effect may be minor, but under acceleration it becomes pronounced.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-4'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-5', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'A technician replaces a worn serpentine belt. After installation, the belt squeals briefly when the engine is cold but goes away when warmed. The MOST likely cause is:', '["The replacement belt is too long","Slight slipping on a pulley due to condensation or belt material until the belt seats fully","The tensioner pulley bearing has failed","A mismatch in belt rib count"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Brief cold squealing from a new belt is common as the rubber conforms to pulley grooves and surface moisture evaporates. If squealing persists or occurs warm, it indicates a worn tensioner, glazed pulley, or incorrect belt. Rib-count mismatches produce constant noise and would cause the belt to mistrack.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-5'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-6', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'When replacing brake pads on a disc brake vehicle, a technician compresses the caliper piston back into the caliper bore. Before doing so, what precaution should be taken?', '["Open the bleeder screw to release pressure while compressing the piston","Remove the master cylinder reservoir cap and siphon out some fluid to prevent overflow as the piston is pushed back","Disconnect the ABS module to prevent error codes","Add brake fluid to the reservoir to prevent air from entering"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pushing the caliper piston back forces fluid backward into the master cylinder reservoir. If the reservoir is full, this fluid has nowhere to go and will overflow, potentially damaging painted surfaces or rubber seals. Removing the reservoir cap and siphoning excess fluid first prevents overflow. (The bleeder screw method also works but requires catching old fluid separately.)', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-6'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-7', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A spark plug removed from a cylinder has a wet, oily black deposit coating the ceramic insulator and electrodes. This most likely indicates:', '["The engine is running too lean","Oil is entering the combustion chamber due to worn piston rings or valve seals","The ignition timing is excessively advanced","The coolant system is leaking into the cylinder"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A wet, oily, black coating on the plug means liquid oil is reaching the combustion chamber, either past worn piston rings from below or past failed valve stem seals from above, and it is being burned along with the fuel. A lean mixture, with too little fuel, leaves a chalky white or very light gray deposit because there is no extra fuel to leave soot. Excessively advanced ignition timing produces detonation symptoms and may erode the electrode, not coat it with oil. A coolant leak into the cylinder bakes onto the plug as a hard white crust, sometimes with a sweet smell, not a wet black film.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-7'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-8', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A vehicle''s power steering pump whines loudly when the steering wheel is turned to full lock in either direction. The fluid level is within the normal range. The MOST likely cause is:', '["Overfilled power steering reservoir","Normal cavitation at the pressure limit, acceptable as long as not held at full lock for extended time","A failing electric power steering motor","A clogged hydraulic return line causing system overpressure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Hydraulic power steering systems reach their maximum pressure limit at full steering lock. The pump continues to build pressure against a closed circuit, causing fluid to cavitate (form vapor bubbles) and produce a whining or moaning sound. This is normal for short periods; holding full lock for extended time can damage the pump. If it whines at all steering positions, that indicates a different problem.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-8'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-9', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 4, 'A visual inspection of a vehicle''s exhaust smoke reveals continuous white smoke from a cold engine that does NOT clear after warm-up. This most likely indicates:', '["Normal condensation burning off","A rich fuel mixture from a faulty injector","Coolant entering the combustion chamber through a failed head gasket","Burning engine oil due to a cracked piston"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Light white smoke on cold startup that clears quickly is normal condensation. Persistent white smoke after warm-up that has a sweet smell and does not dissipate strongly indicates coolant (antifreeze) burning in the cylinders, a hallmark of a blown head gasket or cracked block. Oil smoke tends to be blue-gray with an acrid odor.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-9'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-10', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 5, 'A technician performs a cylinder compression test and finds cylinder 3 has 80 psi while all others read 165 psi. Adding a small amount of oil to cylinder 3 through the spark plug hole raises its compression to 150 psi. What does this indicate?', '["A bent intake valve in cylinder 3","Worn piston rings in cylinder 3, the oil temporarily seals the gap","A cracked cylinder wall in cylinder 3","A leaking head gasket between cylinders 3 and 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This is the wet compression test. Adding oil temporarily seals the ring-to-cylinder-wall gap. If compression rises significantly when oil is added, the low reading is caused by ring wear or blow-by, not by a valve or gasket problem. A valve issue would not improve with oil because valves seal above the rings.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-10'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-11', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 5, 'After replacing a vehicle''s oxygen sensor, the technician clears the fault code and performs a drive cycle, but the check-engine light returns with the same code. The NEXT diagnostic step is to:', '["Replace the oxygen sensor again with a higher-grade part","Check wiring harness continuity and inspect for exhaust leaks upstream of the sensor","Replace the catalytic converter, as it is the usual cause of sensor codes","Reprogram the ECM with updated software"]'::jsonb, 1, 'If a new sensor triggers the same code, the sensor is likely not the root cause. The technician should inspect the wiring harness for shorts, opens, or damaged connectors, and check for exhaust leaks upstream that can introduce false oxygen readings. Replacing parts without checking the circuit is inefficient and costly.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-11'),
  ('AS-MR-B6-12', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 3, 'A technician finds the battery terminals heavily corroded with a white-blue crusty buildup. After cleaning the terminals, what is the correct follow-up action?', '["Replace the battery immediately regardless of its test results","Apply a battery terminal protector spray or grease to prevent future corrosion","Coat the terminals with motor oil for corrosion protection","Tighten the terminal clamps as hard as possible to ensure good contact"]'::jsonb, 1, 'After cleaning corrosion from battery terminals, a protective spray (petroleum-based terminal spray or anti-corrosion felt pads) applied to the terminals significantly reduces the rate of future corrosion by sealing the metal from battery acid vapors. Motor oil is not intended for this purpose and can attract dirt.', true, 'trusted', 'as.maintenance-repair::AS-MR-B6-12'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'Which class of lever has the effort force applied between the fulcrum and the load?', '["First-class lever","Second-class lever","Third-class lever","Fourth-class lever"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A third-class lever places the effort between the fulcrum and the load. Common examples include tweezers, fishing rods, and the human forearm lifting a weight. Choice A (first-class) places the fulcrum between effort and load, like a seesaw or pliers. Choice B (second-class) places the load between fulcrum and effort, like a wheelbarrow or bottle opener. Choice D (fourth-class) does not exist in mechanics; only three classes of lever are defined, distinguished by which of the three elements (fulcrum, load, effort) sits in the middle.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-1'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A first-class lever has its fulcrum exactly in the middle, with a 20-pound weight on each side. The lever is:', '["Balanced, with no mechanical advantage","Tipped toward the left side","Tipped toward the right side","Providing a mechanical advantage of 2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A lever balances when torques are equal: W1 x D1 = W2 x D2. With 20 pounds at equal distances, both torques match and the lever is balanced. Mechanical advantage = effort arm / load arm = 1, so no force is multiplied. Choice B (tipped left) and choice C (tipped right) ignore that the moments are equal. Choice D (MA of 2) requires the effort arm to be twice the load arm; here they are equal. A first-class lever with arms of equal length only redirects force, much like a fixed pulley.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-2'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A lever has a 4-foot effort arm and a 1-foot load arm. What is the mechanical advantage?', '["1","2","4","5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Lever MA equals effort arm divided by load arm: MA = 4 / 1 = 4. This means 1 pound of effort can lift a 4-pound load (ignoring the lever''s own weight). Choice A (1) would require equal arm lengths and corresponds to a balanced first-class lever with no mechanical advantage. Choice B (2) halves the correct ratio. Choice D (5) adds the arm lengths (4 + 1) instead of dividing them. Mechanical advantage is always a ratio of effort arm to load arm, never a sum.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-3'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A movable pulley is attached to the load rather than to a fixed point. Compared to a single fixed pulley, a single movable pulley:', '["Provides no change in mechanical advantage","Doubles the mechanical advantage to 2 by supporting the load with two rope segments","Triples the mechanical advantage to 3","Reverses the direction of pull with no force benefit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single movable pulley is attached to the load and supported by two rope segments. Each segment shares half the load, so the effort needed is half the load weight; MA = 2. The trade-off is that the effort end of the rope must travel twice as far as the load rises (conservation of work). Choice A (no change) describes a fixed pulley, not a movable one. Choice C (triples to 3) requires three supporting strands, which a single movable pulley does not have. Choice D (reverses direction with no force benefit) describes a fixed pulley''s behavior, not a movable one.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-4'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A 90-pound load is placed 2 feet from the fulcrum of a lever. To balance the load, how much force must be applied at a point 6 feet from the fulcrum on the other side?', '["15 pounds","30 pounds","45 pounds","180 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lever equilibrium: Load × Load arm = Effort × Effort arm. 90 × 2 = Effort × 6. Effort = 180 / 6 = 30 pounds. The common trap is dividing the load by the load arm (90 / 2 = 45) rather than setting up the full balance equation.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-5'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A compound pulley system has one fixed pulley and two movable pulleys, resulting in 5 rope segments supporting the load. If the load weighs 200 pounds, how much effort force is needed (ignoring friction)?', '["20 pounds","40 pounds","50 pounds","100 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mechanical advantage = number of rope segments supporting the load = 5. Effort = Load / MA = 200 / 5 = 40 pounds. Dividing by the number of pulleys rather than rope segments is the common error.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-6'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A crowbar (first-class lever) is 4 feet long. The fulcrum is placed 6 inches from the load end. How long is the effort arm?', '["6 inches","42 inches","3.5 feet","4 feet"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total lever length = 4 feet = 48 inches. Load arm = 6 inches. Effort arm = 48 − 6 = 42 inches. MA = 42 / 6 = 7, a significant mechanical advantage. The trap is reporting the effort arm as 4 feet (the whole lever).', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-7'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 3, 'A flagpole uses a fixed pulley at the top. When you pull the rope down, the flag goes up. What does this pulley change?', '["The magnitude of the required force","Only the direction of the applied force","Both the direction and the magnitude of the force","The speed of the rope only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single fixed pulley has a mechanical advantage of 1, it does not reduce the force needed. Its only benefit is redirecting the force: you pull down to move the load up, which is more convenient. To reduce required force you need a movable pulley or a compound system.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-8'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'A block-and-tackle system supports a 360-pound load with 6 rope segments. You pull the free rope end upward 12 feet. How far does the load actually rise?', '["2 feet","6 feet","12 feet","72 feet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'With 6 rope segments sharing the load, you trade force for distance: MA = 6. Load distance = rope distance / MA = 12 / 6 = 2 feet. You exert 360 / 6 = 60 pounds of effort but must pull 6 feet of rope for each foot the load moves.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-9'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'A wheelbarrow is a second-class lever. The wheel axle acts as the fulcrum; the load sits in the center; the handles are gripped at the far end. If the load weighs 150 pounds and sits 1.5 feet from the axle, and the handles are 4.5 feet from the axle, how much upward force at the handles is needed to lift the load?', '["50 pounds","75 pounds","100 pounds","225 pounds"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Torque balance: Effort x Effort arm = Load x Load arm. So Effort x 4.5 = 150 x 1.5 = 225 lb-ft. Effort = 225 / 4.5 = 50 pounds. Choice B (75 pounds) is half the load weight, the answer for a single movable pulley, not a second-class lever with these arm lengths. Choice C (100 pounds) ignores the load arm and divides 150 by some other ratio. Choice D (225 pounds) is the torque value (in lb-ft) being misread as a force. MA = effort arm / load arm = 4.5 / 1.5 = 3, so effort is one-third of load weight.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-10'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 4, 'Two pulleys are connected by a belt. The driving pulley has a diameter of 8 inches and turns at 300 RPM. The driven pulley has a diameter of 4 inches. At what RPM does the driven pulley spin?', '["150 RPM","300 RPM","600 RPM","1200 RPM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Belt-connected pulleys have rim speeds equal (no slip), so RPM is inversely proportional to diameter: Driven RPM = Driver RPM x (Driver d / Driven d) = 300 x (8 / 4) = 600 RPM. Choice A (150 RPM) inverts the ratio and treats the larger pulley as the faster one. Choice B (300 RPM) leaves the speed unchanged, ignoring the size difference. Choice D (1200 RPM) doubles the correct answer, possibly multiplying by 4 instead of by 2. The smaller driven pulley always spins faster than the larger driver when belt-coupled.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-11'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 5, 'A mechanic uses a breaker bar that is 24 inches long to loosen a bolt. She can apply 60 pounds of force. The bolt requires 180 pound-inches of torque to loosen. Can she loosen it, and if not, what minimum bar length is needed?', '["Yes, 24 inches is sufficient","No; she needs at least 3 inches","No; she needs at least 30 inches","No; she needs at least 36 inches"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Torque = Force × Arm length = 60 × 24 = 1,440 pound-inches. The bolt requires only 180 pound-inches, so 24 inches is more than sufficient. The trap is misreading the question; 60 × 24 = 1,440, which greatly exceeds 180.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-12'),
  ('MC-LP-B6-13', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 5, 'A lever system is set up with the fulcrum 1 foot from the load end and 5 feet from the effort end (total 6 feet). A 200-pound load is placed at the load end. How much effort is needed, and what is the direction of effort relative to the load for a first-class lever?', '["40 pounds applied upward, same direction as the load pushes","40 pounds applied downward, opposite direction to the load","200 pounds applied downward","40 pounds applied horizontally"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Effort = Load × Load arm / Effort arm = 200 × 1 / 5 = 40 pounds. In a first-class lever the fulcrum is between effort and load, so effort and load forces act in opposite directions, pressing down at the effort end lifts the load end up. The effort is applied downward (opposite to the upward force the load exerts on its end).', true, 'trusted', 'mc.levers-pulleys::MC-LP-B6-13'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'Two meshing spur gears always rotate in:', '["the same direction","opposite directions","alternating directions depending on speed","the same direction only when they are the same size"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two external spur gears mesh, the teeth push against each other at the contact point. Equal and opposite contact forces (Newton''s Third Law) cause the two gears to spin in opposite directions. Choice A (same direction) only happens with an idler gear between them, or with internal gears. Choice C (alternating depending on speed) is not how gear direction works; direction is set by geometry, not speed. Choice D (same direction when equal size) is also wrong; same-size meshing gears still rotate opposite each other. To get same direction without size change, an idler gear must be inserted.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-1'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'A driving gear has 8 teeth and the driven gear has 24 teeth. The gear ratio (driven:driver) is:', '["1:3","3:1","8:1","1:8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gear ratio (driven to driver) equals teeth on driven divided by teeth on driver: 24 / 8 = 3:1. The driving gear turns three times for every one turn of the driven gear, producing a 3:1 speed reduction and a 3:1 torque multiplication. Choice A (1:3) inverts the ratio, which would describe a speed-up gear set (small driver, larger driven). Choice C (8:1) and choice D (1:8) use the wrong tooth count or completely skip the division step. Direction of the ratio (driven:driver vs driver:driven) must always be matched to context; the convention here is driven first.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-2'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'Gear A has 12 teeth and turns at 600 RPM. It meshes with Gear B, which has 36 teeth. How fast does Gear B rotate?', '["100 RPM","200 RPM","300 RPM","1,800 RPM"]'::jsonb, 1, 'RPM is inversely proportional to tooth count: RPM_B = RPM_A x (Teeth_A / Teeth_B) = 600 x (12 / 36) = 600 x (1/3) = 200 RPM. Choice A (100 RPM) divides by 6 instead of 3, doubling the reduction. Choice C (300 RPM) only halves the speed, applying a 2:1 ratio. Choice D (1,800 RPM) multiplies by 3 instead of dividing, treating the larger gear as the faster one. The bigger gear always rotates slower than the smaller gear it meshes with; torque trades up by the same factor speed trades down.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-3'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'In a gear train, decreasing rotational speed by using a larger driven gear also has what effect on torque?', '["Torque decreases proportionally","Torque increases proportionally","Torque is unaffected by the gear ratio","Torque doubles regardless of the ratio"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gears trade speed for torque (assuming no friction losses). When the driven gear is larger, it turns slower but the torque multiplies by the same ratio. If speed is halved, torque is doubled. This is why low gears in a vehicle provide more pulling force.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-4'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'Three gears are in a row: Gear 1 (driver, 10 teeth) meshes with Gear 2 (20 teeth, idler), which meshes with Gear 3 (10 teeth). In which direction does Gear 3 turn relative to Gear 1?', '["Opposite direction, the idler reverses the direction once","Same direction, each mesh reverses direction, and two reversals return to original","Gear 3 does not rotate when an idler is present","Gear 3 rotates 90 degrees out of phase with Gear 1"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each external gear mesh reverses the direction of rotation. Gear 1 to Gear 2 is one reversal; Gear 2 to Gear 3 is a second reversal. Two reversals return Gear 3 to the same rotational direction as Gear 1. The idler also makes the final speed ratio depend only on the first and last gears (10 and 10), not the idler in the middle, so the speed ratio is 1:1. Choice A (opposite) counts only one reversal. Choice C (does not rotate) misunderstands what an idler does; it transmits motion. Choice D (90 degrees out of phase) confuses rotational direction with phase angle, which is not a quantity defined for spur gears.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-5'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'A wheel and axle system has a wheel radius of 15 cm and an axle radius of 3 cm. A 60-Newton load is hung from the axle. What force must be applied at the rim of the wheel to hold the load in equilibrium?', '["4 N","12 N","60 N","300 N"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MA of a wheel and axle = wheel radius / axle radius = 15 / 3 = 5. Effort = Load / MA = 60 / 5 = 12 N. A common trap is dividing 60 by 15 (the wheel radius alone) to get 4 N, confusing radius with MA.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-6'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 3, 'A gear reduction system uses a 5-tooth pinion driving a 40-tooth ring gear. The input shaft turns at 2,000 RPM. What is the output RPM, and how does the output torque compare to the input?', '["250 RPM output; torque is multiplied by 8","250 RPM output; torque is the same","16,000 RPM output; torque is divided by 8","400 RPM output; torque is multiplied by 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Output RPM = Input RPM x (Pinion teeth / Ring teeth) = 2,000 x (5/40) = 250 RPM. The gear reduction ratio is 40/5 = 8:1. In an ideal gear set, what is lost in speed is gained in torque, so output torque = input torque x 8. Choice B (250 RPM, same torque) gets the speed right but ignores the speed-torque trade-off. Choice C (16,000 RPM, torque /8) inverts the formula and treats the small gear as the driven side. Choice D (400 RPM, torque x 5) uses the wrong ratio (5 instead of 8). Gear ratio always equals teeth_driven / teeth_driver.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-7'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'A bicycle chainring has 48 teeth and the rear sprocket has 16 teeth. For each complete revolution of the pedals, how many times does the rear wheel turn?', '["1 time","2 times","3 times","4 times"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Chain drives behave like gears: rear wheel revolutions per pedal revolution = chainring teeth / sprocket teeth = 48 / 16 = 3. Each pedal stroke turns the rear wheel three times, giving a speed advantage at the cost of higher pedaling force. Choice A (1 time) ignores the tooth ratio entirely. Choice B (2 times) halves the correct ratio. Choice D (4 times) uses the wrong division (perhaps 48 / 12 or similar). Larger chainring relative to sprocket means more wheel revolutions per pedal turn, which is the trade-off cyclists make for higher top speed.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-8'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'In a planetary gear set, the sun gear has 20 teeth, each of three planet gears has 10 teeth, and the ring gear has 40 teeth. If the ring gear is held fixed and power is applied to the sun gear, which output produces the highest torque?', '["The planet carrier (output through the arm holding the planets)","The ring gear (despite being held)","The sun gear itself","All outputs produce identical torque"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When the ring gear is fixed and the sun drives the system, the planet gears walk around the fixed ring, carrying the planet carrier (arm) as output. The speed reduction is significant (overall ratio = 1 + Ring/Sun = 1 + 40/20 = 3:1), giving 3× torque multiplication at the carrier, the highest available output torque configuration for this setup.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-9'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 4, 'A worm gear pair has a worm with 1 thread (start) and a worm wheel with 50 teeth. If the worm shaft turns at 1,500 RPM, at what speed does the worm wheel turn?', '["1 RPM","30 RPM","50 RPM","75,000 RPM"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single-start worm advances the worm wheel by one tooth per full worm revolution. With 50 teeth on the wheel, the gear ratio is 50:1. Output RPM = Input RPM / 50 = 1,500 / 50 = 30 RPM. Choice A (1 RPM) over-reduces, dividing by 1,500 or otherwise inflating the ratio. Choice C (50 RPM) leaves out one step in the division. Choice D (75,000 RPM) multiplies instead of dividing, treating the worm wheel as a speed-up element. Worm gears are extreme speed reducers and large torque multipliers, often used where high torque at low speed is needed.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-10'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 5, 'A 4-speed manual transmission has gear ratios of 3.5:1, 2.2:1, 1.4:1, and 1:1 for first through fourth gear. In first gear with the engine producing 200 Newton-meters of torque, approximately how much torque is available at the transmission output shaft (ignoring drivetrain losses)?', '["57 Nm","200 Nm","440 Nm","700 Nm"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Gear reduction multiplies torque: Output torque = Engine torque x Gear ratio = 200 Nm x 3.5 = 700 Nm. Choice A (57 Nm) divides 200 by 3.5, inverting the formula and treating first gear as a speed-up. Choice B (200 Nm) ignores the gear ratio and just lists engine torque, which would only be the case in fourth gear (1:1). Choice C (440 Nm) uses the 2.2:1 second-gear ratio instead of first gear. First gear has the highest reduction and therefore the highest output torque, which is exactly why vehicles start from rest in first gear.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-11'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 5, 'Two meshing gears have a center-to-center distance of 18 cm. Gear A (the driver) has a pitch radius of 6 cm. Expressing gear ratio as driven-to-driver, what is the gear ratio?', '["1:1","1:2","2:1","3:1"]'::jsonb, 2, 'For meshing external gears the center-to-center distance equals the sum of the two pitch radii. So radius_B = 18 minus 6 = 12 cm. Pitch radius is proportional to tooth count, so the driven-to-driver ratio is 12 to 6, which simplifies to 2:1. The driven gear (B) is twice as large, so for every one rotation of the driver it turns half a revolution, and its torque is doubled. ''1:1'' would require equal radii (9 and 9). ''1:2'' inverts the convention and would describe driver-to-driven instead. ''3:1'' would require radius_B = 18, which violates the geometric constraint.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-12'),
  ('MC-GW-B6-13', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A rack and pinion gear system converts which type of motion to which?', '["Rotary motion to linear motion","Linear motion to circular oscillation","Vertical motion to horizontal rotary motion","Torque to electrical energy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A rack is a straight, flat gear; a pinion is a circular gear. When the pinion rotates, its teeth engage the rack and push it along its length, converting rotary motion into linear motion. This is the operating principle of rack-and-pinion steering, where steering-wheel rotation becomes linear motion of the tie rods. Choice B (linear to circular oscillation) reverses the input/output and adds oscillation, which is not what a rack-and-pinion does. Choice C (vertical to horizontal rotary) garbles the geometry; the conversion is rotary-to-linear, not vertical-to-horizontal. Choice D (torque to electricity) describes a generator, not a mechanical gear set.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.gears-wheels::MC-GW-B6-13'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'A 50-pound box sits on a rough surface. A horizontal force of 20 pounds is applied but the box does not move. Which statement correctly describes the friction force acting on the box?', '["Friction is 50 pounds, opposing the weight of the box","Friction is 20 pounds, exactly opposing the applied force","Friction is zero because the box is not moving","Friction is 70 pounds, combining weight and applied force"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Static friction adjusts to exactly cancel the applied horizontal force when the object is not moving. The box is in equilibrium, so the horizontal forces must balance: static friction = 20 pounds directed opposite to the applied force.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-1'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Compared to static friction, kinetic (sliding) friction for the same object on the same surface is generally:', '["Greater","Equal","Less","Dependent only on velocity"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Kinetic (sliding) friction is generally less than the maximum static friction for the same surfaces. Once an object breaks free of static friction and begins sliding, fewer microscopic surface interlocks form, so the resisting force drops. Choice A (greater) reverses the well-established relationship. Choice B (equal) ignores the difference between coefficients of static and kinetic friction. Choice D (depends only on velocity) is wrong; for most practical surfaces, kinetic friction is approximately constant with velocity at typical speeds. This is why a heavy object takes more force to start moving than to keep moving.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-2'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A 100-pound block rests on a horizontal surface with a coefficient of static friction of 0.4. What minimum horizontal force is needed to start the block moving?', '["20 pounds","40 pounds","60 pounds","100 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maximum static friction equals the coefficient of static friction times the normal force: f_s = mu_s x N = 0.4 x 100 = 40 pounds. On a horizontal surface, normal force equals the object''s weight, so 40 pounds of push is the minimum to start motion. Choice A (20 pounds) halves the coefficient or uses 0.2 by mistake. Choice C (60 pounds) inflates the coefficient to 0.6. Choice D (100 pounds) ignores the coefficient and uses the full weight as the friction force, which would only be true if mu_s equaled 1.0.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-3'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A 200-pound box is being dragged across a floor. The coefficient of kinetic friction is 0.25. What is the friction force resisting the motion?', '["25 pounds","50 pounds","80 pounds","200 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Kinetic friction equals the coefficient times the normal force: f_k = mu_k x N = 0.25 x 200 = 50 pounds. On a flat floor the normal force equals the box''s weight. Choice A (25 pounds) halves the coefficient to 0.125. Choice C (80 pounds) uses a coefficient of 0.4 instead of 0.25. Choice D (200 pounds) ignores the coefficient and uses the full weight, which would only apply if mu_k were 1.0 (an extreme value rarely seen). Friction always scales with normal force, not with the applied force.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-4'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A 60-pound block is placed on a ramp inclined at 30 degrees. The normal force on the block from the ramp surface equals the component of the block''s weight perpendicular to the ramp surface. If the ramp is smooth (frictionless), the normal force is approximately:', '["30 pounds","52 pounds","60 pounds","120 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Normal force = W × cos(θ) = 60 × cos(30°) = 60 × 0.866 ≈ 52 pounds. The component pulling the block down the ramp = W × sin(30°) = 60 × 0.5 = 30 pounds. The normal force is NOT equal to the full weight on a ramp, it is reduced by the cosine of the angle.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-5'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A person pushes down at an angle on a lawnmower handle. The downward component of the pushing force increases the normal force on the mower''s wheels. What effect does this have on friction?', '["Friction decreases because the mower moves forward","Friction increases because friction depends on normal force","Friction is unchanged because only horizontal force causes motion","Friction is eliminated by the forward-directed component"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Friction force equals the coefficient of friction times the normal force: f = mu x N. Adding a downward component of push increases the normal force the floor exerts upward on the mower wheels, and friction scales directly with that normal force. Choice A (decreases) reverses the relationship; pushing down increases, not decreases, the resistance. Choice C (unchanged) ignores that the vertical force component adds to the weight, raising the normal force. Choice D (eliminated) is physically impossible; no horizontal component can cancel friction. This is why pulling at an upward angle is easier than pushing at a downward angle.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-6'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 3, 'A 120-pound crate is on a frictionless surface. Two horizontal forces act on it: 50 pounds to the right and 30 pounds to the left. What is the net force and the resulting acceleration? (Use weight ÷ 32 ft/s² to find mass in slugs.)', '["Net 20 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 5.3 ft/s²","Net 80 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 21 ft/s²","Net 20 pounds right; acceleration ≈ 2.5 ft/s²","Net 50 pounds right; no acceleration because friction balances it"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Net force = 50 - 30 = 20 pounds to the right. Mass in slugs = weight / g = 120 / 32 = 3.75 slugs. Acceleration = F_net / m = 20 / 3.75 = 5.33 ft/s^2 to the right. Choice B (80 pounds; 21 ft/s^2) adds the two forces instead of subtracting them. Choice C (20 pounds; 2.5 ft/s^2) uses weight (120 lb) directly as mass instead of dividing by g, doubling the apparent mass. Choice D (50 pounds; no acceleration) misreads the surface as having friction; with no friction, the only horizontal forces are the two applied pushes.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-7'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A 500-Newton engine rests on a steel workbench. The coefficient of static friction between the engine and bench is 0.3. A horizontal force of 160 N is applied to the engine. Does the engine move, and what is the maximum static friction force?', '["Yes, the engine moves; maximum static friction was 150 N, which 160 N exceeds","Yes, the engine moves; maximum static friction was 160 N, which the applied force just equals","No, the engine stays put; maximum static friction was 150 N, but it grows to match the 160 N applied","No, the engine stays put; maximum static friction was 160 N opposing the applied force"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Compute the static-friction ceiling: f_s,max = μ_s × N = 0.3 × 500 = 150 N. The applied force of 160 N exceeds that ceiling, so the engine begins to slide. Choice B (150 vs 160 is mistakenly read as equal) ignores the 10 N gap that triggers motion. Choice C is the most common misconception: students think static friction always rises to match whatever force is applied, but it actually caps at μ_s × N. Choice D treats kinetic friction as the answer at rest and uses the wrong number entirely; static friction never exceeds its ceiling.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-8'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A block slides down a ramp at a constant speed. At constant speed, which of the following must be true?', '["There is no friction force on the block","The component of gravity along the ramp exactly equals the kinetic friction force","The normal force equals the gravitational force","The coefficient of kinetic friction is zero"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Constant velocity means zero acceleration, so the net force along the ramp is zero. The component of gravity pulling the block down the ramp (W sin theta) must be exactly canceled by kinetic friction (mu_k x N) acting up the ramp. Choice A (no friction) would leave gravity unopposed and the block would accelerate, not move at constant speed. Choice C (normal equals gravity) is true only on a flat surface; on a ramp, normal force equals W cos theta, less than full weight. Choice D (mu_k = 0) is equivalent to choice A and contradicts the constant-speed observation.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-9'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 4, 'A 40-kg box sits on a horizontal floor. Coefficient of static friction = 0.5, kinetic friction = 0.35. A horizontal force of 180 N is applied. What is the friction force and does the box move? (g = 10 m/s²)', '["Friction = 200 N, box does not move","Friction = 180 N, box does not move","Maximum static friction = 200 N; 180 N < 200 N so box stays; friction = 180 N","Box moves; kinetic friction = 140 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Normal force = mg = 40 × 10 = 400 N. Maximum static friction = 0.5 × 400 = 200 N. Applied force = 180 N < 200 N, so the box does NOT move. When stationary, static friction equals the applied force: 180 N. Kinetic friction (140 N) is only relevant if the box were sliding.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-10'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 5, 'A crate is being pushed across a rough floor at constant velocity with a horizontal force of 80 N. If the floor surface is then treated to reduce the coefficient of kinetic friction by half, and the same 80-N force is maintained, what happens to the crate?', '["It continues at the same constant velocity","It decelerates and stops","It accelerates because the applied force now exceeds the reduced friction","It reverses direction"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Originally, applied force (80 N) balanced friction (80 N) for constant velocity. Halving the coefficient of kinetic friction halves the friction force to 40 N while the applied force stays at 80 N. Net force = 80 - 40 = 40 N in the direction of motion. By Newton''s Second Law, a = F_net / m > 0, so the crate accelerates. Choice A (same velocity) ignores the new force imbalance. Choice B (decelerates) reverses the direction of the net force; less friction means less resistance, not more. Choice D (reverses direction) would require a net force opposite to motion, which is not the case here.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-11'),
  ('MC-FF-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 5, 'A 10-kg block rests on a 25-degree incline. The coefficient of static friction is 0.5. Will the block slide? (Use g = 10 m/s², sin 25° ≈ 0.42, cos 25° ≈ 0.91)', '["Yes, because gravity down the ramp exceeds maximum static friction","No, because maximum static friction exceeds gravity''s ramp component","It will slide at exactly constant velocity","Insufficient information without knowing the block''s surface material"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gravity along ramp = mg sin 25° = 10 × 10 × 0.42 = 42 N. Normal force = mg cos 25° = 10 × 10 × 0.91 = 91 N. Maximum static friction = 0.5 × 91 = 45.5 N. Since 45.5 N > 42 N, static friction can fully oppose the sliding tendency. The block does not slide.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.forces-friction::MC-FF-B6-12'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'A screw is a simple machine based on which other simple machine?', '["Lever","Wheel and axle","Inclined plane wrapped in a helix","Pulley"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A screw is geometrically an inclined plane wrapped helically around a cylinder. The pitch (distance between threads) is the height of the inclined plane, and the circumference traveled per rotation is its length. Choice A (lever) is unrelated; a screw does not rotate around a fixed fulcrum like a lever. Choice B (wheel and axle) is the closest second answer because screws are turned by a wheel-like head, but the underlying geometry that creates the linear advance is the spiral ramp itself, not a wheel-axle radius ratio. Choice D (pulley) does not match; pulleys use ropes and grooves, not threaded inclines.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-1'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'Pascal''s principle states that pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is:', '["absorbed by the fluid and converted to heat","transmitted equally in all directions throughout the fluid","reduced in proportion to the depth of the fluid","only transmitted upward in the fluid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pascal''s principle states that pressure applied to an enclosed, incompressible fluid is transmitted equally in all directions and to every surface bounding the fluid. This is the foundation of hydraulic systems, brakes, and lifts. Choice A (absorbed and converted to heat) describes friction or compression losses, not the transmission of pressure. Choice C (reduced by depth) is true for static fluid pressure due to gravity but is not Pascal''s principle; Pascal''s law concerns the added pressure from external force. Choice D (only upward) is geometrically wrong; fluids transmit applied pressure in every direction at once.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-2'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A frictionless ramp is 12 feet long and rises 3 feet vertically. What is its mechanical advantage?', '["3","4","9","36"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mechanical advantage of an inclined plane = length of slope / vertical height = 12 / 3 = 4. A longer ramp (relative to height) requires less force but the load must travel a greater distance. MA = 4 means you need 1/4 of the load''s weight as effort force.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-3'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A hydraulic system input piston has an area of 5 in² and the output piston has an area of 25 in². If the input force is 100 pounds, what force does the output piston exert?', '["20 pounds","100 pounds","500 pounds","2,500 pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hydraulic force multiplication: F_out = F_in x (A_out / A_in) = 100 x (25 / 5) = 100 x 5 = 500 pounds. Choice A (20 pounds) inverts the area ratio and divides force by 5 instead of multiplying. Choice B (100 pounds) ignores the area difference entirely. Choice D (2,500 pounds) multiplies force by the output area alone (100 x 25), ignoring the input area in the denominator. Hydraulics multiply force by the ratio of areas; the input piston moves a longer distance with less force, the output piston moves a shorter distance with more force, conserving work.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-4'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A ramp 20 feet long rises 5 feet. A 240-pound load is pushed up the ramp. What effort force is required (frictionless)?', '["12 pounds","40 pounds","48 pounds","60 pounds"]'::jsonb, 3, 'MA = ramp length / height = 20 / 5 = 4. Effort = Load / MA = 240 / 4 = 60 pounds. A trap answer of 48 pounds corresponds to 240 / 5 (dividing by height instead of MA).', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-5'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A hydraulic brake system has an input piston area of 1 in² and the brake caliper piston area is 3 in². A driver applies 30 pounds of force at the brake pedal, which the booster amplifies by a factor of 4 before reaching the master cylinder. How much clamping force does the caliper exert?', '["30 pounds","90 pounds","120 pounds","360 pounds"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two stages of multiplication apply in series. Booster: 30 x 4 = 120 pounds at the master cylinder. Hydraulic area ratio: 120 x (3/1) = 360 pounds at the caliper. Choice A (30 pounds) ignores both stages. Choice B (90 pounds) applies only the hydraulic ratio to the bare pedal force (30 x 3 = 90), skipping the booster. Choice C (120 pounds) stops after the booster and ignores the hydraulic stage. When mechanical and hydraulic advantages chain together, you multiply their factors: total MA = 4 x 3 = 12, and final force = 30 x 12 = 360 pounds.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-6'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 3, 'A wedge has a length of 10 inches and a thickness (wide end) of 2 inches. You drive it under a 600-pound rock. How much driving force is needed to generate the lifting force (assuming MA fully transfers)?', '["60 pounds","120 pounds","300 pounds","600 pounds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Wedge MA = length / thickness = 10 / 2 = 5. Driving force = Load / MA = 600 / 5 = 120 pounds. Choice A (60 pounds) doubles the wedge MA to 10, perhaps using length / (thickness/2). Choice C (300 pounds) halves the load and ignores the MA, treating the wedge like a simple lever with MA = 2. Choice D (600 pounds) skips the wedge entirely and uses the load weight as the required force. A wedge converts a small driving force along its length into a much larger splitting force perpendicular to its motion, just like an inclined plane in mirror image.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-7'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'In a hydraulic system, the input piston moves down 10 inches with an area of 2 in². The output piston has an area of 8 in². How far does the output piston move upward?', '["1.25 inches","2.5 inches","5 inches","40 inches"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fluid volume is conserved: Volume in = Volume out. Input volume = 2 in² × 10 in = 20 in³. Output: 20 in³ = 8 in² × d. d = 20 / 8 = 2.5 inches. The output piston moves a shorter distance but with proportionally more force, the same trade-off as any mechanical advantage system.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-8'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'A loading ramp is 18 feet long and rises 6 feet. An 800-pound engine is pushed up the ramp with a steady force. How much work is done on the engine as it is raised the full 6 feet vertically? (Work = Force × Distance traveled; use the vertical height.)', '["800 foot-pounds","2,400 foot-pounds","4,800 foot-pounds","14,400 foot-pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Work done against gravity = weight × vertical height = 800 × 6 = 4,800 foot-pounds. The ramp''s MA (18/6 = 3) reduces the effort force to 800/3 ≈ 267 pounds, but you push over 18 feet of ramp: 267 × 18 = 4,800 ft-lb, the same result, confirming conservation of energy. Work done on the load always equals weight × height, regardless of the path.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-9'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-10', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 4, 'A hydraulic press has an input cylinder of area 3 cm² and an output cylinder of area 75 cm². A technician pushes the input piston down 50 cm. What is the output force if the input force is 60 N?', '["60 N","300 N","1,500 N","3,750 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area ratio = 75 / 3 = 25. Output force = 60 × 25 = 1,500 N. The output piston moves 50 × (3/75) = 2 cm, short distance but large force. Output piston travel is inversely proportional to the area ratio, confirming energy conservation.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-10'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-11', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 5, 'An engine hoist uses a compound system: a 3:1 lever feeds into a 4-rope pulley block-and-tackle. An engine weighs 600 pounds. What is the minimum effort force required at the lever input to lift the engine?', '["50 pounds","200 pounds","400 pounds","600 pounds"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When simple machines are combined in series, their mechanical advantages multiply: Total MA = 3 x 4 = 12. Effort = Load / Total MA = 600 / 12 = 50 pounds. Choice B (200 pounds) uses only the pulley MA of 3, ignoring the lever. Choice C (400 pounds) reduces the load by only 1.5, perhaps averaging the MAs (3+4)/2 instead of multiplying. Choice D (600 pounds) ignores both stages and uses the full engine weight. Compound machines trade input force for input distance: you pull through 12 times the distance the engine rises.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-11'),
  ('MC-IPH-B6-12', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 5, 'A hydraulic system output piston has an area of 50 in². The system pressure is 200 psi. What force does the output piston exert?', '["4 pounds","250 pounds","10,000 pounds","1,000,000 pounds"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Force = Pressure × Area = 200 psi × 50 in² = 10,000 pounds. This is the fundamental hydraulic force formula. The trap answer 250 pounds comes from adding (200 + 50) rather than multiplying, and 4 pounds comes from dividing (200 / 50).', true, 'trusted', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::MC-IPH-B6-12'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-1', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'Newton''s Second Law of Motion states that force equals mass times acceleration (F = ma). If a 2-kg object has an acceleration of 10 m/s², what is the net force on it?', '["5 N","12 N","20 N","0.2 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Newton''s Second Law: F = m x a = 2 kg x 10 m/s^2 = 20 N. Choice A (5 N) divides incorrectly (a / m / 2). Choice B (12 N) adds mass and acceleration (2 + 10), mixing incompatible units. Choice D (0.2 N) inverts the formula and divides mass by acceleration (2 / 10). Force is proportional to both mass and acceleration; the units (N = kg m/s^2) confirm the multiplicative relationship. Heavier objects need more force for the same acceleration; lighter objects accelerate more under the same force.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-1'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-2', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'A ball is thrown horizontally from a building ledge. At the instant it leaves the thrower''s hand, which direction does gravity act on it?', '["Horizontally, in the direction of throw","Upward, opposing the throw","Vertically downward, regardless of horizontal motion","At a 45-degree angle combining horizontal and vertical"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Near Earth''s surface, gravity acts vertically downward at 9.8 m/s^2 regardless of horizontal motion. The instant the ball leaves the hand, the only force on it (ignoring air resistance) is the downward pull of gravity. Choice A (horizontal in direction of throw) confuses initial velocity with the gravitational force; the throw gives velocity, not a continued force. Choice B (upward) reverses gravity''s direction. Choice D (45 degrees) adds a horizontal component to gravity that does not exist; horizontal and vertical motions are independent in projectile motion, with gravity acting only on the vertical component.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-2'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-3', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'What is the momentum of a 4-kg object moving at 15 m/s?', '["3.75 kg·m/s","11 kg·m/s","60 kg·m/s","225 kg·m/s"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Momentum p = mass × velocity = 4 kg × 15 m/s = 60 kg·m/s. Dividing instead of multiplying (4/15 ≈ 0.27 or 15/4 = 3.75) inverts the formula. Momentum is a vector quantity with units of kg·m/s.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-3'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-4', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 5, 'In a perfectly inelastic collision, two objects stick together after impact. What is conserved in this type of collision?', '["Kinetic energy only","Momentum only","Both kinetic energy and momentum","Neither momentum nor kinetic energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In any collision (elastic or inelastic), total momentum is conserved. In a perfectly inelastic collision, kinetic energy is NOT conserved, some is converted to heat, sound, and deformation. Elastic collisions conserve both momentum and kinetic energy.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-4'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-5', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A rocket in space fires its engines and accelerates. Newton''s Third Law explains this by stating that:', '["Objects in space have no inertia and respond to any force","The exhaust gases are pushed backward, and the rocket is pushed forward by an equal and opposite reaction force","The rocket''s mass decreases as fuel is burned, increasing speed automatically","Gravity pulls the rocket forward in the direction of acceleration"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Newton''s Third Law: for every action force there is an equal and opposite reaction force. The rocket pushes exhaust gases backward (action); the gases push the rocket forward with an equal force (reaction). Because the action-reaction pair acts on the rocket and the gases (not on the surrounding air), thrust works in a vacuum. Choice A (no inertia in space) is wrong; objects retain their mass and inertia everywhere. Choice C (mass loss alone causes speed) ignores that a force is needed to accelerate the remaining mass. Choice D (gravity pulls forward) misidentifies the force; gravity pulls toward planetary masses, not in the direction of acceleration.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-5'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-6', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'A 3-kg object moving east at 8 m/s collides with a 3-kg object at rest. They stick together. What is the velocity of the combined mass immediately after the collision?', '["8 m/s east","4 m/s east","0 m/s","2 m/s east"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Conservation of momentum: p_before = (3 × 8) + (3 × 0) = 24 kg·m/s. Combined mass = 6 kg. v_after = 24 / 6 = 4 m/s east. The combined mass is twice the original, so velocity is halved. This is a perfectly inelastic collision, kinetic energy is not conserved but momentum is.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-6'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-7', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'A ball is thrown upward and reaches its highest point. At that exact moment, what is the ball''s velocity and what is its acceleration?', '["Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration = 0 m/s² (weightless at peak)","Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration = 9.8 m/s² downward","Velocity = peak speed; acceleration = 9.8 m/s² upward","Velocity = 0 m/s; acceleration is upward until it reverses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At the highest point, vertical velocity is momentarily zero (the ball is neither moving up nor down). However, gravity still acts downward at 9.8 m/s² continuously, acceleration due to gravity never stops, regardless of the object''s velocity. This is a common misconception: zero velocity does not mean zero acceleration.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-7'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-8', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 3, 'Two balls are dropped simultaneously from the same height: Ball A has a mass of 1 kg, Ball B has a mass of 5 kg. Ignoring air resistance, which hits the ground first?', '["Ball A, because it is lighter and falls more easily","Ball B, because gravity exerts more force on it","They hit at the same time","It depends on the shape of the balls"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Galileo''s principle: in the absence of air resistance, all objects fall with the same gravitational acceleration (g ≈ 9.8 m/s²) regardless of mass. Although gravity exerts more force on Ball B, Ball B also has more inertia (F = ma → a = F/m, and F and m both scale with mass, so a = g for all). Both hit simultaneously.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-8'),
  ('MC-MP-B6-9', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 4, 'A stationary 8-kg bowling ball is struck by a 0.5-kg cue ball moving at 20 m/s. After the collision, the cue ball bounces straight back at 10 m/s. Using conservation of momentum, what is the approximate velocity of the bowling ball after the collision?', '["0.94 m/s in the original direction of the cue ball","1.875 m/s in the original direction","20 m/s in the original direction","10 m/s backward"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Taking the cue ball''s initial direction as positive: p_before = 0.5 × 20 + 8 × 0 = 10 kg·m/s. p_after = 0.5 × (−10) + 8 × v_bowling. 10 = −5 + 8v → 8v = 15 → v = 1.875 m/s in the original forward direction. The cue ball reverses direction (negative), transferring most of its momentum to the heavier ball.', true, 'trusted', 'mc.motion-projectile::MC-MP-B6-9'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a large right triangle with a right angle at the bottom-left corner. Piece B is a small right triangle with the right angle at the top-right corner. Piece C is a rectangle. When pieces A, B, and C are assembled together, which figure results?', '["A large rectangle whose width equals the base of piece A","A square with side length equal to the height of piece A","A large right triangle with no interior gaps","An L-shaped piece with a notch on one side"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Piece A (large right triangle) and piece B (small right triangle) share matching hypotenuse angles. Placing B against A along the hypotenuse fills the diagonal strip and produces a rectangle whose width equals A''s base. Piece C (rectangle) then extends the figure in the same width direction, completing a larger rectangle. ''A large right triangle with no interior gaps'' cannot form, because adding a rectangle (piece C) to a triangle straightens one side and disqualifies the triangle outline. ''A square'' would require both dimensions to match, which the pieces'' proportions do not guarantee. ''An L-shape'' requires a notch that the rectangle C is specifically filling.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-1'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two pieces are shown: Piece A is a medium square with a dot in its center. Piece B is an identical medium square with no markings. When placed side by side along their right and left edges respectively, what shape results?', '["A large square","A tall thin rectangle","A wide rectangle with the dot on the left half","A wide rectangle with the dot on the right half"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two identical squares placed edge to edge span twice the width and the same height, producing a 2:1 wide rectangle. Piece A (with the dot) is on the left, so the dot sits in the left half. ''A large square'' would require placing the squares to also double the height, which side-by-side placement does not do. ''A tall thin rectangle'' confuses the long axis: the squares meet horizontally, so the result is wide. ''Wide rectangle with the dot on the right half'' reverses the placement of piece A.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-2'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Four small right triangles, each identical and each with a right angle at the bottom-left, are shown. When all four are assembled by rotating pairs to face each other and joining along their hypotenuses, what shape do they form?', '["A large right triangle","A rectangle","A parallelogram","An irregular pentagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two right triangles joined along their hypotenuses (one rotated 180 degrees relative to the other) form a rectangle, since the right-angle corners are now diagonally opposite and the legs line up edge to edge. Doing this with all four triangles produces two such rectangles, which then sit side by side to make one larger rectangle. ''A large right triangle'' would require pairing along legs, not hypotenuses, and would leave a triangular outline rather than a four-sided one. ''A parallelogram'' would result from sliding rather than reflecting the pieces. ''An irregular pentagon'' requires five sides, but the four-triangle hypotenuse pairing has exactly four straight edges.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-3'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a large equilateral triangle marked with an arrow pointing up. Piece B is an identical equilateral triangle with no marking. Piece C is a small equilateral triangle. Pieces A and B are joined along one edge with B flipped (pointing down). Where should piece C be placed to complete a larger equilateral triangle?', '["Along the left edge of piece A","In the gap at the upper-right where the two piece edges don''t meet","In the corner gap at the bottom where the combined A-B shape has an open notch","On top of piece A to extend it upward"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Joining two equilateral triangles along a shared edge with opposite orientations (one apex up, one apex down) creates a rhombus shape, not a complete equilateral triangle. A small equilateral triangle is needed to fill the bottom-corner notch where the combined shape sweeps inward, completing the larger equilateral triangle outline. ''Along the left edge'' would extend the figure sideways rather than fill any gap. ''In the upper-right gap'' does not match the bottom-pointing geometry of the joined pair. ''On top of piece A'' would simply double-cover existing area rather than complete a new shape.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-4'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Four pieces are shown: Piece A is a large square. Piece B is a right triangle whose legs are each half the side length of piece A. Piece C is an identical triangle to B. Piece D is an identical triangle to B. When B, C, and D are assembled and attached to piece A, which shape results?', '["A larger square","A regular hexagon","A square with one corner cut off","A pentagon with one right angle"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The geometry depends on whether the triangles attach inside or outside the square. Pressed against three corners of the square externally, with the right angle of each triangle matching a corner, each triangle extends one side of the square outward. The combined boundary becomes a five-sided figure where one corner retains the original 90 degree angle of the square. ''A regular hexagon'' would require equal angles and sides, which extending three corners cannot produce. ''A larger square'' would require four matching extensions, not three. ''A square with one corner cut off'' is the inverse arrangement (subtracting rather than adding).', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-5'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Two pieces are given: Piece A is an L-shaped piece (a 3×2 rectangle with a 1×1 square removed from one corner). Piece B is a small 1×1 square. When piece B is placed in the missing corner of piece A, what shape results?', '["A 3×2 rectangle","A 2×3 rectangle (same thing, different orientation)","A T-shape","A 4×1 strip"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Piece A is a 3 by 2 rectangle with a 1 by 1 corner removed, leaving an L-shape. Piece B is exactly the 1 by 1 square that was removed. Placing B back into the missing corner restores the original 3 by 2 rectangle. The 2 by 3 rectangle option is the same shape with axes swapped, but the puzzle specifies a 3 by 2 orientation. ''A T-shape'' would form only if B were attached to the outside of the L, extending a leg. ''A 4 by 1 strip'' would require breaking apart and re-arranging the L, which the problem does not allow.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-6'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Three pieces are given: Piece A is a medium isosceles right triangle with the right angle at top. Piece B is an identical triangle. Piece C is a small square whose side equals the leg length of pieces A and B. When A and B are placed with their hypotenuses together, then C is attached to one open side, which figure results?', '["A larger isosceles right triangle","A square","A rectangle that is twice as wide as it is tall","A rectangle with a triangular bump on one end"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two isosceles right triangles joined along their hypotenuses form a square whose side equals the triangles'' leg length. Adding piece C, a square of the same side length, along one open edge of that square extends it horizontally into a rectangle measuring 2 leg-lengths wide and 1 leg-length tall, a 2:1 ratio. ''A larger isosceles right triangle'' would require placing the triangles'' legs together instead of hypotenuses. ''A square'' covers only the first step (triangles alone) before C is added. ''A rectangle with a triangular bump'' would result only if C were attached at an angle or off-center, not flush along an edge.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-7'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Five pieces are labeled A–E. Piece A is a large square. Pieces B and C are identical right triangles each with legs equal to half the side of A. Piece D is a small square with side equal to one-quarter the side of A. Piece E is a thin rectangle. When all five pieces are assembled without gaps or overlaps, which overall shape results?', '["A large right triangle","A large square larger than piece A","A large rectangle that is twice as long as it is wide","A T-shape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The pieces include a large square A, two triangles with legs equal to half of A''s side, a small square equal to one-quarter of A''s side, and a thin rectangle. Combined areas can in principle tile a square whose side is 1.5 times piece A. The triangles fill two corner gaps, the small square fills a quarter-corner gap, and the rectangle bridges the remaining strip. ''A large right triangle'' has the wrong outline (3 sides instead of 4). ''A 2:1 rectangle'' would leave gaps that the given piece set cannot fill. ''A T-shape'' has notches that an enclosed tiling does not produce.', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-8'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Piece A is a large right triangle with the right angle at the lower-left, the vertical leg on the left, and the horizontal leg on the bottom. Piece B is a smaller right triangle that is congruent to the upper-left half of piece A when it is cut along its median. Piece C is the remaining lower-right portion of that median cut. When B and C are reassembled, which shape do they form?', '["A square","A shape identical to piece A","A rectangle","A parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pieces B and C are described as the two halves of piece A cut along its median to the hypotenuse. Reuniting them along that cut line restores piece A exactly. The result is geometrically identical to the original triangle. ''A square'' would require the cut to produce four equal corners, which a single median cut cannot do. ''A rectangle'' would require the cut piece pair to share a right angle on every corner, which a triangle''s halves do not. ''A parallelogram'' would require sliding rather than re-attaching B and C, separating them rather than re-joining them.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-9'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Four pieces: Piece A is a large square with a diagonal line drawn from the top-left to the bottom-right corner. Pieces B, C, D are right triangles of equal size. When B, C, and D are placed against piece A so that each triangle''s hypotenuse aligns with an outer edge of A, which overall assembled figure results?', '["A regular octagon","A larger square rotated 45°","A plus sign (cross shape)","A star shape"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Adding isosceles right triangles to the outside of a square with their hypotenuses flush along three sides extends three of the square''s edges outward into points. Depending on the proportions of the triangles, the assembled outline forms a larger square oriented at 45 degrees relative to the original. ''A regular octagon'' would require eight equal sides and angles, which only emerges from a more symmetric cut. ''A plus sign'' results from placing the triangles on the inside or from using rectangles instead. ''A star shape'' requires triangles on every side with notches between them, not flush hypotenuses.', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-10'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a large rectangle (3 units wide, 2 units tall). Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 units and 1 unit. Piece C is a right triangle identical to B. B and C are mirror images of each other. When B is placed against the right side of A (hypotenuse facing A''s right edge), and C is placed against the left side (mirrored), which shape results?', '["A regular hexagon","A parallelogram","A hexagon with two right angles","A parallelogram with clipped corners"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Placing two opposite-facing right triangles on the short ends of a rectangle, each angled in the same slant direction (mirror images that nonetheless lean the same way along the long axis), converts the rectangle into a parallelogram. The triangles shift each short side into a slanted edge while preserving the top and bottom horizontal edges. ''A regular hexagon'' has six sides with equal lengths and angles, neither of which the rectangle plus triangle pair produces. ''A hexagon with two right angles'' would require the original short sides of the rectangle to survive as vertical edges, but the triangles replace them. ''A parallelogram with clipped corners'' would require additional cuts.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-11'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Six pieces labeled A–F. Piece A is a medium square. Piece B is a medium square of identical size. Piece C is a right triangle with legs equal to the side of A. Piece D is an identical triangle to C. Piece E is a small rectangle 1×2 units. Piece F is a 1×1 square. All pieces assembled without gaps or overlap: which overall shape is formed?', '["A square whose side equals twice the side of piece A","A rectangle twice as long as it is wide","An irregular pentagon","A large right triangle"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Two squares of side s (A and B) form a 2s by s rectangle when joined edge to edge. The two right triangles with legs s each fill the two open corners above (or below), extending the figure into a 2s by 2s square. The thin rectangle E and the small square F fit into the remaining interior gaps to complete the tiling. The result is a square whose side equals 2s, twice piece A. ''A 2:1 rectangle'' covers only the first step. ''An irregular pentagon'' has five sides, which an enclosed tiling does not produce. ''A large right triangle'' has the wrong outline entirely.', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-12'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Piece A is a large isosceles trapezoid with a long base of 4 units, a short top of 2 units, and height 2 units. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 units each. Piece C is an identical right triangle to B. When B is placed against trapezoid A''s left slanted edge and C is placed against the right slanted edge, what overall shape is formed?', '["A large rectangle 4 units wide and 2 units tall","A large square 4 units on each side","A regular hexagon","A parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The trapezoid has a long base of 4 and short top of 2, leaving a horizontal offset of 1 unit on each slanted side. Each right triangle placed against a slanted edge fills the gap between that slant and a vertical line, extending the trapezoid into a rectangle with width matching the long base and height matching the trapezoid''s height. The result is a 4 by 2 rectangle. ''A 4 by 4 square'' would require doubling the height. ''A regular hexagon'' needs six equal sides, not four. ''A parallelogram'' would result if both triangles slanted in the same direction, but mirrored triangles square off both ends.', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-13'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Piece A is a large square. A smaller square piece B (half the side of A) is cut from the center-right of A, leaving an L-shape. Piece C is that same smaller square. Piece D is a right triangle with legs equal to half the side of A. When pieces A (L-shape), C, and D are assembled in a flat arrangement without overlap, what results?', '["A shape identical to the original large square A","A right triangle larger than piece D","A rectangle that is 1.5 times as long as it is wide","A pentagon"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Re-attaching the missing square (piece C) to the L-shaped remainder restores the original large square. Adding the right triangle D, which has legs equal to half the side of A, along one outer edge extends the figure by a triangular bump. With the right proportion choice, that bump completes the shape into a rectangle 1.5 times longer than it is wide. ''A shape identical to the original square'' ignores piece D. ''A right triangle'' would require the square to fold into a triangle, which it cannot. ''A pentagon'' would result from triangle D being attached at an angle or only partially.', false, 'draft', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-14'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-15', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 3, 'Pieces A, B, C, D are four congruent parallelograms, each with a horizontal top edge and slanted sides leaning to the right. When the four pieces are arranged in a 2×2 grid with alternating orientations (every other piece flipped upside down), what overall shape is formed?', '["A large parallelogram","A large rectangle","A rhombus","An irregular hexagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each parallelogram leans the same direction on its own, but flipping every other parallelogram in a 2 by 2 grid reverses its slant. When laid out, the slanted edges of adjacent flipped and unflipped pieces meet to form straight vertical edges along the left and right of the grid, while the top and bottom remain horizontal. The combined boundary is a rectangle. ''A large parallelogram'' would result from placing all four in the same orientation, not alternating. ''A rhombus'' has four equal slanted sides, which alternating parallelograms cancel out. ''An irregular hexagon'' would require six sides, but the alternation produces exactly four straight edges.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-15'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-16', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Seven pieces: Piece A is a regular hexagon with a dot at its center. Pieces B through G are six equilateral triangles, each with one side equal to the side length of hexagon A. When all six triangles (B–G) are placed against each outer edge of hexagon A, what shape results?', '["A larger regular hexagon","A 12-pointed star","A regular 12-sided polygon (dodecagon)","A six-pointed Star of David shape"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A regular hexagon has 120 degree interior angles. At every hexagon vertex, two adjacent triangles meet, each contributing one 60 degree base angle. That leaves 360 minus 120 minus 60 minus 60 equals 120 degrees of empty space outside the hexagon at each vertex, which is a concave inward notch. The six triangle apexes form the convex outward points, and the six concave notches sit between them, producing a six-pointed Star of David shape (hexagram). ''A larger regular hexagon'' is the trap of assuming adjacent triangle edges line up, but they meet at a 120 degree concave angle, not 180. A ''dodecagon'' would need equal convex angles, not alternating tips and notches. A ''12-pointed star'' would need 12 tips, but the figure has only 6.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-16'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-17', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4 units. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4 units (identical to A). Piece C is a 3 by 4 rectangle. When A and B are joined along their hypotenuses to form a rectangle, and C is placed along the 4-unit side of that combined rectangle, what shape is formed?', '["A square with side 5 units","A rectangle 4 units wide and 6 units tall","A rectangle 3 units wide and 8 units tall","A 3 by 4 rectangle"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two right triangles with legs 3 and 4 joined along their hypotenuses reconstitute a 3 by 4 rectangle (area 12), because cutting a rectangle along its diagonal gives exactly those two triangles. Placing the second 3 by 4 rectangle C against the 4-unit side stacks the two rectangles into a 4 wide by 6 tall figure (total area 24). ''A 5 by 5 square'' has area 25 and does not match the combined area. ''A 3 by 8 rectangle'' would require joining the rectangles along their 3-unit sides, not the 4-unit sides specified in the stem. ''A 3 by 4 rectangle'' counts only the first step of assembly.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-17'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Pieces A–D are four identical right trapezoids, each with a long parallel side of 4 units, a short parallel side of 2 units, and height 2 units. The slanted leg rises from the right end of the long base. When the four trapezoids are arranged so that each slanted leg fits flush against the next piece''s slanted leg (alternating flip), what overall shape results?', '["A large square","A large regular octagon","A large rectangle 8 units wide and 4 units tall","A large parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each pair of mirrored trapezoids (normal + flipped) forms a rectangle 6 units wide and 2 units tall. Two such pairs stacked vertically give a rectangle 6×4 — but joining all four end-to-end yields 8 units wide × 2 units tall when laid flat. Accounting for all edges correctly: four trapezoids in alternating-flip row produce an 8×2 rectangle; two rows give 8×4.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-18'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 4, 'Three pieces: Piece A is a medium square (side = 2 units) with a diagonal arrow pointing from the bottom-left to the top-right corner. Piece B is a right triangle with legs 2 and 2 units (the lower-left half of a same-sized square). Piece C is a right triangle with legs 2 and 2 units (the upper-right half). When A, B, and C are assembled flat without overlap, what shape results?', '["A 2×4 rectangle","A large right triangle with legs 4 units each","A large square with side 2√2","A 2×2 square with two triangular ears on the sides"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Piece A is a 2 by 2 square (area 4). Pieces B and C are right triangles with legs 2 and 2 (area 2 each). Total area = 8, matching a right triangle with legs 4 and 4. The square fits one corner of that larger triangle and the two right triangles fill the other two corner regions. ''A 2 by 4 rectangle'' has area 8 too, but its four-right-angle outline does not match the L-shaped reassembly. ''A square with side 2 times sqrt 2'' has area 8 but requires a rotated arrangement. ''A 2 by 2 square with triangular ears'' leaves protrusions rather than enclosing a clean shape.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-19'),
  ('AO-PA-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 5, 'Five pieces are shown. Piece A is a large equilateral triangle (side 4 units). Pieces B, C, D are small equilateral triangles (side 2 units). Piece E is a rhombus made from two small equilateral triangles joined at one edge. When A, B, C, D, and E are assembled, which shape results?', '["A regular hexagon with side 2 units","A larger equilateral triangle with side 6 units","A trapezoid","A regular hexagon with side 4 units"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Measure everything in units of small triangles (side 2 each). Large triangle A (side 4) holds 4 small-triangle areas. The three small triangles add 3. The rhombus E (two joined) adds 2. Total = 9, exactly the area of an equilateral triangle with side 6. They tile that triangle with A at one corner, the rhombus filling an adjacent strip, and the small triangles completing the outer edge. ''A hexagon side 2'' has area 6 small-triangle units, too small. ''A trapezoid'' has the wrong outline. ''A hexagon side 4'' has area 24, far too large.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.pattern-assembly::AO-PA-B7-20'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A rectangular prism (box) is sitting with its longest dimension running left to right. If you rotate it 90° by tipping it backward (the top face tilts away from you, rotating around the back-bottom edge), which face is now on top?', '["The original top face","The original bottom face","The original back face","The original front face"]'::jsonb, 3, 'When the prism tips backward around its back-bottom edge, that edge stays fixed and the cube falls onto its back face. The original top rotates away to become the new back, the original front swings upward to occupy the top position, and the original bottom moves to face the viewer as the new front. So the new top is the original front face. ''The original top face'' would only stay on top if no rotation occurred. ''The original bottom face'' would require a 180 degree rotation. ''The original back face'' rotates downward to the bottom, not upward.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-1'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube has colored stickers: top = orange, bottom = purple, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = white. The cube is picked up and turned upside-down (rotated 180° around a horizontal front-to-back axis). What color is now on top?', '["Orange","Purple","Red","Blue"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Flipping the cube 180 degrees around the horizontal front-to-back axis spins it like a wheel through the front and back faces, swapping top with bottom and left with right while front and back remain fixed. The original bottom (purple) ends up on top. ''Orange'' would only stay on top if no rotation had occurred. ''Red'' and ''Blue'' label the front and back faces, which the axis preserves rather than moves to the top.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-2'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'You are looking directly at the front face of a rectangular prism. It is then rotated 90 degrees around its vertical axis so that the left side swings toward you. Which face is now facing you?', '["The original front face","The original right face","The original back face","The original left face"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The stem tells you directly which face moves where: the left side swings toward you, so the new front is the original left face. After this quarter turn, the original front has rotated to become the new right side, the original right has rotated to the new back, and the original back has rotated to the new left. Choice B confuses the rotation direction (right swinging forward would be a rotation in the opposite sense). Choice A would require no rotation at all. Choice C would require a 180 degree spin, not 90.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-3'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube: top = silver, bottom = gold, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90° to the right around the vertical axis (the right face swings to the front). Then rotate 90° forward — tilting the new top toward you, pivoting around the new front-bottom edge. What color is now on top after both rotations?', '["Yellow","Silver","Red","Blue"]'::jsonb, 0, 'After rotation 1 (90° right around vertical axis): the right face (yellow) moves to front, the front (red) moves to left, the left (green) moves to back, the back (blue) moves to right; top stays silver. After rotation 2 (90° forward, pivoting around the front-bottom edge): the new front face (yellow) swings up to become the new top. Final top = yellow (index 0).', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-4'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A rectangular prism is 2 units wide, 3 units tall, and 4 units deep. You view it from directly in front. If you then view it from directly above (bird''s-eye view), what shape do you see?', '["A 2×3 rectangle","A 2×4 rectangle","A 3×4 rectangle","A 4×4 square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The bird''s-eye view from directly above shows the prism''s top face, which is bounded by width and depth: 2 by 4. Height drops out of the view because the eye looks straight down along that axis. ''2 by 3'' is the front view (width by height). ''3 by 4'' is the side view (height by depth). ''4 by 4'' has no matching face on the prism. Each viewpoint projects out the dimension along its sight line, so identifying which dimension disappears (height for the top view) gives the answer directly.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-5'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has colored faces: top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate 90° to the left around its vertical axis, then rotate 90° backward (top tilts away from you, pivoting around the back-bottom edge). What color is now facing you (front) after both rotations?', '["Blue","White","Black","Yellow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rotation 1 (90° left, vertical): left (blue) → back, back (green) → right, right (yellow) → front, front (red) → left. Top = white, bottom = black. Rotation 2 (90° backward, around back-bottom edge): new top = original back = green; new front = original top = white; new bottom = original front = yellow; new back = original bottom = black. Front face = white.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-6'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A solid triangular prism rests with one rectangular face flat on a table. You view it from the front and see a rectangle. What shape do you see when you view it from the left end?', '["A rectangle","A triangle","A square","A trapezoid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A triangular prism has two triangular end faces and three rectangular side faces connecting them. The front view (a rectangular face) shows a rectangle. Looking at the left end reveals the triangular cross-section at that end. ''A rectangle'' would result from any side-face view but not an end-face view. ''A square'' would require equal-sided rectangles, which the problem does not guarantee. ''A trapezoid'' results from cutting a prism obliquely, not from looking at its standard end face.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-7'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube is placed with face 1 on top. It is then rotated 90° forward twice in a row (each time the top tilts toward you, pivoting around the front-bottom edge). After both rotations, which original face is now on top?', '["The original top face (face 1)","The original front face","The original bottom face (face opposite face 1)","The original back face"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each 90 degree forward rotation cycles the faces so that the face at the back rotates up to become the new top, the original top moves forward to become the new front, the original front rotates down to the bottom, and the original bottom rotates back to the rear. After one rotation, the original back is on top. After two rotations, the face that was at back-after-the-first rotation (which is the original bottom) is now on top. ''The original top'' would only return after four rotations. ''The original front'' is on top after three rotations, not two. ''The original back'' is on top after one rotation only.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-8'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube has faces numbered 1 (top), 2 (bottom), 3 (front), 4 (back), 5 (left), 6 (right). It is rotated 90° to the right (around vertical axis), then 90° to the right again, then 90° forward (around front-bottom edge). What number is on top?', '["1","3","4","2"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Starting state: top=1, bottom=2, front=3, back=4, left=5, right=6. Right rotation 1 (vertical axis): right→front, old front→left, old left→back, old back→right; top and bottom unchanged. After rot1: front=6, left=3, back=5, right=4; top=1, bottom=2. Right rotation 2: front=4, left=6, back=3, right=5; top=1, bottom=2. Forward rotation 3 (top toward you, front-bottom pivot): top→front, front→bottom, bottom→back, back→top. New top = old back = 3. Answer = 3, choice b, index 1.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-9'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A rectangular prism has dimensions 1×2×4 (height × width × depth). If you slice it with a horizontal plane halfway up its height, what shape is the cross-section?', '["A 1×2 rectangle","A 2×4 rectangle","A 1×4 rectangle","A square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A horizontal slice through the rectangular prism, taken at any height, exposes a face parallel to the top and bottom. Its dimensions are width by depth, which the problem states as 2 by 4. The vertical height of 1 unit does not appear in the cross-section because the cut is perpendicular to that axis. ''1 by 2'' uses height and width but omits depth. ''1 by 4'' uses height and depth but omits width. ''A square'' would require width equal to depth, which is not the case here.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-10'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees to the right around its vertical axis (the right face swings toward you to become the new front). What color is now on the left side?', '["Blue","Red","Green","Yellow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The stem specifies the direction: the right face swings forward to become the new front. The same quarter turn rotates the original front to the left, the original left to the back, and the original back to the right. Top and bottom sit on the rotation axis and do not move. The new left face shows the original front color, red. ''Blue'' was the original left and has rotated to the back. ''Green'' was the original back and now sits on the right. ''Yellow'' was the original right and is now on the front.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-11'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A regular tetrahedron (4 identical equilateral-triangle faces) rests on one face. You rotate it 120° around the vertical axis passing through the top vertex. How many faces look identical in position to where they started?', '["0","1","2","4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The top vertex stays fixed during a vertical-axis rotation. The face on the bottom (the base) stays in the same horizontal plane. 120° is exactly one-third of a full rotation, which is a symmetry of the triangular base — the base face maps to itself. The three side faces cycle among themselves. So exactly 1 face (the bottom) is in the same position.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-12'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A cube is sliced by a plane that passes through the midpoints of four parallel edges — specifically the four edges running left-to-right on the front and back faces (two on the front face, two on the back). What is the shape of the cross-section?', '["A square","A rectangle that is not a square","A rhombus","A trapezoid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The four edges referenced are the top-front, bottom-front, top-back, and bottom-back edges. Their midpoints sit at the cube''s horizontal middle and form the four corners of a square in the vertical plane running front-to-back through the center. The cross-section is a square. ''A rectangle that is not a square'' would require two distinct edge lengths, but the midpoints are equidistant. ''A rhombus'' has equal sides, but the 90 degree angles here make it specifically a square. ''A trapezoid'' has only one pair of parallel sides, while this cross-section has two pairs.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-13'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 5, 'A solid cylinder is cut by a plane that passes through the cylinder at an angle of 45° to the cylinder''s base (the plane intersects both the top and bottom circles). What shape is the cross-section?', '["A circle","A rectangle","An ellipse","A parabola"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Any plane that cuts a circular cylinder at an angle other than perpendicular (but not parallel to the axis) produces an elliptical cross-section. A perpendicular cut gives a circle; a cut parallel to the axis gives a rectangle.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-14'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-15', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 4, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees backward (the top tilts away, pivoting around the back-bottom edge), then 90 degrees to the left around the vertical axis. What color is on the bottom after both rotations?', '["Red","White","Green","Black"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Track the rotation as a die rolling. Rotation 1 tips the top away from the viewer over the back-bottom edge: the original top swings backward and down to become the new back (so white moves to back), the original back swings down to become the new bottom (green to bottom), the original bottom swings forward and up to become the new front (black to front), and the original front swings up to become the new top (red to top). Left and right are unchanged. Rotation 2 spins the cube about a vertical axis, which never changes top or bottom. The bottom remains green. Choice A (red) traces the rotation in the wrong direction (toward the viewer instead of away). Choice B (white) confuses the new back with the new bottom. Choice D (black) assumes the bottom stays put, ignoring rotation 1 entirely.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-15'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-16', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 3, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. Rotate the cube 90 degrees forward (top tilts toward you, pivoting around the front-bottom edge). What color is now on the back face?', '["White","Green","Red","Black"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A 90 degree forward roll cycles four faces around the cube: top moves to front, front moves to bottom, bottom moves to back, back moves to top. So the original bottom (black) is now on the back. The original top (white) became the new front, not the back, so choice A is the trap of stopping the trace one step early. Choice B (green) confuses the new top with the new back, because the original back face did move during the rotation. Choice C (red) is the trap of keeping the original front in place, but a forward rotation rolls every vertical face by one position.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-16'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A net consists of six squares arranged as follows: a row of four squares (labeled 1–4, left to right), square 5 attached to the top edge of square 2, and square 6 attached to the bottom edge of square 3. When this net is folded, what 3D object is formed?', '["An open-top box","A cube","A rectangular prism that is not a cube","A triangular prism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use square 2 as the base. Square 1 folds up as the left wall, square 3 folds up as the right wall, square 4 (attached to square 3) folds inward from the right wall to form the back wall, square 5 (atop square 2) folds up as the front wall, and square 6 (below square 3) folds inward to cap the top. All six equal squares enclose the volume, forming a cube. ''An open-top box'' covers only 5 squares with no lid. ''A rectangular prism that is not a cube'' would require unequal squares. ''A triangular prism'' requires triangular end faces, which the all-square net cannot produce.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-2'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net has the shape of a cross: one square in the center, one square above, one below, one to the left, one to the right, and one more square attached to the right edge of the rightmost square (6 squares total, forming a plus sign with an extra square on one arm). When folded, which face is opposite the center square?', '["The extra square on the extended arm","The square directly above the center","The square directly below the center","The square to the left of the center"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Label: center=C, top=T, bottom=B, left=L, right=R, extra=E (right of R). Fold: C is the base. T, B, L, R fold up to become four side walls. E, which is two squares away from center in the right direction, folds over to become the top (opposite C). T and B are adjacent to C, so they fold to be front/back walls — not opposite C.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-3'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A net consists of a column of four squares numbered 1–4 (top to bottom). Square 5 is attached to the right edge of square 1, and square 6 is attached to the right edge of square 4. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 2?', '["Square 4","Square 5","Square 6","Square 3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (above 2) folds to become the back wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds to become the front wall. Square 4 (below 3): when 3 is the front wall, 4 folds over it to become the top. Square 5 (right of square 1): when 1 is the back wall, 5 folds along with it to become the right wall. Square 6 (right of square 4): when 4 is the top, 6 folds down to become the left wall. Opposite the base (square 2) is the top = square 4. Answer: square 4, choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-4'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A net for a cube is laid out as follows: a row of three squares (A, B, C) from left to right. Square D is above square B. Square E is below square B. Square F is to the right of square C. When folded, which square is opposite square A?', '["Square C","Square F","Square D","Square E"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign B as the base. A (left of B) folds up to become the left wall. C (right of B) folds up to become the right wall. F (right of C): when C is the right wall, F continues to become the top. D (above B) folds to become the front wall. E (below B) folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=B, top=F, left=A, right=C, front=D, back=E. Opposite A (left) = C (right) = choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-5'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A net consists of a column of four squares (1 at top, 2, 3, 4 at bottom). Square 5 is attached to the left edge of square 2. Square 6 is attached to the right edge of square 3. When folded into a cube, which two squares are opposite each other?', '["Square 1 and square 4","Square 2 and square 4","Square 5 and square 6","Square 1 and square 3"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Fold step by step with square 2 as base. Square 1 (above 2) folds up → back wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds up → front wall. Square 4 (below 3) continues: it folds over the front wall to become the top (opposite base=2). Square 5 (left of 2): folds up → left wall. Square 6 (right of 3): when square 3 becomes the front wall, square 6 (on its right edge) folds to become the right wall. Opposites: bottom(2) ↔ top(4); back(1) ↔ front(3); left(5) ↔ right(6). Therefore squares 5 and 6 are opposite.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-6'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A net consists of a row of four squares (W, X, Y, Z from left to right). Square V is attached to the top edge of square X, and square U is attached to the bottom edge of square Y. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square Z?', '["Square W","Square V","Square U","Square X"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Assign X as the base. W (left of X) folds up to become the left wall. Y (right of X) folds up to become the right wall. Z (right of Y): when Y is the right wall, Z folds over to become the top. V (above X) folds to become the front wall. U (below Y): when Y is the right wall, U is on Y''s bottom edge, folding to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=X, top=Z, left=W, right=Y, front=V, back=U. Opposite Z (top) = X (bottom) = choice d, index 3.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-7'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A T-shaped net of 6 squares: a row of three squares (P, Q, R) forms the top of the T. Square S is below Q. Square T is below S. Square U is below T. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square P?', '["Square R","Square T","Square U","Square S"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Assign Q as the base. P (left of Q) folds up to become the left wall. R (right of Q) folds up to become the right wall. S (below Q) folds up to become the front wall. T (below S): when S is the front wall, T folds over it to become the top. U (below T): when T is the top, U folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=Q, top=T, left=P, right=R, front=S, back=U. Opposite P (left) = R (right) = choice a, index 0.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-8'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net of 6 squares arranged as: Row 1 has squares A and B (A left, B right). Row 2 has squares C and D (C below A, D below B). Row 3 has squares E and F (E below C, F below D). When folded into a rectangular prism (all squares are the same size, so it is a cube), which square is opposite square B?', '["Square A","Square C","Square E","Square F"]'::jsonb, 2, 'This 2×3 grid net folds as follows: let D be the base. C (left of D) folds up → left wall. B (above D, in row 1) folds up → back wall. A (above C, in row 1) is attached to C; it folds to become the top. E (below C, in row 3) folds up → front wall. F (below D, in row 3) folds up → right wall. Faces: bottom=D, top=A, left=C, right=F, back=B, front=E. Opposite B (back) = E (front) = choice c (index 2).', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-9'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net consists of: a central square M, square N attached to M''s top edge, square O attached to N''s top edge, square P attached to M''s right edge, square Q attached to M''s bottom edge, and square R attached to Q''s bottom edge. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square O?', '["Square Q","Square M","Square R","Square N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign M as the base. N (above M) folds to become the back wall. O (above N): when N is the back wall, O folds over it to become the top. P (right of M) folds to become the right wall. Q (below M) folds to become the front wall. R (below Q): when Q is the front wall, R folds over it to become the bottom — but since M is the base, R becomes the additional face; the six faces are M(bottom), O(top), N(back), Q(front), P(right), R(left). Opposite O (top) = M (bottom)? No: each square is a distinct face. The face chain from O downward: O→N→M→Q→R. O and R are two squares apart through the spine, making them opposites. Opposite O = R = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-10'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A cross-shaped net of 5 squares: square 1 in center, squares 2–5 attached to each of its four sides (top, bottom, left, right). A sixth square (6) is attached to the top edge of square 2 (which is above square 1). When folded, which square is opposite square 1 (the center)?', '["Square 2","Square 6","Square 3","Square 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Let square 1 = base. Square 3 (bottom of 1) → front wall. Square 4 (right of 1) → right wall. Square 5 (left of 1) → left wall. Square 2 (top of 1) → back wall. Square 6 (top of 2): when 2 is the back wall, 6 is on 2''s top edge — it folds over to become the top (opposite base 1). Opposite square 1 = square 6.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-11'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 4, 'A net of 6 squares: square A is the base of a column. Above A are squares B, C (in order from bottom to top). Square D is attached to the right edge of A. Square E is attached to the right edge of B. Square F is attached to the left edge of C. When this net is folded into a cube, which square is opposite square F?', '["Square D","Square A","Square E","Square B"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign B as the base. A (below B) folds up to become the front wall. C (above B) folds up to become the back wall. E (right of B) folds to become the right wall. D (right of A): when A is the front wall, D is on A''s right edge and folds to become the bottom. F (left of C): when C is the back wall, F is on C''s left edge and folds to become the left wall. Face assignments: top=B, front=A, back=C, right=E, bottom=D, left=F. Opposite F (left) = E (right) = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-12'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 3, 'A square sheet is folded once by bringing the left edge to meet the right edge (a vertical fold, creating a rectangle half the original width). A hole is then punched through all layers at the center of the folded rectangle. When the sheet is unfolded, how many holes are there, and where?', '["One hole in the exact center of the original sheet","Two holes symmetrically placed left and right of center, each at the vertical midpoint","Four holes at the four quadrant centers","Two holes — one in the center of each half — stacked vertically"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single vertical fold halves the sheet''s width and stacks two layers along the fold. The punch goes through both layers at the center of the folded rectangle. When unfolded, the two punch holes appear mirrored across the vertical fold line, both at the same vertical height (the midpoint). ''One hole in the exact center'' would result only if the punch were on the fold line itself. ''Four holes at quadrant centers'' requires two perpendicular folds, not one. ''Two holes stacked vertically'' would result from a horizontal fold, not vertical.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-13'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-17', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'A cube net is arranged as follows: a zigzag row of four squares — square 1, then square 2 to the right of 1, then square 3 above 2, then square 4 to the right of 3. Square 5 is below square 2. Square 6 is to the right of square 4. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 1?', '["Square 3","Square 4","Square 6","Square 5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (left of 2) folds up to become the left wall. Square 5 (below 2) folds up to become the front wall. Square 3 (above 2) folds up to become the back wall. Square 4 (right of 3): when 3 is the back wall, square 4 is on 3''s right edge and folds to become the right wall. Square 6 (right of 4): when 4 is the right wall, square 6 folds to become the top. Face assignments: bottom=2, top=6, left=1, right=4, front=5, back=3. Opposite left (1) = right (4) = choice b, index 1.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-17'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-1', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A staircase of cubes is built against a wall: the first column from the left is 1 cube tall, the second is 2 cubes tall, and the third is 3 cubes tall. Each column is 1 cube wide and 1 cube deep. How many total cubes are in the staircase?', '["5","6","7","9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each column contains as many cubes as its height: 1 + 2 + 3 = 6 cubes. The staircase formula n(n+1)/2 with n = 3 confirms 3 times 4 divided by 2 = 6. ''5'' undercounts, perhaps missing the top cube of the tallest column. ''7'' overcounts by 1. ''9'' applies the formula for a 3 by 3 grid (9 cubes), which is the bounding box rather than the actual staircase shape.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-1'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-2', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A rectangular arrangement of cubes is 4 cubes long, 2 cubes wide, and 1 cube tall (a single flat layer). How many cubes are in the arrangement?', '["6","7","8","10"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the three dimensions: 4 long times 2 wide times 1 tall = 8 cubes. ''6'' undercounts, possibly by adding instead of multiplying (4 + 2 = 6). ''7'' has no clear derivation. ''10'' overcounts, possibly by adding the dimensions and an extra 4 (4 + 2 + 4 = 10). The volume formula L times W times H gives 8 directly.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-2'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-3', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A 2×2×2 cube structure is built from unit cubes. How many unit cubes are used in total?', '["4","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A 2 by 2 by 2 cube structure contains 2 times 2 times 2 = 8 unit cubes. ''4'' is the count of cubes in a single 2 by 2 layer, missing the second layer above. ''6'' is the count of faces on a cube, not unit cubes inside. ''12'' is the count of edges on a cube, also not the unit count. The volume formula resolves directly to 8.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-3'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-4', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A structure has a base layer of 3×3 cubes (9 cubes) and a top layer of only the four corner positions of that 3×3 grid (4 cubes at the corners). How many total cubes are in the structure?', '["9","11","13","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Bottom layer is 3 by 3 = 9 cubes. Top layer has only the four corner positions = 4 cubes. Total = 9 + 4 = 13. ''9'' counts only the bottom and forgets the corners on top. ''11'' miscounts the corner additions (perhaps using 2 instead of 4). ''16'' would result from a fully filled second layer (also 3 by 3), but the problem specifies only the corners.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-4'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-5', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A 3×3×3 large cube is assembled from unit cubes. How many unit cubes have exactly two painted faces if only the outside surface of the large cube is painted?', '["8","12","16","24"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly 2 painted faces sit on the edges of the large cube but not at the corners. A 3×3×3 cube has 12 edges, each with 1 non-corner edge cube. So: 12 × 1 = 12 edge cubes have exactly 2 painted faces.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-5'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-6', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'Looking at a structure from directly above, you see a 3×3 grid with a hole in the center (the center position is empty). All visible squares are exactly 1 cube tall. How many total unit cubes are in the structure?', '["7","8","9","12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 3 by 3 footprint has 9 positions. The center position is empty, so 9 minus 1 = 8 cubes remain. Each cube is 1 unit tall, so there is no additional vertical multiplication. ''7'' undercounts by 1, perhaps removing two positions instead of one. ''9'' ignores the hole. ''12'' overcounts, possibly by treating the structure as having a second layer.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-6'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-7', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 3×3×3 large cube is built from unit cubes. All six outer faces are painted red. How many unit cubes have exactly three painted faces?', '["4","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Three-face cubes sit at the corners of the large painted cube, since each corner sits at the intersection of three outer faces. Any cube has exactly 8 corners, so 8 unit cubes have three painted faces, regardless of the cube''s overall size (as long as it is at least 2 units per side). ''4'' confuses corners with face count of a tetrahedron or a different solid. ''6'' is the count of face centers (one-face cubes). ''12'' is the count of edges (two-face cubes for a 3 by 3 by 3 cube).', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-7'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-8', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 5×5×5 large cube is assembled from unit cubes. How many unit cubes are completely hidden (touch no outer face)?', '["9","16","27","64"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Peel off the painted outer shell, one cube thick, on every side. The hidden interior of a 5 by 5 by 5 cube measures (5 minus 2) cubed = 3 cubed = 27 unit cubes. ''9'' uses 3 squared instead of 3 cubed, dropping a dimension. ''16'' uses 4 squared, mixing up the formula. ''64'' uses 4 cubed, which is the surface cube count rather than the hidden interior. The (n minus 2) cubed rule applies to any cube with n at least 3.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-8'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-9', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A 4×4×4 large cube is built from unit cubes and all six outer faces are painted. How many unit cubes have exactly one painted face?', '["16","24","36","48"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly one painted face are in the center of each face (not on any edge). Each face of a 4×4×4 cube has (4−2)² = 4 such cubes. Six faces × 4 = 24 cubes with exactly one painted face.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-9'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-10', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A tower is built: bottom layer is 4×4 (16 cubes), next layer is 3×3 (9 cubes) centered on the first, next is 2×2 (4 cubes), then 1×1 (1 cube). How many unit cubes are in the tower?', '["25","28","30","32"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the cubes per layer: 16 + 9 + 4 + 1 = 30. The pyramid follows the sequence of perfect squares from 1 to n squared, summed: in this case 4 squared plus 3 squared plus 2 squared plus 1 squared. ''25'' uses only 16 + 9, omitting the upper two layers. ''28'' undercounts by 2. ''32'' overcounts, possibly adding an extra layer. The straightforward sum of squares from 1 to 4 gives 30.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-10'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-11', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'A 3×3×3 cube has all six faces painted blue. It is then cut into 27 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have NO painted faces at all?', '["0","1","6","8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Zero-paint cubes have no exposed face. For a 3 by 3 by 3 cube, peel off the outer shell on every side: the hidden interior is (3 minus 2) cubed = 1 cubed = 1 unit cube, the single cube at the very center. ''0'' would be correct only for cubes 2 by 2 by 2 or smaller, where every unit cube touches an outer face. ''6'' is the count of face-center cubes (one-face cubes), each of which has one painted side. ''8'' is the corner count (three-face cubes).', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-11'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-12', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 4, 'An L-shaped structure is built on a table: one arm is 4 cubes long, 1 cube wide, and 1 cube tall. The other arm is 3 cubes long, 1 cube wide, and 2 cubes tall. The two arms share 1 corner cube. How many total cubes are in the structure?', '["9","10","11","13"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Count each arm separately, then subtract the shared cube to avoid double-counting. Arm 1 has 4 times 1 times 1 = 4 cubes. Arm 2 has 3 times 1 times 2 = 6 cubes. The two arms share 1 corner cube at their junction. Total = 4 + 6 minus 1 = 9. ''10'' forgets to subtract the shared cube. ''11'' overcounts further. ''13'' adds two extra cubes, possibly from miscounting arm 2. The inclusion-exclusion adjustment (subtract the overlap) is essential.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-12'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-13', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'A 4×4×4 large cube is built from unit cubes and all six outer faces are painted. How many unit cubes have exactly two painted faces?', '["12","24","36","48"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unit cubes with exactly two painted faces lie on the edges of the large cube but not at corners. A cube has 12 edges; each edge of a 4×4×4 cube has (4−2) = 2 non-corner cubes. Total: 12 × 2 = 24 cubes with exactly two painted faces.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-13'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-14', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 3, 'From the front, a structure appears as: 3 cubes across on the bottom row, 2 cubes in the middle row (centered), 1 cube on top (centered). Each stack is 1 cube deep. How many total cubes are in this pyramid viewed from the side?', '["4","5","6","9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the rows: 3 + 2 + 1 = 6 cubes. Each row is 1 cube deep, so the depth dimension does not multiply the count. ''4'' undercounts by 2, perhaps missing rows. ''5'' undercounts by 1. ''9'' would result from a 3 by 3 grid in every row instead of a stepped pyramid. The triangular pattern n + (n-1) + ... + 1 gives 6 for n = 3.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-14'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'A contractor charges a flat fee of $120 plus $45 per hour. A second contractor charges $60 per hour with no flat fee. For what number of hours will both contractors charge the same total amount?', '["4 hours","6 hours","8 hours","10 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set 120 + 45h = 60h, so 120 = 15h and h = 8 hours, where the per-hour gap of $15 closes the $120 flat fee. Choice 4 hours divides $120 by $30, mixing the rate difference with the wrong spread. Choice 6 hours divides $120 by $20, miscomputing the per-hour differential. Choice 10 hours divides $120 by $12, treating the gap as smaller than the actual $15 per hour.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B7-D5-1'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 5, 'A gear with 18 teeth meshes with a gear with 45 teeth. If the smaller gear rotates at 250 rpm, how fast does the larger gear rotate?', '["80 rpm","100 rpm","125 rpm","150 rpm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Speeds are inversely proportional to teeth, so larger gear rpm = 250 × (18/45) = 250 × 0.4 = 100 rpm. Choice 80 rpm uses about 18/56, miscounting the larger gear''s teeth. Choice 125 rpm halves the input speed, treating the ratio as 1:2 instead of 18:45. Choice 150 rpm multiplies by 18/30, undercounting the larger gear''s tooth count by 15 teeth.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B7-D5-2'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 5, 'A soldier''s test score was reduced by 12% due to a grading error. After the error was corrected, the score was increased by 20% of the reduced score. The original score was 250. What is the final corrected score?', '["250.0","264.0","247.2","270.0"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Reduced = 250 × 0.88 = 220, then final = 220 × 1.20 = 264. Choice 250.0 assumes −12% then +20% nets back to the original because the rates cancel, but each percentage applies to a different base. Choice 247.2 multiplies 220 × 1.12, using a 12% increase instead of 20%. Choice 270.0 applies the 20% increase to the original 250 (giving 300) minus the 12% reduction, mixing the order of operations.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.percent::AR-B7-D5-3'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'Two soldiers start at the same point and walk in the same direction. Soldier A walks at 4 mph; Soldier B walks at 6 mph. Soldier B starts 30 minutes after Soldier A. How long after B starts does B catch up with A?', '["45 minutes","1 hour","1 hour 15 minutes","1 hour 30 minutes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A''s head start = 4 × 0.5 = 2 miles, closing rate = 6 − 4 = 2 mph, so catch-up time = 2 ÷ 2 = 1 hour after B starts. Choice 45 minutes uses a 3 mph closing rate, adding instead of subtracting somewhere in the setup. Choice 1 hour 15 minutes uses a slower closing rate near 1.6 mph. Choice 1 hour 30 minutes reports the head-start time (30 min) plus another hour, mixing the two clocks.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.rate-distance-time::two-bodies'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 5, 'A barrel holds 84 gallons. A pump fills it at 7 gallons per minute, but a leak drains it at 1.75 gallons per minute. Starting empty, how many minutes does it take to fill the barrel?', '["12 minutes","14 minutes","16 minutes","18 minutes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Net fill rate = 7 − 1.75 = 5.25 gal/min, so time = 84 ÷ 5.25 = 16 minutes. Choice 12 minutes divides 84 by 7, ignoring the leak entirely. Choice 14 minutes uses about 6 gal/min net, rounding the leak down to 1 gal/min. Choice 18 minutes uses a net rate near 4.67 gal/min, rounding the leak up to about 2.33 and inflating its effect.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B7-D5-5'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'Three workers can paint a room in 6 hours. Two of the workers leave after 2 hours. The remaining worker finishes alone. How many total hours does the job take?', '["12 hours","14 hours","16 hours","18 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total job = 3 × 6 = 18 worker-hours. In the first 2 hours, 3 workers complete 6 worker-hours, leaving 12. One worker alone needs 12 hours for the remainder, so total elapsed time = 2 + 12 = 14 hours. Choice 12 hours forgets the first 2 hours of work and reports just the solo finish. Choice 16 hours uses 14 wh remaining, miscounting the work done in the first phase. Choice 18 hours reports the full worker-hours total.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B7-D5-6'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-7', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A boat travels 48 miles upstream in 4 hours and the same distance downstream in 3 hours. What is the speed of the current?', '["2 mph","3 mph","4 mph","5 mph"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Upstream speed = 48/4 = 12 mph (boat − current); downstream = 48/3 = 16 mph (boat + current); current = (16 − 12) / 2 = 2 mph. Choice 3 mph averages the trip times incorrectly. Choice 4 mph uses the full 16 − 12 = 4 spread without halving it, the most common upstream/downstream trap. Choice 5 mph splits 14 mph and rounds the boat-in-still-water speed up to a friendlier 15.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B7-D5-7'),
  ('AR-B7-D5-8', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 5, 'If 5 machines produce 300 widgets in 4 hours, how many machines are needed to produce 540 widgets in 3 hours?', '["9","10","12","15"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Per-machine rate = 300 / (5 × 4) = 15 widgets per machine-hour; in 3 hours, one machine makes 45 widgets, so machines needed = 540 ÷ 45 = 12. Choice 9 uses 540/60, treating per-machine output as 60 widgets/hr (mixing the time and output). Choice 10 uses 540 / (5 × 11), miscomputing the per-machine 3-hour output. Choice 15 scales 540/300 = 1.8 and multiplies by 5, ignoring the time change from 4 hours to 3 hours.', true, 'trusted', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B7-D5-8'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-2', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'INVETERATE most nearly means:', '["Recently reformed","Deeply experienced","Long-established and unlikely to change","Violently opposed"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Inveterate means firmly established by long habit, as in ''an inveterate smoker who has lit up daily for forty years.'' From Latin inveteratus, made old. Recently reformed is the direct antonym, naming change from a long habit. Deeply experienced is the most dangerous false friend: experienced people have done something for a long time, but inveterate emphasizes that the habit is ingrained and unlikely to change, while experienced is neutral about flexibility. Violently opposed is a register trap drawing on the harsh sound, but inveterate is about permanence, not hostility. Only Long-established and unlikely to change fits.', true, 'trusted', 'wk.headword::inveterate'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-3', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''The diplomat''s ANODYNE speech avoided any statement that might offend either side, leaving the audience with nothing to applaud or protest,'' the word ANODYNE most nearly means:', '["Highly persuasive","Inoffensive to the point of being dull","Deeply critical of both parties","Remarkably brief"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A speech that left ''nothing to applaud or protest'' pins the meaning to deliberate avoidance of any reaction. Anodyne specifically labels content drained of anything that could offend or excite. ''Highly persuasive'' is the opposite of evoking no response. ''Deeply critical of both parties'' would have produced protest, ruling it out. ''Remarkably brief'' addresses length, which the sentence never raises. Only Inoffensive to the point of being dull matches the deliberate blandness the clue describes, including the negative connotation of dullness.', true, 'trusted', 'wk.headword::anodyne'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-4', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The word PUSILLANIMOUS contains the Latin root ANIM (spirit/soul) and the prefix PUSILL- (very small). PUSILLANIMOUS most nearly means:', '["Extremely generous of spirit","Showing a lack of courage; cowardly","Spiritually enlightened","Overly animated or energetic"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PUSILLANIMOUS breaks down as PUSILL- (very small, from Latin pusillus) plus ANIM- (spirit, soul) plus -OUS (adjective-forming), literally ''small-souled.'' A small spirit shrinks from danger, so the word means cowardly. ''Extremely generous of spirit'' is the direct opposite (that would be magnanimous, great-souled). ''Spiritually enlightened'' reads ANIM- correctly but misses PUSILL-, treating ''small'' as humility rather than deficiency. ''Overly animated or energetic'' confuses ANIM- (soul) with animated (lively), a common error since animation and animal share the same root in surface meaning only. Only Showing a lack of courage fits.', true, 'trusted', 'wk.headword::pusillanimous'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-5', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root PATER (father) appears in PATERNALISTIC. A PATERNALISTIC policy is one that:', '["Grants full autonomy to individuals","Restricts freedom supposedly for people''s own good, like a father deciding for a child","Applies equally to all family members","Traces authority through the maternal line"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The root PATER comes from Latin meaning father. Cognates include paternal (fatherly), patriarch (a father-ruler), patron (a protector who acts like a father), paternity (fatherhood), and expatriate (one who has left the fatherland). A paternalistic policy treats adults like children under a father''s authority, restricting choices supposedly for their good. ''Grants full autonomy'' is the opposite. ''Applies equally to all family members'' confuses PATER with FAMIL- (family), which is broader. ''Traces authority through the maternal line'' would require MATER- (mother), the opposite root. Only Restricts freedom supposedly for people''s own good fits PATER plus the over-control connotation.', true, 'trusted', 'wk.headword::pater'),
  ('WK-B7-D5-6', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'SANGUINE most nearly means:', '["Pessimistic about the future","Optimistic and positive","Relating to blood or violence","Slow and deliberate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sanguine means optimistic, especially in a difficult situation. Although it derives from the Latin word for blood (a sanguine complexion was historically linked to a cheerful temperament), in modern usage it consistently means having a positive outlook. ''Relating to blood'' is the etymological trap.', true, 'trusted', 'wk.headword::sanguine'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-1', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Passage: ''The town council voted unanimously to fund the new water treatment plant, citing both aging infrastructure and rising contaminant levels. However, the project manager noted that costs had already exceeded projections by 40%, and the mayor quietly asked engineers to explore a scaled-back alternative.'' What can most reasonably be inferred from this passage?', '["The council regrets its decision to fund the project","The mayor supports the original project without reservation","Concerns about cost may lead to a modified or reduced project scope","Rising contaminant levels have been resolved by the council vote"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mayor''s request to ''explore a scaled-back alternative'' combined with costs 40% over budget strongly implies the original plan may be modified. The council vote shows approval in principle, not necessarily for the original scope. Contaminants are not yet resolved — the plant is only approved, not built.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-B7-D5-1'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Passage: ''Proponents claim the new regulation will protect consumers, but a closer examination reveals that its provisions were drafted almost entirely by the industries it purports to regulate. The oversight committee, composed largely of former industry executives, approved it in a single closed session. Whether this constitutes governance or theater is left as an exercise for the reader.'' What is the author''s tone?', '["Optimistic and encouraging","Objective and purely informational","Sardonic and skeptical","Alarmed and urgent"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The phrase ''left as an exercise for the reader'' is an ironic rhetorical device implying the answer is obvious without stating it. Combined with ''theater'' and the point about industry drafting its own regulations, the tone is sardonic skepticism, not neutral reporting or alarm.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B7-D5-2'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-3', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Passage: ''Urban heat islands form when dense concentrations of pavement, buildings, and human activity replace natural land cover. Cities can be up to 7°F warmer than surrounding rural areas. While tree-planting campaigns are popular, researchers find that highly reflective roof coatings — though less photogenic — reduce surface temperatures more efficiently per dollar invested. Policy makers who overlook this evidence in favor of visible green initiatives may be choosing optics over outcomes.'' What is the main idea?', '["Urban heat islands are caused primarily by industrial pollution","Tree-planting is the most cost-effective solution to urban overheating","Reflective roof coatings are more cost-efficient than tree planting at reducing urban heat, but are less politically appealing","Policy makers should avoid all green initiatives until more research is available"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage contrasts the popularity of tree planting with the superior cost-efficiency of reflective coatings, and explicitly criticizes policy makers who prioritize visible green projects. The main idea is that reflective roofs outperform trees economically but lose on optics.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.passage::urban-heat-island'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-4', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'Passage: ''The permafrost beneath Siberian tundra holds an estimated 1.5 trillion tons of organic carbon — roughly twice the amount currently in the atmosphere. As average temperatures rise, permafrost thaws and the organic material decomposes, releasing carbon dioxide and methane. Methane is approximately 86 times more potent than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over a 20-year period, though its atmospheric lifetime is shorter. Scientists warn this feedback loop could accelerate warming in ways that current climate models may underestimate.'' According to the passage, how much more potent is methane than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over 20 years?', '["20 times","50 times","86 times","100 times"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage gives the figure directly: methane is "approximately 86 times more potent than CO₂ as a greenhouse gas over a 20-year period." Choice C matches that number. Choice A picks up the "20-year period" detail and recycles the 20 as the potency multiplier, which is the classic number-swap trap on detail-recall items. Choice B is a plausible-looking distractor that does not appear anywhere in the passage. Choice D rounds 86 up to a familiar round number that the text does not state. Only C reflects the figure the passage actually provides.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B7-D5-4'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-5', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'Passage: ''The pharmaceutical company released its Phase 2 trial results, showing a 34% reduction in symptom severity versus placebo. Analysts noted, however, that the trial enrolled only 80 participants and excluded patients over 65 and those with common comorbidities. The FDA typically requires Phase 3 trials of 300–3,000 participants before approval.'' What can be most reasonably inferred?', '["The drug will likely receive FDA approval within one year","The Phase 2 results are fraudulent","The drug''s effectiveness in the broader population remains uncertain, and further trials are required","Excluding older patients proves the drug is ineffective for them"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage stacks three constraints: a small 80-person trial, exclusion of older and comorbid patients, and an FDA standard of "Phase 3 trials of 300–3,000 participants before approval." Together those facts point to uncertainty about the broader population and a clear next step. Choice C captures both. Choice A overreaches with a specific approval timeline the passage does not support. Choice B overreaches by leaping from limitations to fraud. Choice D overreaches in the opposite direction, treating exclusion (a study design choice) as proof of ineffectiveness. Only C stays within the evidence.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.inference::PC-B7-D5-5'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Passage: ''Advocates of universal basic income point to pilot programs in Finland and Kenya as proof of concept. Critics counter that these experiments are too small, too short, and too generously funded to scale globally. Both sides marshal the same limited data to opposite conclusions, a reminder that in policy debates, the evidence rarely speaks for itself.'' What is the author''s primary purpose?', '["To advocate for universal basic income","To discredit the critics of universal basic income","To highlight that the same evidence supports opposing conclusions, illustrating limits of policy data","To explain why pilot programs in Finland and Kenya succeeded"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author lays out both sides, then states the takeaway: "in policy debates, the evidence rarely speaks for itself." That meta-point about contested evidence is the actual purpose. Choice C captures it. Choice A misreads the balanced framing as advocacy for one position. Choice B does the same in reverse. Choice D assumes the pilot programs succeeded, when the passage frames their value as contested rather than settled. The author is not picking a side or evaluating outcomes; the author is commenting on how the same data fuels opposite arguments.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B7-D5-6'),
  ('PC-B7-D5-7', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Passage: ''Sleep deprivation does not merely cause fatigue. Research links chronic short sleep to increased risk of cardiovascular disease, metabolic disorders, and impaired immune response. Cognitive effects include reduced working memory, slower reaction time, and impaired judgment — the last of which may be the most dangerous because sleep-deprived individuals consistently underestimate their own impairment. A person who has slept 6 hours may feel alert while performing at the level of someone legally drunk.'' What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Six hours of sleep is sufficient for most adults","Sleep deprivation causes serious physical and cognitive harm, made worse by impaired self-awareness of that harm","Fatigue is the primary danger of insufficient sleep","Legal intoxication limits should apply to sleep-deprived drivers"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage opens by saying sleep deprivation "does not merely cause fatigue," then catalogs physical harms (cardiovascular, metabolic, immune), cognitive harms (memory, reaction time, judgment), and the self-concealing twist that sufferers underestimate their own impairment. Choice B blends all three pieces. Choice A contradicts the passage, which frames six hours as dangerously impaired. Choice C names the harm the author explicitly rejects as the main point. Choice D invents a policy prescription about legal intoxication limits that the passage never proposes. Only B captures the full structure of harms plus hidden impairment.', true, 'trusted', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B7-D5-7'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'A soldier has twice as many push-ups completed as sit-ups. If he does 12 more sit-ups, both totals will be equal. How many push-ups did he complete originally?', '["12","18","24","36"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let sit-ups = s and push-ups = 2s. After 12 more sit-ups: s + 12 = 2s, so s = 12. Original push-ups = 2(12) = 24. The choice 12 returns the sit-up count rather than the push-up count. The choice 18 comes from treating the relation as 2s = s + 6 (halving the 12) or splitting the difference. The choice 36 comes from using 3s instead of 2s for push-ups, treating "twice as many" as "three times as many."', true, 'trusted', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B7-D5-1'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'A right triangle has legs of 5 cm and 12 cm. A square is constructed on the hypotenuse. What is the area of that square?', '["60 cm²","119 cm²","144 cm²","169 cm²"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Pythagorean theorem gives the hypotenuse: c = √(5² + 12²) = √(25 + 144) = √169 = 13 cm. The 5-12-13 triple shows up often. Square on the hypotenuse: 13² = 169 cm². The choice 60 cm² is the triangle''s area (1/2 × 5 × 12), not the square. The choice 119 cm² comes from c² = 144 − 25 (subtracting instead of adding the leg-squares). The choice 144 cm² squares only the longer leg (12²), forgetting the 5² contribution.', true, 'trusted', 'mk.geometry::pythagorean-triple'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Simplify: (2x²y)³ ÷ (4x³y²)', '["2x³y","2x²y","x³y","2xy³"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Cube the numerator: (2x²y)³ = 2³ · x⁶ · y³ = 8x⁶y³. Divide by 4x³y²: 8/4 = 2, x^(6−3) = x³, y^(3−2) = y. Result: 2x³y. The choice 2x²y subtracts exponents before cubing the numerator. The choice x³y forgets to divide the coefficients (leaves 8/4 unsimplified or treats it as 1). The choice 2xy³ swaps the surviving x and y exponents, putting the cube on the wrong variable.', true, 'trusted', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'A tank is 3/8 full. After adding 45 gallons it is 5/8 full. What is the total capacity of the tank?', '["120 gallons","150 gallons","180 gallons","210 gallons"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The 45 gallons raised the level from 3/8 to 5/8, a change of 2/8 = 1/4 of the tank. So 1/4 of capacity = 45 gallons, and capacity = 45 × 4 = 180 gallons. The choice 120 gallons comes from using 3/8 of capacity = 45 (the starting fraction, not the change). The choice 150 gallons comes from 45 ÷ 0.3 or another wrong fraction of capacity. The choice 210 gallons comes from adding the 45 gallons to the wrong base, or using 5/8 of capacity = 45.', true, 'trusted', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B7-D5-4'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'The sum of three consecutive odd integers is 111. What is the largest of the three integers?', '["35","37","39","41"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let the integers be n, n + 2, n + 4. Sum: 3n + 6 = 111, so 3n = 105 and n = 35. Largest = n + 4 = 39. Check: 35 + 37 + 39 = 111. The choice 35 returns the smallest of the three. The choice 37 returns the middle integer. The choice 41 comes from using n + 6 as the largest (treating four integers instead of three).', true, 'trusted', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B7-D5-5'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If 2/3 of a number equals 4/5 of another number, and the first number is 60, what is the second number?', '["40","48","50","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Compute 2/3 of the first number: 2/3 × 60 = 40. Set 4/5 of the second number equal to 40: (4/5)n = 40, so n = 40 × 5/4 = 50. The choice 40 returns the shared value, stopping one step too early. The choice 48 comes from multiplying 40 by 6/5 instead of 5/4. The choice 72 comes from multiplying 60 by 6/5 (using the wrong fraction relationship entirely).', true, 'trusted', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B7-D5-6'),
  ('MK-B7-D5-7', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'A rectangular room is 15 feet long and 10 feet wide. A diagonal brace runs from one corner to the opposite corner. What is the length of the brace, to the nearest whole foot?', '["16 feet","17 feet","18 feet","19 feet"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The diagonal of a rectangle uses the Pythagorean theorem on the length and width. d = √(15² + 10²) = √(225 + 100) = √325 ≈ 18.03 feet, which rounds to 18 feet. The choice 16 feet comes from √(225 + 25) or another arithmetic slip. The choice 17 feet comes from √289 = 17, using 15² + 8² by misreading the width. The choice 19 feet comes from √(225 + 144) and a width-misread to 12.', true, 'trusted', 'mk.geometry::MK-B7-D5-7'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A square sheet of paper has its four corners labeled A (top-left), B (top-right), C (bottom-right), and D (bottom-left). The sheet is folded by bringing corner B down to meet corner D (a diagonal fold along the line from A to C). Which shape does the folded paper form?', '["A smaller square","A right triangle with the right angle at corner A","A right triangle with vertices at A, the merged B-D point, and C","A rectangle"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Folding B onto D means the fold line is the perpendicular bisector of segment BD, which is the diagonal AC. Half of the square reflects across AC. Corners B and D merge to a single point, while A and C stay in place. The visible boundary has vertices at A, C, and the merged B-D point. ''A right triangle with the right angle at corner A'' misplaces the right angle: after folding, the right angle sits at the merged point, not at A. ''A smaller square'' would require a midline fold, not a diagonal one. ''A rectangle'' likewise requires a midline fold rather than a diagonal one.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-18'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'Six squares form a cube net in this arrangement: square 1 is in the top-left position. Square 2 is to the right of square 1. Square 6 is to the right of square 2. Square 3 is below square 2. Square 4 is to the right of square 3. Square 5 is above square 4 (same column as 4, sharing square 4''s top edge). When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square 1?', '["Square 4","Square 5","Square 6","Square 3"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Assign square 2 as the base. Square 1 (left of 2) folds up to become the left wall. Square 6 (right of 2) folds up to become the right wall. Square 3 (below 2) folds up to become the front wall. Square 4 (right of 3): when 3 is the front wall, square 4 is on 3''s right edge and folds to become the top. Square 5 (above 4): when 4 is the top, square 5 folds to become the back wall. Face assignments: bottom=2, top=4, left=1, right=6, front=3, back=5. Opposite left (1) = right (6) = choice c, index 2.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-19'),
  ('AO-PF-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 5, 'A rectangular sheet (2 units wide, 4 units tall) is folded in half by bringing the top edge to the bottom edge (horizontal fold → 2×2 square). Then folded again bringing the top edge to the bottom edge (another horizontal fold → 2×1 rectangle, four layers). A hole is punched at the center of this 2×1 rectangle through all layers. When fully unfolded, how many holes appear and how are they arranged?', '["One hole in the center of the sheet","Two holes side by side across the middle of the sheet","Four holes in a vertical column at the sheet''s horizontal center","Four holes in a 2×2 grid"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The first fold (top to bottom) creates 2 layers stacked vertically. The second fold (top to bottom again) creates 4 layers stacked vertically. Each fold halves the vertical extent and doubles the layers along the vertical axis, leaving the horizontal axis untouched. Punching the center of the 4-layer rectangle puts 4 punch points along the vertical axis at the horizontal center when unfolded, each at a different vertical position spaced by the fold intervals. ''One hole'' covers only a single layer. ''Two holes side by side'' would require a vertical fold, not horizontal. ''Four holes in a 2 by 2 grid'' requires perpendicular folds rather than two parallel folds.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::AO-PF-B7-20'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A 5×5×5 large cube is painted on all outer faces and then cut into 125 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have exactly one painted face?', '["36","48","54","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Unit cubes with exactly one painted face sit at the center of each outer face (not on any edge). Each face of a 5×5×5 cube has (5−2)² = 9 such cubes. Six faces × 9 = 54 unit cubes with exactly one painted face.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-18'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-19', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A hollow open-top box is built from unit cubes: outer dimensions are 4 wide × 4 deep × 3 tall, with walls and bottom exactly 1 unit thick and no top face. How many unit cubes make up this box?', '["28","36","40","48"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Build the count layer by layer. The bottom layer is a solid 4 by 4 = 16 cubes (the floor). Each of the 2 upper layers is the wall only: outer 4 by 4 = 16 positions minus the inner hollow 2 by 2 = 4 positions, leaving 12 wall cubes per upper layer. Two upper layers contribute 12 times 2 = 24. Total = 16 + 24 = 40. ''28'' undercounts, possibly with one upper layer only. ''36'' undercounts by 4, possibly missing the floor''s interior or one wall layer. ''48'' overcounts, possibly treating the upper layers as solid 4 by 4 = 16 each.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-19'),
  ('AO-SC-B7-20', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 5, 'A 4×4×4 large cube painted on all six outer faces is cut into 64 unit cubes. How many unit cubes have zero painted faces?', '["0","4","8","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hidden interior cubes do not touch any outer face. The hidden core of a 4 by 4 by 4 cube measures (4 minus 2) cubed = 2 cubed = 8 unit cubes. ''0'' would apply only for cubes 2 by 2 by 2 or smaller. ''4'' undercounts the interior. ''16'' overcounts, possibly by squaring 4 (the surface count of one face) instead of cubing 2. The (n minus 2) cubed rule works for any cube with n at least 3.', true, 'trusted', 'ao.spatial-counting::AO-SC-B7-20'),
  ('AO-3D-B7-18', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube: top = silver, bottom = gold, front = red, back = blue, left = green, right = white. The cube is rotated 180° around the vertical axis (spinning a half-turn so the front face goes all the way to the back). What color is now facing you (front)?', '["Red","Blue","Green","White"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 180 degree rotation around the vertical axis spins the cube halfway, so the original front swings all the way around to the back, and the original back rotates to the front. Top and bottom sit on the rotation axis and stay fixed. The original back (blue) becomes the new front. ''Red'' was the original front and is now on the back. ''Green'' and ''White'' are the left and right faces, which a vertical-axis rotation swaps with each other but does not move to the front (after a full 180 degree turn, left and right have also swapped, but neither ends up at the front).', true, 'trusted', 'ao.3d-visualization::AO-3D-B7-18'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A warehouse stores 24 boxes. Each box holds 12 items. How many items are in the warehouse?', '["36","252","288","296"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the count of boxes by items per box: 24 x 12. Break it down: 24 x 10 = 240, then 24 x 2 = 48, and 240 + 48 = 288. Choice 36 adds 24 + 12 instead of multiplying. Choice 252 reflects a mis-carried digit in the 24 x 12 column (treating 2 x 24 as 28). Choice 296 adds 8 too many, likely from carrying twice. The correct total is 288 items.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-1'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A truck began the day with 156 packages. The driver delivered 89. How many packages remain on the truck?', '["57","67","77","245"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract delivered packages from the starting count: 156 - 89. Stack the numbers and borrow from the tens column: 16 - 9 = 7 in the ones place, then 14 - 8 = 6 after borrowing in the tens place, giving 67. Verify by adding back: 89 + 67 = 156. Choice 245 adds the two numbers, inverting the operation entirely. Choice 77 forgets to subtract 1 from the tens column after borrowing, leaving 5 instead of 4. Choice 57 reflects subtracting 99 instead of 89, a misread digit. The driver has 67 packages left on the truck.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-2'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A bakery splits 144 cookies evenly into 12 boxes. How many cookies go in each box?', '["11","12","13","132"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide total cookies by number of boxes to find the size of each share: 144 / 12. Recall the multiplication fact 12 x 12 = 144, so the quotient is 12. Verify by multiplying back: 12 cookies per box x 12 boxes = 144 cookies total, matching the starting number. Choice 132 subtracts 12 from 144, treating the problem as removal rather than even partition into groups. Choice 11 reflects an off-by-one slip, perhaps recalling 11 x 12 = 132. Choice 13 over-shoots, since 13 x 12 = 156, which exceeds the actual total. Each box contains exactly 12 cookies.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-3'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A clerk buys 6 notebooks at $3.25 each. What is the total cost?', '["$9.25","$18.50","$19.50","$19.75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply quantity by unit price: 6 x $3.25. Split the price into whole dollars and cents to simplify. The dollar portion gives 6 x $3 = $18.00, and the cents portion gives 6 x $0.25 = $1.50. Add the parts: $18.00 + $1.50 = $19.50. Choice $9.25 adds 6 + 3.25, inverting the operation by using addition instead of multiplication. Choice $18.50 forgets the carry from the cents multiplication, treating 6 x $0.25 as $0.50 rather than $1.50. Choice $19.75 adds an extra quarter from a miscounted carry in the cents column. The total cost is $19.50.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-4'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A depot starts with 1,247 rounds. A shipment adds 968, and a training event uses 415. How many rounds remain?', '["1,690","1,800","2,215","2,630"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Work through the two operations in order: first add the shipment, then subtract the training expenditure. Step one: 1,247 + 968 = 2,215. Step two: 2,215 - 415 = 1,800. Choice 2,215 stops after the addition step, reporting the intermediate sum as the final answer without subtracting the training rounds. Choice 2,630 adds all three numbers together, ignoring that the training event removes rounds rather than adds them. Choice 1,690 reflects subtracting 525 instead of 415, a digit misread that swaps the 1 in the tens place for a 2. The depot has 1,800 rounds remaining.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-5'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A coach divides 84 athletes into 4 equal squads, then adds 15 reserves to one squad. How many athletes are in that enlarged squad?', '["21","27","36","51"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two operations are needed in a specific order: divide the athletes into equal squads first, then add reserves to the one enlarged squad. Step one: 84 / 4 = 21 athletes per squad. Step two: 21 + 15 = 36 athletes in the enlarged squad. Choice 21 reports the squad size before reserves arrive, stopping at the intermediate value and ignoring the second step. Choice 51 adds the reserves twice, computing 21 + 15 + 15 by double-counting the addition step. Choice 27 reflects a miscount in the addition step, perhaps adding 6 instead of 15. The enlarged squad has 36 athletes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-6'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A field has 80 trees. A storm destroys 0.75 of them. How many trees were destroyed?', '["20","60","75","40"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multiply the total count by the decimal fraction to find the affected portion: 0.75 x 80. Convert 0.75 into the equivalent fraction three-quarters, then take three-quarters of 80. One-quarter of 80 is 20, so three-quarters is 3 x 20 = 60. Verify with direct multiplication: 0.75 x 80 = 60. Choice 20 reports the trees that survived the storm (80 - 60), answering the opposite question from what was asked. Choice 75 treats 0.75 as a count of 75 trees directly, ignoring the multiplication. Choice 40 misreads 0.75 as one-half and computes 0.5 x 80. The storm destroyed 60 trees.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-7'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A shopper buys 3 pounds of beef at $4.80 per pound and 2 packs of buns at $3.25 each. She pays with a $30 bill. How much change does she receive?', '["$8.10","$9.10","$9.20","$20.90"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Three steps are required: compute each item subtotal, sum the subtotals to get the bill, then subtract from the amount tendered. Beef subtotal: 3 x $4.80 = $14.40. Bun subtotal: 2 x $3.25 = $6.50. Bill total: $14.40 + $6.50 = $20.90. Change owed: $30.00 - $20.90 = $9.10. Choice $20.90 reports the bill total itself, stopping at the intermediate value before the change calculation. Choice $9.20 reflects a ten-cent rounding error during the addition of subtotals. Choice $8.10 subtracts a miscomputed bill of $21.90. She receives $9.10 in change.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-8'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A driver travels at 60 miles per hour for 2 hours and 45 minutes. How many miles does he cover?', '["120","145","165","180"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert the minutes into a decimal fraction of an hour, then multiply by speed. 45 minutes equals 45/60 = 0.75 hour, so total time is 2.75 hours. Distance equals rate times time: 60 x 2.75 = 165 miles. Split the multiplication for clarity: 60 x 2 = 120, and 60 x 0.75 = 45, then 120 + 45 = 165. Choice 120 uses only the two whole hours, dropping the 45-minute portion. Choice 180 rounds the time up to 3 full hours before multiplying. Choice 145 treats 45 minutes as 0.45 hour, a unit-conversion error. The driver covers 165 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-9'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A teacher needs 3 pencils for each of her 18 students. Pencils are sold only in boxes of 12. What is the minimum number of boxes she must buy?', '["4","5","6","54"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Three steps: find total pencils needed, divide by box size to get boxes, then round up because partial boxes cannot be purchased. Pencils needed: 18 students x 3 pencils each = 54 pencils. Boxes required: 54 / 12 = 4.5 boxes. Since stores sell only whole boxes, round up to 5 so the class has enough. Buying only 4 boxes provides 48 pencils, leaving the class 6 short. Choice 4 rounds down and leaves the class short. Choice 54 reports the total pencil count rather than the number of boxes. Choice 6 over-rounds by one box, buying more than necessary. She must buy 5 boxes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-10'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A 5-gallon bucket of paint covers 1,750 square feet. How many gallons are needed to cover 4,200 square feet?', '["8","10","12","14"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up a unit-rate problem in two steps: find coverage per gallon, then divide the target area by that rate to find gallons needed. Coverage per gallon: 1,750 / 5 = 350 square feet per gallon. Gallons needed for 4,200 square feet: 4,200 / 350 = 12 gallons. Verify by multiplying back: 12 x 350 = 4,200, which matches the target area exactly. Choice 10 reflects dividing 4,200 by an incorrect per-gallon rate of 420. Choice 14 doubles the original five-gallon bucket without checking the proportion of areas. Choice 8 results from a miscomputed per-gallon rate near 525. The job requires 12 gallons of paint.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-11'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A worker earns $18 per hour for regular time and 1.5 times that for any hours over 40 in a week. She works 46 hours. What is her total pay?', '["$828","$882","$900","$1,242"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Split the 46 hours into regular and overtime portions, compute each pay segment, then add. Regular hours: 40 at $18 each = $720. Overtime hours: 46 - 40 = 6 hours. Overtime rate: 1.5 x $18 = $27 per hour. Overtime pay: 6 x $27 = $162. Total: $720 + $162 = $882. Choice $828 pays all 46 hours at the regular $18 rate (46 x $18 = $828), ignoring the overtime premium. Choice $1,242 applies the 1.5x multiplier to every hour worked rather than only hours above 40. Choice $900 rounds the overtime pay to a clean number. Her total pay is $882.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-12'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A truck has a maximum load of 2,000 pounds. Equipment weighing 380 pounds is already on board. How many 45-pound crates can be added without exceeding the limit?', '["32","35","36","44"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two steps: find remaining weight capacity after the existing load, then divide by crate weight. Remaining capacity: 2,000 - 380 = 1,620 pounds available. Crates that fit: 1,620 / 45 = 36 exactly, with no remainder. Verify: 36 x 45 = 1,620, exactly filling the remaining capacity. Choice 44 divides the full 2,000 by 45, ignoring the 380 pounds of equipment already on board. Choice 35 rounds the answer down by one, even though 36 crates fit perfectly. Choice 32 reflects dividing by 50 instead of 45, a misread weight. The truck can carry 36 more crates.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-13'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'Two vehicles start 270 miles apart and drive toward each other. One travels at 55 mph and the other at 35 mph. How many hours until they meet?', '["2.7","3","4","5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two objects move toward each other, the gap between them shrinks at a rate equal to the sum of their speeds. Add the speeds first, then divide the starting distance by that combined rate. Combined closing speed: 55 + 35 = 90 mph. Time to meet: 270 / 90 = 3 hours. Verify: in 3 hours the first car covers 55 x 3 = 165 miles and the second covers 35 x 3 = 105 miles, totaling 270. Choice 2.7 divides 270 by 100, a slipped digit. Choice 4 divides by the slower speed only. Choice 5 uses the faster speed alone. They meet in 3 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-14'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A tank holds 240 gallons when full. Water flows in at 8 gallons per minute while a drain removes 3 gallons per minute. Starting empty, how many minutes does it take to fill the tank?', '["30","48","53","80"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two opposing rates are at work, so find the net fill rate, then divide tank volume by that rate. Net rate: 8 gallons in minus 3 gallons out = 5 gallons per minute of actual filling. Time to fill: 240 / 5 = 48 minutes. Verify: in 48 minutes, 8 x 48 = 384 gallons flow in while 3 x 48 = 144 drain out, leaving 240 in the tank, matching its capacity. Choice 30 uses only the 8-gallon inflow, ignoring the drain. Choice 80 uses only the drain rate, inverting the problem. Choice 53 reflects a miscomputed net rate near 4.5. The tank fills in 48 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-15'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A student earns scores of 78, 85, and 92 on three tests. After a fourth test, her average across all four is exactly 84. What did she score on the fourth test?', '["79","81","82","84"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use the average formula: total points equals average times count. Required total: 84 x 4 = 336. Sum of first three: 78 + 85 + 92 = 255. Fourth score: 336 - 255 = 81. Choice 84 assumes the fourth score must equal the average, which only holds when the prior scores already average to 84. Choice 82 reflects an arithmetic slip in summing 78 + 85 + 92 as 254. Choice 79 subtracts in the wrong direction. She scored 81.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-16'),
  ('AR-AF-NEW-17', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'What is the sum of all whole numbers from 1 to 50, inclusive?', '["1,225","1,275","1,325","2,550"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use the arithmetic series formula: sum equals n times (n + 1) divided by 2, where n is the largest number. Here n = 50, so sum = 50 x 51 / 2 = 2,550 / 2 = 1,275. Choice 2,550 forgets to divide by 2, reporting n times (n + 1) directly. Choice 1,225 uses n = 49 by accident, summing 1 to 49. Choice 1,325 adds 50 to 1,275 a second time. The correct sum is 1,275.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-NEW-17'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 25% of 60?', '["12","15","18","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent of an amount uses the formula (percent/100) x amount. Plug in: 0.25 x 60 = 15. Choice 12 comes from using 20% instead of 25%, reading the percent loosely. Choice 18 comes from using 30% instead of 25%, also a misread. Choice 20 results from dividing 60 by 3, which would be one-third, not one-quarter. Reading 25% as one-quarter is a useful shortcut: 60 divided by 4 equals 15. Either method, formula or fraction conversion, lands on 15 cleanly.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, '30 is what percent of 150?', '["15%","20%","25%","30%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent-of-total uses the formula (part/whole) x 100. Plug in: (30/150) x 100 = 20%. A quick check: 150 divided by 5 equals 30, so 30 is one-fifth of 150, and one-fifth is 20%. Choice 15% halves the part incorrectly. Choice 25% comes from dividing 30 by 120 instead of 150, a wrong-base error that ignores the stated total. Choice 30% mistakes the part value for the answer, ignoring that the question asks for a ratio. The whole always goes in the denominator.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 15% of 80?', '["8","10","12","16"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent of an amount uses (percent/100) x amount. Plug in: 0.15 x 80 = 12. A fast method splits 15% into 10% plus 5%: 10% of 80 is 8, 5% of 80 is 4, and the sum is 12. Choice 8 stops at 10% and forgets the extra 5%. Choice 10 comes from rough rounding between the two pieces. Choice 16 doubles to 20% by mistake, treating 15% as if it were closer to one-fifth. The 10%-plus-5% trick handles most tip-style and sales-tax calculations quickly without a calculator.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'A recruit answered 18 questions correctly out of 20. What percent did the recruit get right?', '["80%","85%","90%","95%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent correct uses (correct/total) x 100. Plug in: (18/20) x 100 = 90%. Choice 80% comes from miscounting 4 missed instead of 2, since 16/20 = 80%, or from doubling the number wrong before converting. Choice 85% splits the difference without computing. Choice 95% comes from treating 1 missed question as 5% instead of 2 missed as 10%. The shortcut: each missed question out of 20 is worth 5 percentage points, so 2 missed equals 10 points off 100%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A $50 shirt is on sale for 30% off. What is the sale price?', '["$15","$20","$30","$35"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Sale price after a percent discount uses original x (1 - discount). Plug in: 50 x 0.70 = $35. Choice $15 confuses percent off with percent paid: 30% of 50 is the discount amount, not the price paid. Choice $20 comes from subtracting 30 directly from 50, treating the percent as a dollar amount. Choice $30 comes from using 40% off instead of 30%. The customer always pays (100 - discount)% of the original, which here is 70% of $50.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A dinner bill is $80. With an 18% tip, what is the total amount paid?', '["$14.40","$80.18","$94.40","$98.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total with tip uses bill x (1 + tip rate). Plug in: 80 x 1.18 = $94.40. The tip alone is 0.18 x 80 = $14.40, which appears as choice $14.40 but represents only the tip, not the total. Choice $80.18 treats 18% as 18 cents, a decimal-place error. Choice $98.00 uses 22.5% rounding or adds $18 flat instead of 18%. The question asks for the total paid, so the tip must be added to the original bill.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::AR-PC-NEW-6'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A recruit increased pushup reps from 100 to 125. What is the percent increase?', '["20%","25%","30%","125%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent increase uses (new - old)/old x 100. Plug in: (125 - 100)/100 x 100 = 25 / 100 x 100 = 25%. Choice 20% uses the new value 125 as the denominator (25/125), a wrong-base error common in percent-change problems. Choice 30% comes from rough estimation between 25 and 33. Choice 125% treats the new total as the percent change instead of computing the change relative to the starting value. The original value always goes in the denominator for percent change, because the question asks how much the count grew compared with where it started.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::percent-change'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A $200 item has an 8% sales tax. What is the total cost?', '["$208","$212","$216","$280"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total with tax uses price x (1 + tax rate). Plug in: 200 x 1.08 = $216. Tax alone is 0.08 x 200 = $16, then add to the price: 200 + 16 = $216. Choice $208 treats 8% as 8 dollars flat. Choice $212 uses 6% by mistake (0.06 x 200 = $12, plus $200 = $212). Choice $280 confuses 8% with 40% or treats tax as a much larger rate. A shortcut for 8% of a round number: take 10% and subtract one-fifth of it. 10% of 200 is 20, one-fifth of 20 is 4, so 8% is 16.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::AR-PC-NEW-8'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A practice score rose from 40 to 52. What is the percent increase?', '["12%","23%","30%","52%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Percent increase uses (new - old)/old x 100. Plug in: (52 - 40)/40 x 100 = 12/40 x 100 = 30%. Choice 23% divides by the new value 52 instead of the original 40, the classic wrong-base error. Choice 12% reports the raw point gain as a percent, ignoring the formula. Choice 52% mistakes the new score for the answer. The original value is always the denominator in percent change problems, because the question asks how much it grew relative to where it started.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::percent-change'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A $500 loan charges 6% simple interest per year. How much interest accrues over 2 years?', '["$30","$50","$60","$66"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Simple interest uses I = principal x rate x time. Plug in: 500 x 0.06 x 2 = $60. Choice $30 forgets the time factor and computes only one year of interest. Choice $50 misreads the rate as 5% and computes 500 x 0.05 x 2 = $50. Choice $66 reflects compound interest applied incorrectly (500 x 1.06 x 1.06 minus 500 rounds near 61.80, then bumped). Simple interest never compounds: each year adds the same fixed dollar amount, calculated from the original principal only.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::simple-interest'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A mile time dropped from 8:00 minutes to 6:00 minutes. What is the percent decrease?', '["20%","25%","33%","75%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent decrease uses (old - new)/old x 100. Plug in: (8 - 6)/8 x 100 = 2/8 x 100 = 25%. Choice 20% comes from dividing by 10 or a similar wrong-base slip. Choice 33% divides by the new value 6 instead of the original 8, a wrong-base error that inflates the answer. Choice 75% reports the ratio of new to old (6/8) as if it were the decrease, confusing percent remaining with percent change. Faster runs mean a decrease in time, but the formula stays the same.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::percent-change'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'A jacket costs $80. It is marked down 25%, then 8% sales tax is added to the sale price. What is the final price?', '["$60.00","$62.40","$64.80","$67.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sequential percent changes apply one at a time. Step 1: 80 x 0.75 = $60 sale price. Step 2: 60 x 1.08 = $64.80 final. Choice $60.00 stops after the discount and forgets to add tax. Choice $62.40 applies tax to the original $80 instead of the discounted $60, then subtracts the discount, an order error. Choice $67.00 combines 25% off and 8% tax into a single 17% net change, but sequential percentages on different bases do not add directly. The base for tax is the sale price, not the sticker price.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'After a 20% discount, a backpack costs $48. What was the original price?', '["$57.60","$60.00","$68.00","$76.80"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Working backward from a discounted price uses original = sale/(1 - discount). Plug in: 48/0.80 = $60. Choice $57.60 multiplies $48 by 1.20, treating the discount as if it added back as a percent increase on the sale price, but 20% of $48 is not the same as 20% of the original. Choice $68 adds a flat $20 to the sale price. Choice $76.80 divides by 0.625 or applies the wrong adjustment. The sale price represents 80% of the original, so dividing by 0.80 recovers 100%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-PC-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 5, 'A stock rises 20% one month, then falls 20% the next month. What is the net percent change from the starting price?', '["0% (no change)","4% decrease","4% increase","20% decrease"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Chained percent changes apply to different bases. Start with 1.00, multiply by 1.20 for the rise: 1.20. Then multiply by 0.80 for the fall: 1.20 x 0.80 = 0.96, which is a 4% decrease from the start. Choice 0% adds the percentages directly (+20 - 20 = 0), the classic trap, but the 20% drop applies to a larger base than the 20% gain did. Choice 4% increase reverses the direction. Choice 20% decrease ignores the first rise entirely. Equal-percent up-then-down sequences always net to a small loss.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::sequential-gain-loss'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A car travels at a steady 55 mph for 4 hours. How far does it go?', '["13.75 miles","59 miles","220 miles","275 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 55 mph times 4 hours, which is 220 miles. The choice 13.75 reverses the operation and divides 55 by 4. The choice 59 adds rate and time instead of multiplying. The choice 275 uses 5 hours instead of 4, a common slip when rereading the problem. Always identify which quantity is missing and pick the matching form of the formula before plugging in numbers.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-1'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A cyclist rides 36 miles at 12 mph. How long does the ride take?', '["2 hours","3 hours","4 hours","24 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use T = D / R. Time equals 36 miles divided by 12 mph, which is 3 hours. The choice 2 divides 36 by 18 by mistake. The choice 4 divides 36 by 9, often from misreading the rate. The choice 24 multiplies distance by 2 instead of dividing, the classic operation-flip trap. When you want time, isolate it on one side of the formula first so the arithmetic step is clear.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-2'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A runner averages 8 mph for 2 hours. How far does she run?', '["4 miles","10 miles","16 miles","82 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 8 mph times 2 hours, which is 16 miles. The choice 4 divides 8 by 2, reversing the operation. The choice 10 adds the rate and time. The choice 82 concatenates the digits, a sign of skipping the formula entirely. Even with friendly numbers, write D = R x T before computing so the operation is locked in.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-3'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A train moves at 75 mph for 6 hours. How many miles does it cover?', '["12.5 miles","81 miles","450 miles","475 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 75 mph times 6 hours, which is 450 miles. The choice 12.5 divides 75 by 6. The choice 81 adds the two numbers. The choice 475 comes from a multiplication slip where 75 x 6 is read as 75 x 6 + 25. Multiply column by column on scratch paper if the product is not automatic, and always pair the unit of the answer (miles) with the formula.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-4'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A car drives at 65 mph for 2.5 hours. How far does it travel?', '["26 miles","130 miles","162.5 miles","195 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use D = R x T. Distance equals 65 mph times 2.5 hours, which is 162.5 miles. Compute 65 x 2 = 130, then add half of 65, which is 32.5, for 162.5. The choice 26 divides 65 by 2.5. The choice 130 ignores the half hour. The choice 195 uses 3 hours instead of 2.5. With decimal time, split the hours into whole and fractional parts and multiply each before adding.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-5'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A bus drives at 40 mph for 45 minutes. How far does it go?', '["18 miles","30 miles","45 miles","1,800 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert minutes to hours first. 45 minutes equals 0.75 hour. Then D = R x T = 40 x 0.75 = 30 miles. The choice 18 uses 0.45 hour, a unit-conversion error treating minutes as a decimal. The choice 45 simply restates the time number with the wrong unit. The choice 1,800 multiplies 40 by 45 without converting minutes. Always convert mixed time units to hours before applying the formula.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-6'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A delivery van covers 240 miles at an average speed of 48 mph. How long does the trip take?', '["4 hours","5 hours","6 hours","192 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use T = D / R. Time equals 240 miles divided by 48 mph. 48 times 5 is 240, so the trip takes 5 hours. The choice 4 divides 240 by 60 by mistake. The choice 6 divides 240 by 40. The choice 192 subtracts 48 from 240, the wrong operation entirely. When the rate is close to a round number, test the round number first as a sanity check before doing long division.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-7'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A jogger runs for 1 hour 30 minutes at 22 mph on a bike-jog trail. How far does she go?', '["11 miles","23.5 miles","33 miles","44 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 1 hour 30 minutes to 1.5 hours. Then D = R x T = 22 x 1.5 = 33 miles. Compute 22 x 1 = 22 and add half of 22, which is 11, for 33. The choice 11 reports only the half-hour portion. The choice 23.5 adds 22 and 1.5. The choice 44 uses 2 hours instead of 1.5. Mixed time formats are the most common error source, so always rewrite them as a single decimal or fraction of an hour first.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-8'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A truck covers 90 miles in 1.5 hours. What is its average speed?', '["45 mph","60 mph","75 mph","135 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use R = D / T. Speed equals 90 miles divided by 1.5 hours, which is 60 mph. Multiply numerator and denominator by 2 to clear the decimal: 180 / 3 = 60. The choice 45 divides 90 by 2 instead of 1.5. The choice 75 splits the difference between 90 and 60 in a guessing pattern. The choice 135 multiplies 90 by 1.5 instead of dividing, the classic operation flip when solving for rate.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-9'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A driver covers the first 120 miles at 60 mph and the next 180 miles at 45 mph. What is the average speed for the entire trip?', '["50 mph","52.5 mph","54 mph","55 mph"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Average speed equals total distance divided by total time, not the average of the two rates. Time for leg one is 120 / 60 = 2 hours. Time for leg two is 180 / 45 = 4 hours. Total distance is 300 miles in 6 hours, so the average is 50 mph. The choice 52.5 is the arithmetic mean of 60 and 45, the classic trap. The choices 54 and 55 weight the legs incorrectly. When segments differ in length and rate, always sum the actual times.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-10'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'Two cars leave the same point heading the same direction. Car A travels at 50 mph and Car B travels at 65 mph. How far apart are they after 3 hours?', '["15 miles","45 miles","150 miles","345 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Same direction, so use the rate difference. The gap grows at 65 - 50 = 15 mph. After 3 hours the gap is 15 x 3 = 45 miles. The choice 15 reports only the rate difference and forgets the time. The choice 150 uses the sum of the rates, which would apply only if the cars were heading opposite directions. The choice 345 adds the two distances they traveled. For chase problems, work with the difference of the rates from the start.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-11'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A hiker walks 3 miles at 4 mph, then 5 miles at 5 mph. How long does the full hike take?', '["1 hour","1.5 hours","1.75 hours","2 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Compute each leg separately, then add. Leg one takes 3 / 4 = 0.75 hour. Leg two takes 5 / 5 = 1 hour. Total time is 0.75 + 1 = 1.75 hours. The choice 1 reports only the second leg. The choice 1.5 averages the two legs incorrectly. The choice 2 rounds 1.75 up to a tidier number. Resist the urge to average times or rates across legs of different lengths. Sum the actual minutes each piece takes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-12'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 4, 'A car leaves a rest stop at 60 mph. One hour later, a second car leaves the same rest stop on the same road at 75 mph. How far from the rest stop does the second car catch the first?', '["240 miles","270 miles","300 miles","375 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When the second car starts, the first car has a 60-mile head start. The closing speed is 75 - 60 = 15 mph. Catch-up time is 60 / 15 = 4 hours. Distance from the rest stop is 75 x 4 = 300 miles. The choice 240 uses the slower car''s distance at 4 hours, which is the same point but computed inconsistently in a way that often misfires. The choice 270 averages the two cars. The choice 375 uses 5 hours by mistake. Track who starts when and which rate is the gap closer.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-13'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 4, 'Two trains start 360 miles apart and head toward each other on parallel tracks. One travels at 55 mph and the other at 65 mph. How long until they meet?', '["2 hours","3 hours","3.6 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two objects move toward each other, add the rates to get the closing speed. 55 + 65 = 120 mph. Time to meet is 360 / 120 = 3 hours. The choice 2 uses only one rate. The choice 3.6 divides 360 by 100, a common slip when adding rates carelessly. The choice 6 uses the difference of the rates instead of the sum, which applies to same-direction chase problems. Sum for converging motion, subtract for catch-up.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::two-bodies'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A boat moves at 15 mph in still water. On a river with a 3 mph current, the boat travels 36 miles downstream and then 36 miles back upstream. How long does the round trip take?', '["4 hours","4.8 hours","5 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Downstream the current adds to the boat speed, so the effective rate is 15 + 3 = 18 mph. Upstream the current subtracts, giving 15 - 3 = 12 mph. Downstream time is 36 / 18 = 2 hours. Upstream time is 36 / 12 = 3 hours. Total is 5 hours. The choice 4 averages the two leg times. The choice 4.8 divides total distance 72 by 15, ignoring the current. The choice 6 divides 72 by 12, using only the slower leg''s rate. Compute each leg with its own effective rate.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-15'),
  ('AR-RD-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A plane flies 600 miles with a 40 mph tailwind, then returns the same 600 miles against a 40 mph headwind. Its airspeed in still air is 200 mph. What is the total flight time for the round trip?', '["5 hours","6 hours","6.25 hours","7.5 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Ground speed outbound is 200 + 40 = 240 mph. Ground speed returning is 200 - 40 = 160 mph. Outbound time is 600 / 240 = 2.5 hours. Return time is 600 / 160 = 3.75 hours. Total is 6.25 hours. The choice 5 ignores the wind and uses 1,200 / 240. The choice 6 averages the two leg times. The choice 7.5 doubles 3.75, treating both legs as the slow leg. The arithmetic mean of two rates never gives the right round-trip time when distances are equal but rates differ.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-NEW-16'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A pancake recipe uses flour and sugar in a 2:1 ratio. If a baker uses 4 cups of flour, how much sugar is needed?', '["2 cups","3 cups","6 cups","8 cups"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Set up the proportion flour/sugar = 2/1 = 4/x. Cross-multiply: 2x = 4, so x = 2 cups. The choice 8 cups multiplies 4 by 2 instead of dividing, treating flour as the smaller part. The choice 6 cups adds the parts (4 + 2) instead of scaling. The choice 3 cups subtracts 1 from 4 instead of applying the ratio. Sugar is the smaller quantity here, so it must be less than the flour amount.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::recipe-ratio'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'Concrete is mixed with cement and sand in a 1:3 ratio. If 5 bags of cement are used, how many bags of sand are needed?', '["8","12","15","20"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up cement/sand = 1/3 = 5/x. Cross-multiply: x = 15 bags. The choice 8 adds the parts (5 + 3) instead of scaling. The choice 20 multiplies 5 by 4 (the total ratio parts) instead of by 3. The choice 12 subtracts 3 from a wrong total. Sand needs three times the cement, so each cement bag pairs with three sand bags, giving 5 times 3.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-2'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'In a classroom the ratio of boys to girls is 3:4. If there are 9 boys, how many girls are in the class?', '["10","12","13","16"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up boys/girls = 3/4 = 9/x. Cross-multiply: 3x = 36, so x = 12 girls. The choice 13 adds 4 to 9 instead of scaling proportionally. The choice 16 applies the scale factor 4 to the wrong number (4 times 4). The choice 10 mixes addition and the ratio incorrectly. Scaling the 3 up to 9 means multiplying by 3, so the 4 also scales by 3 to reach 12.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-3'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A paint mix uses red and white in a 1:2 ratio. If 3 quarts of red are used, how much white is needed?', '["1.5 quarts","5 quarts","6 quarts","9 quarts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up red/white = 1/2 = 3/x. Cross-multiply: x = 6 quarts. The choice 1.5 quarts flips the ratio and divides instead of multiplying. The choice 5 quarts adds the parts (3 + 2) instead of scaling. The choice 9 quarts multiplies 3 by 3 (the total parts) instead of by 2. White is twice the red, so 3 quarts of red pairs with 6 quarts of white.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-4'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'On a map, 1 inch represents 25 miles. Two towns are 6.5 inches apart on the map. How far apart are they in reality?', '["31.5 miles","150 miles","162.5 miles","175 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up inches/miles = 1/25 = 6.5/x. Cross-multiply: x = 162.5 miles. The choice 31.5 adds 25 and 6.5 instead of multiplying. The choice 150 drops the 0.5 inch from the calculation. The choice 175 rounds 6.5 up to 7 before multiplying. Each inch on the map equals 25 actual miles, so 6.5 inches scales directly to 6.5 times 25.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::map-scale'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A cookie recipe uses 3 cups of flour to make 8 cookies. How many cups of flour are needed to make 60 cookies?', '["20 cups","22.5 cups","24 cups","65 cups"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up flour/cookies = 3/8 = x/60. Cross-multiply: 8x = 180, so x = 22.5 cups. The choice 20 cups multiplies 60 by 1/3 instead of 3/8. The choice 24 cups uses the wrong ratio of 60 divided by something close. The choice 65 cups adds 60 and 5 with no proportional logic. Each cookie needs 3/8 cup of flour, so 60 cookies need 60 times 3/8.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::recipe-ratio'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A server tips at a rate of $4 for every $25 of bill. If the bill is $87.50, what tip should be left at this rate?', '["$12.50","$14.00","$17.50","$21.88"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Set up tip/bill = 4/25 = x/87.50. Cross-multiply: 25x = 350, so x = $14.00. The choice $12.50 applies a flat 1/7 ratio incorrectly. The choice $17.50 uses a 20 percent tip rate, not the 16 percent given. The choice $21.88 uses a 25 percent rate from confusing the 25 in the ratio. The given ratio is 4 out of 25, which is 16 percent, so 87.50 times 0.16 gives 14.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-7'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'On a map, 2 centimeters represents 15 kilometers. If two cities are 9 centimeters apart on the map, how far apart are they?', '["22 km","45 km","67.5 km","135 km"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up cm/km = 2/15 = 9/x. Cross-multiply: 2x = 135, so x = 67.5 km. The choice 135 km forgets to divide by 2 after multiplying 9 by 15. The choice 45 km uses 1 cm per 5 km, the wrong scale. The choice 22 km adds 15 and 9 minus 2. Each centimeter equals 7.5 km, so 9 centimeters equals 67.5 km.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::map-scale'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'In a class the ratio of boys to girls is 3:5. If the class has 32 students total, how many are boys?', '["8","12","19","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The ratio 3:5 means 3 + 5 = 8 total parts. Boys are 3/8 of the total: 32 times 3/8 = 12 boys. The choice 19 treats the part-to-part ratio as part-to-whole, computing 32 times 3/5. The choice 20 makes the same error in the other direction (32 times 5/8). The choice 8 just reports the total parts. Always add the ratio parts before splitting a known total.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-9'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'Concrete is mixed with cement, sand, and gravel in a 1:2:4 ratio. A batch contains 35 cubic feet of concrete total. How much gravel is in the batch?', '["5 cubic feet","10 cubic feet","20 cubic feet","28 cubic feet"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the parts: 1 + 2 + 4 = 7 total parts. Gravel is 4/7 of the total: 35 times 4/7 = 20 cubic feet. The choice 28 cubic feet treats 4/5 as the gravel share, forgetting to include cement in the sum. The choice 10 cubic feet uses 4/14, dividing by twice the correct total. The choice 5 cubic feet divides 35 by 7 without scaling up. Add all three parts of the ratio before taking the gravel fraction.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::recipe-ratio'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'A paint blend uses red, yellow, and blue in a 4:3:2 ratio. If the blend contains 18 ounces of blue, how many ounces is the entire blend?', '["54 oz","63 oz","72 oz","81 oz"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Blue is 2 parts. Each part equals 18 divided by 2, or 9 ounces. Add the parts: 4 + 3 + 2 = 9 total parts. Total blend = 9 parts times 9 ounces = 81 ounces. The choice 54 oz multiplies 18 by 3, treating yellow''s ratio number as the scale factor. The choice 72 oz uses 8 parts, forgetting blue itself. The choice 63 oz uses 7 parts, dropping blue. Find the per-part value first, then multiply by total parts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-11'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'A bag contains red, blue, and green marbles in a 2:3:5 ratio. The bag has 24 red marbles. How many green marbles are in the bag?', '["36","48","60","96"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Red is 2 parts and equals 24 marbles, so each part equals 12 marbles. Green is 5 parts: 5 times 12 = 60 green marbles. The choice 36 multiplies 12 by 3, giving the blue count instead of green. The choice 48 treats green as 4 parts (12 times 4) by miscounting the ratio. The choice 96 reports blue plus green combined (3 + 5 = 8 parts at 12 each), answering for the non-red total rather than green alone. Find the value of one part by dividing the known quantity by its ratio number, then multiply by the target ratio number.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-12'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'A salad dressing mixes oil, vinegar, and water in a 1:2:5 ratio. If the recipe uses 30 ounces of water, how many ounces of dressing does it make total?', '["36 oz","42 oz","48 oz","75 oz"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Water is 5 parts and equals 30 ounces, so each part equals 6 ounces. Add the parts: 1 + 2 + 5 = 8 total parts. Total dressing = 8 times 6 = 48 ounces. The choice 36 oz misadds the ratio as 1 + 2 + 3 = 6 total parts and multiplies 6 by 6. The choice 42 oz uses 7 parts, dropping one of the smaller components. The choice 75 oz multiplies 30 by 2.5, treating the ratio additively. Find the per-part value, add all parts, then multiply.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::recipe-ratio'),
  ('AR-RP-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'Six workers can paint a house in 10 days. Working at the same rate, how many days will 4 workers need to paint the same house?', '["6.67 days","8 days","12 days","15 days"]'::jsonb, 3, 'This is inverse proportion: fewer workers means more days. Total work equals 6 times 10 = 60 worker-days. With 4 workers, days = 60 divided by 4 = 15 days. The choice 6.67 days applies direct proportion (10 times 4/6), shrinking the time as workers shrink. The choice 12 days subtracts 2 workers and adds 2 days. The choice 8 days reduces time even more, the opposite of what should happen. When one quantity decreases, the other increases by the inverse factor.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-NEW-14'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A paperback book costs $12. How much do 5 of these books cost?', '["$17","$55","$60","$65"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the unit price by the quantity: 12 x 5 = 60, so 5 books cost $60. Choice $17 adds 12 and 5 instead of multiplying, a slip that happens when small numbers nudge the brain toward addition. Choice $55 misreads the price as $11 and computes 11 x 5, or drops a dollar when carrying. Choice $65 adds an extra $5, a common slip from rounding 12 up to 13 before multiplying. The structure is a single-step unit-cost problem, and the only operation needed is one multiplication.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-1'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-2', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A teacher splits 24 students into 4 equal groups. How many students are in each group?', '["5","6","8","20"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide the total by the number of groups: 24 / 4 = 6 students per group. Choice A comes from dividing 24 by 5 by accident, then rounding to a nearby whole number. Choice C results from dividing 24 by 3, a common error when a student confuses the number of groups with the number of dividers needed between groups. Choice D comes from subtracting 4 from 24 instead of dividing, a misread of the cue phrase ''split into.'' One operation, equal-share division, is all this question asks for, and the keyword ''equal groups'' is the signal to divide.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-2'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-3', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A train travels at a constant 60 miles per hour. How far does it travel in 3 hours?', '["20 miles","63 miles","120 miles","180 miles"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Distance equals rate times time: 60 x 3 = 180 miles. Choice A inverts the formula and divides 60 by 3 instead of multiplying, which would give a speed-per-hour fraction rather than a distance. Choice B adds 60 and 3 instead of multiplying, a classic operator swap when the rate and time numbers look small. Choice C uses 2 hours instead of 3, an off-by-one read on the time value. Distance-rate-time is one of the most common word-problem setups, and at this difficulty only a single product is required to reach the answer.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-3'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-4', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A bakery starts the day with 48 muffins. By noon, 19 muffins have been sold. How many muffins remain?', '["29","31","39","67"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract the amount sold from the starting count: 48 - 19 = 29 muffins remain. Choice B comes from subtracting 17 instead of 19, a digit misread on the ones place. Choice C results from subtracting only the 9 in 19 and ignoring the tens digit, leaving 39 muffins. Choice D adds the two numbers instead of subtracting, which is the operator-flip trap when the word ''sold'' is glossed over and the stem is read as a combine-totals problem. A single subtraction handles the whole problem, and careful alignment of place values prevents the digit-slip distractors.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-4'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-5', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A shirt is marked $25, and a store offers 20% off. What is the sale price?', '["$5","$20","$24.50","$30"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find 20% of $25 (which is $5), then subtract from the original: 25 - 5 = $20. Choice A reports only the discount amount and forgets to subtract from the price, a stopping-too-early mistake. Choice C treats 20% as 2%, taking $0.50 off instead of $5, a decimal-place slip. Choice D adds the discount to the price rather than subtracting it, the operator-flip error when the cue word ''off'' is missed. Percent-off problems are two-step: compute the discount amount, then apply it in the correct direction to reach the sale price.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-5'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'Marcus earns $14 per hour. He works 6 hours on Monday and 4 hours on Tuesday. How much does he earn in total for both days?', '["$56","$84","$140","$1,400"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the hours first, then multiply by the rate: 6 + 4 = 10 hours, and 10 x 14 = $140. Choice A multiplies only Tuesday''s 4 hours by 14, dropping Monday entirely. Choice B multiplies only Monday''s 6 hours by 14, dropping Tuesday entirely. Choice D misplaces the decimal, sliding a zero so the hourly rate is treated as $140 instead of $14, a place-value slip. Two-day pay problems need both days summed before the wage rate is applied, and the order of operations matters when the same wage covers both shifts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-6'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-7', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'Three pizzas are each cut into 8 slices. If 4 friends share all the slices equally, how many slices does each friend get?', '["3","6","8","12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find the total slices first: 3 x 8 = 24, then divide among 4 people: 24 / 4 = 6 slices each. Choice A divides 12 by 4, using only one pizza. Choice C reports the slices per pizza, skipping the share step. Choice D divides 24 by 2 instead of 4, halving the friends. The two operations have to happen in order, multiply then divide, and missing either step lands on a wrong choice.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-7'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-8', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A car travels 240 miles using 8 gallons of gas. What is the car''s mileage in miles per gallon?', '["30 mpg","32 mpg","248 mpg","1,920 mpg"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Miles per gallon equals miles divided by gallons: 240 / 8 = 30 mpg. Choice B comes from dividing 256 by 8, a digit slip that reads the miles value wrong. Choice C adds 240 and 8 instead of dividing, an operator-swap error that ignores the per-unit cue in the question. Choice D multiplies 240 by 8, which would give total miles if you drove 8 full tanks, not a rate per gallon. The phrase ''per gallon'' signals division, with miles as the numerator and gallons as the denominator, and getting the order right matters since flipping it produces gallons per mile.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-8'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-9', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A bag contains 60 marbles. One-fourth are red, one-third are blue, and the rest are green. How many marbles are green?', '["15","20","25","35"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Red: 60 x 1/4 = 15. Blue: 60 x 1/3 = 20. Green: 60 - 15 - 20 = 25. Choice A reports the red count only. Choice B reports the blue count only. Choice D adds the red and blue counts instead of subtracting them from 60, taking the wrong complement. Fraction-of-total problems often hide the answer in the last step, so the leftover quantity, not either named fraction, is what the stem asks for.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-9'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-10', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'Jordan saved $150. He spent 40% of his savings on a bike, then spent 25% of the remaining money on a helmet. How much money does Jordan have left?', '["$30.00","$52.50","$67.50","$90.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Bike cost: 150 x 0.40 = $60, leaving 150 - 60 = $90. Helmet: 90 x 0.25 = $22.50, leaving 90 - 22.50 = $67.50. Choice $30.00 subtracts the bike cost twice, computing 90 - 60 by mistake. Choice $52.50 adds the two percentages (65%) and takes that off $150 directly: 150 - 97.50 = $52.50. Choice $90.00 stops after the bike purchase and forgets the helmet. The key move is using the post-bike balance as the new base for the 25%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-10'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-11', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A pancake recipe uses 2 cups of flour to serve 4 people. How many cups of flour are needed to serve 10 people using the same recipe?', '["2.5 cups","4 cups","5 cups","8 cups"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up a proportion: 2 cups / 4 people = x / 10 people, so x = (2 x 10) / 4 = 5 cups. Choice A reverses the ratio and divides 10 by 4. Choice B doubles the recipe to serve 8 people instead of 10, an undershoot. Choice D multiplies 2 by 4 instead of by 10/4, applying the wrong scaling factor. Proportion problems require keeping the same quantity (flour or people) in the same position on both sides of the equation.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-11'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-12', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A student''s five test scores are 78, 85, 92, 89, and 76. What is the average of these scores?', '["82","84","85","88"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the scores: 78 + 85 + 92 + 89 + 76 = 420. Divide by 5: 420 / 5 = 84. Choice A undercounts the sum by 10 (likely reading 78 as 68). Choice C reports the median (the middle score when sorted: 76, 78, 85, 89, 92) instead of the mean. Choice D divides 440 by 5, an addition error in the sum. Averages have two stages, and a single arithmetic slip in the sum is the most common way to miss this kind of item.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-12'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-13', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A worker assembles 12 widgets in 45 minutes. Working at the same rate, how many widgets can the worker assemble in 3 hours?', '["32","36","48","60"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 3 hours to 180 minutes, then scale: 180 / 45 = 4, and 4 x 12 = 48 widgets. Choice A multiplies 12 by 3 hours without converting units, treating hours and 45-minute blocks as equal. Choice B uses 135 minutes (2.25 hours) instead of 180. Choice D multiplies 12 by 5, assuming five 45-minute blocks fit in 3 hours rather than four. The unit conversion from hours to minutes (or to 45-minute blocks) is the trip-up step.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-13'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-14', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'Two trains leave the same station at the same time, traveling in opposite directions. One train moves at 55 mph and the other at 65 mph. After how many hours are the trains 360 miles apart?', '["1.5 hours","3 hours","4.5 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When objects move in opposite directions, their separation rate is the sum of their speeds: 55 + 65 = 120 mph. Time = distance / rate = 360 / 120 = 3 hours. Choice 1.5 hours doubles the combined rate to 240 mph (perhaps by also doubling each speed) and computes 360 / 240. Choice 4.5 hours misreads 65 as 25 (digit slip), uses 80 mph as the combined rate, and computes 360 / 80. Choice 6 hours averages the two speeds to get 60 mph instead of summing, then divides 360 / 60. The combined-rate setup is the load-bearing step.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-14'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-15', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'An inlet pipe can fill a tank in 6 hours. A drain pipe can empty the full tank in 9 hours. If both pipes are open and the tank starts empty, how long will it take to fill the tank?', '["3 hours","7.5 hours","15 hours","18 hours"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Add the rates with the drain as negative: 1/6 - 1/9 = 3/18 - 2/18 = 1/18 tank per hour. Time to fill one tank = 18 hours. Choice A subtracts 6 from 9 and reports the difference. Choice B averages 6 and 9 to get 7.5, ignoring that the pipes work against each other. Choice C adds the two times (6 + 9) instead of combining rates. Work-rate problems require rates, not times, to be combined, with the sign matching whether each pipe fills or drains.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-15'),
  ('AR-WP-NEW-16', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, '$1,000 is deposited in an account earning 5% interest compounded annually. How much interest is earned after 2 years?', '["$100.00","$102.50","$105.00","$110.25"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Compound balance after 2 years: 1000 x (1.05)^2 = 1000 x 1.1025 = $1,102.50. Interest earned is 1102.50 - 1000 = $102.50. Choice A applies simple interest (1000 x 0.05 x 2), missing the compounding bump. Choice C reports only the first year''s interest (1000 x 0.05). Choice D reports the multiplier 1.1025 scaled to $110.25, mistakenly using a $1,000 principal at 10.25% per year for one year, or forgetting to subtract the original principal from a slightly mis-scaled balance. Compound interest answers are always slightly above the simple-interest figure for the same period.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-NEW-16'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x + 7 = 15, what is the value of x?', '["7","8","22","9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Isolate x by subtracting 7 from both sides: x + 7 - 7 = 15 - 7, which gives x = 8. Choice 22 is the sign-error trap that comes from adding 7 to 15 instead of subtracting. Choice 7 is the constant on the left side rather than the variable''s value. Choice 9 results from subtracting 6 instead of 7. The inverse operation of addition is subtraction, so a positive constant added to x must be subtracted to undo it.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-1'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x - 9 = 4, what is x?', '["-5","5","13","36"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add 9 to both sides to isolate x: x - 9 + 9 = 4 + 9, which gives x = 13. Choice -5 is the sign-error trap from subtracting 9 from 4 instead of adding. Choice 5 reverses the direction by computing 9 - 4. Choice 36 comes from multiplying 9 and 4 instead of using inverse operations. Subtraction of a positive constant is undone by addition of that same constant on both sides.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-2'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If 6x = 42, what is x?', '["6","7","8","36"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide both sides by 6 to isolate x: 6x / 6 = 42 / 6, which gives x = 7. Choice 6 is the coefficient itself, not the solution value of the variable. Choice 8 results from a division error treating 42 as 48 in the head. Choice 36 comes from subtracting 6 from 42 instead of dividing, an inverted-operation trap. Multiplication of x by a coefficient is undone by dividing both sides by that coefficient, not by subtracting it from both sides.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-3'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 4x + 3 = 19, what is x?', '["4","5.5","16","22"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 3 from both sides to clear the constant: 4x + 3 - 3 = 19 - 3, which gives 4x = 16. Then divide both sides by 4: x = 4. Choice 16 is the intermediate value of 4x reported instead of x. Choice 22 adds 3 to 19 instead of subtracting, a sign-error on transposition. Choice 5.5 comes from dividing 22 by 4 after that same transposition error. The order matters: undo addition first, then undo multiplication, because the coefficient binds tighter to the variable.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-4'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 5x - 2 = 23, what is x?', '["4.2","5","21","25"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add 2 to both sides: 5x = 25. Then divide by 5: x = 5. Choice 25 is the intermediate value of 5x reported as the answer instead of x. Choice 21 comes from subtracting 2 from 23 instead of adding, a sign-error trap. Choice 4.2 results from dividing 21 by 5 after the same transposition error. A negative constant on the variable side must be added to both sides, then the coefficient must be divided out.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-5'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If x/3 + 4 = 9, what is x?', '["5","13","15","39"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Subtract 4 from both sides: x/3 = 5. Then multiply both sides by 3: x = 15. Choice 5 is the intermediate value of x/3 reported instead of x. Choice 13 comes from adding 4 to 9 instead of subtracting, a sign-error on transposition. Choice 39 results from multiplying 13 by 3 after the same transposition error. Division by a constant is undone by multiplying both sides by that constant after the addition is cleared.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-6'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 3(x - 2) = 18, what is x?', '["4","6","8","20"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distribute the 3: 3x - 6 = 18. Add 6 to both sides: 3x = 24. Divide by 3: x = 8. Choice 4 comes from subtracting 6 from both sides instead of adding, yielding 3x = 12 and then x = 4. Choice 6 drops the constant entirely after distributing and divides 18 by 3, ignoring the -6 term. Choice 20 reports the value of 3x - 4 by skipping the divide step (3x = 24, then 24 - 4). Both terms inside the parentheses must be multiplied by the factor outside, and the -6 must be moved to the right side by adding.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-7'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If -2x + 9 = 1, what is x?', '["-4","4","5","-5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 9 from both sides: -2x = -8. Divide by -2: x = 4. Choice -4 is the sign-error trap from dividing -8 by 2 instead of -2, or from forgetting that negative divided by negative is positive. Choice 5 comes from adding 9 to 1 instead of subtracting and then dividing by 2. Choice -5 compounds both errors. When the variable has a negative coefficient, the final division by that negative must flip the sign of the result.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-8'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 4(2x + 1) = 28, what is x?', '["3","3.375","13.5","27"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Distribute the 4: 8x + 4 = 28. Subtract 4 from both sides: 8x = 24. Divide by 8: x = 3. Choice 13.5 comes from dropping the 4 entirely on the left side (writing 2x + 1 = 28), then solving 2x = 27 to get x = 13.5. Choice 3.375 results from 8x + 1 = 28: the student multiplies 2x by 4 but leaves the 1 unmultiplied, then solves 8x = 27 to get x = 3.375. Choice 27 is the intermediate value 28 - 1, reported before dividing. The factor outside the parentheses must hit every term inside.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-9'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 5 - 3x = -7, what is x?', '["-4","4","-2/3","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 5 from both sides: -3x = -12. Divide by -3: x = 4. Choice -4 is the sign-error trap from dividing -12 by 3 instead of -3, ignoring that a negative divided by a negative yields positive. Choice -2/3 comes from adding 5 to -7 to get -2 then dividing by 3, a transposition error. Choice 2/3 compounds the same transposition with the sign-flip. Negative coefficients on the variable demand careful tracking of signs through the final division.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-10'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 7x - 4 = 3x + 12, what is x?', '["2","4","8","16"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 3x from both sides: 4x - 4 = 12. Add 4 to both sides: 4x = 16. Divide by 4: x = 4. Choice 16 is the intermediate value of 4x reported instead of x. Choice 2 comes from a sign-error of subtracting 4 from 12 instead of adding, giving 4x = 8. Choice 8 results from 7x + 3x = 10x and then 10x = 16 with arithmetic slips on combining variable terms. Move variable terms to one side and constants to the other before isolating.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-11'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 2x + 5 = 17, what is the value of x² - x?', '["6","12","30","42"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Solve for x first: 2x + 5 = 17, so 2x = 12 and x = 6. Substitute into x² - x: 6² - 6 = 36 - 6 = 30. Choice 6 stops at x without computing the expression, a common premature-stop trap. Choice 12 is the intermediate value of 2x from the first equation. Choice 42 comes from x² + x = 36 + 6, a sign-error on the second term. Always read what the question asks for after solving for the variable, not just the variable''s value.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-12'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If 5x + 8 = 2x - 7, what is x?', '["-5","5","-1/3","1/3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 2x from both sides: 3x + 8 = -7. Subtract 8 from both sides: 3x = -15. Divide by 3: x = -5. Choice 5 is the sign-error trap from dropping the negative on the final division. Choice -1/3 comes from adding 8 to -7 to get 1 instead of subtracting, then dividing by 3 with a sign flip. Choice 1/3 compounds both arithmetic and sign errors. Negative results are common when variable coefficients on the left exceed those on the right but the constants pull the answer below zero.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-13'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'If x + y = 10 and x - y = 4, what is x?', '["3","6","7","14"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the two equations: (x + y) + (x - y) = 10 + 4, which gives 2x = 14, so x = 7. Choice 14 is the intermediate value of 2x reported instead of x. Choice 3 is the value of y, not x: substituting x = 7 into x + y = 10 gives y = 3. Choice 6 comes from averaging the right-hand sides incorrectly. Adding the two equations cancels the y terms because their coefficients are opposites, leaving a single-variable equation in x.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-14'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If -3x > 12, which describes x?', '["x > 4","x > -4","x < 4","x < -4"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Divide both sides by -3. Dividing or multiplying an inequality by a negative number flips the direction of the inequality: x < -4. Choice x > -4 is the trap of dividing without flipping the sign, the most common inequality error. Choice x > 4 also fails to flip the sign and additionally drops the negative on -4. Choice x < 4 flips the sign but drops the negative result. Two operations must happen together when dividing an inequality by a negative: compute the numeric result and reverse the inequality symbol.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-15'),
  ('MK-AL-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'If 2x + y = 11 and x + y = 7, what is y?', '["3","4","7","11"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract the second equation from the first: (2x + y) - (x + y) = 11 - 7, which gives x = 4. Substitute x = 4 into x + y = 7: 4 + y = 7, so y = 3. Choice 4 is the value of x, not y, a common premature-stop trap when the question asks for the other variable. Choice 7 is the right-hand side of the second equation, not y. Choice 11 is the right-hand side of the first equation. Subtracting one equation from another with matching y coefficients eliminates y, but here it isolates x.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-NEW-16'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 3⁴.', '["12","27","64","81"]'::jsonb, 3, 'An exponent means repeated multiplication of the base. 3⁴ equals 3 · 3 · 3 · 3, which equals 81. Choice 12 multiplies the base and exponent (3 × 4), a common shortcut error. Choice 27 stops one step early at 3³. Choice 64 confuses the base and exponent and computes 4³ instead. Only the full product 3 · 3 · 3 · 3 = 81 applies the definition of an exponent correctly.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-1'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Simplify x³ · x⁴.', '["x⁷","x¹²","x","2x⁷"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents. x³ · x⁴ becomes x^(3+4), which equals x⁷. Choice x¹² multiplies the exponents instead of adding them, which is the rule for a power raised to a power, not multiplication. Choice x subtracts the exponents as if dividing. Choice 2x⁷ incorrectly doubles the coefficient; the bases each have an implied coefficient of 1, and 1 · 1 stays 1.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 2⁵.', '["10","16","25","32"]'::jsonb, 3, '2⁵ means multiply 2 by itself five times: 2 · 2 · 2 · 2 · 2, which equals 32. Choice 10 multiplies the base by the exponent (2 × 5), which ignores the meaning of exponents. Choice 16 stops one factor short at 2⁴. Choice 25 swaps the base and exponent and computes 5². Working through each doubling, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, confirms 32 is correct.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-3'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify x⁸ / x³.', '["x¹¹","x²⁴","x⁵","x⁵/³"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When dividing powers with the same base, subtract the exponents. x⁸ / x³ becomes x^(8-3), which equals x⁵. Choice x¹¹ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplication, not division. Choice x²⁴ multiplies the exponents, which applies to a power of a power. Choice x⁵/³ treats the exponents as a fraction left over after subtraction, mixing rules. Subtracting exponents during same-base division produces x⁵.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify (x³)⁴.', '["x⁷","x¹²","x⁸¹","x⁶⁴"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When raising a power to a power, multiply the exponents. (x³)⁴ becomes x^(3·4), which equals x¹². Choice x⁷ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplying same-base expressions, not nesting. Choice x⁸¹ raises 3 to the fourth power and treats that as the exponent. Choice x⁶⁴ raises 4 to the third power. Multiplying the two exponents directly gives x¹².', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Rewrite x⁻³ with a positive exponent.', '["1/x³","-x³","-3x","1/(-x³)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A negative exponent means take the reciprocal of the base with a positive exponent. x⁻³ equals 1/x³. Choice -x³ treats the negative exponent as a negative sign on the result, which confuses two different operations. Choice -3x multiplies the base by the exponent. Choice 1/(-x³) puts the negative on the base itself, which would only happen if the base were written as (-x). The rule converts the negative exponent into a positive exponent in the denominator.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-6'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify (y²)⁵.', '["y⁷","y¹⁰","y²⁵","y³²"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When raising a power to a power, multiply the exponents. (y²)⁵ becomes y^(2·5), which equals y¹⁰. Choice y⁷ adds the exponents, which is the rule for multiplying same-base terms, not nesting. Choice y²⁵ squares the outer exponent and uses that as the result. Choice y³² evaluates 2⁵ and treats that as the exponent. The correct move is to multiply 2 and 5 to get y¹⁰.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-7'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify (2x³)².', '["2x⁶","4x⁵","4x⁶","4x⁹"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When an exponent applies to a product, distribute it to each factor. (2x³)² becomes 2² · (x³)², which equals 4 · x⁶, or 4x⁶. Choice 2x⁶ squares the variable part but forgets to square the coefficient. Choice 4x⁵ squares the coefficient but adds exponents instead of multiplying them. Choice 4x⁹ raises the inside exponent to the outside power instead of multiplying. The product 4x⁶ applies both the coefficient and exponent rules.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Expand (x + 3)(x + 4).', '["x² + 12","2x + 7","x² + 7x + 7","x² + 7x + 12"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Use FOIL to expand: first x · x = x², outer x · 4 = 4x, inner 3 · x = 3x, last 3 · 4 = 12. Combine like terms 4x + 3x to get 7x. The product is x² + 7x + 12. Choice x² + 12 multiplies only the first and last terms and skips the middle. Choice 2x + 7 adds the binomials instead of multiplying. Choice x² + 7x + 7 forgets to multiply the constants and uses 3 + 4 instead of 3 · 4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-9'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify (xy²)³.', '["xy⁶","x³y⁵","x³y⁶","x³y⁸"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distribute the exponent across each factor in the product, multiplying exponents when raising a power to a power. (xy²)³ becomes x³ · (y²)³, which equals x³y⁶. Choice xy⁶ raises only y to the third power and leaves x with exponent 1. Choice x³y⁵ adds exponents 2 and 3 instead of multiplying. Choice x³y⁸ raises 2 to the third power and treats that as the exponent of y. The product rule cubes each factor.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-10'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify x⁵ · x⁻².', '["x⁷","x³","x⁻¹⁰","1/x³"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents, including negatives. x⁵ · x⁻² becomes x^(5 + (-2)), which equals x³. Choice x⁷ adds 5 and 2 as if both were positive, ignoring the negative sign. Choice x⁻¹⁰ multiplies the exponents instead of adding them. Choice 1/x³ flips the result to the denominator, which would apply only if the final exponent were negative. The sum 5 + (-2) = 3 keeps the answer in the numerator.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Expand (x - 2)(x + 5).', '["x² - 10","x² - 3x - 10","x² + 3x + 10","x² + 3x - 10"]'::jsonb, 3, 'FOIL: first x · x = x², outer x · 5 = 5x, inner -2 · x = -2x, last -2 · 5 = -10. Combine 5x and -2x to get 3x. The result is x² + 3x - 10. Choice x² - 10 skips the middle terms. Choice x² - 3x - 10 reverses the sign on the middle term, a common error from subtracting instead of adding 5x and -2x. Choice x² + 3x + 10 keeps the constant positive, forgetting that a positive times a negative is negative.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-12'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² + 7x + 10.', '["(x + 1)(x + 10)","(x + 2)(x + 5)","(x + 3)(x + 4)","(x - 2)(x - 5)"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find two numbers that multiply to 10 and add to 7. The pair 2 and 5 works because 2 · 5 = 10 and 2 + 5 = 7, so the factors are (x + 2)(x + 5). Choice (x + 1)(x + 10) multiplies to 10 but adds to 11. Choice (x + 3)(x + 4) adds to 7 but multiplies to 12. Choice (x - 2)(x - 5) multiplies to 10 but adds to -7, flipping the sign on the middle term.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-13'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² - x - 12.', '["(x - 4)(x + 3)","(x + 4)(x - 3)","(x - 4)(x - 3)","(x + 6)(x - 2)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Find two numbers that multiply to -12 and add to -1. The pair -4 and 3 works because -4 · 3 = -12 and -4 + 3 = -1, so the factors are (x - 4)(x + 3). Choice (x + 4)(x - 3) multiplies to -12 but adds to 1, the wrong sign on the middle term. Choice (x - 4)(x - 3) multiplies to 12, not -12. Choice (x + 6)(x - 2) multiplies to -12 but adds to 4. Sign placement matters because the constant is negative.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-14'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Simplify ((x²)³)².', '["x⁷","x⁸","x¹²","x⁶⁴"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Apply the power of a power rule from the inside out, multiplying exponents at each step. (x²)³ becomes x⁶. Then (x⁶)² becomes x^(6·2), which equals x¹². Choice x⁷ adds the three exponents 2 + 3 + 2 instead of multiplying. Choice x⁸ multiplies 2 · 4, treating the outer 2 as applying to the inner 2. Choice x⁶⁴ evaluates 2⁶ and treats that as the exponent. Multiplying 2 · 3 · 2 gives 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Factor x² + 10x + 25.', '["(x + 5)²","(x - 5)²","(x + 5)(x - 5)","(x + 25)(x + 1)"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Look for two numbers that multiply to 25 and add to 10. The pair 5 and 5 works, so the factors are (x + 5)(x + 5), which equals (x + 5)². This is a perfect square trinomial. Choice (x - 5)² expands to x² - 10x + 25, with the wrong sign on the middle term. Choice (x + 5)(x - 5) is the difference of squares, which would produce x² - 25 and no middle term. Choice (x + 25)(x + 1) multiplies to 25 but adds to 26.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-16'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Evaluate 7⁰.', '["0","1","7","undefined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Any nonzero number raised to the zero power equals 1, so 7⁰ equals 1. The rule follows from the division pattern: 7^n / 7^n equals 1, but using the exponent rule it also equals 7^(n-n), which equals 7⁰. Choice 0 confuses the exponent with the result. Choice 7 keeps the base when the exponent is zero, mixing it up with the rule for an exponent of 1. Choice undefined applies only to 0⁰, not to a nonzero base.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-17'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Factor x² - 49.', '["(x - 7)²","(x + 7)²","(x + 7)(x - 7)","(x - 49)(x + 1)"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The expression is a difference of squares because 49 equals 7² and there is no middle term. The pattern a² - b² factors as (a + b)(a - b), so x² - 49 becomes (x + 7)(x - 7). Choice (x - 7)² expands to x² - 14x + 49, which has a middle term and the wrong constant sign. Choice (x + 7)² expands to x² + 14x + 49. Choice (x - 49)(x + 1) multiplies to -49 but produces x² - 48x - 49, not a clean difference of squares.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-18'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-19', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Which expression equals x^(1/2)?', '["x/2","√x","1/x²","2/x"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A fractional exponent of 1/2 means take the square root of the base, so x^(1/2) equals √x. The general rule states x^(1/n) equals the nth root of x. Choice x/2 divides the base by 2, treating the exponent as a regular fraction multiplier. Choice 1/x² applies the negative-exponent rule and squares the base, mixing two unrelated operations. Choice 2/x flips the fraction and uses the base as a denominator. Only the square root matches the fractional exponent definition.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-19'),
  ('MK-EP-NEW-20', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Evaluate 25^(1/2).', '["5","12.5","50","625"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A fractional exponent of 1/2 means take the square root of the base, so 25^(1/2) equals √25, which equals 5. Choice 12.5 multiplies 25 by 1/2, treating the exponent as a regular multiplier instead of a root. Choice 50 multiplies 25 by 2, applying the reciprocal of the exponent as a multiplier. Choice 625 squares 25, which would happen with an exponent of 2 rather than 1/2. The square root, not multiplication, defines a 1/2 power.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-NEW-20'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, '1/2 + 1/4 = ?', '["2/6","3/4","1/6","2/4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rewrite 1/2 with a denominator of 4 so both fractions share a common base: 1/2 equals 2/4. Now add the numerators while holding the denominator fixed: 2/4 plus 1/4 equals 3/4. The result is already in lowest terms because 3 and 4 share no common factor. The choice 2/6 comes from adding numerators and denominators separately, which is not how fraction addition works. The choice 2/4 is the converted form of 1/2 alone, with no addition performed. The choice 1/6 reflects a similar add-everything error applied with the wrong sign.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-1'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, '0.3 + 0.4 = ?', '["0.07","0.7","0.34","7"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Line up the decimal points and add tenths to tenths. Three tenths plus four tenths equals seven tenths, written 0.7. Since each addend has only one digit after the decimal point, the sum also has one digit after the decimal point. The choice 0.07 places the sum two decimal places to the right, treating 0.3 and 0.4 as hundredths rather than tenths. The choice 0.34 concatenates the digits without performing any addition. The choice 7 drops the decimal point entirely and gives a whole number. Only 0.7 preserves the place value of the original addends.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-2'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 1/2 of 0.5?', '["0.25","1.0","0.5","0.1"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Taking half of a number means multiplying by 1/2, which equals 0.5. Compute 0.5 times 0.5: multiply 5 by 5 to get 25, then place two decimal places in the product because each factor has one decimal place. The result is 0.25. As a fraction, 1/2 times 1/2 equals 1/4, which converts to 0.25 and confirms the answer. The choice 1.0 results from adding 0.5 to itself instead of halving. The choice 0.5 leaves the value unchanged, ignoring the halving step. The choice 0.1 misplaces the decimal point.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-3'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '1/3 + 1/4 = ?', '["2/7","7/12","1/7","2/12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The denominators 3 and 4 share no common factors, so the least common denominator is their product, 12. Convert each fraction: 1/3 becomes 4/12 because 1 times 4 is 4 and 3 times 4 is 12, while 1/4 becomes 3/12 because 1 times 3 is 3 and 4 times 3 is 12. Add the numerators: 4 plus 3 equals 7. The sum is 7/12, already in lowest terms since 7 is prime. The choice 2/7 comes from adding numerators and denominators directly. The choice 1/7 reflects a similar error with a subtraction step. The choice 2/12 ignores the conversion step.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-4'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '2/3 × 3/5 = ? (lowest terms)', '["6/15","5/8","2/5","1/5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply numerators across and denominators across without finding a common denominator, since this is multiplication. 2 times 3 is 6, and 3 times 5 is 15, giving 6/15. Reduce by dividing both by their greatest common factor, 3: 6 divided by 3 is 2, and 15 divided by 3 is 5. The result is 2/5. The choice 6/15 is the unsimplified product, which fails the lowest-terms requirement stated in the stem. The choice 5/8 comes from adding numerators and denominators instead of multiplying. The choice 1/5 reflects an over-reduction error that drops too much from the numerator.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-5'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'Write 0.6 as a fraction in lowest terms.', '["6/10","3/5","2/3","6/100"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The decimal 0.6 means six tenths, written as the fraction 6/10. To put this in lowest terms, find the greatest common factor of 6 and 10, which is 2. Divide both top and bottom by 2: 6 over 10 becomes 3 over 5. Since 3 and 5 share no common factor, 3/5 is fully reduced. The choice 6/10 is correct in value but not in lowest terms, so it fails the stated requirement. The choice 2/3 is close in decimal value, 0.666..., but not equal to 0.6 exactly. The choice 6/100 misreads the place value, treating 0.6 as six hundredths.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-6'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, '5/8 − 1/4 = ?', '["4/4","3/8","1/2","4/8"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find a common denominator before subtracting. The denominators 8 and 4 share 4 as a factor, and 8 is a multiple of 4, so use 8 as the common denominator. Convert 1/4 to eighths by multiplying top and bottom by 2: 1/4 equals 2/8. Subtract: 5/8 minus 2/8 equals 3/8. Since 3 and 8 share no common factor, 3/8 is already in lowest terms. The choice 4/4 comes from subtracting numerators and denominators separately. The choice 1/2 reflects a guess at a familiar fraction near the answer. The choice 4/8 forgets the conversion and subtracts 1 from 5 directly.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-7'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, '2 1/3 + 1 1/4 = ?', '["3 2/7","3 7/12","3 1/12","4 7/12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add whole parts first: 2 plus 1 equals 3. For the fractional parts, use the common denominator 12: 1/3 becomes 4/12, and 1/4 becomes 3/12. Add 4/12 plus 3/12 to get 7/12. Combine the whole part with the fractional part: 3 and 7/12. The choice 3 2/7 adds numerators and denominators of the fractional parts. The choice 3 1/12 subtracts instead of adds. The choice 4 7/12 adds an extra whole unit that does not arise here.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-8'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'Express 1/3 as a decimal.', '["0.3","0.33","0.333...","0.13"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Perform long division of 1 by 3. The first digit after the decimal point is 3, with remainder 1. The next digit is again 3, with remainder 1, and the pattern continues forever. The result is 0.333..., a repeating decimal, often written with a bar over the 3. The choice 0.3 truncates after one place and loses accuracy. The choice 0.33 truncates after two places and is still short of the exact value, falling between 0.33 and 0.34. The choice 0.13 misorders the digits and gives a much smaller number. Only 0.333... captures the full repeating pattern.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-9'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'Which fraction is largest: 3/5, 5/8, 7/12, 2/3?', '["3/5","5/8","7/12","2/3"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert each to a decimal for direct comparison, rounded to three places. 3 divided by 5 equals 0.600 exactly. 5 divided by 8 equals 0.625 exactly. 7 divided by 12 equals 0.583 with a 3 repeating. 2 divided by 3 equals 0.666 with a 6 repeating. Even without exact decimals, the comparison is clear: 0.666... is larger than 0.625, which is larger than 0.600, which is larger than 0.583. So 2/3 is the largest fraction. Comparing numerators or denominators alone fails because both differ across the four fractions. Decimal conversion gives a single common scale that makes the ordering immediate.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-10'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, '3 1/2 − 1 3/4 = ?', '["2 1/4","1 3/4","1 1/4","2 3/4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert both to improper fractions to avoid borrowing errors. 3 1/2 becomes 7/2, which equals 14/4. 1 3/4 stays as 7/4. Subtract: 14/4 minus 7/4 equals 7/4. Convert back to a mixed number: 7 divided by 4 is 1 with remainder 3, giving 1 3/4. The choice 2 1/4 results from subtracting whole parts and fractional parts separately without borrowing. The choice 1 1/4 drops half a unit somewhere in the borrow. The choice 2 3/4 reverses the operation.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-11'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(3/4) ÷ (2/3) = ?', '["1/2","6/12","1 1/8","2/4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Dividing by a fraction means multiplying by its reciprocal, the flip-and-multiply rule. Flip the divisor 2/3 to 3/2, then multiply: 3/4 times 3/2. Multiply numerators across to get 9, and multiply denominators across to get 8, giving 9/8. Convert 9/8 to a mixed number: 9 divided by 8 is 1 with remainder 1, so the result is 1 1/8. The choice 1/2 comes from multiplying 3/4 by 2/3 without flipping. The choice 6/12 also reflects multiplying instead of dividing. The choice 2/4 simplifies the same multiplication error. Only flipping and multiplying gives 1 1/8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-12'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, 'What is 1/2 of 3/4 of 8?', '["3","6","4","12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Work from the inside out. Three-fourths of 8 is 6, since 8 divided by 4 is 2 and 2 times 3 is 6. Then one-half of 6 is 3. Equivalently, multiply across: 1/2 times 3/4 times 8 equals 24/8 equals 3. The choice 6 stops after the first step and forgets to take half. The choice 4 reflects taking half of 8 first and ignoring the 3/4. The choice 12 adds the steps instead of multiplying them.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-13'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(1/2 + 1/3) ÷ (1/6) = ?', '["5/36","5","1/5","6/5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add inside the parentheses first using a common denominator of 6, since 6 is the least common multiple of 2 and 3. Convert: 1/2 becomes 3/6, and 1/3 becomes 2/6. Add the numerators to get 5/6. Now divide by 1/6 by flipping the divisor and multiplying: 5/6 times 6/1 equals 30/6, which simplifies to 5. The choice 5/36 multiplies by 1/6 instead of dividing. The choice 1/5 reverses the final operation entirely. The choice 6/5 inverts the answer. Only flipping the divisor and multiplying delivers 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-14'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, '(2/5) ÷ (4/15) = ? Express as a mixed number in lowest terms.', '["8/75","1 1/2","4/3","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Invert the divisor and multiply: 2/5 times 15/4 equals 30/20. Reduce by dividing top and bottom by 10: 30 over 20 becomes 3 over 2. Convert to a mixed number as the stem requests: 3/2 equals 1 1/2. The choice 8/75 multiplies the original fractions without flipping the divisor. The choice 4/3 comes from inverting the wrong fraction, flipping 2/5 to 5/2 and then misreducing. The choice 2/3 inverts the final answer. Only 1 1/2 is the simplified quotient in the requested mixed-number form.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-15'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Which fraction equals 0.1818... (the 18 repeats)?', '["18/100","9/50","2/11","1/9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use the standard rule for repeating decimals: a two-digit repeating block becomes that block over 99. So 0.1818... equals 18/99. Reduce by dividing top and bottom by the greatest common factor, 9: 18 over 99 becomes 2 over 11. Verify by long division: 2 divided by 11 produces 0.181818..., confirming the match. The choice 18/100 equals 0.18 exactly, with no repeating tail. The choice 9/50 also equals 0.18 exactly and terminates. The choice 1/9 equals 0.111..., a different repeating pattern. Only 2/11 produces the 0.18 repeat shown in the stem.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-16'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Which fraction has a terminating decimal expansion?', '["1/3","1/6","1/7","1/8"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A fraction in lowest terms terminates exactly when its denominator factors into only 2s and 5s. Check each denominator. 3 has a factor of 3, so 1/3 repeats. 6 equals 2 times 3, so 1/6 repeats. 7 is prime and not 2 or 5, so 1/7 repeats. 8 equals 2 times 2 times 2, with only 2s, so 1/8 terminates. Indeed 1/8 equals 0.125 exactly. Only denominators built from 2s and 5s alone produce terminating decimals.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-17'),
  ('MK-FR-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'Compare 7/16 and 0.4375.', '["7/16 > 0.4375","7/16 < 0.4375","7/16 = 0.4375","Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 7/16 to a decimal by dividing 7 by 16. Long division gives 0.4375 exactly, with no remainder, since 16 equals 2 to the fourth power and produces a terminating decimal. The two values are identical. The choices claiming inequality assume a rounding gap that does not exist here. The choice for cannot be determined is incorrect because exact conversion is always possible when the denominator is a power of 2. Only the equality statement matches the conversion.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-NEW-18'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'A rectangular rug measures 8 ft by 5 ft. What is its area?', '["13 sq ft","26 sq ft","40 sq ft","45 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area of a rectangle is length times width: 8 times 5 equals 40 square feet. Choice 13 sq ft adds the sides instead of multiplying. Choice 26 sq ft computes the perimeter (2 times 8 plus 2 times 5) and confuses it with area. Choice 45 sq ft is 9 times 5, a multiplication slip. Area always carries square units; perimeter carries linear units. When the question asks how much surface a rug covers, you want square feet, which signals area, not perimeter.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-1'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'What is the circumference of a circle with radius 6 in? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["18.84 in","28.26 in","37.68 in","113.04 in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Circumference equals 2 pi r: 2 times 3.14 times 6 equals 37.68 inches. Choice 18.84 in uses pi r and forgets the factor of 2. Choice 28.26 in is pi times r squared divided by 4, a garbled mix of formulas. Choice 113.04 in is the area pi r squared (3.14 times 36), which is square inches, not linear inches. Circumference is a distance around the circle, so the units must be linear inches, not square inches.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-2'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'A square patio has sides of 7 ft. What is its perimeter?', '["14 ft","21 ft","28 ft","49 ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Perimeter of a square is 4 times the side length: 4 times 7 equals 28 feet. Choice 14 ft doubles the side as if the figure were a line segment with two ends. Choice 21 ft uses three sides only. Choice 49 ft is 7 squared, which gives the area in square feet, not the perimeter in linear feet. Perimeter measures the fence-line distance around the patio, so it must use linear units and count all four equal sides.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-3'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'A triangle has a base of 10 cm and a height of 6 cm. What is its area?', '["16 sq cm","30 sq cm","60 sq cm","120 sq cm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Area of a triangle is one-half base times height: 0.5 times 10 times 6 equals 30 square centimeters. Choice 16 sq cm adds base and height instead of multiplying. Choice 60 sq cm forgets the one-half factor and treats the triangle like a rectangle. Choice 120 sq cm doubles that error. The one-half factor exists because a triangle is exactly half of a rectangle with the same base and height, so any triangle area must include it.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-4'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'A right triangle has legs of 6 in and 8 in. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', '["10 in","100 in","14 in","48 in"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Using the Pythagorean theorem, a squared plus b squared equals c squared: 36 plus 64 equals 100, so c equals the square root of 100, which is 10 inches. Choice 100 in forgets to take the square root at the end and reports c squared as if it were c. Choice 14 in adds the legs directly (6 + 8 = 14), skipping the theorem entirely. Choice 48 in multiplies the legs (6 x 8). The 6-8-10 triple is a scaled 3-4-5; recognizing it on sight saves time. The hypotenuse is always the side opposite the right angle and is the longest side.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::pythagorean-triple'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'What is the surface area of a cube with edge length 4 in?', '["16 sq in","64 sq in","96 sq in","384 sq in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A cube has 6 identical square faces. Each face has area 4 squared, which is 16 square inches. Total surface area is 6 times 16, which equals 96 square inches. Choice 16 sq in gives only one face. Choice 64 sq in is 4 cubed, the volume in cubic inches. Choice 384 sq in is 6 times 64, mixing volume with the face count. Surface area uses square units; volume uses cubic units. Watching units catches the volume-vs-surface confusion fast.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-6'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A rectangular shipping crate is 5 ft long, 3 ft wide, and 2 ft tall. What is its volume?', '["10 cubic ft","15 cubic ft","30 cubic ft","62 cubic ft"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Volume of a rectangular prism is length times width times height: 5 times 3 times 2 equals 30 cubic feet. Choice 10 cubic ft multiplies only length and height, omitting width. Choice 15 cubic ft multiplies length and width and forgets the height entirely, a common error when people stop at base area. Choice 62 cubic ft is the surface area 2(lw + lh + wh), not the volume. Volume needs all three dimensions and uses cubic units.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-7'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A soda can is shaped like a cylinder with radius 2 in and height 5 in. What is its volume? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["31.4 cubic in","62.8 cubic in","78.5 cubic in","125.6 cubic in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Volume of a cylinder is pi r squared times height: 3.14 times 4 times 5 equals 62.8 cubic inches. Choice 31.4 cubic in uses pi r h, forgetting to square the radius. Choice 78.5 cubic in is pi r squared times r, using radius instead of height. Choice 125.6 cubic in doubles the answer, likely from using diameter (4) where radius (2) belongs and then squaring. Always square the radius in pi r squared and keep diameter and radius separated.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-8'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'A right triangle has one leg of 5 m and a hypotenuse of 13 m. What is the length of the other leg?', '["8 m","12 m","14 m","18 m"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Use a squared plus b squared equals c squared, where c is the hypotenuse: 5 squared plus b squared equals 13 squared, so 25 plus b squared equals 169. Then b squared equals 144, and b equals 12 meters. Choice 8 m subtracts 5 from 13 as if the sides were collinear. Choice 14 m adds them. Choice 18 m is 13 plus 5. This is the 5-12-13 triple. The hypotenuse is the longest side and always sits opposite the right angle.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::pythagorean-triple'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'What is the area of a circle with diameter 10 cm? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["15.7 sq cm","31.4 sq cm","78.5 sq cm","314 sq cm"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First convert diameter to radius: 10 divided by 2 equals 5 cm. Area is pi r squared: 3.14 times 25 equals 78.5 square centimeters. Choice 15.7 sq cm is half the circumference, mixing formulas. Choice 31.4 sq cm is the circumference using the diameter (pi times d). Choice 314 sq cm squares the diameter instead of the radius (3.14 times 100). Whenever a circle problem gives diameter, halve it before using pi r squared so the radius is squared, not the diameter.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-10'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'Two triangles are similar. The smaller has sides 4, 6, and 8 in. The longest side of the larger triangle is 20 in. What is the length of its shortest side?', '["10 in","12 in","15 in","16 in"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Similar triangles have a constant scale factor. The longest side scales from 8 to 20, so the factor is 20 divided by 8, which equals 2.5. The shortest side scales from 4 in, so 4 times 2.5 equals 10 inches. Choice 12 in scales the middle side (6 times 2). Choice 15 in scales the middle side by 2.5 (correct factor, wrong side). Choice 16 in doubles the shortest side using a factor of 2 from a wrong pairing. Always pair corresponding sides before computing the scale factor.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-11'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'A garden is a rectangle 12 ft by 6 ft with a semicircle attached to one short end. What is the total area? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["72 sq ft","86.13 sq ft","100.26 sq ft","172.5 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The rectangle area is 12 times 6, which equals 72 square feet. The semicircle sits on the short end, so its diameter is 6 ft and its radius is 3 ft. A full circle would be pi times 9, or 28.26; half of that is 14.13 square feet. Total area is 72 plus 14.13, which equals 86.13 square feet. Choice 72 sq ft skips the semicircle. Choice 100.26 sq ft adds a full circle instead of a half. Choice 172.5 sq ft uses the wrong radius (6 instead of 3) and forgets to halve.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-12'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'A circle has radius 12 in. What is the length of an arc that subtends a central angle of 90 degrees? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["9.42 in","18.84 in","37.68 in","75.36 in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 90-degree central angle is one-fourth of the full 360-degree circle, so the arc is one-fourth of the circumference. Circumference is 2 pi r: 2 times 3.14 times 12 equals 75.36 inches. One-fourth of 75.36 is 18.84 inches. Choice 9.42 in halves the radius then takes one-fourth, double-shrinking. Choice 37.68 in is half the circumference (a semicircle, not a quarter). Choice 75.36 in is the full circumference. Match the angle fraction to the full 360 before slicing the circumference.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-13'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'What is the surface area of a closed cylinder with radius 3 ft and height 7 ft? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["131.88 sq ft","188.4 sq ft","197.82 sq ft","263.76 sq ft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Surface area of a closed cylinder is 2 pi r squared plus 2 pi r h. The two circular ends are 2 times 3.14 times 9, which equals 56.52 square feet. The side is 2 times 3.14 times 3 times 7, which equals 131.88 square feet. Total is 56.52 plus 131.88, which equals 188.4 square feet. Choice 131.88 sq ft is the lateral side only and forgets the two ends. Choice 197.82 sq ft is the volume pi r squared h (3.14 times 9 times 7), wrong formula entirely. Choice 263.76 sq ft double-counts the side.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-14'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'Two parallel lines are cut by a transversal. One of the angles formed measures 65 degrees. What is the measure of its co-interior (same-side interior) angle?', '["25 degrees","65 degrees","115 degrees","130 degrees"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When parallel lines are cut by a transversal, co-interior (same-side interior) angles are supplementary, so they sum to 180 degrees. 180 minus 65 equals 115 degrees. Choice 25 degrees uses 90 minus 65, treating the angles as complementary, which would only apply if they summed to a right angle. Choice 65 degrees treats them as corresponding or alternate-interior angles, which are equal but not the relationship asked for. Choice 130 degrees doubles 65, a slip. Same-side interior pairs are always supplementary when the lines are parallel.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-NEW-15'),
  ('MK-GE-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'In a 30-60-90 triangle, the shorter leg is 5 in. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', '["5 in","10 in","5 times square root of 3 in","10 times square root of 3 in"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In a 30-60-90 right triangle, the side ratios are 1 to square root of 3 to 2, corresponding to the sides opposite the 30, 60, and 90 degree angles. The shorter leg (opposite 30) is 5 in, so the hypotenuse (opposite 90) is 2 times the shorter leg, which is 10 inches. Choice 5 in repeats the shorter leg. Choice 5 times square root of 3 in is the longer leg (opposite 60), not the hypotenuse. Choice 10 times square root of 3 in doubles the longer leg, mixing two ratios. The hypotenuse is always opposite the right angle and is twice the shorter leg in a 30-60-90.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::pythagorean-triple'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-1', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Which of the following is a prime number?', '["9","15","17","21"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A prime number has exactly two positive divisors: 1 and itself. Check each: 9 = 3 × 3, 15 = 3 × 5, and 21 = 3 × 7, so each has divisors beyond 1 and itself. Only 17 has no positive divisors except 1 and 17, making it prime. A common trap is forgetting that small odd composites like 9, 15, and 21 are not prime just because they look prime at a glance. Another trap is treating 1 as prime, but 1 has only one divisor and is excluded from the primes by definition.', false, 'draft', 'mk.number-properties::identify-prime'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-2', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'What is the value of |-12|?', '["-12","0","12","144"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Absolute value gives the distance of a number from zero on the number line, which is never negative. The distance from -12 to 0 is 12 units, so |-12| = 12. A common trap is leaving the negative sign in place and answering -12, but absolute value strips the sign. Another trap is squaring the number to get 144, which confuses |x| with x². A third trap is collapsing the bars to 0, which only applies when the input itself is 0.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-2'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-3', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Is 84 divisible by 4?', '["Yes, because 84 ÷ 4 = 21 with no remainder","No, because 84 is odd","No, because 84 is not a multiple of 8","No, because 8 + 4 = 12 is not divisible by 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A number is divisible by 4 when its last two digits form a number divisible by 4. The last two digits of 84 are 84, and 84 ÷ 4 = 21 with no remainder, so 84 is divisible by 4. The first No choice is wrong on a factual level: 84 ends in 4 and is even, not odd. The second No choice confuses divisibility by 4 with divisibility by 8 (every multiple of 8 is a multiple of 4, but not the reverse). The third No choice applies the digit-sum rule, which belongs to 3 and 9, not 4. Only the Yes choice supplies a valid verdict and reason.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-3'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-4', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'What is the smallest prime factor of 30?', '["1","2","3","5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The prime factors of 30 are 2, 3, and 5, since 30 = 2 × 3 × 5. The smallest of these is 2. A common trap is selecting 1, but 1 is not prime and is excluded from any prime factorization. Another trap is forgetting that 2 is prime because it is the only even prime, leading test-takers to skip it and pick 3. The smallest prime factor of any even number is always 2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-4'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the greatest common factor (GCF) of 18 and 24?', '["2","3","6","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each number: 18 = 2 × 3², and 24 = 2³ × 3. The GCF takes the lowest power of each shared prime: 2¹ × 3¹ = 6. The trap of selecting 72 confuses GCF with LCM, since 72 is the least common multiple of 18 and 24. The traps of 2 and 3 stop after finding one shared prime instead of multiplying all shared primes together. The GCF is always less than or equal to the smaller of the two numbers.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::gcf'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-6', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the least common multiple (LCM) of 4 and 6?', '["2","10","12","24"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each: 4 = 2² and 6 = 2 × 3. The LCM takes the highest power of every prime present: 2² × 3 = 12. The trap of selecting 2 confuses LCM with GCF, since 2 is the greatest common factor of 4 and 6. The trap of 24 multiplies the two numbers directly, which only gives the LCM when the numbers share no common factor. The trap of 10 adds the numbers instead of building from their prime factorizations.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::lcm'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-7', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'How many positive factors does 12 have?', '["3","4","5","6"]'::jsonb, 3, 'List all positive integers that divide 12 evenly: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 12. That is 6 factors total. A common trap is excluding 1 or 12 from the count and answering 4, but every positive integer counts itself and 1 among its factors. Another trap is counting only the prime factors (2 and 3) and answering 2 or stopping at 3. A shortcut: 12 = 2² × 3¹, so factor count = (2 + 1)(1 + 1) = 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-7'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-8', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'Which of the following is a perfect square?', '["18","24","36","50"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A perfect square is an integer that equals some integer squared. Check each: √18 ≈ 4.24, √24 ≈ 4.90, √36 = 6 exactly, and √50 ≈ 7.07. Only 36 = 6² is a perfect square. A common trap is picking 50 because it ends in 0 and looks clean, but perfect squares can end in 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, or 9, never in 2, 3, 7, or 8. Another trap is picking 18 or 24 because they are even, but evenness alone does not make a perfect square.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-8'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-9', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'Which of the following is NOT a prime number?', '["2","11","27","31"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Check each for divisors beyond 1 and itself: 11 and 31 have none, so both are prime. 27 = 3 × 9 = 3³, which is composite. The number 2 is prime because its only divisors are 1 and 2, even though it is even. A common trap is picking 2 because being even feels like it should disqualify a prime, but 2 is the only even prime. Another trap is missing that 27 is 3³, since 27 is odd and looks prime to test-takers who only screen for even composites.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::identify-prime'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-10', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the greatest common factor (GCF) of 12, 18, and 30?', '["2","3","6","60"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Factor each: 12 = 2² × 3, 18 = 2 × 3², and 30 = 2 × 3 × 5. The GCF uses the lowest power of each prime shared by all three: 2¹ × 3¹ = 6. The trap of 60 confuses GCF with LCM. The traps of 2 and 3 stop after finding one shared prime instead of multiplying every prime shared across all three numbers. Note that 5 appears only in 30, so it cannot be part of the GCF; a prime must be in every number to count.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::gcf'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-11', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the least common multiple (LCM) of 3, 4, and 6?', '["1","12","24","72"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Factor each: 3 = 3, 4 = 2², and 6 = 2 × 3. The LCM takes the highest power of every prime that appears in any number: 2² × 3 = 12. The trap of 72 multiplies all three numbers together, which overcounts shared primes. The trap of 24 doubles 12 unnecessarily, perhaps by forgetting that 6 is already covered when both 3 and 4 are present. The trap of 1 confuses LCM with GCF, since the GCF of 3, 4, and 6 is 1.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::lcm'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-12', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Is 432 divisible by 9?', '["No, because 432 is not a multiple of 6","Yes, because 4 + 3 + 2 = 9","No, because 432 is not divisible by 3","No, because 432 does not end in 0 or 9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A number is divisible by 9 when the sum of its digits is divisible by 9. For 432, the digit sum is 4 + 3 + 2 = 9, which is divisible by 9, so 432 is divisible by 9 (432 ÷ 9 = 48). The first No fails on its premise: 432 is in fact a multiple of 6 (432 ÷ 6 = 72), and divisibility by 6 is not the test for 9. The second No claims 432 is not divisible by 3, which is false; any multiple of 9 is also a multiple of 3. The last-digit rule belongs to 5 or 10, not 9.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-12'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-13', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'The product of an even integer and an odd integer is always:', '["Odd","Even","Prime","A perfect square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Any even integer contains a factor of 2. When that even integer is multiplied by an odd integer, the factor of 2 remains in the product, so the product is even. For example, 4 × 3 = 12 and 6 × 5 = 30. The trap of selecting odd misapplies the rule that odd × odd = odd to a mixed case. The trap of prime ignores that even products greater than 2 cannot be prime, since they have 2 as a factor. The trap of perfect square assumes structure that the rule does not guarantee.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-13'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-14', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'The sum of two odd integers is always:', '["Odd","Even","Prime","Divisible by 4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Write any odd integer as 2k + 1 for some integer k. The sum of two odd integers is (2a + 1) + (2b + 1) = 2a + 2b + 2 = 2(a + b + 1), which is a multiple of 2 and therefore even. Examples: 3 + 5 = 8 and 7 + 9 = 16. The trap of odd extends the wrong intuition that odd inputs yield odd outputs under addition. The trap of divisible by 4 holds only sometimes (3 + 5 = 8 works, but 3 + 7 = 10 does not). The trap of prime fails for almost every example.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-14'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-15', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'A trainer wants to split 24 boys and 36 girls into the largest possible teams, with each team having the same number of boys and the same number of girls. How many teams can she make?', '["6","12","60","72"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Largest equal groups across two counts requires the greatest common factor. Factor: 24 = 2³ × 3 and 36 = 2² × 3². GCF = 2² × 3 = 12, so she can make 12 teams, each with 24 ÷ 12 = 2 boys and 36 ÷ 12 = 3 girls. The trap of 60 adds the totals (24 + 36) and treats the result as the team count. The trap of 72 reaches for the LCM, which solves repeat-cycle problems, not equal-grouping problems. The trap of 6 stops at a shared factor without checking whether a larger one exists.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-15'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-16', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Bus A leaves every 15 minutes and Bus B leaves every 20 minutes. If both buses leave together at 8:00 AM, when will they next leave together?', '["8:35 AM","8:45 AM","9:00 AM","10:00 AM"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The next shared departure time is the least common multiple of the two intervals. Factor: 15 = 3 × 5 and 20 = 2² × 5. LCM = 2² × 3 × 5 = 60, so the buses next leave together after 60 minutes, at 9:00 AM. The trap of 8:35 AM adds the two intervals (15 + 20 = 35). The trap of 10:00 AM multiplies the intervals (15 × 20 = 300 minutes), which overcounts the shared factor of 5. The trap of 8:45 AM picks the next multiple of 15 without checking 20.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-16'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-17', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Simplify √72.', '["6√2","2√18","8√3","12√2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Find the largest perfect-square factor of 72. Factor: 72 = 36 × 2, and 36 is a perfect square. So √72 = √36 × √2 = 6√2. The trap of 2√18 pulls out only a partial factor (4) and leaves a square inside the radical, since 18 = 9 × 2 still has a perfect-square factor. The trap of 8√3 mismatches the factorization (8² × 3 = 192, not 72). The trap of 12√2 doubles the correct coefficient, perhaps from confusing 72 with 144. Always extract the largest perfect square.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-17'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-18', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Simplify √50.', '["2√5","5√2","10√5","25√2"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find the largest perfect-square factor of 50. Factor: 50 = 25 × 2, and 25 is a perfect square. So √50 = √25 × √2 = 5√2. The trap of 2√5 swaps the coefficient and the radicand, since (2√5)² = 20, not 50. The trap of 25√2 fails to take the square root of 25 and leaves it as a coefficient. The trap of 10√5 picks the wrong factor pair (10 × 5) where neither 10 nor 5 is a perfect square. The check: (5√2)² = 25 × 2 = 50.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-18'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-19', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'What is the prime factorization of 60?', '["2 × 30","2² × 15","2² × 3 × 5","2 × 3 × 10"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A prime factorization expresses a number as a product of prime numbers only. Break 60 down: 60 = 2 × 30 = 2 × 2 × 15 = 2 × 2 × 3 × 5 = 2² × 3 × 5. Every factor in the final form is prime. The trap of 2 × 30 stops too early, since 30 is composite. The trap of 2² × 15 also stops short, since 15 = 3 × 5 is composite. The trap of 2 × 3 × 10 includes 10, which is composite (10 = 2 × 5). A prime factorization is complete only when every factor is prime.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-19'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-20', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'How many positive divisors does 36 have?', '["6","8","9","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use the divisor-count formula: if n = p^a × q^b, then n has (a + 1)(b + 1) positive divisors. Factor: 36 = 2² × 3². Divisor count = (2 + 1)(2 + 1) = 9. Verify by listing: 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 9, 12, 18, 36, which is 9 divisors. The trap of 6 counts only some divisors or confuses divisors with prime factors. The trap of 8 forgets that 36 itself counts as a divisor. The trap of 12 may come from adding the exponents (2 + 2) and multiplying by 3, which is not the correct rule.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-20'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-21', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Three consecutive integers have a sum of 72. What is the middle integer?', '["22","23","24","25"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let the three consecutive integers be n - 1, n, and n + 1, where n is the middle integer. Their sum is (n - 1) + n + (n + 1) = 3n. Set 3n = 72, so n = 24. Check: 23 + 24 + 25 = 72. A useful shortcut for any odd count of consecutive integers: the sum divided by the count gives the middle term directly. The trap of 23 picks the smallest of the three. The trap of 25 picks the largest. The trap of 22 may come from dividing 72 by 3 and then subtracting 2 by mistake.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-NEW-21'),
  ('MK-NP-NEW-22', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'What is the sum of the first five prime numbers?', '["18","26","28","39"]'::jsonb, 2, 'List the first five primes in order: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11. Remember that 1 is not prime and 2 is the only even prime. Sum them: 2 + 3 + 5 + 7 + 11 = 28. The trap of 26 counts 9 as prime and lists 2, 3, 5, 7, 9, missing that 9 = 3 x 3. The trap of 39 skips 2 by assuming all primes are odd, listing 3, 5, 7, 11, 13. The trap of 18 counts 1 as prime and lists 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, stopping one prime short of the real first five.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::identify-prime'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Recycling at home is one of the easiest ways to help the environment. Sorting paper, plastic, and glass takes only a few minutes each week, but it keeps tons of waste out of landfills. Most cities now provide curbside bins at no extra cost, so the equipment is already there. The habit costs nothing and the payoff for local landfills is real. Every household should make recycling part of its weekly routine."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["explain how recycling facilities sort materials","encourage readers to recycle at home","compare landfills in different cities","describe the history of curbside recycling"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The closing sentence states the goal directly: "Every household should make recycling part of its weekly routine." That imperative, paired with "easiest ways to help" and "only a few minutes," marks the piece as persuasion. Choice B names that purpose. Choice A picks a technical angle the passage never enters, since sorting is mentioned only as effort the reader spends. Choice C invents a city-to-city comparison that does not appear. Choice D adds historical framing the passage does not provide. Only B fits the directive tone.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-1'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The new community park is a wonderful addition to our neighborhood. The walking trails are beautiful, the playground equipment is top quality, and the open lawns give families a perfect place to gather on weekends. The benches along the main path are already filled most evenings, and the new splash pad has been a favorite with children all summer. Residents should be proud of what their tax dollars built."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["skeptical","enthusiastic","indifferent","regretful"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Every adjective in the passage is praise: "wonderful," "beautiful," "top quality," "perfect," "proud." That stacked positive language signals enthusiasm rather than measured approval. Choice B names that tone. Choice A reverses the polarity, treating celebration as doubt. Choice C ignores the value-loaded vocabulary, which is the opposite of indifferent. Choice D imports regret the passage never expresses, since the author closes with pride rather than loss. Only B fits the consistently warm and celebratory language.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-2'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Reminder: All employees must complete the annual safety training by the end of the month. The training takes about thirty minutes and can be accessed through the company portal using your standard login credentials. Once complete, your manager will be notified automatically and no paperwork needs to be submitted. Failure to complete the training on time may delay payroll processing for the following pay period."

The author''s primary purpose in this memo is to:', '["praise employees for completing training quickly","inform employees of a deadline and how to meet it","argue that safety training should be made shorter","warn that the company is being investigated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The memo opens with "Reminder" and then lists the deadline, the time required, and how to access the training. That structure is straight notification. Choice B captures the informative purpose. Choice A invents praise the memo never offers, since employees are being prompted rather than thanked. Choice C reverses the position, since the author treats the thirty-minute length as a small ask, not a problem. Choice D escalates the routine consequence "may delay payroll" into an investigation the memo does not mention.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-3'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"I bought this blender expecting another disappointment. The last three I tried in this price range either burned out within weeks or struggled with anything thicker than a smoothie. Instead, this one crushed ice on the first try, cleaned up in under a minute, and has run every morning for six months without complaint. The motor still sounds the way it did out of the box. For under fifty dollars, I would call that a small miracle."

The author''s attitude toward the blender is best described as:', '["pleasantly surprised","wildly obsessive","mildly disappointed","coolly analytical"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author primes the reader for letdown with "expecting another disappointment," then flips with "Instead, it crushed ice on the first try" and "a small miracle." That contrast signals surprise paired with approval. Choice A names that exact attitude. Choice B overshoots into obsession, when the praise is measured rather than fanatical. Choice C contradicts the passage by holding onto disappointment the author explicitly drops. Choice D undersells the warmth in "small miracle," treating an excited review as a neutral analysis.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-4'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The proposal claims the new policy will save the city millions, but the numbers come from an internal estimate, not an independent audit. The same office that drafted the proposal also produced the financial projections that support it. Supporters keep citing the savings figure as if it were settled fact, and last week a council member quoted it on the radio without noting its source. Until outside reviewers verify the math, residents deserve to ask harder questions."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["openly hostile","skeptical","fully convinced","uninterested"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author flags the source of the numbers as "an internal estimate, not an independent audit" and calls for "outside reviewers" before treating the figure as fact. That is doubt grounded in process, not attack. Choice B names that skeptical tone. Choice A overshoots into hostility, since the author proposes verification rather than condemnation. Choice C reverses the position by treating the savings claim as accepted, which the passage refuses to do. Choice D ignores the active push for harder questions, which is the opposite of disengaged.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-5'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To: All staff. The fourth-floor copier will be out of service Thursday afternoon for scheduled maintenance. Please route urgent print jobs to the second-floor machine, which has the same drivers installed and accepts the same employee codes. Bulk print jobs over two hundred pages should be moved to Wednesday afternoon if possible. Service should be restored by 5 p.m., and a follow-up email will confirm the copier is available again. Thank you for your patience."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this memo is to:', '["apologize for repeated equipment failures","notify staff of a brief outage and offer a workaround","warn that the copier may be permanently removed","request feedback on copier performance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The memo states the outage window, offers the second-floor machine as an alternative, and gives a restoration time. Choice B captures that notify-and-redirect purpose. Choice A reads "thank you for your patience" as apology for repeated problems, but the passage describes one scheduled maintenance event, not a pattern of failures. Choice C invents a permanent removal the memo never raises. Choice D imports a feedback request that does not appear; nothing in the memo asks staff to evaluate the copier.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-6'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Walking the same streets where my grandmother sold flowers seventy years ago, I notice that the shopfronts have all changed. The bakery on the corner is now a phone store, and the small market where she bought her ribbon closed before I was born. Yet the morning light hitting the brick still looks the way it did in her old photographs, and the cracked sidewalk near the church has not been repoured. Cities do not stay the same, yet small details survive longer than we expect."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["nostalgic","bitter","scientific","alarmed"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author anchors the present in the past with "my grandmother sold flowers seventy years ago," "her old photographs," and "small details survive." That looking-back warmth is nostalgia rather than complaint. Choice A names that tone. Choice B imports bitterness the passage never voices, since the author notes loss without resentment. Choice C ignores the personal, memory-laden vocabulary, which is the opposite of detached observation. Choice D escalates a gentle reflection into alarm, when the closing sentence is consoling rather than urgent.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-7'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Early results from the trial suggest the new treatment may reduce recovery time by about two days. The sample was small, follow-up was short, and outcomes varied across age groups. Patients over sixty saw the largest effect, while younger participants showed almost none. The researchers themselves stop short of recommending broader use, and the published paper calls for a multi-site replication before any guidelines are updated. The findings are promising enough to justify a larger study, though not yet to change clinical practice."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["cautiously optimistic","enthusiastic","dismissive","alarmed"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author balances hope with limits: "promising enough to justify a larger study" sits next to "sample was small" and "not yet to change clinical practice." That paired structure is the signature of cautious optimism. Choice A names it. Choice B overshoots into enthusiasm, ignoring the qualifiers the author keeps inserting. Choice C reverses the position by treating the results as worth dismissing, when the passage explicitly calls them promising. Choice D imports alarm that nothing in the passage supports, since the framing is measured rather than worried.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-8'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The mayor''s plan to add bike lanes downtown is a reasonable start, even if it falls short of what the traffic studies recommended. The original review called for protected lanes on twelve streets; the approved plan funds only seven. Half a fix is still better than none, and the lanes that are being built happen to cover the most dangerous intersections, including the two with the highest crash counts in last year''s report. Residents who wanted more should treat this as a foundation, not a finish line."

The author would most likely agree with which statement?', '["The plan is a disappointing failure that should be rejected.","The plan is an acceptable first step that needs to be expanded.","The plan is exactly the right size and does not need additional work.","The plan is irrelevant because traffic patterns will not change."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author calls the plan "a reasonable start" and tells residents to treat it as "a foundation, not a finish line," which combines approval of the current step with a demand for more. Choice B captures both halves. Choice A reads the criticism as outright rejection, ignoring "reasonable start" and "better than none." Choice C drops the call for expansion the author explicitly makes. Choice D invents fatalism about traffic that the passage never expresses, since the lanes are credited with covering the most dangerous intersections.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-9'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Coastal communities have always rebuilt after storms. Generations of families have torn out drywall, replaced shingles, and put their lives back together more times than they care to count. What is new is the speed with which the same neighborhoods are being asked to rebuild again, sometimes twice in a single decade. Insurance maps are being redrawn quietly, premiums in flagged zones have doubled in five years, and the cost of staying is no longer just measured in lumber and shingles."

The author''s primary purpose in writing this passage is to:', '["celebrate the resilience of coastal towns","raise concern about rising costs and risks of coastal rebuilding","explain how insurance maps are technically constructed","argue that coastal communities should be abandoned immediately"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author pivots on "What is new is the speed" and notes that "the cost of staying is no longer just measured in lumber and shingles," which signals worry about a shifting situation. Choice B captures that concern. Choice A picks up the opening line about rebuilding but misses the warning that follows. Choice C invents a technical explanation the passage does not provide, since insurance maps are mentioned only as evidence. Choice D overshoots into a call for abandonment the author never makes, since the passage raises stakes without prescribing exit.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-10'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The latest software update promises faster load times, sharper graphics, and a redesigned interface that the company describes as a complete rethink of the workflow. Reviewers have been quick to call it a leap forward, and early demo videos have circulated widely. The benchmarks the company released cover load times and rendering speed, both of which are genuinely improved. Whether the new interface actually helps users finish tasks any faster is a separate question, and one the company has not chosen to answer with data."

The author''s attitude toward the update is best described as:', '["openly cynical","skeptical","appreciative","indifferent"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author reports the marketing claims, notes the reviewer praise, then isolates a missing piece: "a separate question, and one the company has not chosen to answer with data." That targeted doubt is skepticism. Choice B names it. Choice A overshoots into cynicism, which would imply the author assumes bad faith rather than asking for evidence. Choice C reverses the position by treating the author as approving, when the closing sentence withholds approval. Choice D ignores the pointed final clause, which is the opposite of disengaged.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-11'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The old library building is not beautiful in any conventional sense. Its bricks are dark, its windows are narrow, and the front steps slope at an angle no architect would defend today. But generations have walked those steps to find books they could not afford anywhere else, and that history sits in the walls more firmly than any renovation could."

The author''s attitude toward the library is best described as:', '["admiring","appreciative","sentimental and uncritical","professionally detached"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author acknowledges the building''s flaws plainly: "not beautiful," "dark," "narrow," "slope at an angle no architect would defend." The warmth arrives only in the closing pivot to what the building has meant for readers. That balance is appreciation, valuing the function and history without praising the form. Choice B fits. Choice A overshoots into admiration, which would treat the building itself as worthy of praise. Choice C drops the author''s frank critique of the architecture. Choice D ignores the personal closing line about generations of readers.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-12'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee''s report concludes that the program has, on the whole, met its stated objectives. A closer reading of the appendix shows that two of those objectives were revised downward halfway through the review period. The remaining metrics are real, and the gains they describe are real, even if the bar they cleared is lower than the one originally set."

The author would most likely agree with which statement?', '["The program is a clear success and the report should be accepted as written.","The program produced genuine gains, but the report''s headline claim overstates the result.","The program failed on every measure and the committee is hiding the truth.","The program''s metrics are unimportant and should be ignored entirely."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author validates part of the report by calling "the gains they describe" real, then flags that "two of those objectives were revised downward" and the "bar they cleared is lower than the one originally set." That is partial credit plus a caveat about the headline. Choice B captures both. Choice A drops the caveat the author insists on. Choice C escalates a calibration concern into total failure and concealment, which the passage does not support. Choice D dismisses the metrics the author explicitly affirms as real.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-13'),
  ('PC-ATP-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 5, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Critics of the new arts grant point out, fairly, that the selection process favored applicants from a small number of established institutions. The committee has acknowledged the imbalance and promised changes for next cycle. None of that erases the fact that the funded projects, judged on their own merits, are among the strongest the program has produced in a decade."

The author''s position is best described as:', '["fully defending the grant process against any criticism","rejecting the funded projects because of the flawed process","acknowledging the process flaw while still affirming the quality of the results","refusing to take any position on the outcome"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The author concedes the critique with "point out, fairly" and notes the committee''s promised changes, then pivots with "None of that erases the fact" to defend the projects on quality. That two-part move is precisely a process concession plus a results endorsement. Choice C names it. Choice A drops the concession the author openly makes. Choice B drops the endorsement the author insists on with "strongest the program has produced in a decade." Choice D ignores the clear final position, since the author commits to a verdict rather than hedging.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-ATP-NEW-14'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'The Hoover Dam was completed in 1936 after five years of continuous construction. Located on the border between Nevada and Arizona, it stands 726 feet tall. The dam created Lake Mead, which is the largest reservoir in the United States by volume. During its construction, more than 21,000 workers were employed, and 96 of them died on the job. The dam generates approximately four billion kilowatt-hours of electricity each year, serving customers in three states. Originally called the Boulder Dam, it was renamed in 1947 to honor President Herbert Hoover, who had championed the project while serving as Secretary of Commerce.

According to the passage, in what year was the Hoover Dam completed?', '["1931","1936","1947","1921"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The first sentence states, "The Hoover Dam was completed in 1936 after five years of continuous construction." Choice 1931 reflects when construction began (five years before 1936) but is not the completion year, an off-by-one trap on the five-year span. Choice 1947 is when the dam was renamed to honor Hoover, not when it was completed; it is a correct-but-wrong-question trap pulled from the closing sentence. Choice 1921 has no support in the passage; it is a plausible-looking distant date with no anchor in the text. Only 1936 directly matches the topic sentence and the completion question.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-1'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Honeybees communicate the location of food sources through a behavior called the waggle dance. A returning forager performs the dance on the vertical surface of the honeycomb, using a figure-eight pattern. The angle of the straight portion of the dance relative to vertical indicates the direction of the food source relative to the sun. The duration of the waggle phase signals the distance to the source. Karl von Frisch first decoded this behavior in the 1940s, work that earned him a Nobel Prize in 1973. Researchers have since confirmed that bees adjust the dance to account for the sun''s movement across the sky.

According to the passage, what is the name of the behavior bees use to communicate food location?', '["The figure-eight signal","The waggle dance","The forager pattern","The honeycomb dance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The opening sentence reads, "Honeybees communicate the location of food sources through a behavior called the waggle dance." Choice "figure-eight signal" describes the dance''s shape but is not its name. Choice "forager pattern" combines two real words from the passage (forager, pattern) into a label the passage never uses. Choice "honeycomb dance" trades on the location of the dance (the honeycomb) but is not what the behavior is called. Only "waggle dance" appears as the explicit name.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-2'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Solar panels convert sunlight directly into electricity using photovoltaic cells made primarily of silicon. The cells contain two layers of silicon that have been treated with different chemicals to give one layer a positive charge and the other a negative charge. When photons from sunlight strike the cells, they knock electrons loose, creating a flow of current. A single residential solar panel typically produces between 250 and 400 watts of power under ideal conditions. Most home installations use 20 to 30 panels arranged on a roof. The first practical silicon solar cell was developed at Bell Labs in 1954.

According to the passage, what material are photovoltaic cells primarily made of?', '["Copper","Silicon","Aluminum","Carbon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The opening sentence states cells are "made primarily of silicon." Copper is a common electrical material but the passage never mentions it; it is a plausible-sounding contradiction that readers might guess for anything electrical. Aluminum is similarly never named; it is a swap with another common conductor used in real-world wiring. Carbon is mentioned nowhere; it is included as a plausible chemistry-sounding distractor because of its broad role in materials science. Only silicon appears in the topic sentence as the primary material making up photovoltaic cells, so it is the single supported answer.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-3'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'The Pony Express was a mail delivery service that operated from April 1860 to October 1861. It used a relay of riders on horseback to carry letters between St. Joseph, Missouri, and Sacramento, California. The route covered approximately 1,900 miles and was usually completed in about 10 days. Riders changed horses every 10 to 15 miles at stations along the route, and they changed riders every 75 to 100 miles. The service ended just two days after the transcontinental telegraph line was completed, making the slower mail relay obsolete. Despite its short life, the Pony Express became a lasting symbol of the American West.

According to the passage, when did the Pony Express begin operating?', '["October 1860","April 1861","April 1860","October 1861"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states the service "operated from April 1860 to October 1861," identifying April 1860 as the start date. Choice October 1860 is a swap of the end-of-service month into the start year, a deliberately mixed pair. Choice April 1861 is a swap of the start month into the end year, the mirror image of the previous trap. Choice October 1861 is the date the service ended, not when it began, a correct-but-wrong-question trap. Only April 1860 matches the start date given explicitly in the topic sentence of the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-4'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Coffee plants thrive in a narrow band of climates near the equator known as the bean belt. Brazil leads the world in coffee production, growing roughly one-third of the global supply. The two commercially important species are arabica and robusta. Arabica beans, prized for their smoother flavor, account for about 60 percent of world production but require cooler temperatures and higher elevations. Robusta plants tolerate heat and lower altitudes, and they contain nearly twice the caffeine of arabica. Most premium specialty coffees are arabica. Vietnam is the largest producer of robusta, while Colombia specializes almost entirely in arabica.

According to the passage, which country is the largest producer of robusta coffee?', '["Brazil","Colombia","Vietnam","Ethiopia"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Near the end the passage states, "Vietnam is the largest producer of robusta." Brazil leads in overall coffee production at roughly one-third of global supply, not specifically robusta, so it is a correct-but-wrong-question trap that confuses overall leadership with category leadership. Colombia specializes almost entirely in arabica, the opposite species, making it a plausible swap of roles between the two named producers. Ethiopia is never mentioned and is included as a coffee-knowledge distractor since it is widely associated with coffee origins. Only Vietnam is explicitly tied to robusta leadership in the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-5'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'The human skeleton contains 206 bones in adulthood, but newborns are born with about 270. The difference is explained by the fusion of bones during growth, especially in the skull and spine. The longest bone in the body is the femur, located in the thigh, while the smallest is the stapes, found in the middle ear and measuring only about three millimeters. Bones serve several functions, including supporting the body, protecting organs, producing blood cells inside the marrow, and storing minerals such as calcium. Roughly half of all bones in the adult skeleton are located in the hands and feet.

According to the passage, what is the smallest bone in the human body?', '["The femur","The stapes","A bone in the spine","A bone in the hand"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The middle of the passage states, "the smallest is the stapes, found in the middle ear." The femur is named as the longest bone, not the smallest, making it a swap-of-roles trap. "A bone in the spine" plays on the fusion detail mentioned earlier but the passage never names any spine bone as smallest. "A bone in the hand" exploits the closing detail that half of all bones are in hands and feet, an over-generalization. Only the stapes is identified as smallest.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-6'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Workplace ergonomics is the science of designing tasks and tools to fit the worker rather than forcing the worker to adapt. A properly configured office workstation places the top of the monitor at eye level, with the screen about an arm''s length away. Chairs should support the lower back, and feet should rest flat on the floor or on a footrest. The keyboard should be positioned so that the elbows form roughly a 90-degree angle. Studies by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration show that ergonomic improvements can reduce repetitive strain injuries by up to 60 percent. Frequent short breaks further reduce fatigue.

According to the passage, where should the top of a computer monitor be positioned?', '["At chin level","At eye level","Slightly above eye level","An arm''s length below eye level"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "the top of the monitor at eye level, with the screen about an arm''s length away." "Chin level" is a plausible-sounding contradiction not in the text. "Slightly above eye level" is the kind of detail readers may guess but the passage gives exactly "at eye level," not above it. "An arm''s length below eye level" mashes together two true details (an arm''s length away, eye level) into a false position. Only "at eye level" matches the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-7'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Hurricanes are tropical storms that form over warm ocean waters near the equator. To be classified as a hurricane, a storm must produce sustained winds of at least 74 miles per hour. Storms are ranked on the Saffir-Simpson scale, which assigns a category from 1 through 5 based on wind speed. A Category 1 hurricane has winds between 74 and 95 miles per hour, while a Category 5 has sustained winds above 157 miles per hour. The Atlantic hurricane season officially runs from June 1 through November 30, with peak activity typically occurring in mid-September. Hurricanes are called typhoons in the western Pacific.

According to the passage, what is the minimum sustained wind speed for a storm to be classified as a hurricane?', '["95 miles per hour","157 miles per hour","74 miles per hour","60 miles per hour"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states a storm "must produce sustained winds of at least 74 miles per hour" to be classified as a hurricane. 95 mph is the upper bound of Category 1 on the Saffir-Simpson scale, a correct-but-wrong-question trap pulled from the middle of the passage. 157 mph is the threshold for Category 5, the most severe rating, and represents the opposite extreme of the scale rather than the minimum. 60 mph is a plausible-sounding wind speed for tropical storms but the passage never gives that figure. Only 74 mph matches the stated minimum hurricane classification threshold.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-8'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'The Apollo program landed twelve astronauts on the Moon between 1969 and 1972 across six successful missions. Apollo 11, in July 1969, made the first landing, with Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin walking on the surface while Michael Collins remained in orbit. The final mission, Apollo 17, in December 1972, included geologist Harrison Schmitt, the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon. Apollo 13, in April 1970, was intended to land but suffered an oxygen tank explosion and looped around the Moon without landing. The Apollo astronauts collectively returned 842 pounds of lunar samples to Earth.

According to the passage, who was the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon?', '["Neil Armstrong","Buzz Aldrin","Michael Collins","Harrison Schmitt"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage states, "Apollo 17, in December 1972, included geologist Harrison Schmitt, the only trained scientist to walk on the Moon." Armstrong and Aldrin are named as the first to walk on the Moon during Apollo 11, but neither is described as a trained scientist. Collins is named as the Apollo 11 astronaut who remained in orbit and never walked on the surface at all. Among four named astronauts, only Schmitt is explicitly identified as the trained scientist.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-9'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Vaccines work by training the immune system to recognize specific pathogens without causing the disease itself. Live attenuated vaccines, such as the one for measles, use a weakened form of the virus. Inactivated vaccines, like the standard flu shot, use a killed version of the pathogen. Subunit vaccines, such as the one for hepatitis B, contain only specific pieces of the pathogen rather than the whole microbe. mRNA vaccines, used against COVID-19, give cells instructions to produce a harmless piece of the virus to trigger an immune response. Each approach has trade-offs in storage requirements, manufacturing speed, and how long protection lasts.

According to the passage, which type of vaccine is the standard flu shot?', '["Live attenuated","Inactivated","Subunit","mRNA"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "Inactivated vaccines, like the standard flu shot, use a killed version of the pathogen." Live attenuated is the category given for the measles vaccine, a correct-but-wrong-question trap among the four types listed. Subunit is the category for hepatitis B, not the flu shot. mRNA is the technology used against COVID-19. Each wrong choice is a real vaccine category from the passage but is tied there to a different disease, not to the flu shot.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-10'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Plate tectonics describes how Earth''s outer shell is divided into roughly a dozen large pieces called plates that move slowly over the planet''s mantle. The plates interact in three main ways. At convergent boundaries, plates collide, sometimes pushing one plate beneath the other in a process called subduction. The Andes Mountains formed this way. At divergent boundaries, plates pull apart, allowing magma to rise and create new crust, as in the Mid-Atlantic Ridge. At transform boundaries, plates slide past each other horizontally, generating frequent earthquakes; California''s San Andreas Fault is the best-known example. Average plate movement is about two to four inches per year.

According to the passage, the Andes Mountains formed at what type of plate boundary?', '["Divergent","Transform","Convergent","Subduction"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states, "At convergent boundaries, plates collide... The Andes Mountains formed this way." Divergent boundaries are tied to the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, not the Andes. Transform boundaries are tied to the San Andreas Fault and frequent earthquakes, not mountain building. "Subduction" is mentioned in the passage as a process that can occur at convergent boundaries, but it is not itself a type of boundary; it is an over-generalization of a sub-detail. Only convergent matches the boundary type for the Andes.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-11'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'OSHA reporting rules require employers to record any work-related injury that meets specific criteria. A case must be logged if it results in death, days away from work, restricted work activity, transfer to another job, loss of consciousness, or a significant injury diagnosed by a licensed health-care professional. Minor cuts treated with a bandage and standard first aid do not have to be recorded. Employers must also report serious incidents directly to OSHA within set time limits: any fatality within 8 hours and any inpatient hospitalization, amputation, or loss of an eye within 24 hours. Records must be retained for five years.

According to the passage, within how many hours must an employer report a work-related fatality to OSHA?', '["24 hours","8 hours","5 hours","48 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states, "any fatality within 8 hours and any inpatient hospitalization, amputation, or loss of an eye within 24 hours." 24 hours is the deadline for hospitalizations, amputations, and eye loss, a correct-but-wrong-question trap that swaps the two reporting windows. 5 hours echoes the "five years" retention period reshaped from years into hours; no such 5-hour rule exists in the passage. 48 hours is a plausible-sounding compliance window often associated with regulatory deadlines but is never mentioned in this text. Only 8 hours matches the fatality-reporting deadline stated explicitly.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-12'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'The Great Barrier Reef, located off the northeastern coast of Australia, is the largest coral reef system in the world. It stretches more than 1,400 miles and is composed of nearly 3,000 individual reefs and 900 islands. The reef supports over 1,500 species of fish, 400 species of coral, and 4,000 types of mollusks. It is visible from space and was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1981. Climate change, agricultural runoff, and crown-of-thorns starfish are the main threats to its survival. Mass coral bleaching events occurred in 2016, 2017, 2020, and 2022.

Which of the following is NOT mentioned in the passage as a threat to the Great Barrier Reef?', '["Climate change","Agricultural runoff","Crown-of-thorns starfish","Commercial fishing"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage lists "Climate change, agricultural runoff, and crown-of-thorns starfish" as the main threats to the reef. Climate change is explicitly named as a main threat, so it does appear. Agricultural runoff is explicitly named in the same sentence and likewise appears. Crown-of-thorns starfish is explicitly named alongside the other two, also appearing in the text. Commercial fishing sounds like a plausible reef threat that readers may guess from outside knowledge, but it never appears in this passage, making it the only option not mentioned and therefore the correct answer to a NOT-mentioned question.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-13'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'A standard home electrical panel in the United States distributes 240-volt service through a series of circuit breakers. Most lighting and outlet circuits operate on 15-amp or 20-amp breakers at 120 volts. Larger appliances draw 240 volts: electric dryers typically use 30-amp breakers, electric ranges use 40-amp or 50-amp breakers, and central air-conditioning condensers use 30-amp or 40-amp breakers. Each breaker is designed to trip when current exceeds its rating, preventing wires from overheating. Modern code also requires ground-fault circuit interrupters in bathrooms, kitchens, garages, and outdoor outlets, and arc-fault interrupters in bedrooms.

Which of the following appliances is NOT mentioned in the passage?', '["Electric dryer","Electric range","Central air-conditioning condenser","Electric water heater"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage names three specific appliances drawing 240 volts: "electric dryers typically use 30-amp breakers, electric ranges use 40-amp or 50-amp breakers, and central air-conditioning condensers use 30-amp or 40-amp breakers." Electric dryer is mentioned by name with its breaker rating. Electric range is mentioned with its breaker rating. Central air-conditioning condenser is mentioned with its breaker rating. Electric water heaters are a real 240-volt appliance and sound plausible to a reader bringing outside knowledge, but they never appear in this passage, making them the only choice not mentioned in the text.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-14'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'A balanced diet recommended by the U.S. Dietary Guidelines includes five food groups: fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy. Fruits and vegetables should fill roughly half of each plate. At least half of grain servings should be whole grains rather than refined grains. Protein foods include lean meats, poultry, eggs, seafood, beans, peas, nuts, and soy products. Dairy options include milk, yogurt, cheese, and fortified soy beverages. The guidelines also recommend limiting added sugars to less than 10 percent of daily calories, saturated fats to less than 10 percent of daily calories, and sodium to less than 2,300 milligrams per day.

Which of the following is NOT listed in the passage as one of the five food groups?', '["Vegetables","Grains","Fats","Dairy"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage names "fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy" as the five food groups in the U.S. Dietary Guidelines. Vegetables is explicitly named in that list. Grains is explicitly named in that list. Dairy is explicitly named in that list. Fats are discussed only as something to limit, with saturated fats specifically capped at less than 10 percent of daily calories, and they are never listed as a food group. Fats is therefore the only option not in the five-group list, making it the correct answer to the NOT-listed question.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-15'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A small business tracks its monthly utility bills to budget for the year. In January, electricity costs were $420 and natural gas was $310. By July, electricity had risen to $680 due to air-conditioning demand, while natural gas had fallen to $90. Water charges remained steady at about $75 per month throughout the year. Internet and phone service together cost $185 per month on a flat plan. The owner noticed that combined utility expenses in July exceeded combined utility expenses in January, even though heating costs had dropped substantially during the warmer months.

Based on the passage, by approximately how much did the company''s combined utility bill increase from January to July?', '["$30","$220","$260","$170"]'::jsonb, 0, 'January totals: $420 + $310 + $75 + $185 = $990. July totals: $680 + $90 + $75 + $185 = $1,030. The increase is $1,030 minus $990, which equals $40, closest to $30 among the choices. $260 reflects only the electricity rise ($680 minus $420). $220 over-counts by mixing electricity and gas changes in one direction. $170 conflates partial swings. Only $30 approximates the true net change once gas savings offset most of the electricity increase.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-16'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A regional hospital reports its emergency department traffic each quarter. In the first quarter, the department treated 4,200 patients, with an average wait time of 38 minutes. In the second quarter, patient volume rose to 5,100 and average wait time stretched to 52 minutes. The third quarter saw 5,400 patients with a wait time of 49 minutes after two additional triage nurses were hired in late June. In the fourth quarter, holiday-related cases pushed volume to 5,800, but wait times held at 50 minutes thanks to the staffing change. Administrators consider any quarter with average wait under 45 minutes a success.

Based on the passage, how many quarters met the administrators'' success criterion?', '["Zero","One","Two","Three"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Success requires average wait under 45 minutes. Q1 wait is 38 minutes, which meets the criterion. Q2 is 52 minutes, which fails. Q3 is 49 minutes, which still fails despite improvement after the triage hires. Q4 is 50 minutes, which also fails. Only one quarter meets the standard. "Zero" overlooks Q1, the lowest wait time in the year. "Two" likely arises from mistakenly treating Q3''s near-45 figure as passing the threshold. "Three" assumes most quarters succeeded, the opposite of what the recorded numbers actually show.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-17'),
  ('PC-DR-NEW-18', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 5, 'A community library tracks book checkouts by category. Fiction accounts for about 45 percent of all checkouts, biography for 15 percent, science and technology for 12 percent, children''s books for 20 percent, and reference for the remainder. In the most recent year, the library logged 60,000 total checkouts. Staff have noticed that biography circulation has roughly doubled since a popular streaming documentary series launched two years ago. The library plans to expand its biography collection if the category exceeds 10,000 annual checkouts in the coming year.

Based on the passage, approximately how many biography checkouts did the library record in the most recent year?', '["6,000","9,000","12,000","10,000"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Biography is stated as 15 percent of 60,000 total checkouts. Computing 15 percent of 60,000 gives 9,000 biography checkouts in the most recent year. 6,000 corresponds to 10 percent and would match the lower-end share but contradicts the stated 15 percent figure for biography. 12,000 corresponds to 20 percent, which is the figure given for children''s books, a correct-but-wrong-question swap between two categories. 10,000 is the trigger number for collection expansion in the coming year, not the current biography total. Only 9,000 is consistent with the stated 15 percent share.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-DR-NEW-18'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Honeybees navigate using polarized sunlight, even on cloudy days when humans see only diffuse gray sky overhead. Their compound eyes contain specialized receptors that detect the orientation of light waves passing through the atmosphere. When researchers covered hive entrances with polarizing filters that scrambled the natural light pattern, foragers returning from familiar feeding sites became visibly disoriented and circled the hive for extended periods before they could land.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Honeybees rely on detecting polarized light patterns to orient themselves","Honeybees cannot see at all when the sky is cloudy","Honeybees have compound eyes with specialized receptors","Honeybees produce more honey on sunny days than on cloudy days"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage states bees use polarized light for navigation and that scrambling that pattern disoriented even experienced foragers, which directly supports choice A as a one-step inference from cause and effect. Choice B contradicts the passage, which explicitly says bees navigate even on cloudy days when humans see only gray. Choice C is the under-reach trap, restating an explicit detail about receptors without drawing any inference from it. Choice D is off-topic; honey production is never mentioned anywhere in the passage. Choice A is the cleanest one-step read of the evidence.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-1'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Concrete poured in freezing weather can fail catastrophically. Water in the wet mix expands as it crystallizes into ice, creating internal pressure that fractures the curing matrix before the cement can develop strength. Contractors working in cold climates use heated enclosures, insulated blankets, or chemical accelerators to keep concrete above 40 degrees Fahrenheit during the first 24 hours after pouring.

Based on the passage, which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["The first day after pouring is the most vulnerable period for concrete in cold conditions","Concrete poured in summer never develops any structural defects","Chemical accelerators are more effective than insulated blankets","Heated enclosures are required by building codes in every cold region"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage specifies that protective measures target the first 24 hours after pouring, which implies that window is when freezing damage is most likely to occur. Choice A captures this one-step inference cleanly. Choice B over-reaches; the passage focuses on cold weather and never claims summer concrete is defect-free. Choice C over-reaches by ranking effectiveness among methods the passage merely lists side by side. Choice D over-reaches by inferring a legal mandate from a description of common practice. The 24-hour detail points clearly to choice A.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-2'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Sourdough bread relies on wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria that live in the flour and surrounding air. Unlike commercial baker''s yeast, which produces consistent rise times, wild cultures vary in activity depending on temperature, humidity, and the specific strains present in a kitchen. Two bakers using identical recipes in different homes will often produce loaves with noticeably different textures and flavors.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Environmental conditions affect the outcome of sourdough baking","Commercial baker''s yeast produces better-tasting bread than wild yeast","Lactic acid bacteria are harmful to people who eat sourdough","Professional bakers always control humidity in their kitchens"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage explicitly ties variation in texture and flavor to differences in temperature, humidity, and local strains across kitchens, which supports choice A as a direct one-step inference. Choice B over-reaches by introducing a quality judgment the passage never makes; consistency is mentioned, not superiority. Choice C contradicts the implication that these bacteria are a normal and expected part of sourdough fermentation. Choice D over-reaches by inferring professional behavior from a passage that only describes home bakers using identical recipes. Choice A is the cleanest read.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-3'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Modern wind turbines automatically pitch their blades to limit rotation speed during high winds. If a blade caught the full force of a gust without adjusting, centrifugal stress could rip it from the hub. The pitch control system rotates each blade along its long axis, reducing the effective angle that strikes the wind and slowing the rotor before damage occurs.

The passage suggests that pitch control primarily exists to:', '["Protect turbine components from wind-induced mechanical failure","Increase electricity output during periods of low wind","Reduce noise complaints from nearby residents","Allow turbines to operate without any electronic monitoring"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes pitch control as a response to dangerous high winds that would otherwise generate centrifugal stress capable of tearing blades from the hub, which supports choice A directly. Choice B contradicts the passage, which describes the system slowing rotation rather than boosting output during low wind. Choice C is off-topic; noise complaints are never mentioned anywhere in the text. Choice D contradicts the implication of an automatic system, which requires monitoring of wind conditions to function. Protection from mechanical failure is the clearest single-step inference.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-4'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Lithium-ion batteries lose capacity faster when stored at full charge in warm conditions. A battery held at 100 percent in a hot garage may lose 35 percent of its original capacity within a year, while the same battery kept at 50 percent charge in a cool basement might lose only 4 percent over the same period. Manufacturers therefore recommend storing rarely used devices at moderate charge levels in temperature-controlled spaces.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Storing a laptop fully charged in a warm closet accelerates battery degradation","Lithium-ion batteries last longer than nickel-cadmium batteries","Cool temperatures alone are enough to prevent any capacity loss","Manufacturers recommend never charging a battery above 50 percent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Choice A combines two stated conditions, full charge plus warm storage, to draw a specific applied inference about a laptop in a warm closet, which is the textbook two-step pattern this difficulty level expects. Choice B is off-topic; no other battery chemistry is mentioned for comparison. Choice C over-reaches by inferring complete prevention when the passage shows only reduced loss at four percent rather than zero. Choice D over-reaches by turning a storage recommendation into a charging prohibition; the passage addresses rarely used devices, not daily use.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-5'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'City planners studying foot traffic found that pedestrians overwhelmingly prefer routes with continuous shade during summer months. On one downtown corridor, a sidewalk lined with mature oak trees carried four times the foot traffic of a parallel route two blocks away, even though the shaded path added roughly 90 seconds to most trips. After the city removed several diseased oaks, monthly counts on the shaded corridor fell sharply.

Based on the passage, which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Pedestrians will accept modestly longer walks in exchange for shade","Oak trees are the only tree species that attract foot traffic","Removing trees has no measurable effect on pedestrian behavior","Most pedestrians avoid downtown areas during summer entirely"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage states that pedestrians chose the shaded route despite the added 90 seconds and that traffic dropped sharply when trees were removed. Combining these two facts supports choice A as a two-step inference about preference and trade-off. Choice B over-reaches; oaks are the specific example used, not a stated species requirement for foot traffic. Choice C directly contradicts the passage, which explicitly describes a sharp drop after tree removal. Choice D contradicts the high four-times traffic count on the shaded corridor in summer.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-6'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Most small claims courts cap awards at amounts between 5,000 and 25,000 dollars depending on the state. Filing fees usually run under 100 dollars, and parties typically argue their own cases without attorneys. Judges aim to resolve disputes within a single brief hearing, often the same morning multiple cases are scheduled. Plaintiffs seeking larger awards or complex remedies must use higher courts, which involve formal procedure and significantly greater expense.

What can be inferred from the passage?', '["Small claims courts are designed to handle low-value disputes quickly and affordably","Small claims court hearings always last several days","Hiring an attorney is prohibited in small claims court","Higher courts award smaller damages than small claims courts"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Choice A integrates the dollar caps, low filing fees, and same-morning hearing format into a coherent two-step inference about the court''s purpose and design. Choice B directly contradicts the same-morning brief-hearing detail given in the passage. Choice C over-reaches; the passage says parties typically self-represent, which describes practice rather than a legal prohibition on hiring attorneys. Choice D contradicts the passage, which states explicitly that larger awards require moving up to higher courts. Choice A is the synthesis the passage clearly invites a reader to draw.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-7'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Coral reefs form only in clear tropical seawater between roughly 73 and 84 degrees Fahrenheit. The animals that build reefs depend on symbiotic algae that photosynthesize inside their tissues, so cloudy water blocks the light those algae need. When ocean temperatures climb above 86 degrees for sustained periods, the corals expel their algal partners and turn white, a condition called bleaching that often kills the colony.

Which conclusion does the passage most strongly support?', '["Reef survival depends on water that is both warm enough and clear enough","Bleached corals always recover if temperatures fall the following week","Tropical seawater never exceeds 86 degrees Fahrenheit","Algae can photosynthesize without any access to sunlight"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage gives a narrow temperature range and a separate clarity requirement, both presented as essential, which supports choice A as a two-fact synthesis about reef-building conditions. Choice B over-reaches with the word always; the passage says bleaching often kills colonies, suggesting recovery is far from guaranteed. Choice C directly contradicts the passage, which describes temperatures climbing above 86 degrees and triggering bleaching. Choice D contradicts the explicit role of light in algal photosynthesis described in the same sentence. Choice A is the disciplined inference.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-8'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Cooking shows that emphasize speed and convenience above all else have shaped a generation of home cooks who panic when a recipe calls for resting dough overnight or simmering stock for hours. We have come to treat any process longer than 30 minutes as a failure of efficiency, as if our grandparents wasted their lives by braising. The richest flavors in any tradition arise from patience, and a kitchen that cannot wait is a kitchen that cannot taste.

Which statement does the author most likely believe?', '["Modern media has trained cooks to undervalue time-intensive techniques","Cooking shows should be banned from television","Older generations cooked exclusively with slow methods","Resting dough overnight is the only worthwhile technique"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author''s frustration with speed-focused shows, the rhetorical question about grandparents, and the closing line about waiting and tasting reveal an implicit assumption that modern media has narrowed cooks'' patience for slow technique, which supports choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the author criticizes a trend in programming, not the existence of cooking shows themselves. Choice C over-reaches with the word exclusively, which the passage never claims. Choice D over-reaches by treating a single example of slow technique as the only valued one. Choice A captures the implicit position.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-9'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Volunteer firefighting departments in rural counties face a recruitment crisis that no amount of equipment funding can solve. Trucks and gear sit unused not because budgets are tight but because fewer working-age residents remain in these communities, and those who stay often commute too far to respond during daylight hours. Until lawmakers grapple with rural depopulation itself, even generous grants will leave stations short-handed at the moments they matter most.

The passage suggests that the author believes:', '["Equipment grants alone cannot fix what is fundamentally a population problem","Volunteer firefighting is no longer a useful model anywhere","Rural residents are unwilling to volunteer for any community service","Lawmakers have already solved the rural depopulation problem"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author treats funding as misdirected because the root cause is demographic rather than financial, an implicit assumption clearly visible in the contrast between budgets and bodies, which supports choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the author critiques the recruitment shortfall in rural areas, not the volunteer model itself or its use elsewhere. Choice C over-reaches by attributing unwillingness when the passage explicitly cites commuting distance and population loss as the cause. Choice D directly contradicts the passage''s call for lawmakers to begin grappling with the issue.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-10'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Public libraries that once defined themselves by their book collections have spent the last decade quietly transforming into community workspaces. Patrons now book private rooms for video interviews, borrow laptop chargers, and use 3D printers as often as they check out novels. Some librarians worry that calling these institutions libraries at all may eventually mislead the public about what they actually offer.

The author would most likely agree that:', '["The traditional definition of a library no longer captures the full range of services offered","Libraries should immediately remove all books from their buildings","Patrons who still read novels are an obstacle to library modernization","Library budgets have grown substantially over the last decade"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes a transformation and quotes librarians worried about an outdated name, which together reveal an implicit assumption that the old definition is becoming inadequate, supporting choice A. Choice B over-reaches; the passage describes evolution alongside continued book lending, not the removal of books. Choice C contradicts the neutral tone toward novel-borrowing patrons, who appear in the same sentence as 3D printer users without judgment. Choice D is off-topic; library budgets are never discussed anywhere in the passage. Choice A captures the implicit position about naming and identity.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-11'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Manufacturers of premium kitchen knives have begun stamping serial numbers on every blade and offering lifetime warranties tied to the original purchaser. Marketing materials describe these moves as quality assurance, but the practice also makes it harder for buyers to resell knives privately and easier for makers to track which retailers discount their inventory. Consumer advocates have started questioning whose interests these programs really serve.

Which statement does the author most likely believe?', '["Lifetime warranty programs may benefit manufacturers more than buyers","Premium kitchen knives are not worth their listed price","Serial numbers always lower the quality of finished blades","Consumer advocates have proven that all warranty programs are fraudulent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author juxtaposes marketing claims about quality assurance with practical effects that constrain resale and police retailers, an implicit assumption that buyers are not the primary beneficiary of these programs, which supports choice A. Choice B is off-topic; the price-to-value question is never argued or even raised in the passage. Choice C over-reaches by inventing a link between serial numbers and product quality that the passage does not make. Choice D over-reaches; the passage says advocates have started questioning, not that they have proven anything fraudulent.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-12'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'A study of urban bicycle commuters found that those who wore high-visibility yellow vests reported feeling safer than those who did not, even though crash data from the same period showed no statistically significant difference in collision rates between the two groups. Researchers cautioned that perceived safety and actual safety can diverge in ways that affect behavior, including how aggressively riders position themselves in traffic.

Which conclusion is best supported by the passage?', '["The perception of being safer does not necessarily reflect actual reductions in crash risk","Yellow vests cause more bicycle collisions than they prevent","Bicycle commuters should stop wearing high-visibility gear","All safety equipment is purely psychological in effect"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage cleanly distinguishes self-reported feelings from crash data and warns explicitly about divergence between perceived and actual safety, which supports choice A without any unsupported leaps. Choice B over-reaches; the data showed no significant difference between groups, not that vests caused additional crashes. Choice C is an unsupported recommendation; the passage offers cautious analysis rather than any prescription for riders. Choice D is the inference-overreach trap, generalizing from one specific finding about vests to a sweeping claim about all safety equipment. Choice A stops exactly where the evidence stops.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-13'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Researchers analyzing customer reviews on a major online retailer noticed that products with average ratings between 4.2 and 4.5 stars tended to outsell products rated 4.8 or higher. Interviews with shoppers suggested that perfect or near-perfect ratings raised suspicion of manipulation, while slightly imperfect ratings struck buyers as more credible. The retailer has not announced any plans to change how ratings are displayed.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Shoppers may interpret slightly imperfect ratings as a signal of authenticity","Ratings above 4.5 stars are always the result of manipulation","The retailer is planning to hide perfect ratings from buyers","Customer reviews have no influence on online purchasing decisions"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Shopper interviews tied buyer suspicion to near-perfect ratings and credibility to slightly imperfect ones, which supports choice A as a careful inference about how buyers read review patterns. Choice B is the over-reach trap, converting a buyer perception into a factual claim that high ratings are manipulated. Choice C directly contradicts the explicit statement that the retailer has announced no display changes. Choice D contradicts the passage, which shows ratings clearly influence sales by linking specific rating ranges to outselling. Choice A stops at what the shoppers themselves report.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-14'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'A regional hospital system that switched from paper charts to a unified electronic medical record initially saw medication errors drop 22 percent. Three years later, however, error rates had crept back to within 4 percent of the original baseline. Quality officers attributed the rebound to alert fatigue, the phenomenon in which clinicians begin to ignore safety warnings after encountering too many false positives during routine work.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Technology gains in safety can erode when human responses to that technology change","Electronic medical records ultimately cause more errors than paper charts","Alert fatigue is unique to hospitals that recently switched systems","Reducing the number of safety alerts would eliminate medication errors entirely"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage describes an initial 22 percent gain that eroded as clinicians adapted to alerts, which supports choice A as a precise inference about behavior eroding technical benefits over time. Choice B over-reaches; error rates rebounded close to but not above the paper baseline, so the system did not cause more errors. Choice C over-reaches by claiming uniqueness the passage never asserts about this hospital system. Choice D over-reaches with the word entirely; the passage offers no guarantee that reducing alerts would eliminate every error. Choice A captures exactly what the rebound implies.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-15'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'A 12-year analysis of municipal recycling programs found that cities mandating clear plastic collection bags had higher reported recycling rates than cities using opaque bags, but landfill audits revealed that the clear-bag cities also threw away slightly more recyclable material in regular trash. Researchers theorized that residents avoided putting questionable items in transparent bags out of social embarrassment, preferring to discard them invisibly.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Visibility-based policies can shift where waste appears without changing total recycling behavior","Clear-bag policies cause residents to recycle more material overall","Opaque bag cities have eliminated recycling contamination","Social embarrassment is the strongest motivator of recycling behavior"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Higher reported rates paired with more recyclables found in landfill trash means visibility shifted disposal location without expanding total recycling, which supports choice A as the disciplined synthesis. Choice B is the almost-but-not-quite trap; higher reported rates initially look like more recycling, but the landfill audit cancels that gain by showing recyclables hidden in regular trash. Choice C over-reaches; opaque-bag cities are never described as contamination-free in the passage. Choice D over-reaches by elevating one researcher theory to the strongest motivator when the passage offers it tentatively. Choice A is the precise read.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-16'),
  ('PC-INF-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 5, 'An evaluation of remote-work pilot programs across 14 large companies found that employees reporting the highest job satisfaction were those who worked remotely two or three days per week, not those who worked remotely full time. Fully remote employees often reported satisfaction comparable to fully in-office employees, but they were also significantly more likely to leave their employer within 18 months. Researchers suggested that satisfaction surveys may miss factors like weak peer attachment that influence retention.

Which conclusion is most strongly supported?', '["Self-reported satisfaction may not fully capture the conditions that keep employees at a job","Fully remote employees are less satisfied than hybrid employees","Companies should require all employees to work in the office at least two days per week","Peer attachment is the only factor that predicts employee turnover"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Comparable satisfaction scores combined with significantly higher attrition imply that the survey instrument misses retention-relevant factors, which is exactly what choice A captures. Choice B is the almost-supported trap; hybrid employees did report the highest satisfaction, but the passage says fully remote workers were comparable to in-office, not lower in a way that proves dissatisfaction drove their exits. Choice C is an unsupported policy recommendation the passage never makes. Choice D over-reaches with only; the passage offers peer attachment as one factor researchers suggested might matter. Choice A respects every qualifier in the evidence.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-INF-NEW-17'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-1', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Hand-washing is the single most effective way to prevent the spread of common illnesses. Soap breaks down the oils on skin that hold germs in place, allowing running water to rinse them away. Twenty seconds of scrubbing is enough to remove most contaminants. Public health agencies continue to promote this simple habit because no vaccine or medication matches its everyday impact. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Twenty seconds of scrubbing removes most contaminants from hands.","Soap dissolves oils that trap germs on the skin.","Public health depends entirely on individual hygiene habits.","Hand-washing is the most effective everyday way to prevent the spread of illness."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first sentence states the thesis directly and the rest of the passage supports it with mechanism and endorsement. The option about soap dissolving oils that trap germs describes how the mechanism works, a supporting detail rather than the central claim. The twenty-seconds-of-scrubbing option cites a specific duration, again a detail in service of the main point. The choice that says public health depends entirely on individual hygiene habits over-generalizes, a stronger claim than the passage makes. Only the keyed option restates the explicit topic sentence without adding or narrowing its scope.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-1'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-2', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'A library card offers more than free books. Most public libraries now lend audiobooks, streaming films, museum passes, and even hotspots for home internet. Cardholders can attend tax workshops, language classes, and resume clinics at no cost. The card has quietly become one of the most versatile free resources available to residents. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Public libraries are the most important institutions in any community.","Tax workshops and resume clinics are popular library offerings.","A library card gives access to a wide range of free resources beyond books.","Libraries lend internet hotspots to people without home service."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states that a card offers more than books, and the rest of the passage lists examples of that range plus the free-resource framing. The option about libraries lending internet hotspots isolates one example service, a single supporting detail. The option naming tax workshops and resume clinics picks up two specific programs from the example list, again narrower than the central claim. The choice calling libraries the most important institutions in any community inflates the argument with language the passage never uses, a clear over-generalization. The keyed option mirrors the opening sentence and captures the variety theme that ties the supporting details together.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-2'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-3', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Sleep is essential for memory consolidation. During deep sleep, the brain replays the day''s experiences and strengthens the neural connections tied to important information. People who sleep fewer than six hours a night routinely score lower on memory tests the next day. Adequate rest is not a luxury for students; it is part of the learning process itself. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Sleeping less than six hours lowers next-day memory test scores.","Students should treat sleep as more important than studying.","The brain replays daily experiences during deep sleep.","Adequate sleep is essential for forming and retaining memories."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first sentence names sleep as essential for memory consolidation, and the closing sentence reinforces it by calling rest part of the learning process itself. The option about scoring lower on memory tests after fewer than six hours reports a specific finding cited as supporting evidence rather than the central claim. The choice describing the brain''s nightly replay of daily experiences names the neural mechanism, another piece of supporting detail that explains why the thesis holds. The option saying students should treat sleep as more important than studying over-generalizes by ranking the two, a direct comparison the passage does not make. The keyed answer captures the central claim that sleep and memory formation are tightly linked.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-3'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-4', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Recycling aluminum saves enormous amounts of energy. Producing a can from recycled aluminum uses about ninety-five percent less electricity than making one from raw ore. The metal can be melted and reformed indefinitely without losing any strength or quality. For every ton of aluminum recycled, the equivalent of several barrels of oil is conserved nationwide. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Recycled aluminum cans require ninety-five percent less electricity to produce.","Aluminum can be melted and reused without losing strength.","Recycling aluminum conserves a large amount of energy.","Industrial recycling could replace most oil production."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The opening sentence states the thesis about energy savings, and the rest of the passage quantifies and reinforces it with electricity figures and oil-equivalent conservation. The choice citing the ninety-five percent electricity figure repeats a specific statistic offered as evidence, a supporting detail rather than the main idea. The option about aluminum being melted and reused without losing strength addresses the metal''s durability under repeated recycling, another supporting fact that explains why aluminum recycling is so efficient. The choice claiming industrial recycling could replace most oil production wildly over-generalizes, a claim the passage never makes. The keyed option restates the topic sentence in plain terms.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-4'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-5', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'City planners in many regions are widening sidewalks, lowering speed limits, and adding shaded benches. Cars still dominate most corridors, but pedestrian counts on retrofitted blocks have climbed sharply. Shop owners along these streets report higher foot traffic and longer customer visits. Even short walks in better-designed neighborhoods correlate with improved cardiovascular health in older residents. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Shop owners earn more money when sidewalks are widened.","Older residents have better hearts than younger residents in walkable areas.","Cities should ban cars from downtown corridors.","Walkable street design produces measurable economic and health benefits."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage stacks two parallel results, business gains and health gains, after describing the design changes that produced them. The implied thesis ties pedestrian-friendly design to both outcomes, and it sits across the second and third sentences rather than in one place. The option saying shop owners earn more money captures only the commercial half and overstates with the word earn, a supporting detail. The choice comparing older residents'' hearts to younger residents distorts the health claim into a generational comparison the passage never makes. The option calling for cities to ban cars from downtown corridors pushes a policy position the passage avoids, since it explicitly notes cars still dominate most corridors. The keyed answer holds both supporting threads together.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-5'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-6', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'When a household water heater fails, the symptoms often appear gradually. Showers grow lukewarm over several weeks, and the tank may begin to hum or rattle as sediment builds. Rust-tinted water from the hot tap is a later warning sign. Homeowners who replace a failing unit on a planned schedule typically pay less than those who wait for a flood. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Rust-tinted hot water means a water heater has already failed.","Most water heaters last fewer than ten years before failing.","Sediment buildup is the leading cause of water-heater problems.","Recognizing early warning signs of water-heater failure helps homeowners avoid costly emergencies."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first three sentences catalogue warning signs and the final sentence links advance recognition to lower cost, implying the thesis. The option saying rust-tinted hot water means the heater has already failed treats one symptom as a definitive verdict, a misread of the passage''s late warning sign language. The choice naming sediment buildup as the leading cause asserts a ranking the passage never makes. The option about most heaters lasting fewer than ten years introduces a lifespan figure that does not appear in the passage at all. The keyed answer joins the symptoms half to the cost half.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-6'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-7', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'A well-written cover letter does more than repeat a resume. It connects past experience to the specific role, names the hiring manager when possible, and uses the company''s own language about its goals. Recruiters often skim a stack of applications in seconds, so the opening lines must give them a reason to keep reading. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Cover letters should always name the hiring manager.","Recruiters spend only a few seconds reviewing each application.","A strong cover letter is tailored to the role and designed to hold a recruiter''s attention.","Resumes are less important than cover letters in modern hiring."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage outlines what a good cover letter does, namely connect experience to the role and mirror the company''s language, and then explains why, the recruiter-skim context. The thesis combines tailoring with attention-holding across the two halves of the paragraph. The option about recruiters spending only seconds repeats the skim detail as if it were the central point, an isolated supporting fact. The choice saying cover letters should always name the hiring manager absolutizes one suggested practice with the word always, sliding past the passage''s softer when possible. The option ranking resumes as less important than cover letters invents a head-to-head comparison the passage never makes. The keyed option ties the writing advice to the audience constraint that drives it.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-7'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-8', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'Honey produced near a beekeeper''s home tastes different from honey produced fifty miles away. Local flora determine the flavor profile because bees forage within a few miles of the hive. Spring honey from orchard country carries a light apple-blossom note, while late-summer honey from a meadow tastes darker and fuller. Even neighboring counties can yield jars with distinct character. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Bees forage within a few miles of their hive.","Local honey is healthier than honey from distant regions.","Honey''s flavor reflects the specific plants bees forage near their hive.","Spring honey is lighter than late-summer honey."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage contrasts honey from different areas and explains the cause: nearby flora that the bees forage on. The thesis sits across the first two sentences and is then reinforced by the spring-versus-summer example. The option about bees foraging within a few miles isolates the range mechanism, a detail that supports rather than states the main idea. The choice contrasting spring and late-summer honey captures one seasonal example, again a piece of evidence rather than the central claim. The option calling local honey healthier than distant honey introduces a health claim the passage never makes. The keyed answer joins the observed flavor variation to its botanical cause, which is what the four sentences collectively argue.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-8'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-9', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Most modern bicycles use cable-actuated brakes that work well in dry conditions. In wet weather, however, water and grit on the rim reduce the friction that stops the wheel. Riders who ride year-round increasingly switch to disc brakes, which clamp a dedicated rotor near the hub. The rotor stays cleaner and provides consistent stopping power across temperatures. Bike shops report that disc-equipped models now account for the majority of new sales above entry level. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Disc brakes are displacing rim brakes because they perform more consistently in varied conditions.","Most new bicycles sold are now equipped with disc brakes.","Cable-actuated brakes work poorly in wet weather.","Year-round cyclists need specialized equipment to ride safely."]'::jsonb, 0, 'No single sentence states the thesis; it emerges from the contrast between rim and disc performance, the wet-weather problem, and the closing sales trend at bike shops. The option saying cable-actuated brakes work poorly in wet weather captures only the weakness of the older system, a supporting half. The choice reporting that most new bicycles now ship with disc brakes states the sales detail in isolation without explaining why the shift is happening, an accurate-but-tangential restatement. The option claiming year-round cyclists need specialized equipment over-generalizes about safety and necessity, neither of which the passage actually frames that way. The keyed answer synthesizes the performance reason and the market shift into one statement.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-9'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-10', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Community gardens often start with a single empty lot and a handful of volunteers. Within a season, raised beds appear, neighbors begin trading produce, and unfamiliar faces become regulars. Crime statistics on blocks with active gardens tend to drift downward over the following years. City officials in several regions now treat these gardens as low-cost public-safety investments rather than purely agricultural projects. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Crime rates fall sharply on every block with a community garden.","Cities should subsidize gardening supplies for low-income residents.","Community gardens function as social investments that strengthen neighborhoods beyond food production.","Empty lots are the most common starting points for community gardens."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage moves from origin to social effects to municipal reframing without naming a single topic sentence. The synthesized point is that gardens deliver social value far beyond the produce they grow. The option about empty lots being the most common starting points grabs the opening fact rather than the central argument. The choice saying crime rates fall sharply on every block overstates the trend, while the passage uses softer hedging like tend and drift downward. The option urging cities to subsidize gardening supplies for low-income residents proposes a policy the passage never recommends or even mentions. The keyed answer captures the full arc that the four sentences trace together.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-10'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-11', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'The cost of solar panels has fallen sharply over the past fifteen years. Battery prices, once the bottleneck for home installations, have also dropped significantly. Utility companies face a new dynamic: customers who once bought every kilowatt now sell power back during peak hours. Some regulators are rewriting rate structures to reflect a grid that flows in both directions. The old one-way model is increasingly difficult to defend. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Regulators are updating rate structures in some regions.","Solar panel prices have fallen over the past fifteen years.","Home solar installations will soon replace traditional power plants.","Cheaper solar and battery technology is reshaping the relationship between utilities and customers."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage threads price drops, customer behavior, regulatory response, and a closing judgment about how hard the old one-way model is to defend. The thesis must tie the technology shift to the changing utility relationship. The option that solar panel prices have fallen over fifteen years reports only the price half of the story, a supporting fact. The choice about regulators updating rate structures in some regions captures only the institutional response, again a supporting piece. The option predicting that home solar will soon replace traditional power plants advances a far stronger claim than the passage actually makes about a two-way grid. The keyed answer integrates the cause, the customer behavior, and the institutional response into one statement.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-11'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-12', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Reading aloud to young children does more than entertain. It exposes them to vocabulary and sentence structures that rarely appear in everyday conversation. Children who are read to regularly enter kindergarten with measurably larger vocabularies than peers who are not. Even shared reading at bedtime, lasting only minutes, contributes to the language gap that schools spend years trying to close. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Schools are unable to close the language gap among students.","Vocabulary in books rarely overlaps with everyday speech.","Bedtime stories last only a few minutes for most families.","Reading aloud to young children builds vocabulary that shapes their school readiness."]'::jsonb, 3, 'Four sentences move from the activity to its vocabulary mechanism to its measurable effect on kindergarten readiness and the language gap that follows. The synthesized point ties reading aloud directly to school readiness. Choice B picks up a duration detail about how brief bedtime reading is, an aside rather than the argument. Choice C captures the vocabulary mechanism without naming the educational outcome it produces. Choice D distorts the closing line about schools spending years to close the gap into a flat claim that schools have failed entirely. The keyed answer holds the cause and the educational outcome together, matching what all four sentences build.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-12'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-13', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Many drivers assume premium gasoline cleans their engine better than regular fuel. In most vehicles, however, the octane rating governs only how resistant the fuel is to premature ignition under compression. Detergent additives are mandated for all grades sold in the United States, so cleaning performance is largely equivalent across the pump. Cars whose owner''s manuals specify regular fuel gain no measurable benefit from premium and only pay more per gallon. A small group of high-compression engines does require premium, but for everyone else the upgrade is purely a charge against the wallet. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Premium gasoline cleans engines more effectively than regular gasoline.","Detergent additives are mandated in all grades of gasoline sold in the United States.","Premium gasoline benefits only the small set of engines that require it; for most drivers it is wasted money.","Octane rating measures resistance to premature ignition under compression."]'::jsonb, 2, 'Several factual claims compete for the spotlight: detergent additive rules, the octane definition, the owner''s-manual specification, and the high-compression exception. The primary point is the cost-benefit verdict in the last sentence, framed against the common cleaning-power assumption that opens the passage. Choice B isolates a supporting fact about mandated additives, the mechanism for why cleaning is equivalent. Choice C defines octane, more supporting machinery for the larger argument. Choice D directly contradicts the passage, which is the assumption being refuted from the start. The keyed answer captures the verdict the passage was built to deliver.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-13'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-14', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Many beginning cooks blame their knives when chopping feels slow or unsafe. A dull blade certainly increases the force required and the chance of a slip, and most home knives are duller than their owners realize. Cutting boards matter too; glass and stone surfaces destroy edges within weeks. Yet experienced cooks point out that grip and posture govern far more than equipment. A sharp knife held poorly is still slow, while a modest knife held well moves quickly through onions and herbs. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Glass and stone cutting boards damage knife edges quickly.","Home cooks should buy sharper knives to improve their results.","A dull blade increases the force required to cut and raises the risk of slips.","Technique influences chopping speed and safety more than equipment alone."]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two themes compete inside the passage: equipment matters (dullness, board surface) and technique matters more (grip, posture, knife handling). The yet pivot in sentence four signals which claim is primary, and the closing onions-and-herbs example reinforces it. Choice B captures a supporting detail about how dull blades increase force and slip risk. Choice C captures the cutting-board surface detail, another piece of equipment evidence. Choice D draws an equipment recommendation that the passage explicitly downgrades in favor of technique over gear. The keyed answer reflects the experienced-cooks pivot that organizes the whole passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-14'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-15', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Online customer reviews shape modern purchasing in two directions at once. Buyers consult them before committing money, especially for items they cannot inspect in person, and a single string of negative ratings can sink a product. At the same time, sellers have learned to solicit, edit, and occasionally fabricate reviews to manage their ratings. Platforms publish trust-and-safety reports, but enforcement is uneven and reviewers themselves often cannot tell genuine praise from paid copy. The marketplace runs on a system that buyers depend on and many sellers quietly distort. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Online reviews remain central to purchasing decisions even as their reliability is widely compromised.","Negative reviews can sink a product''s sales on most platforms.","Buyers should stop relying on online reviews when making purchases.","Platforms publish trust-and-safety reports about review fraud."]'::jsonb, 0, 'The passage develops two opposing forces: buyer dependence on reviews and seller distortion of them. The closing sentence makes both sides explicit. Choice B captures only the buyer-impact side. Choice C reports a platform action without the broader argument. Choice D draws a prescription the passage never offers, especially given the opening insistence on how central reviews remain. The keyed answer holds the dependence and the distortion in the same statement, matching the closing summary.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-15'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-16', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'When a city replaces a stretch of asphalt with permeable pavers, the visible difference is small. The pavers look much like ordinary stone, and traffic crosses them without noticing. Underground, however, rainwater that once ran off the surface and overwhelmed storm drains now seeps through gaps between the stones into a gravel bed below. Local creeks downstream show fewer pollution spikes after heavy storms, and basement flooding complaints drop on neighboring blocks. The repaving looks ordinary, but the watershed quietly works differently. Skeptics often ask why the city did not simply build larger drains; engineers respond that the new surface costs less to maintain across its lifespan and treats the cause rather than the symptom. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["Cities should require permeable pavement on every new project.","Permeable paving produces meaningful environmental and economic benefits that are not visible at street level.","Engineers prefer permeable pavers over larger storm drains.","Permeable pavers look much like ordinary stone surfaces."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage hinges on the contrast between appearance and outcome: an ordinary-looking surface delivers downstream environmental and cost benefits. The author''s overall point is that the value is real but hidden. Choice B captures only the appearance half. Choice C grabs the engineers-prefer detail without the broader payoff. Choice D pushes a policy mandate the passage avoids. The keyed answer integrates the invisible-but-meaningful framing that the opening, the middle examples, and the closing engineer comparison all support.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-16'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-17', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Productivity advice often centers on tools: a new planner, a tracking app, a different notebook system. New hires especially gravitate to whatever system their manager praises, hoping the right method will close the gap between effort and output. Most observers of long careers tell a different story. The colleagues who consistently finish what they start rarely use unusual tools; they protect their attention from interruption, decide quickly which tasks belong to them, and review their week before it begins. The tools merely record habits already in place. A planner is not a substitute for the underlying discipline, though many buyers hope it will be. Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Many new hires copy whatever productivity system their manager praises.","Planners are useful only when paired with a tracking app.","Effective workers protect their attention and plan their weeks in advance.","Lasting productivity comes from underlying habits rather than from the specific tools people adopt."]'::jsonb, 3, 'The passage contrasts tool-focused hopes with habit-focused reality and closes by saying a planner is not a substitute for the underlying discipline it tries to capture. The author''s overall claim runs through every sentence and emerges only by inference. Choice B captures the new-hire copying detail, a piece of color rather than the thesis. Choice C lists the supporting habits like attention protection and weekly review without naming the tool-versus-habit thesis itself. Choice D invents a recommendation about pairing planners with tracking apps that the passage never makes and would actually contradict. The keyed answer states the underlying argument that organizes the contrast and the closing judgment.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-17'),
  ('PC-MI-NEW-18', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 5, 'Volunteer firefighters once formed the backbone of rural emergency response in many regions. Decades ago, neighbors who farmed or worked nearby trades could reach the firehouse within minutes of a tone. The economic geography has shifted: fewer residents work where they live, training requirements have grown, and the average volunteer is now over fifty. Recruiting drives produce modest gains that rarely keep pace with retirements. Some counties have begun staffing a paid skeleton crew during weekdays while preserving the volunteer roster for nights and weekends. Communities that once relied entirely on neighbors are quietly reorganizing around a hybrid model, even when local pride still describes the department as volunteer. What is the main idea of this passage?', '["The average volunteer firefighter is now over fifty years old.","Volunteer firefighting is no longer a viable model anywhere in the country.","Rural fire response is gradually shifting from a purely volunteer model to a hybrid arrangement driven by economic and demographic pressures.","Some counties pay a small daytime crew while keeping volunteers for nights and weekends."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage traces a historical baseline, names the pressures, and describes the structural response, closing on the gap between local self-description and reality. The author''s overall point is the underlying transition. Choice B isolates a demographic statistic. Choice C captures the hybrid example without the larger trend it illustrates. Choice D over-generalizes to nowhere viable, while the passage describes a gradual reorganization that still includes volunteers. The keyed answer states the inferential thesis that organizes every sentence in the paragraph.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-MI-NEW-18'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''The driver was so RECKLESS that he ran three red lights and nearly hit a pedestrian,'' the word RECKLESS most nearly means:', '["careless","skilled","patient","cautious"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The sentence describes a driver running three red lights and nearly hitting a pedestrian, behavior that shows no regard for safety or for traffic law. That evidence pins the meaning to ''careless.'' ''Skilled'' contradicts the near-collision, since skilled driving would avoid that outcome rather than produce it. ''Patient'' contradicts running red lights, which is impatient behavior that refuses to wait. ''Cautious'' is the direct opposite of ignoring traffic signals and endangering people on foot. Only ''careless'' matches a driver who disregards rules and consequences at once.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::reckless'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''Her argument was so COMPELLING that even her opponents agreed she was right,'' the word COMPELLING most nearly means:', '["persuasive","lengthy","confusing","polite"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that even her opponents agreed she was right, an outcome that only happens when an argument actually convinces the people who started out against it. That pins the meaning to ''persuasive.'' ''Lengthy'' describes duration and would not by itself flip opponents to agreement, since long arguments often bore listeners. ''Confusing'' contradicts the outcome, since a confusing argument would not produce agreement from anyone. ''Polite'' describes tone, not force, and politeness alone does not change opponents'' minds. Only ''persuasive'' explains why opponents conceded the point against their own position.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::compelling'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''The hiking trail was so OBSCURE that we had to push aside branches just to see where it went,'' the word OBSCURE most nearly means:', '["hidden","popular","steep","wide"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is having to push aside branches just to see the trail, which means the path was concealed from view. That pins the meaning to ''hidden.'' ''Popular'' contradicts the overgrown condition, since a popular trail would be cleared by foot traffic. ''Steep'' describes incline, not visibility, and pushing branches aside is about seeing the path, not climbing it. ''Wide'' contradicts a trail covered by branches. Only ''hidden'' fits a path that has to be uncovered to follow.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::obscure'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''She was METHODICAL about her morning routine, doing every task in the same order at the same time each day,'' the word METHODICAL most nearly means:', '["systematic","rushed","cheerful","lazy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is doing every task in the same order at the same time each day, which describes a fixed system rather than a loose habit. That pins the meaning to ''systematic.'' ''Rushed'' contradicts a routine performed at consistent times, since rushing varies with pressure and rarely repeats on schedule. ''Cheerful'' describes mood and is not implied by repeating an order of tasks on a clock. ''Lazy'' contradicts the discipline of completing every task daily without skipping any. Only ''systematic'' captures a routine governed by both order and timing.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::methodical'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''After learning he had passed the bar exam, Marcus felt EUPHORIC and called everyone he knew to share the news,'' the word EUPHORIC most nearly means:', '["overjoyed","anxious","exhausted","indifferent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is passing the bar exam and calling everyone he knew to share the news, behavior driven by intense happiness rather than ordinary satisfaction. That pins the meaning to ''overjoyed.'' ''Anxious'' contradicts the celebration, since an anxious person would not broadcast good news to a long list of contacts. ''Exhausted'' would mean wanting rest after the strain of the exam, not picking up the phone to call person after person. ''Indifferent'' contradicts the eagerness to tell everyone, since indifference produces silence. Only ''overjoyed'' explains the impulse to share the achievement so widely.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::euphoric'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''The loss of her grandmother had a PROFOUND effect on her, changing how she viewed family and time,'' the word PROFOUND most nearly means:', '["deep","brief","amusing","unclear"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that the loss changed how she viewed family and time, which describes a fundamental shift in outlook rather than a passing reaction. That pins the meaning to ''deep.'' ''Brief'' contradicts a change in worldview, which by definition persists once it takes hold. ''Amusing'' contradicts grief over a grandmother''s death and the serious reflection that followed. ''Unclear'' contradicts the sentence, which names exactly what changed in concrete terms: her view of family and her view of time. Only ''deep'' fits an effect that reaches a person''s core perspective and reshapes it.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::profound'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The monk lived in an AUSTERE cabin with only a wooden bed, a single chair, and one bowl,'' the word AUSTERE most nearly means:', '["plain","luxurious","crowded","cheerful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is a cabin with only a wooden bed, a single chair, and one bowl, an inventory stripped of comfort and limited to bare necessities. That pins the meaning to ''plain.'' ''Luxurious'' is the direct opposite of owning three sparse items made of wood and clay. ''Crowded'' contradicts the short list of furnishings, which signals emptiness rather than abundance of objects. ''Cheerful'' describes mood, and the bare list conveys severity and restraint rather than warmth or decoration. Only ''plain'' fits a dwelling defined by the deliberate absence of extras.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::austere'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The climber''s grip on the icy ledge was PRECARIOUS, and a single gust of wind could have sent her falling,'' the word PRECARIOUS most nearly means:', '["unstable","firm","comfortable","permanent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that a single gust of wind could have sent her falling, which describes a hold one small force away from failing completely. That pins the meaning to ''unstable.'' ''Firm'' contradicts the risk of falling from a breeze, since a firm grip would withstand normal weather. ''Comfortable'' contradicts hanging on an icy ledge with no margin for error or rest. ''Permanent'' contradicts a grip that could end in an instant from one passing gust. Only ''unstable'' captures a position that depends entirely on conditions not changing, even for a second.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::precarious'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''Critics called the new album DERIVATIVE, pointing out that nearly every song borrowed melodies from earlier hits by other artists,'' the word DERIVATIVE most nearly means:', '["unoriginal","complex","popular","experimental"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that nearly every song borrowed melodies from earlier hits by other artists, which is the textbook definition of work taken from existing sources. That pins the meaning to ''unoriginal.'' ''Complex'' describes structure and is not implied by copying melodies. ''Popular'' describes reception, not source, and critics are faulting the album rather than praising its sales. ''Experimental'' contradicts borrowing from established hits, since experimentation departs from familiar material. Only ''unoriginal'' matches the critics'' charge.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::derivative'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''The doctor assured the worried parents that the small bump was INNOCUOUS and would fade on its own within a week,'' the word INNOCUOUS most nearly means:', '["harmless","painful","contagious","permanent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is the doctor reassuring worried parents and predicting the bump would fade within a week, two signals that together rule out anything dangerous. That pins the meaning to ''harmless.'' ''Painful'' contradicts reassurance offered to anxious parents, since pain would call for treatment rather than calm. ''Contagious'' would prompt warnings about spread to other family members, not assurance about a quick fade. ''Permanent'' is the direct opposite of fading on its own within a week. Only ''harmless'' fits a finding that calms parents and predicts a quiet resolution without intervention.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::innocuous'),
  ('WK-CTX-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''His FACETIOUS remark about the bride''s dress at the rehearsal made everyone uncomfortable, since no one could tell whether he meant the insult or was only joking,'' the word FACETIOUS most nearly means:', '["flippant","sincere","respectful","tearful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The evidence is that listeners could not tell whether he meant the insult or was only joking, which describes humor offered at an inappropriate moment. That pins the meaning to ''flippant.'' ''Sincere'' contradicts the possibility that he was joking, since sincere speech is meant straight. ''Respectful'' contradicts insulting a bride at her rehearsal. ''Tearful'' describes emotion and does not match a remark that reads as a joke. Only ''flippant'' captures a comment that treats a serious moment as material for humor.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::facetious'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix RE- means again or back. Based on this, REPLAY most nearly means:', '["to play before","to play once and stop","to play again","to refuse to play"]'::jsonb, 2, 'REPLAY decomposes into RE- (again, back) plus PLAY. The prefix RE- appears in REWIND, REVISIT, and REBUILD, all signaling repetition or return. Choice A inverts the meaning by swapping RE- for PRE- (before). Choice B drops the prefix entirely and defines only the root. Choice D confuses RE- with the negating prefix REF- in REFUSE, which carries a different Latin origin (re- plus fundere, to pour back). The correct reading combines repetition with the action of playing.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::replay'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix NON- means not or absence of. Based on this, NONFICTION most nearly means:', '["writing that is made up","writing that is not made up","writing that is poorly done","writing that is unfinished"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NONFICTION breaks into NON- (not) plus FICTION (invented narrative). The prefix NON- works the same way in NONSTOP, NONPROFIT, NONVERBAL, and NONSENSE, each simply negating the root that follows. Choice A defines fiction itself and ignores the prefix entirely, the most common error when the test taker rushes past the leading morpheme. Choice C confuses NON- with the Latin MAL- (bad) seen in MALPRACTICE and MALFUNCTION, which carries a moral judgment NON- does not. Choice D confuses NON- with the suffix -LESS or with the prefix UN- as in UNFINISHED. NONFICTION names writing grounded in fact rather than invention.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::nonfiction'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 1, 'The prefix DIS- means not, opposite of, or away. Based on this, DISLOYAL most nearly means:', '["extremely loyal","loyal at times","not loyal","loyal to a leader"]'::jsonb, 2, 'DISLOYAL splits into DIS- (not, opposite of) plus LOYAL. The same prefix appears in DISAGREE, DISHONEST, and DISCONNECT, each reversing the root. Choice A inverts the meaning by treating DIS- as an intensifier, a common error since spoken stress can sound emphatic. Choice B softens the negation into a partial state the prefix does not allow. Choice D ignores the prefix and defines only the root. DISLOYAL describes someone who fails to keep faith with a person, cause, or country.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::disloyal'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The prefix TRANS- means across or beyond. The word TRANSPORT therefore is best defined as:', '["to carry across or from one place to another","to store in a harbor","to repair a damaged vehicle","to load goods onto a ship"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TRANSPORT combines TRANS- (across) with the Latin root PORT (to carry), the same root in PORTER, IMPORT, and EXPORT. The prefix appears in TRANSMIT, TRANSFER, and TRANSCONTINENTAL with consistent meaning. Choice B mistakes PORT the prefix-bearing root for PORT meaning harbor, a homograph trap. Choice C invents a meaning unsupported by either morpheme. Choice D names a specific shipping action but ignores the across or beyond element supplied by TRANS-. TRANSPORT denotes movement of people or goods across distance.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::trans'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The suffix -LESS means without. Based on this, FEARLESS most nearly means:', '["easily frightened","feeling moderate fear","causing fear in others","without fear"]'::jsonb, 3, 'FEARLESS attaches the suffix -LESS (without) to the root FEAR. The same suffix produces HOPELESS, ENDLESS, and HARMLESS, each signaling absence of the root quality. Choice A reverses the meaning, the kind of error that arises when a reader confuses -LESS with -FUL. Choice B softens the absolute negation the suffix demands. Choice C confuses -LESS with the agentive suffix -SOME as in FEARSOME, which means causing fear. FEARLESS describes a person or action free from fear.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::less'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The suffix -FUL means full of or characterized by. The word PLAYFUL therefore most nearly means:', '["full of or showing a desire to play","without any sense of play","tired from playing too much","skilled at a particular game"]'::jsonb, 0, 'PLAYFUL joins the root PLAY with the suffix -FUL (full of). The same suffix produces JOYFUL, CAREFUL, and HOPEFUL, each meaning full of the root quality. Choice B reverses the meaning by treating -FUL as if it were -LESS. Choice C drifts toward modern colloquial English where playful is sometimes loosely linked to exhaustion, but morphology does not support that reading. Choice D narrows the word to athletic skill, ignoring the broad sense of disposition the suffix supplies. PLAYFUL describes a mood or behavior marked by lighthearted fun.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::playful'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The prefix INTER- means between or among. Based on this, INTERSTATE most nearly means:', '["inside a single state","between two or more states","owned by the state government","below the state level"]'::jsonb, 1, 'INTERSTATE pairs INTER- (between, among) with STATE. The same prefix carries through INTERNATIONAL, INTERACT, INTERSECT, and INTERVIEW, each describing something that occurs between or among multiple parties. Choice A confuses INTER- with INTRA- (within), a high-frequency trap since the two prefixes differ by a single letter but reverse the meaning, as in INTRASTATE commerce that stays within one state. Choice C ignores the prefix entirely and assigns government ownership unsupported by the morphology. Choice D confuses INTER- with SUB- (below) or with the suffix -ARY indicating subordinate rank. An INTERSTATE highway runs between states, which is why the federal system carries that label.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::inter'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The prefix MAL- means bad or wrongful. The word MALCONTENT therefore is best defined as:', '["a person who is satisfied","a person who avoids conflict","a person who is dissatisfied or rebellious","a person who lacks ambition"]'::jsonb, 2, 'MALCONTENT joins MAL- (bad, wrongful) with CONTENT (satisfied). The same prefix drives MALFUNCTION, MALPRACTICE, MALEVOLENT, and MALICE, each signaling a corrupt or harmful version of the root. Choice A defines CONTENT alone and ignores the prefix entirely, the most common slip when a reader recognizes only the familiar second morpheme. Choice B confuses MAL- with the prefix DIS- (apart, away) or with the idea of withdrawal, but MAL- carries no sense of avoidance. Choice D drifts into a vague personality description unsupported by either morpheme. A MALCONTENT is a person whose dissatisfaction often expresses itself as grumbling or open rebellion against authority.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::malcontent'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The suffix -ISM means a doctrine, belief, or practice. Based on this, BAPTISM most nearly means:', '["the person who performs a religious rite","the practice or rite of baptizing","a building used for religious services","the study of religious texts"]'::jsonb, 1, 'BAPTISM combines the Greek root BAPT (to dip, immerse) with the suffix -ISM (practice, doctrine). The same suffix produces CAPITALISM, JOURNALISM, and CRITICISM, each naming a practice or system. Choice A confuses -ISM with the agentive suffix -IST, which names the person who practices (BAPTIST). Choice C confuses -ISM with -ARY or -ERY (BAPTISTRY, the building). Choice D confuses -ISM with -OLOGY (study of). BAPTISM names the rite itself rather than its practitioner, location, or academic study.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::baptism'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The word AMBIDEXTROUS contains the prefix AMBI- (both) and the root DEXTR- (right hand, skill). AMBIDEXTROUS most nearly means:', '["unable to use either hand well","able to use both hands with equal skill","preferring the left hand","lacking coordination"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AMBIDEXTROUS decomposes into AMBI- (both) plus DEXTR- (right hand, skill) plus the adjective suffix -OUS. The same prefix appears in AMBIGUOUS (both ways) and AMBIVALENT (both feelings). Choice A inverts the meaning by stripping the positive sense of DEXTR-. Choice C confuses DEXTR- with SINISTR- (left hand), the Latin opposite preserved in SINISTER. Choice D ignores both morphemes and describes a generic lack of physical skill. AMBIDEXTROUS describes a person who handles tools, writing, or tasks equally well with either hand.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ambidextrous'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word MISANTHROPE contains the Greek prefix MIS- (hatred of) and the root ANTHROP- (humankind). MISANTHROPE most nearly means:', '["a person who studies human cultures","a person who hates or distrusts humankind","a person who acts wrongly toward others","a person who lives among other people"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MISANTHROPE comes from Greek MIS- (hatred) plus ANTHROP- (man, humankind), the same root in ANTHROPOLOGY and PHILANTHROPY. The trap is that Greek MIS- (hatred, as in MISOGYNY) is spelled identically to the Latin MIS- (wrongly, as in MISJUDGE), but the two prefixes are unrelated. Choice A confuses MISANTHROPE with ANTHROPOLOGIST, swapping the prefix for the suffix -OLOGIST. Choice C applies the Latin MIS- (wrongly) instead of the Greek one. Choice D ignores the hostility carried by MIS- entirely. A MISANTHROPE actively dislikes the human race.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::misanthrope'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-12', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word BIBLIOPHILE contains the root BIBLIO- (book) and the suffix -PHILE (lover of). BIBLIOPHILE most nearly means:', '["one who writes books","one who fears books","one who loves and collects books","one who sells books"]'::jsonb, 2, 'BIBLIOPHILE pairs BIBLIO- (book) with -PHILE (lover of), the same suffix in AUDIOPHILE and FRANCOPHILE. The trap is the closely spelled -PHOBE (fear of), which reverses the meaning, as in CLAUSTROPHOBE. Choice A confuses -PHILE with the agentive ending in AUTHOR. Choice B applies -PHOBE instead of -PHILE, a high-value distractor because the suffixes look almost identical to a quick reader. Choice D narrows the word to commercial activity not supported by either morpheme. A BIBLIOPHILE is a devoted reader and collector of books.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::bibliophile'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-13', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The suffix -EFY (a variant of -IFY) means to make or cause to become. The word LIQUEFY therefore is best defined as:', '["to make solid","to make liquid","to remove liquid from","to study the properties of liquid"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LIQUEFY joins LIQU- (the root in LIQUID) with -EFY (to make), a rare variant of -IFY preserved in only a handful of words such as PUTREFY and STUPEFY. Most English verbs use -IFY (CLARIFY, MAGNIFY), so spellers often miswrite LIQUIFY, but the dictionary form keeps the older -EFY. Choice A inverts the meaning by treating -EFY as if it carried negation. Choice C confuses -EFY (to make) with the prefix DE- (to remove). Choice D confuses -EFY with -OLOGY (study of). LIQUEFY names the process of melting or dissolving a solid into liquid form.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::liquefy'),
  ('WK-PFX-NEW-14', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 5, 'The word EPIDERMIS contains the Greek prefix EPI- (upon, over) and the root DERM- (skin). EPIDERMIS most nearly means:', '["the deepest layer of skin","the outer layer of skin","the layer beneath the skin","a disease affecting the skin"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EPIDERMIS combines EPI- (upon, over) with DERM- (skin), the same root in DERMATOLOGY. The trap is the prefix APO- (away from), which looks and sounds similar to EPI- but reverses the spatial sense, as in APOSTASY. Choice A confuses EPI- with HYPO- (under), the prefix found in HYPODERMIC (under the skin). Choice C also applies HYPO- or SUB- instead of EPI-. Choice D confuses the prefix with the suffix -ITIS (inflammation) or -OSIS (condition). EPIDERMIS names the outermost protective layer of skin covering the body.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::epidermis'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root TELE appears in TELEPHONE, TELESCOPE, and TELEVISION. The root TELE most nearly means:', '["far or distant","sound","picture or image","machine"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TELE comes from Greek tele, meaning far or distant. Cognates include telephone (distant sound), telescope (viewing what is distant), television (distant viewing), telegraph (writing at a distance), and teleport (carry across distance). ''Sound'' is a trap because telephone involves sound, but PHON carries that meaning, not TELE. ''Picture or image'' confuses the function of television with the root, since VIS supplies the image meaning. ''Machine'' is a generic association with electronics, but TELE never refers to a device, only to distance.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::tele'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root AUTO appears in AUTOMATIC, AUTOBIOGRAPHY, and AUTONOMY. The root AUTO most nearly means:', '["machine","self","car","moving"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AUTO comes from Greek autos, meaning self. Cognates include autobiography (self-written life story), autonomy (self-rule), automatic (acting on its own without outside help), autograph (a self-written signature), and autocrat (a self-appointed ruler). ''Machine'' confuses AUTO with the English word automation, but the underlying root means self, not the device performing the action. ''Car'' is the most common English association with auto, yet automobile literally means self-moving, where AUTO still means self. ''Moving'' belongs to MOT or MOB (motor, mobile), separate Latin roots unrelated to AUTO.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::auto'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'The root ZOO appears in ZOOLOGY, ZODIAC, and PROTOZOA. The root ZOO most nearly means:', '["cage or enclosure","animal or living thing","wild","garden"]'::jsonb, 1, 'ZOO comes from Greek zoion, meaning animal or living being. Cognates include zoology (study of animals), protozoa (first-form animals, single-celled), zodiac (originally a circle of animal-shaped constellations), and zoophyte (an animal-plant hybrid such as coral). ''Cage or enclosure'' reflects the modern English word zoo as a place, but the root itself names the creatures inside, not the building around them. ''Wild'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by FER (feral, ferocious), not ZOO. ''Garden'' belongs to HORT (horticulture, horticulturist), unrelated to ZOO.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::zoology'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 1, 'Based on the root THERM (meaning heat), the word THERMAL most likely means:', '["relating to cold","relating to heat","relating to weather","relating to light"]'::jsonb, 1, 'THERM comes from Greek therme, meaning heat. Cognates include thermal (relating to heat), thermometer (heat measurer), thermos (heat-retaining container), hypothermia (low body heat), and geothermal (heat from the earth). ''Relating to cold'' is the opposite, the trap students fall into because hypothermia involves being cold, though the root itself names heat. ''Relating to weather'' confuses THERM with general climate words, but weather belongs to METEOR (meteorology). ''Relating to light'' belongs to PHOT (photograph) or LUM, separate roots.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::therm'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root MAR appears in MARINE, MARITIME, and SUBMARINE. The root MAR most nearly means:', '["sand or shore","sea","boat","salt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MAR comes from Latin mare, meaning sea. Cognates include marine (relating to the sea), maritime (concerning sea navigation), submarine (under the sea), mariner (a sailor), and aquamarine (sea-water blue). ''Sand or shore'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by LITTOR (littoral) or AREN (arena, originally sand), not MAR. ''Boat'' confuses the vessel with the body of water, since submarines are boats but MAR points to the sea itself. ''Salt'' belongs to SAL (saline, salary), a different Latin root, even though seas are salty.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::marine'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-6', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root LUM appears in ILLUMINATE, LUMINOUS, and LUMINARY. The root LUM most nearly means:', '["heat","light","color","shadow"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LUM comes from Latin lumen, meaning light. Cognates include illuminate (to light up), luminous (giving off light), luminary (a shining person or body), lumen (a unit of light), and translucent (light passing through). ''Heat'' is a related-but-distinct concept because hot objects often glow, yet heat belongs to THERM or CALOR, not LUM. ''Color'' belongs to CHROM (chromatic), often confused because colored objects reflect light. ''Shadow'' is the opposite of LUM and belongs to UMBRA (umbrella, penumbra), the Latin root for shade.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::illuminate'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-7', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'The root HELIO appears in HELIOCENTRIC, HELIOTROPE, and HELIUM. The root HELIO most nearly means:', '["heat","sun","sky","star"]'::jsonb, 1, 'HELIO comes from Greek helios, meaning sun. Cognates include heliocentric (sun-centered), heliotrope (a plant that turns toward the sun), helium (the element first detected in sunlight), and perihelion (closest point to the sun in an orbit). ''Heat'' is a related-but-distinct concept because the sun gives heat, but heat itself is THERM. ''Sky'' belongs to CEL (celestial) or URAN (Uranus), separate roots. ''Star'' belongs to ASTER or STELL (astronomy, stellar), commonly confused with HELIO because both involve space, yet HELIO names only our sun.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::helio'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-8', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 2, 'MONOTONE shares its root with MONOPOLY and MONARCH. The shared root means:', '["money","one or single","voice","rule"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MONO comes from Greek monos, meaning one or single. Cognates include monotone (one tone), monopoly (one seller), monarch (one ruler), monologue (one person speaking), and monogamy (one partner). ''Money'' confuses MONO with monetary words, which actually use MONET (Latin moneta), an unrelated root. ''Voice'' is a trap because monotone involves voice, yet the voice meaning belongs to VOC, while MONO contributes only the one. ''Rule'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by ARCH (monarch, anarchy), which is the second half of monarch, not MONO.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::monotone'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-9', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root AMBI appears in AMBIDEXTROUS, AMBIGUOUS, and AMBIVALENT. The root AMBI most nearly means:', '["around","both","uncertain","skilled"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AMBI comes from Latin ambi, meaning both or on both sides. Cognates include ambidextrous (using both hands), ambiguous (having both meanings), ambivalent (having both feelings), and amphibian (living in both water and on land, from the Greek cognate amphi). ''Around'' belongs to CIRCUM (circumference) or PERI (perimeter), often confused because ambient sound surrounds you. ''Uncertain'' describes the result of ambiguity, not the root itself. ''Skilled'' is the common-cognate trap from ambidextrous, but AMBI supplies both, while DEXTER supplies the skilled or right-handed meaning.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ambi'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-10', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root MAGN appears in MAGNIFY, MAGNANIMOUS, and MAGNITUDE. The root MAGN most nearly means:', '["strong","great or large","many","powerful attraction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MAGN comes from Latin magnus, meaning great or large. Cognates include magnify (make larger), magnitude (greatness in size), magnanimous (great-souled, generous), magnificent (great in deed), and magnate (a great person in business). ''Strong'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by FORT (fortify) or ROBUST, not MAGN. ''Many'' belongs to MULTI or POLY, often confused with great because both suggest abundance. ''Powerful attraction'' is the common-cognate trap from magnet, an unrelated word borrowed from a place name (Magnesia), not the size root.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::magn'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-11', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root MIT/MISS appears in TRANSMIT, EMIT, MISSILE, and DISMISS. This root most nearly means:', '["to send","to receive","to throw","to allow"]'::jsonb, 0, 'MIT/MISS comes from Latin mittere, meaning to send. Cognates include transmit (send across), emit (send out), missile (something sent), dismiss (send away), and submit (send under, yield). ''To receive'' is the opposite and belongs to CIP/CEPT (receive, accept), commonly confused because messages must be both sent and received. ''To throw'' belongs to JECT (eject, reject), a related-but-distinct action since throwing and sending overlap. ''To allow'' is the common-cognate trap from permit and admit, where the English meaning has drifted, while the underlying root still means send.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::miss'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-12', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The root JUR/JUS appears in JURY, JUSTICE, PERJURY, and JURISDICTION. This root most nearly means:', '["law or oath","judge","court","punishment"]'::jsonb, 0, 'JUR/JUS comes from Latin jus, meaning law, right, or sworn oath. Cognates include jury (a sworn body), justice (lawful rightness), perjury (false oath), jurisdiction (the speaking of law), and jurisprudence (the study of law). ''Judge'' belongs to JUDIC (judicial, adjudicate), a related-but-distinct root for the person, not the law itself. ''Court'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by CUR (curia, courthouse), where law is applied. ''Punishment'' belongs to PEN or PUN (penalty, punitive), the consequence of breaking law, not law itself.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::jury'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-13', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The root VOR appears in CARNIVORE, HERBIVORE, OMNIVORE, and VORACIOUS. This root most nearly means:', '["to grow","to devour or eat greedily","to hunt","to feed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'VOR comes from Latin vorare, meaning to devour or swallow whole. Cognates include carnivore (meat-devourer), herbivore (plant-devourer), omnivore (all-devourer), voracious (greedy in appetite), and devour itself. ''To grow'' belongs to CRESC (crescendo, increase), an unrelated concept. ''To hunt'' is a related-but-distinct action supplied by VEN (venatic) or PRED (predator), since hunting precedes devouring. ''To feed'' is the gentler common-cognate trap, since carnivores do feed, yet VOR specifically carries the violent, greedy swallowing, not ordinary eating, which is ED or NUTR.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::carnivore'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-14', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The root NOM/NOMEN appears in NOMINATE, NOMENCLATURE, and IGNOMINIOUS. This root most nearly means:', '["number","name","law","honor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'NOM/NOMEN comes from Latin nomen, meaning name. Cognates include nominate (to put a name forward), nomenclature (a system of names), ignominious (without good name, shameful), pseudonym (false name), and renown (re-named, famous). ''Number'' is the common-cognate trap because numerator and enumerate share the NUM root, a different Latin word that students confuse with NOM. ''Law'' belongs to LEG or JUR, separate roots. ''Honor'' is the opposite of ignominious and is supplied by HONOR or DIGNI (dignity), related-but-distinct concepts shaped by but not equal to a good name.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::nomen'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-15', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root FID appears in FIDELITY, CONFIDE, PERFIDY, and BONA FIDE. The root FID most nearly means:', '["faith or trust","loyalty","secret","promise"]'::jsonb, 0, 'FID comes from Latin fides, meaning faith or trust. Cognates include fidelity (faithfulness), confide (to trust with a secret), perfidy (betrayal of trust), bona fide (in good faith), and infidel (one without faith). ''Loyalty'' is the close common-cognate trap since fidelity often translates as loyalty, yet loyalty itself comes from LEG (lawful), while FID carries the broader trust meaning. ''Secret'' confuses the act of confiding with the root, but secret belongs to SECR (secret, secrete). ''Promise'' is a related-but-distinct concept supplied by PROMIS or VOW, the result of trust rather than its root.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::fidelity'),
  ('WK-ROOT-NEW-16', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The root JECT appears in EJECT, INJECT, PROJECT, and DEJECTED. The root JECT most nearly means:', '["to send","to throw","to push","to fall"]'::jsonb, 1, 'JECT comes from Latin jacere, meaning to throw or hurl. Cognates include eject (throw out), inject (throw in), project (throw forward), dejected (thrown down, low in spirit), and trajectory (the path of a thrown object). ''To send'' belongs to MIT/MISS (transmit, missile), a related-but-distinct action commonly confused because both move things outward, yet sending implies a destination while throwing does not. ''To push'' belongs to PEL/PULS (propel, expulsion), the contact-force root. ''To fall'' is the opposite direction, supplied by CAD/CAS (cascade, casualty), often confused with dejected because both involve downward motion.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ject'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-1', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'CANDID most nearly means:', '["frank","cautious","candied","polite"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Candid means honest and straightforward in expression, as in a candid review that holds nothing back. Frank carries the same sense of open, unguarded speech. Cautious is the antonym trap: a cautious speaker filters and hedges, the opposite of candid. Candied is a sound-alike that means coated in sugar and has no relation to honesty. Polite is a register-confusion distractor; candid speakers may be polite or blunt, but politeness describes manners rather than openness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::candid'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-2', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'INNOCUOUS most nearly means:', '["harmless","innocent","ignorant","harmful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Innocuous means producing no injury or offense, as in an innocuous comment that no one took badly. Harmless is a direct match. Innocent is a sound-alike and partial-overlap trap; it refers to lack of guilt or moral fault, not lack of harmful effect. Ignorant is another sound-alike pulled by the prefix in, but it means lacking knowledge. Harmful is the antonym, naming the exact quality innocuous denies.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::innocuous'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-3', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'IMMINENT most nearly means:', '["impending","eminent","immense","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Imminent means about to occur, as in an imminent storm that forces the crew indoors within minutes. Impending shares the meaning of a near, unavoidable arrival. Eminent is the classic sound-alike trap; it means distinguished or prominent in reputation and has nothing to do with timing. Immense is another sound-alike that describes great size, not closeness in time. Distant is the antonym, placing the event far from the present.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::imminent'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-4', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'AMICABLE most nearly means:', '["friendly","talkative","hostile","amicus"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Amicable means marked by goodwill, as in an amicable settlement that leaves both parties on decent terms. Friendly captures that cooperative warmth. Talkative is a register-confusion distractor; an amicable person may speak little, since the word describes disposition rather than volume of speech. Hostile is the antonym, naming the antagonism amicable resolves. Amicus is a Latin sound-alike root meaning friend, but as a standalone English word it does not mean friendly the way amicable does.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::amicable'),
  ('WK-SN-NEW-5', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'DESPONDENT most nearly means:', '["dejected","responsive","dependent","elated"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Despondent means cast down in spirits to the point of losing hope, as in a despondent candidate who stops returning calls after the rejection. Dejected matches that low, defeated mood. Responsive is a sound-alike pulled from the spond root meaning to answer or pledge, but it describes reactivity, not sorrow. Dependent is another sound-alike that means relying on others, with no emotional content. Elated is the antonym, naming the high spirits despondency lacks.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::despondent'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-1', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A platoon has 9 squads. Each squad has 8 soldiers. How many soldiers are in the platoon?', '["17","64","72","81"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply squads by soldiers per squad: 9 x 8 = 72. The choice 17 comes from adding 9 + 8 instead of multiplying. The choice 64 is 8 x 8, mistaking the squad count for 8. The choice 81 is 9 x 9, mistaking the squad size for 9. The correct total is 72 soldiers.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-1'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-2', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A mechanic has 132 bolts and needs to put them into bins of 11. How many full bins can be made?', '["11","12","13","121"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide the total by the bin size: 132 / 11 = 12. The choice 11 reverses the relationship, dividing by 12 instead. The choice 13 is one too many, a counting slip. The choice 121 is 11 x 11, multiplying instead of dividing. Exactly 12 full bins can be made.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-2'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-3', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A supply room had 250 batteries. After issuing 95, how many batteries remain?', '["145","155","165","345"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract what was issued from the starting count: 250 - 95 = 155. The choice 145 subtracts 105 by mis-borrowing. The choice 165 subtracts only 85. The choice 345 adds the two numbers instead of subtracting. The correct count remaining is 155 batteries.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-3'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-4', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A unit orders 7 cases of water at $9.50 each and 1 case of juice at $12. What is the total order cost?', '["$66.50","$78.50","$80.00","$152.00"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find each subtotal, then add: 7 x $9.50 = $66.50 for water, plus $12 for juice, giving $78.50. The choice $66.50 forgets to add the juice case. The choice $80.00 rounds $9.50 up to $10 before multiplying. The choice $152.00 treats the juice price as $12 per case times 7 as well. The correct total is $78.50.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-4'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A barracks holds 18 rooms on each of 4 floors. If 12 rooms are currently empty, how many rooms are occupied?', '["60","64","72","84"]'::jsonb, 0, 'First find the total rooms: 18 x 4 = 72. Then subtract the empty rooms: 72 - 12 = 60 occupied. The choice 64 subtracts only 8. The choice 72 is the total before removing empties. The choice 84 adds 12 instead of subtracting. The correct count is 60 occupied rooms.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-5'),
  ('AR-AF-FLOOR-6', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A convoy of 5 trucks each carries 240 sandbags. The sandbags are then split evenly among 8 checkpoints. How many sandbags does each checkpoint get?', '["120","150","300","1,200"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Find the total first: 5 x 240 = 1,200 sandbags. Then divide among the checkpoints: 1,200 / 8 = 150. The choice 120 divides only one truck''s load (240 / 2). The choice 300 divides by 4 instead of 8. The choice 1,200 is the total before splitting. Each checkpoint gets 150 sandbags.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-AF-FLOOR-6'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-1', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 40% of 90?', '["13","36","45","50"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert the percent to a decimal and multiply: 0.40 x 90 = 36. The choice 13 comes from 90 - 40 - 37 style subtraction error. The choice 45 is half of 90, confusing 40% with 50%. The choice 50 subtracts 40 from 90. The correct value is 36.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-2', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, '12 is what percent of 48?', '["12%","25%","36%","40%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide the part by the whole, then convert: 12 / 48 = 0.25, which is 25%. The choice 12% just restates the part as a percent. The choice 36% comes from 48 - 12 read as a percent. The choice 40% misreads the fraction as 12/30. The correct answer is 25%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'A recruit got 21 of 28 questions right on a quiz. What percent did the recruit score?', '["70%","75%","78%","84%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide correct by total: 21 / 28 = 0.75, which is 75%. The choice 70% rounds the fraction down carelessly. The choice 78% comes from 21 / 27. The choice 84% reflects 7 missed treated as 16% off (28 - 4 logic). The correct score is 75%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-4', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A $120 pair of boots is on sale for 35% off. What is the sale price?', '["$42","$78","$85","$155"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The discount is 0.35 x $120 = $42, so the sale price is $120 - $42 = $78. The choice $42 is the discount amount, not the price paid. The choice $85 takes 30% off instead of 35%. The choice $155 adds the discount instead of subtracting it. The correct sale price is $78.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-5', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A soldier''s run time improved from 30 minutes to 24 minutes. What is the percent decrease?', '["6%","20%","24%","25%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percent change uses the original value as the base: the decrease is 30 - 24 = 6 minutes, and 6 / 30 = 0.20, which is 20%. The choice 6% mistakes the raw drop for the percent. The choice 24% divides by the new time. The choice 25% divides 6 by 24 instead of 30. The correct decrease is 20%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::percent-change'),
  ('AR-PC-FLOOR-6', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A meal costs $40. A 6% tax is added to the bill. What is the total amount paid?', '["$42.40","$44.00","$46.00","$64.00"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The tax is 0.06 x $40 = $2.40, so the total is $40 + $2.40 = $42.40. The choice $44.00 uses a 10% tax. The choice $46.00 adds $6 by treating 6% as $6 flat. The choice $64.00 adds $24 by reading 6% as 60%. The correct total is $42.40.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::AR-PC-FLOOR-6'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-1', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A motorcycle travels at a steady 50 miles per hour for 3 hours. How far does it travel?', '["53 miles","100 miles","150 miles","165 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distance equals rate times time: 50 x 3 = 150 miles. The choice 53 adds the rate and time. The choice 100 multiplies by 2 hours instead of 3. The choice 165 reflects a slipped 55 mph rate. The correct distance is 150 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-1'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-2', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A hiker covers 18 miles walking at 3 miles per hour. How many hours does the hike take?', '["3 hours","6 hours","15 hours","54 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals distance divided by rate: 18 / 3 = 6 hours. The choice 3 restates the speed. The choice 15 subtracts 3 from 18 instead of dividing. The choice 54 multiplies 18 by 3. The correct time is 6 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-2'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-3', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A drone flies 120 miles in 2 hours at a constant speed. What is its speed?', '["40 mph","60 mph","118 mph","240 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Speed equals distance divided by time: 120 / 2 = 60 mph. The choice 40 divides by 3 hours. The choice 118 subtracts 2 from 120. The choice 240 multiplies 120 by 2. The correct speed is 60 mph.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-3'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A car drives at 60 mph for 1 hour and 30 minutes. How far does it travel?', '["75 miles","90 miles","100 miles","120 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert the time to hours: 1 hour 30 minutes is 1.5 hours. Then distance equals 60 x 1.5 = 90 miles. The choice 75 uses 1.25 hours. The choice 100 rounds 1.5 up to nearly 1.67 hours. The choice 120 doubles the rate for 2 hours. The correct distance is 90 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-4'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-5', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A bus must cover 210 miles and averages 35 mph. How long will the trip take?', '["5 hours","6 hours","7 hours","175 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals distance divided by rate: 210 / 35 = 6 hours. The choice 5 divides by 42. The choice 7 divides by 30. The choice 175 subtracts 35 from 210. The correct travel time is 6 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-5'),
  ('AR-RD-FLOOR-6', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A jet flies 1,400 miles in 2 hours and 30 minutes. What is its average speed?', '["480 mph","560 mph","700 mph","3,500 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert the time to hours: 2 hours 30 minutes is 2.5 hours. Then speed equals 1,400 / 2.5 = 560 mph. The choice 480 divides by 2.92. The choice 700 divides by 2 hours, ignoring the extra 30 minutes. The choice 3,500 multiplies instead of dividing. The correct speed is 560 mph.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-RD-FLOOR-6'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-1', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A fuel mix uses oil and gas in a 1:4 ratio. If 2 quarts of oil are used, how many quarts of gas are needed?', '["4 quarts","6 quarts","8 quarts","16 quarts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The ratio means 4 parts gas for every 1 part oil. With 2 quarts of oil, multiply by 4: 2 x 4 = 8 quarts of gas. The choice 4 uses the raw ratio number without scaling. The choice 6 adds 4 to 2. The choice 16 squares the scaling. The correct amount is 8 quarts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-FLOOR-1'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'In a kennel the ratio of dogs to cats is 5:2. If there are 10 dogs, how many cats are there?', '["2 cats","4 cats","5 cats","20 cats"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 10 dogs are double the ratio''s 5, so multiply the cat side by 2 as well: 2 x 2 = 4 cats. The choice 2 uses the raw ratio number. The choice 5 confuses dog and cat parts. The choice 20 multiplies 10 by 2 on the wrong side. The correct count is 4 cats.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-FLOOR-2'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-3', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A trail mix uses peanuts and raisins in a 3:1 ratio. If 12 ounces of peanuts are used, how many ounces of raisins are needed?', '["3 ounces","4 ounces","9 ounces","36 ounces"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The scale factor is 12 / 3 = 4, so multiply the raisin side by 4: 1 x 4 = 4 ounces. The choice 3 uses the raw ratio number without scaling. The choice 9 takes three-quarters of 12. The choice 36 multiplies 12 by 3. The correct amount is 4 ounces.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-FLOOR-3'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-4', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A printer produces 5 pages every 4 seconds. At that rate, how many pages does it produce in 60 seconds?', '["48 pages","60 pages","75 pages","300 pages"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Set up a proportion: 5 pages per 4 seconds equals x pages per 60 seconds. The 60 seconds is 15 times 4, so multiply 5 by 15: 5 x 15 = 75 pages. The choice 48 uses 4 pages per 4 seconds. The choice 60 just restates the seconds. The choice 300 multiplies 5 by 60. The correct output is 75 pages.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-FLOOR-4'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-5', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A blueprint uses a scale of 1 inch to 8 feet. A wall measures 5.5 inches on the blueprint. How long is the actual wall?', '["13.5 feet","40 feet","44 feet","48 feet"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Each inch represents 8 feet, so multiply: 5.5 x 8 = 44 feet. The choice 13.5 adds 8 and 5.5. The choice 40 uses 5 inches instead of 5.5. The choice 48 uses 6 inches. The correct length is 44 feet.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::map-scale'),
  ('AR-RP-FLOOR-6', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'A team of 4 painters finishes a job in 9 days. Working at the same rate, how many days would 6 painters take?', '["6 days","7.5 days","11 days","13.5 days"]'::jsonb, 0, 'This is an inverse proportion: total work is 4 x 9 = 36 painter-days. With 6 painters, divide: 36 / 6 = 6 days. The choice 7.5 averages the two crew sizes. The choice 11 adds days for more workers, which is backwards. The choice 13.5 scales in the wrong direction. The correct time is 6 days.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-RP-FLOOR-6'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A notebook costs $4. How much do 7 notebooks cost?', '["$11","$24","$28","$32"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the unit price by the quantity: 4 x 7 = $28. The choice $11 adds 4 and 7. The choice $24 uses 6 notebooks. The choice $32 uses 8 notebooks. The correct cost is $28.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-1'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-2', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A jug holds 64 ounces of water. If 5 people each drink 9 ounces, how many ounces are left?', '["19 ounces","45 ounces","50 ounces","55 ounces"]'::jsonb, 0, 'First find how much is drunk: 5 x 9 = 45 ounces. Then subtract from the jug: 64 - 45 = 19 ounces. The choice 45 is the amount consumed, not the amount left. The choice 50 subtracts only 14. The choice 55 subtracts only 9. The correct amount left is 19 ounces.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-2'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-3', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A class of 32 students is divided into teams of 4. How many teams are formed?', '["6","8","28","128"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide the class size by the team size: 32 / 4 = 8 teams. The choice 6 divides by 5. The choice 28 subtracts 4 from 32. The choice 128 multiplies 32 by 4. The correct number of teams is 8.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-3'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-4', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A worker earns $18 per hour and works 7 hours, then receives a $25 bonus. What are the total earnings?', '["$126","$133","$151","$175"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Compute the hourly pay first: 18 x 7 = $126. Then add the bonus: $126 + $25 = $151. The choice $126 forgets the bonus. The choice $133 adds the bonus to 6 hours of pay. The choice $175 treats the bonus as a 7th-hour rate of $25 plus 18 x 6 plus extras. The correct total is $151.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-4'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-5', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A car uses 6 gallons of gas to travel 180 miles. How many miles can it travel on 10 gallons at the same rate?', '["186 miles","240 miles","300 miles","1,080 miles"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Find the mileage per gallon: 180 / 6 = 30 miles per gallon. Then multiply by 10 gallons: 30 x 10 = 300 miles. The choice 186 adds 6 to 180. The choice 240 uses 8 gallons. The choice 1,080 multiplies 180 by 6. The correct distance is 300 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-5'),
  ('AR-WP-FLOOR-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A box contains 48 candies. One-half are chocolate and one-fourth are caramel. The rest are mints. How many mints are there?', '["12","16","24","36"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Chocolate is one-half of 48, which is 24. Caramel is one-fourth of 48, which is 12. Together that is 36, leaving 48 - 36 = 12 mints. The choice 16 miscounts caramel as one-third. The choice 24 is the chocolate count. The choice 36 is the chocolate-plus-caramel total. The correct count of mints is 12.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-WP-FLOOR-6'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x + 8 = 20, what is the value of x?', '["8","12","20","28"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 8 from both sides: x = 20 - 8 = 12. The choice 8 restates the constant being moved. The choice 20 leaves the equation unsolved. The choice 28 adds 8 instead of subtracting. The correct value is 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-1'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-2', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If 7x = 56, what is the value of x?', '["7","8","49","63"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide both sides by 7: x = 56 / 7 = 8. The choice 7 restates the coefficient. The choice 49 subtracts 7 from 56. The choice 63 adds 7 to 56. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-2'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-3', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'If x - 5 = 11, what is the value of x?', '["6","11","16","55"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add 5 to both sides: x = 11 + 5 = 16. The choice 6 subtracts 5 instead of adding. The choice 11 leaves the equation unsolved. The choice 55 multiplies 11 by 5. The correct value is 16.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-3'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-4', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 3x + 5 = 26, what is the value of x?', '["7","9","21","63"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 5 from both sides to get 3x = 21, then divide by 3: x = 7. The choice 9 forgets to subtract the 5 first (27 / 3). The choice 21 stops after subtracting and skips the division. The choice 63 multiplies 21 by 3 instead of dividing. The correct value is 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-4'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-5', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 2x - 7 = 13, what is the value of x?', '["3","10","20","40"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add 7 to both sides to get 2x = 20, then divide by 2: x = 10. The choice 3 subtracts 7 instead of adding (6 / 2). The choice 20 stops after adding and skips the division. The choice 40 multiplies 20 by 2 instead of dividing. The correct value is 10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-5'),
  ('MK-AL-FLOOR-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'Solve for y: 4(y - 2) = 12.', '["1","2.5","5","8"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide both sides by 4 to get y - 2 = 3, then add 2: y = 5. Alternatively distribute to 4y - 8 = 12, so 4y = 20 and y = 5. The choice 1 divides 12 by 4 then subtracts 2. The choice 2.5 forgets to distribute the 4 to the 2. The choice 8 adds 2 to 6 from a halving error. The correct value is 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-AL-FLOOR-6'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-1', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 4³.', '["12","43","64","81"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An exponent means repeated multiplication: 4 x 4 x 4 = 64. The choice 12 multiplies the base by the exponent (4 x 3). The choice 43 reads the notation as a two-digit number. The choice 81 is 3⁴, swapping base and exponent. The correct value is 64.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-FLOOR-1'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-2', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Evaluate 10².', '["12","20","100","1,000"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Squaring means multiplying the base by itself: 10 x 10 = 100. The choice 12 adds 10 and 2. The choice 20 multiplies the base by the exponent (10 x 2). The choice 1,000 is 10³. The correct value is 100.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-FLOOR-2'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'Simplify a² · a³.', '["a⁵","a⁶","a","2a⁵"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents: 2 + 3 = 5, giving a⁵. The choice a⁶ multiplies the exponents instead of adding. The choice a subtracts the exponents. The choice 2a⁵ wrongly doubles the base coefficient. The correct result is a⁵.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-4', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify a⁹ / a⁴.', '["a²·²⁵","a⁵","a¹³","a³⁶"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When dividing powers with the same base, subtract the exponents: 9 - 4 = 5, giving a⁵. The choice a²·²⁵ divides the exponents. The choice a¹³ adds them. The choice a³⁶ multiplies them. The correct result is a⁵.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-FLOOR-4'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-5', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Combine like terms: 5x + 3x - 2x.', '["6x","6x³","10x","30x"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Like terms share the same variable, so add and subtract the coefficients: 5 + 3 - 2 = 6, giving 6x. The choice 6x³ wrongly multiplies the variable parts. The choice 10x adds all three coefficients without subtracting. The choice 30x multiplies the coefficients. The correct result is 6x.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-FLOOR-5'),
  ('MK-EP-FLOOR-6', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify (2a³)².', '["2a⁶","4a⁵","4a⁶","2a⁹"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Raise both the coefficient and the variable to the outer power: 2² = 4, and (a³)² = a⁶ by multiplying exponents. The result is 4a⁶. The choice 2a⁶ forgets to square the coefficient. The choice 4a⁵ adds the exponents instead of multiplying. The choice 2a⁹ cubes the exponent and skips the coefficient. The correct result is 4a⁶.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-EP-FLOOR-6'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-1', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 1/3 + 1/3?', '["1/6","2/3","2/6","1/9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'With the same denominator, add the numerators and keep the denominator: 1 + 1 = 2 over 3, giving 2/3. The choice 1/6 adds the denominators. The choice 2/6 adds both numerators and denominators. The choice 1/9 multiplies the denominators. The correct sum is 2/3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-1'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-2', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 0.5 + 0.25?', '["0.30","0.55","0.75","0.255"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Line up the decimal points and add: 0.50 + 0.25 = 0.75. The choice 0.30 adds only the leading digits. The choice 0.55 misaligns the place values. The choice 0.255 concatenates the digits without adding. The correct sum is 0.75.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-2'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-3', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'Convert 3/4 to a decimal.', '["0.34","0.43","0.75","1.33"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide the numerator by the denominator: 3 / 4 = 0.75. The choice 0.34 reads the fraction as digits. The choice 0.43 reverses those digits. The choice 1.33 divides 4 by 3 instead. The correct decimal is 0.75.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-3'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'What is 3/5 - 1/2?', '["1/10","2/3","1/5","2/7"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Use a common denominator of 10: 3/5 is 6/10 and 1/2 is 5/10, so 6/10 - 5/10 = 1/10. The choice 2/3 subtracts numerators and denominators directly. The choice 1/5 ignores the denominator difference. The choice 2/7 adds across. The correct difference is 1/10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-4'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-5', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'What is 3/4 × 2/9 in lowest terms?', '["1/6","5/13","6/36","6/13"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiply numerators and denominators: 3 x 2 = 6 over 4 x 9 = 36, giving 6/36, which reduces to 1/6. The choice 5/13 adds across. The choice 6/36 is correct before reducing, so it is not in lowest terms. The choice 6/13 adds the denominators. The correct simplified product is 1/6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-5'),
  ('MK-FR-FLOOR-6', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'What is 0.6 of 45?', '["7.5","21","27","75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The word ''of'' means multiply: 0.6 x 45 = 27. The choice 7.5 divides 45 by 6. The choice 21 uses 0.46 by misreading. The choice 75 divides 45 by 0.6 instead of multiplying. The correct value is 27.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-FR-FLOOR-6'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-1', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'What is the area of a rectangle that is 9 inches long and 4 inches wide?', '["13 sq in","26 sq in","36 sq in","45 sq in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area of a rectangle is length times width: 9 x 4 = 36 square inches. The choice 13 adds the two sides. The choice 26 is the perimeter (2 x 9 plus 2 x 4). The choice 45 uses a width of 5. The correct area is 36 square inches.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-1'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'What is the perimeter of a square with sides of 6 cm?', '["12 cm","24 cm","30 cm","36 cm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A square has 4 equal sides, so the perimeter is 4 x 6 = 24 cm. The choice 12 doubles only one side. The choice 30 uses 5 sides. The choice 36 is the area (6 x 6), not the perimeter. The correct perimeter is 24 cm.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-2'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-3', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'Two angles of a triangle measure 50 degrees and 60 degrees. What is the third angle?', '["50 degrees","70 degrees","80 degrees","110 degrees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The angles of a triangle sum to 180 degrees, so the third is 180 - 50 - 60 = 70 degrees. The choice 50 just repeats a given angle. The choice 80 subtracts from 190 by mis-adding. The choice 110 is the sum of the two given angles, not the remaining one. The correct angle is 70 degrees.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-3'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-4', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'What is the area of a circle with a radius of 5 inches? Use pi equals 3.14.', '["15.7 sq in","31.4 sq in","78.5 sq in","157 sq in"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area of a circle is pi times the radius squared: 3.14 x 5² = 3.14 x 25 = 78.5 square inches. The choice 15.7 is half the circumference. The choice 31.4 is the full circumference (2 x pi x 5). The choice 157 uses a radius of 10 by doubling. The correct area is 78.5 square inches.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-4'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-5', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'What is the volume of a rectangular box that is 4 ft long, 3 ft wide, and 2 ft tall?', '["9 cubic ft","24 cubic ft","26 cubic ft","48 cubic ft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Volume of a box is length times width times height: 4 x 3 x 2 = 24 cubic feet. The choice 9 adds the three dimensions. The choice 26 is the surface area divided in part, a common mix-up. The choice 48 doubles the correct volume. The correct volume is 24 cubic feet.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-5'),
  ('MK-GE-FLOOR-6', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'A rectangle has an area of 48 square feet and a length of 8 feet. What is its width?', '["6 feet","8 feet","40 feet","56 feet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Since area equals length times width, divide the area by the length: 48 / 8 = 6 feet. The choice 8 restates the length. The choice 40 subtracts 8 from 48. The choice 56 adds 8 to 48. The correct width is 6 feet.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-GE-FLOOR-6'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-1', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Which of the following is an even number?', '["27","33","46","51"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An even number is divisible by 2, which means it ends in 0, 2, 4, 6, or 8. Only 46 ends in 6. The choices 27, 33, and 51 all end in odd digits and are therefore odd. The correct answer is 46.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-FLOOR-1'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-2', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'What is the value of |-9|?', '["-9","0","9","18"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Absolute value is the distance from zero, which is always non-negative, so |-9| = 9. The choice -9 leaves the sign unchanged. The choice 0 confuses absolute value with rounding to zero. The choice 18 doubles the number. The correct value is 9.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-FLOOR-2'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-3', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Which of the following numbers is divisible by 5?', '["32","44","58","65"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A number is divisible by 5 when it ends in 0 or 5. Only 65 ends in 5. The choices 32, 44, and 58 end in other digits and leave a remainder when divided by 5. The correct answer is 65.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-NP-FLOOR-3'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-4', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the greatest common factor of 12 and 30?', '["3","6","12","60"]'::jsonb, 1, 'List the factors: 12 has 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12 and 30 has 1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 15, 30. The largest shared factor is 6. The choice 3 is a common factor but not the greatest. The choice 12 is a factor of 12 only. The choice 60 is the least common multiple, not the greatest common factor. The correct answer is 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::gcf'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the least common multiple of 6 and 8?', '["2","14","24","48"]'::jsonb, 2, 'List multiples until they match: 6, 12, 18, 24 and 8, 16, 24. The smallest shared multiple is 24. The choice 2 is the greatest common factor, not the multiple. The choice 14 adds the two numbers. The choice 48 is the product of 6 and 8, which is a common multiple but not the least. The correct answer is 24.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::lcm'),
  ('MK-NP-FLOOR-6', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'Which number in this list is prime: 39, 49, 53, or 55?', '["39","49","53","55"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A prime number has exactly two factors, 1 and itself. 53 cannot be divided evenly by any number from 2 through 7, so it is prime. The choice 39 is 3 x 13. The choice 49 is 7 x 7. The choice 55 is 5 x 11. The correct answer is 53.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::identify-prime'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-1', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A supply room receives 6 boxes, and each box holds 12 flashlights. How many flashlights are there in total?', '["18","60","72","84"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply boxes by flashlights per box: 6 x 12 = 72. The choice 18 adds 6 + 12 instead of multiplying. The choice 60 is 5 x 12, undercounting by one box. The choice 84 is 7 x 12, overcounting by one box. The correct total is 72.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-1'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-2', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A truck is loaded with 480 rations to be split evenly among 16 squads. How many rations does each squad receive?', '["28","30","32","34"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Divide total rations by squads: 480 / 16 = 30. The choice 28 results from dividing by 17 by mistake. The choice 32 results from dividing by 15. The choice 34 comes from rounding up an incorrect quotient. The correct amount is 30.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-2'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-3', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A warehouse has 1,250 helmets. After shipping out 875, how many helmets remain?', '["325","375","425","475"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract shipped from total: 1,250 - 875 = 375. The choice 325 subtracts 925 by misreading the number shipped. The choice 425 subtracts 825. The choice 475 subtracts 775. The correct remainder is 375.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-3'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-4', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A unit orders 14 cases of water bottles. Each case contains 24 bottles. If 96 bottles are used the first day, how many remain?', '["240","264","288","336"]'::jsonb, 0, 'First find the total: 14 x 24 = 336 bottles. Then subtract usage: 336 - 96 = 240. The choice 264 subtracts only 72. The choice 288 subtracts only 48. The choice 336 is the total before any bottles are used. The correct remainder is 240.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-4'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-5', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 3, 'A motor pool has 9 vehicles. Each vehicle needs 7 quarts of oil, and oil comes in 5-quart jugs. How many jugs must be purchased so every vehicle is filled?', '["12","13","14","63"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Total oil needed is 9 x 7 = 63 quarts. Divide by jug size: 63 / 5 = 12.6, so 13 jugs are needed because 12 jugs supply only 60 quarts. The choice 12 ignores the remainder. The choice 14 rounds up too far. The choice 63 is the quarts needed, not jugs. The correct count is 13.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-5'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-6', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A contractor buys materials for 2,340 dollars, splits the cost equally with 2 partners so all 3 pay the same, then each partner gets a 60 dollar rebate. What does each partner finally pay?', '["700","720","780","1,110"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Split among 3 people: 2,340 / 3 = 780 each. Subtract the rebate: 780 - 60 = 720. The choice 700 subtracts 80. The choice 780 ignores the rebate. The choice 1,110 splits between only 2 people. The correct amount is 720.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-6'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-1', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 10% of 250?', '["2.5","25","125","250"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Ten percent means multiply by 0.10: 250 x 0.10 = 25. The choice 2.5 is 1% of 250. The choice 125 is 50% of 250. The choice 250 is the whole amount. The correct value is 25.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-2', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'A recruit answered 45 of 60 questions correctly. What percent did the recruit answer correctly?', '["65%","70%","75%","80%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide correct by total: 45 / 60 = 0.75, which is 75%. The choice 65% misdivides. The choice 70% rounds incorrectly. The choice 80% would require 48 correct. The correct percent is 75%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-3', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A jacket costs 80 dollars and is marked down 25%. What is the sale price?', '["20","55","60","75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The discount is 80 x 0.25 = 20 dollars, so the sale price is 80 - 20 = 60. The choice 20 is the discount amount, not the price. The choice 55 subtracts 25 dollars instead of 25 percent. The choice 75 subtracts only 5 dollars. The correct price is 60.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-4', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 3, 'A town''s population grew from 4,000 to 4,600 in one year. What was the percent increase?', '["6%","13%","15%","60%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The increase is 4,600 - 4,000 = 600. Divide by the original: 600 / 4,000 = 0.15, which is 15%. The choice 6% misplaces the decimal. The choice 13% divides by the new total instead of the original. The choice 60% misreads the increase. The correct increase is 15%.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::percent-change'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-5', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'A 200 dollar item is discounted 20%, and then 8% sales tax is added to the discounted price. What is the final cost?', '["160.00","172.80","184.00","192.00"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Apply the discount first: 200 x 0.80 = 160. Then add tax: 160 x 1.08 = 172.80. The choice 160.00 omits the tax. The choice 184.00 applies tax to the original 200 before discount and mishandles the order. The choice 192.00 subtracts only 4%. The correct cost is 172.80.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-6', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 5, 'After a 15% raise, an employee earns 4,600 dollars per month. What was the monthly salary before the raise?', '["3,910","3,910.00","4,000","4,060"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The new salary is 115% of the old: old x 1.15 = 4,600, so old = 4,600 / 1.15 = 4,000. The choices 3,910 and 3,910.00 incorrectly subtract 15% of the new salary. The choice 4,060 subtracts only 540. The correct prior salary is 4,000.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::AR-B11-PCT-6'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-1', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A car travels at 50 miles per hour for 3 hours. How far does it travel?', '["53","100","150","200"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distance equals rate times time: 50 x 3 = 150 miles. The choice 53 adds 50 + 3. The choice 100 uses 2 hours. The choice 200 uses 4 hours. The correct distance is 150 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-1'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-2', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A runner covers 18 miles in 3 hours. What is the runner''s average speed in miles per hour?', '["5","6","9","21"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Speed equals distance divided by time: 18 / 3 = 6 miles per hour. The choice 5 misdivides. The choice 9 divides by 2 hours. The choice 21 adds 18 + 3. The correct speed is 6 miles per hour.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-2'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-3', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'How long does it take to drive 240 miles at a steady 60 miles per hour?', '["3 hours","4 hours","5 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals distance divided by rate: 240 / 60 = 4 hours. The choice 3 hours uses 80 miles per hour. The choice 5 hours uses 48 miles per hour. The choice 6 hours uses 40 miles per hour. The correct time is 4 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-3'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-4', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A train leaves a station traveling 45 miles per hour. After 2 hours it speeds up to 65 miles per hour for the next 3 hours. How far has it traveled in total?', '["225","265","285","325"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First leg: 45 x 2 = 90 miles. Second leg: 65 x 3 = 195 miles. Total: 90 + 195 = 285 miles. The choice 225 applies 45 miles per hour to all 5 hours. The choice 265 swaps the two times, using 45 for 3 hours and 65 for 2 hours. The choice 325 applies 65 miles per hour to all 5 hours. The correct distance is 285 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-4'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-5', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 4, 'Two cyclists start at the same point and ride in opposite directions, one at 12 miles per hour and the other at 16 miles per hour. How far apart are they after 2.5 hours?', '["28","40","56","70"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Their separation rate is 12 + 16 = 28 miles per hour. Over 2.5 hours: 28 x 2.5 = 70 miles. The choice 28 is the combined rate for one hour only. The choice 40 multiplies 16 by 2.5 alone. The choice 56 uses 2 hours. The correct distance is 70 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-5'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-6', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 5, 'A pilot flies 600 miles to a base, then flies the same 600 miles back. The trip out takes 2 hours and the return takes 3 hours. What is the average speed for the entire round trip?', '["120","200","240","250"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total distance is 600 + 600 = 1,200 miles. Total time is 2 + 3 = 5 hours. Average speed is 1,200 / 5 = 240 miles per hour. The choice 120 divides one-way distance by total time. The choice 200 is only the return-leg speed of 600 / 3. The choice 250 averages the two leg speeds, which is the wrong method for average speed. The correct value is 240 miles per hour.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-6'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-1', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 1, 'A recipe uses 2 cups of flour for every 3 cups of water. If 6 cups of flour are used, how many cups of water are needed?', '["4","7","9","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Flour tripled from 2 to 6, so water must triple too: 3 x 3 = 9 cups. The choice 4 doubles the flour amount instead. The choice 7 adds 4 to 3. The choice 12 doubles 6. The correct amount is 9 cups.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::recipe-ratio'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-2', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'The ratio of officers to enlisted in a unit is 1 to 8. If there are 40 enlisted, how many officers are there?', '["5","8","32","48"]'::jsonb, 0, 'For every 8 enlisted there is 1 officer: 40 / 8 = 5 officers. The choice 8 restates the ratio number. The choice 32 subtracts 8 from 40. The choice 48 adds 8 to 40. The correct count is 5 officers.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-2'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-3', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'A map uses a scale of 1 inch to 25 miles. Two cities are 4.5 inches apart on the map. How many miles apart are they?', '["29.5","100","112.5","125"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply inches by the scale: 4.5 x 25 = 112.5 miles. The choice 29.5 adds 4.5 to 25. The choice 100 uses 4 inches. The choice 125 uses 5 inches. The correct distance is 112.5 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::map-scale'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-4', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'A class of 35 students has a boy-to-girl ratio of 3 to 4. How many boys are in the class?', '["12","15","20","21"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The ratio has 3 + 4 = 7 parts, so each part is 35 / 7 = 5 students. Boys are 3 parts: 3 x 5 = 15. The choice 12 uses 4 parts incorrectly assigned. The choice 20 is the number of girls. The choice 21 uses the ratio numbers as a sum. The correct count is 15 boys.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-4'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-5', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'If 4 machines produce 600 parts in a day, how many parts can 7 machines produce in a day at the same rate?', '["900","1,050","1,200","1,500"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each machine makes 600 / 4 = 150 parts per day. With 7 machines: 150 x 7 = 1,050 parts. The choice 900 uses 6 machines. The choice 1,200 uses 8 machines. The choice 1,500 uses 10 machines. The correct output is 1,050 parts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-5'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-6', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 5, 'A sum of 720 dollars is split among three people in the ratio 2 to 3 to 4. How much does the person with the largest share receive?', '["160","240","320","360"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The ratio totals 2 + 3 + 4 = 9 parts, so each part is 720 / 9 = 80 dollars. The largest share is 4 parts: 4 x 80 = 320. The choice 160 is the smallest share. The choice 240 is the middle share. The choice 360 splits the money in half. The correct amount is 320.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-6'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-1', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 1, 'A recruit had 28 dollars and earned 15 more for chores. How much money does the recruit have now?', '["13","33","43","53"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Add the earnings to the starting amount: 28 + 15 = 43. The choice 13 subtracts instead of adding. The choice 33 adds only 5. The choice 53 adds 25. The correct total is 43.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-1'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-2', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A book has 320 pages. If a reader finishes 40 pages each night, how many nights will it take to finish the book?', '["6","7","8","9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide total pages by pages per night: 320 / 40 = 8 nights. The choice 6 uses 53 pages per night. The choice 7 rounds down incorrectly. The choice 9 adds an extra night. The correct answer is 8 nights.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-2'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-3', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'Tickets cost 12 dollars each. A group buys 9 tickets and pays with a 150 dollar bill. How much change should they receive?', '["42","48","54","108"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The cost is 9 x 12 = 108 dollars. Change is 150 - 108 = 42. The choice 48 uses 8 tickets. The choice 54 uses 8 tickets and a different price. The choice 108 is the cost, not the change. The correct change is 42.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-3'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-4', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'A worker earns 18 dollars per hour for the first 40 hours and 27 dollars per hour for each hour beyond 40. What is the worker''s pay for a 46-hour week?', '["828","882","918","1,242"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Regular pay is 40 x 18 = 720. Overtime is 6 x 27 = 162. Total is 720 + 162 = 882. The choice 828 pays the 6 overtime hours at the regular rate. The choice 918 pays all 46 hours plus an error. The choice 1,242 pays all 46 hours at the overtime rate. The correct pay is 882.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-4'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-5', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 4, 'A tank holds 60 gallons and is one-fourth full. A pump adds 9 gallons per minute. How many minutes until the tank is full?', '["4","5","6","7"]'::jsonb, 1, 'One-fourth of 60 is 15 gallons present, so 60 - 15 = 45 gallons are still needed. At 9 gallons per minute: 45 / 9 = 5 minutes. The choice 4 uses 36 gallons needed. The choice 6 uses 54 gallons needed. The choice 7 ignores the water already present. The correct time is 5 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-5'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-6', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'A father is 3 times as old as his son. In 12 years he will be twice as old as his son. How old is the son now?', '["10","12","24","36"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Let the son be s, so the father is 3s. In 12 years: 3s + 12 = 2(s + 12). Solving gives 3s + 12 = 2s + 24, so s = 12. The choice 10 fails the future condition. The choice 24 is twice the son''s age. The choice 36 is the father''s current age. The correct age is 12.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-6'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-7', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 1, 'A barracks has 4 floors with 15 rooms on each floor. How many rooms are there in total?', '["19","45","60","75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply floors by rooms per floor: 4 x 15 = 60. The choice 19 adds 4 + 15. The choice 45 uses 3 floors. The choice 75 uses 5 floors. The correct total is 60.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-7'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-7', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 1, 'What is 50% of 86?', '["33","43","50","86"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fifty percent means half: 86 / 2 = 43. The choice 33 subtracts incorrectly. The choice 50 restates the percent. The choice 86 is the whole. The correct value is 43.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-1', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 1, 'Solve for x: x + 9 = 17.', '["6","8","9","26"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 9 from both sides: x = 17 - 9 = 8. The choice 6 subtracts 11. The choice 9 restates the constant. The choice 26 adds instead of subtracting. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-1'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-2', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'Solve for x: 3x - 4 = 20.', '["6","8","16","24"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add 4 to both sides to get 3x = 24, then divide by 3: x = 8. The choice 6 divides 20 by 3 then rounds. The choice 16 forgets to divide by 3 after subtracting. The choice 24 stops before dividing. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-2'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-3', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If 5x + 2 = 3x + 14, what is x?', '["3","4","6","8"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Subtract 3x from both sides to get 2x + 2 = 14, then 2x = 12, so x = 6. The choice 3 divides 12 by 4. The choice 4 mishandles the constants. The choice 8 adds instead of subtracting terms. The correct value is 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-3'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-4', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 2(x + 3) = 18, what is x?', '["6","9","12","15"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide both sides by 2 to get x + 3 = 9, then subtract 3: x = 6. The choice 9 stops before subtracting 3. The choice 12 distributes incorrectly. The choice 15 adds 3 instead of subtracting. The correct value is 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-4'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-5', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 4, 'Solve for y: (y / 4) + 5 = 12.', '["7","17","28","68"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Subtract 5 to get y / 4 = 7, then multiply by 4: y = 28. The choice 7 stops before multiplying. The choice 17 adds 5 instead of subtracting. The choice 68 multiplies 17 by 4. The correct value is 28.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-5'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-6', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 5, 'Solve for x: 4x - 7 = 2x + 11.', '["2","6","9","18"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Subtract 2x from both sides to get 2x - 7 = 11, then add 7 to get 2x = 18, so x = 9. The choice 2 mishandles the constants. The choice 6 divides 18 by 3. The choice 18 stops before dividing by 2. The correct value is 9.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-6'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-1', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 1, 'What is 4 squared?', '["6","8","16","44"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Four squared means 4 x 4 = 16. The choice 6 adds 4 + 2. The choice 8 multiplies 4 x 2. The choice 44 places the digits side by side. The correct value is 16.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-B11-EP-1'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-2', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify: x^3 times x^4.', '["x^7","x^12","x^1","2x^7"]'::jsonb, 0, 'When multiplying like bases, add the exponents: 3 + 4 = 7, giving x^7. The choice x^12 multiplies the exponents. The choice x^1 subtracts them. The choice 2x^7 incorrectly doubles the base. The correct result is x^7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-3', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 2, 'Simplify: (x^5) / (x^2).', '["x^2","x^3","x^7","x^10"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When dividing like bases, subtract the exponents: 5 - 2 = 3, giving x^3. The choice x^2 subtracts in the wrong order. The choice x^7 adds the exponents. The choice x^10 multiplies them. The correct result is x^3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-4', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify: (3x^2)(4x^3).', '["7x^5","12x^5","12x^6","7x^6"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multiply the coefficients (3 x 4 = 12) and add the exponents (2 + 3 = 5), giving 12x^5. The choice 7x^5 adds the coefficients. The choice 12x^6 multiplies the exponents. The choice 7x^6 makes both errors. The correct result is 12x^5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-5', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Expand: (x + 5)(x + 2).', '["x^2 + 7x + 10","x^2 + 10x + 7","x^2 + 7x + 7","x^2 + 10"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Use FOIL: x times x is x^2, the outer and inner terms give 2x + 5x = 7x, and 5 times 2 is 10. The result is x^2 + 7x + 10. The choice x^2 + 10x + 7 swaps the middle and last terms. The choice x^2 + 7x + 7 mishandles the constant. The choice x^2 + 10 drops the middle term. The correct expansion is x^2 + 7x + 10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-B11-EP-5'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-6', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 5, 'Factor completely: x^2 - 9.', '["(x - 3)(x - 3)","(x + 3)(x + 3)","(x - 3)(x + 3)","(x - 9)(x + 1)"]'::jsonb, 2, 'This is a difference of squares: x^2 - 9 = (x - 3)(x + 3). The choices (x - 3)(x - 3) and (x + 3)(x + 3) each produce a middle term and the wrong sign on the constant. The choice (x - 9)(x + 1) does not multiply back to x^2 - 9. The correct factoring is (x - 3)(x + 3).', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-B11-EP-6'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-1', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 1/2 + 1/4?', '["1/6","2/6","3/4","1/8"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert 1/2 to 2/4, then add: 2/4 + 1/4 = 3/4. The choice 1/6 adds numerators and denominators. The choice 2/6 makes the same error differently. The choice 1/8 multiplies the fractions. The correct sum is 3/4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-1'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-2', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'What is 2/3 of 21?', '["7","9","14","42"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide 21 by 3 to get 7, then multiply by 2: 7 x 2 = 14. The choice 7 is only one-third. The choice 9 misdivides. The choice 42 doubles 21. The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-2'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-3', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 2, 'Convert 3/8 to a decimal.', '["0.375","0.38","0.625","2.667"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide 3 by 8: 3 / 8 = 0.375. The choice 0.38 rounds prematurely. The choice 0.625 is 5/8. The choice 2.667 divides 8 by 3. The correct decimal is 0.375.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-3'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-4', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'What is 3/4 divided by 1/2?', '["3/8","3/2","1/2","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Dividing by 1/2 is the same as multiplying by 2: 3/4 x 2/1 = 6/4 = 3/2. The choice 3/8 multiplies the fractions instead of inverting the divisor. The choice 1/2 ignores the dividend. The choice 2/3 inverts the wrong fraction. The correct value is 3/2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-4'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-5', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 4, 'Simplify the fraction 18/24 to lowest terms.', '["2/3","3/4","6/8","9/12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The greatest common factor of 18 and 24 is 6: 18 / 6 = 3 and 24 / 6 = 4, giving 3/4. The choice 2/3 reduces by the wrong factor. The choices 6/8 and 9/12 are equivalent but not in lowest terms. The correct simplest form is 3/4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-5'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-6', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 5, 'What is 0.6 written as a fraction in lowest terms?', '["1/6","3/5","6/100","60/10"]'::jsonb, 1, '0.6 is 6/10, which reduces by 2 to 3/5. The choice 1/6 misreads the decimal. The choice 6/100 treats 0.6 as 0.06. The choice 60/10 misplaces the decimal entirely. The correct fraction is 3/5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-6'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-1', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'What is the area of a rectangle that is 8 inches long and 5 inches wide?', '["13","26","40","80"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area equals length times width: 8 x 5 = 40 square inches. The choice 13 adds the sides. The choice 26 is the perimeter. The choice 80 doubles the area. The correct area is 40.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-1'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-2', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'What is the perimeter of a square with a side length of 9 cm?', '["18","27","36","81"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A square has 4 equal sides: 4 x 9 = 36 cm. The choice 18 doubles one side. The choice 27 uses 3 sides. The choice 81 is the area. The correct perimeter is 36.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-2'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-3', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 2, 'Two angles of a triangle measure 50 degrees and 60 degrees. What is the third angle?', '["70","80","90","110"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The angles of a triangle sum to 180 degrees: 180 - 50 - 60 = 70. The choice 80 subtracts incorrectly. The choice 90 assumes a right angle. The choice 110 is the sum of the two given angles. The correct angle is 70 degrees.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-3'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-4', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'What is the area of a triangle with a base of 10 cm and a height of 6 cm?', '["16","30","60","32"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Area equals one-half base times height: 0.5 x 10 x 6 = 30 square cm. The choice 16 adds base and height. The choice 60 omits the one-half. The choice 32 is the perimeter of a related shape. The correct area is 30.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-4'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-5', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 4, 'A right triangle has legs of 6 and 8. What is the length of the hypotenuse?', '["10","12","14","48"]'::jsonb, 0, 'By the Pythagorean theorem, the hypotenuse is the square root of 6^2 + 8^2 = 36 + 64 = 100, which is 10. The choice 12 mishandles the squares. The choice 14 adds the legs. The choice 48 multiplies the legs. The correct length is 10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::pythagorean-triple'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-6', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 5, 'What is the area of a circle with a radius of 5 cm? Use 3.14 for pi.', '["15.7","31.4","78.5","157"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Area equals pi times the radius squared: 3.14 x 5^2 = 3.14 x 25 = 78.5 square cm. The choice 15.7 is half the circumference. The choice 31.4 is the circumference. The choice 157 multiplies by 50 instead of 25. The correct area is 78.5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-6'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-1', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 1, 'Which of the following is a prime number?', '["9","15","21","23"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A prime number has exactly two factors, 1 and itself. 23 has no other factors. The choice 9 is 3 x 3. The choice 15 is 3 x 5. The choice 21 is 3 x 7. The correct prime is 23.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::identify-prime'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-2', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the greatest common factor of 24 and 36?', '["6","8","12","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The largest number that divides both 24 and 36 evenly is 12. The choice 6 is a common factor but not the greatest. The choice 8 divides 24 but not 36. The choice 72 is the least common multiple. The correct answer is 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::gcf'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-3', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 2, 'What is the least common multiple of 4 and 6?', '["2","10","12","24"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The smallest number divisible by both 4 and 6 is 12. The choice 2 is the greatest common factor. The choice 10 is not a multiple of either correctly. The choice 24 is a common multiple but not the least. The correct answer is 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::lcm'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-4', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Evaluate: -7 + 12 - 3.', '["2","-2","8","22"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Work left to right: -7 + 12 = 5, then 5 - 3 = 2. The choice -2 mishandles the signs. The choice 8 adds 12 and 3 then subtracts incorrectly. The choice 22 adds all values as positives. The correct value is 2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B11-NP-4'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-5', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Evaluate using order of operations: 6 + 2 x (5 - 1).', '["14","20","32","44"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Do the parentheses first: 5 - 1 = 4. Then multiply: 2 x 4 = 8. Then add: 6 + 8 = 14. The choice 20 adds before multiplying. The choice 32 multiplies everything together incorrectly. The choice 44 mishandles all operations. The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B11-NP-5'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-6', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 5, 'What is the value of the square root of 144?', '["10","12","14","72"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The square root of 144 is the number that multiplies by itself to give 144, which is 12 because 12 x 12 = 144. The choice 10 gives 100 when squared. The choice 14 gives 196. The choice 72 is half of 144. The correct value is 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B11-NP-6'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-7', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 1, 'What is 0.25 written as a fraction in lowest terms?', '["1/2","1/4","1/5","25/10"]'::jsonb, 1, '0.25 equals 25/100, which reduces to 1/4. The choice 1/2 is 0.5. The choice 1/5 is 0.2. The choice 25/10 misplaces the decimal. The correct fraction is 1/4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-7'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-7', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 1, 'How many degrees are in a straight angle?', '["90","180","270","360"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A straight angle forms a straight line and measures 180 degrees. The choice 90 is a right angle. The choice 270 is three right angles. The choice 360 is a full circle. The correct measure is 180 degrees.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-7'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-7', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 1, 'A walker moves at 3 miles per hour for 2 hours. How far does the walker go?', '["1.5","5","6","8"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Distance equals rate times time: 3 x 2 = 6 miles. The choice 1.5 divides instead of multiplying. The choice 5 adds 3 + 2. The choice 8 uses the wrong factors. The correct distance is 6 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-7'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-7', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 2, 'If 3 pencils cost 1.50 dollars, how much do 10 pencils cost at the same rate?', '["3.00","4.50","5.00","15.00"]'::jsonb, 2, 'One pencil costs 1.50 / 3 = 0.50 dollars. Ten pencils cost 10 x 0.50 = 5.00. The choice 3.00 doubles the original. The choice 4.50 triples it. The choice 15.00 multiplies 10 by 1.50. The correct cost is 5.00.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-7'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-7', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 2, 'A team scored 12 points in the first half and 19 in the second half. The opposing team scored 25 points total. By how many points did the team win?', '["6","7","12","31"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The team scored 12 + 19 = 31 points. The margin is 31 - 25 = 6 points. The choice 7 mishandles the subtraction. The choice 12 uses only the first half. The choice 31 is the team''s total, not the margin. The correct margin is 6 points.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-7'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-8', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 5, 'A crew lays 1,800 feet of cable in 6 equal days, then doubles its daily pace for 4 more days. How many feet are laid in all 10 days?', '["3,000","4,200","4,800","5,400"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Daily pace is 1,800 / 6 = 300 feet. The faster pace is 600 feet per day for 4 days, which is 2,400 feet. Total is 1,800 + 2,400 = 4,200 feet. The choice 3,000 forgets to double the later pace. The choice 4,800 doubles all ten days at the faster rate. The choice 5,400 adds an extra day. The correct total is 4,200.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-8'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-9', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 2, 'A cashier has 7 stacks of bills with 23 bills in each stack. How many bills are there in total?', '["30","141","161","184"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply stacks by bills per stack: 7 x 23 = 161. The choice 30 adds 7 + 23. The choice 141 uses 6 stacks plus an error. The choice 184 uses 8 stacks. The correct total is 161.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-9'),
  ('AR-B11-AF-10', 'AR', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals', 4, 'A team needs to fold 1,000 flyers. Three members fold 120 each and two members fold 95 each. How many flyers still need to be folded?', '["450","540","550","640"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Three members fold 3 x 120 = 360 and two fold 2 x 95 = 190, for 550 folded. Remaining is 1,000 - 550 = 450. The choice 540 mishandles one product. The choice 550 is the number folded, not remaining. The choice 640 subtracts only 360. The correct remainder is 450.', true, 'verified', 'ar.arithmetic-fundamentals::AR-B11-AF-10'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-8', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 2, 'What is 30% of 90?', '["18","24","27","30"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Thirty percent means multiply by 0.30: 90 x 0.30 = 27. The choice 18 is 20% of 90. The choice 24 misjudges the product. The choice 30 restates the percent. The correct value is 27.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::basic-percent'),
  ('AR-B11-PCT-9', 'AR', 'ar.percent', 4, 'A salesperson earns a 6% commission on sales. If commission for the month was 1,080 dollars, what were the total sales?', '["6,480","12,000","16,200","18,000"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Sales times 0.06 equals 1,080, so sales equal 1,080 / 0.06 = 18,000 dollars. The choice 6,480 multiplies 1,080 by 6. The choice 12,000 uses 9 percent. The choice 16,200 mishandles the division. The correct total is 18,000.', true, 'verified', 'ar.percent::single-discount'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-8', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 3, 'A printer prints 45 pages per minute. How many pages can it print in 8 minutes?', '["320","350","360","405"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply rate by time: 45 x 8 = 360 pages. The choice 320 uses 40 pages per minute. The choice 350 mishandles the product. The choice 405 uses 9 minutes. The correct total is 360.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::AR-B11-RDT-8'),
  ('AR-B11-RDT-9', 'AR', 'ar.rate-distance-time', 2, 'A faucet fills a 36-gallon tub at 4 gallons per minute. How many minutes does it take to fill the tub?', '["7","8","9","12"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Time equals volume divided by rate: 36 / 4 = 9 minutes. The choice 7 mishandles the division. The choice 8 uses 4.5 gallons per minute. The choice 12 uses 3 gallons per minute. The correct time is 9 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.rate-distance-time::fill-drain'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-8', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 3, 'A photo that is 4 inches wide and 6 inches tall is enlarged so the width becomes 10 inches. What is the new height if proportions are kept?', '["12","15","16","18"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The scale factor is 10 / 4 = 2.5. New height is 6 x 2.5 = 15 inches. The choice 12 doubles the original. The choice 16 adds the increase to the height directly. The choice 18 triples the height. The correct height is 15 inches.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-8'),
  ('AR-B11-RAT-9', 'AR', 'ar.ratio-proportion', 4, 'A fuel mixture requires gas and oil in a 25 to 1 ratio. How many ounces of oil are needed for 100 ounces of gas?', '["2","4","5","25"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For every 25 ounces of gas, 1 ounce of oil is used: 100 / 25 = 4 ounces of oil. The choice 2 uses a 50 to 1 ratio. The choice 5 uses a 20 to 1 ratio. The choice 25 restates the ratio number. The correct amount is 4 ounces.', true, 'verified', 'ar.ratio-proportion::AR-B11-RAT-9'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-8', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 3, 'A phone plan costs 35 dollars per month plus 0.10 dollars per text. If the bill was 47 dollars, how many texts were sent?', '["100","110","120","130"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Texts cost 47 - 35 = 12 dollars. At 0.10 per text: 12 / 0.10 = 120 texts. The choice 100 uses 10 dollars of texts. The choice 110 mishandles the division. The choice 130 uses 13 dollars of texts. The correct count is 120 texts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-8'),
  ('AR-B11-WRD-9', 'AR', 'ar.word-problems', 5, 'Two pipes fill a pool together. One alone fills it in 6 hours, the other alone in 12 hours. How long does it take with both running together?', '["3 hours","4 hours","6 hours","9 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In one hour the pipes fill 1/6 + 1/12 = 2/12 + 1/12 = 3/12 = 1/4 of the pool, so the full pool takes 4 hours. The choice 3 hours halves the faster pipe''s time of 6 hours. The choice 6 hours uses only the faster pipe. The choice 9 hours averages the two times. The correct time is 4 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.word-problems::AR-B11-WRD-9'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-7', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 3, 'If 6x + 5 = 4x + 17, what is x?', '["3","6","11","12"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subtract 4x from both sides to get 2x + 5 = 17, then 2x = 12, so x = 6. The choice 3 divides 12 by 4. The choice 11 mishandles the constants. The choice 12 stops before dividing. The correct value is 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-7'),
  ('MK-B11-AL-8', 'MK', 'mk.algebra-linear', 2, 'If x / 3 = 7, what is x?', '["4","10","21","37"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply both sides by 3: x = 7 x 3 = 21. The choice 4 subtracts 3. The choice 10 adds 3. The choice 37 mishandles the operation. The correct value is 21.', true, 'verified', 'mk.algebra-linear::MK-B11-AL-8'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-7', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 3, 'Simplify: (2x^3)^2.', '["2x^5","2x^6","4x^5","4x^6"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Square both the coefficient and the power: 2^2 = 4 and (x^3)^2 = x^6, giving 4x^6. The choice 2x^5 adds exponents and ignores the coefficient. The choice 2x^6 squares only the variable. The choice 4x^5 adds the exponents. The correct result is 4x^6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::simplify-power'),
  ('MK-B11-EP-8', 'MK', 'mk.exponents-polynomials', 4, 'Add the polynomials: (3x^2 + 2x - 1) + (x^2 - 5x + 4).', '["4x^2 - 3x + 3","4x^2 + 7x + 3","2x^2 - 3x + 3","4x^2 - 3x - 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Combine like terms: 3x^2 + x^2 = 4x^2, 2x - 5x = -3x, and -1 + 4 = 3, giving 4x^2 - 3x + 3. The choice 4x^2 + 7x + 3 adds the x coefficients without the sign. The choice 2x^2 - 3x + 3 subtracts the squared terms. The choice 4x^2 - 3x - 5 mishandles the constants. The correct sum is 4x^2 - 3x + 3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.exponents-polynomials::MK-B11-EP-8'),
  ('MK-B11-FRC-8', 'MK', 'mk.fractions-decimals', 3, 'What is 5/6 - 1/3?', '["1/3","1/2","4/3","2/3"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert 1/3 to 2/6, then subtract: 5/6 - 2/6 = 3/6 = 1/2. The choice 1/3 subtracts numerators only. The choice 4/3 adds instead of subtracting. The choice 2/3 mishandles the common denominator. The correct value is 1/2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.fractions-decimals::MK-B11-FRC-8'),
  ('MK-B11-GEO-8', 'MK', 'mk.geometry', 3, 'What is the volume of a box that is 4 cm long, 3 cm wide, and 5 cm tall?', '["12","27","60","94"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Volume equals length times width times height: 4 x 3 x 5 = 60 cubic cm. The choice 12 multiplies only length and width. The choice 27 adds the dimensions and cubes. The choice 94 is the surface area. The correct volume is 60.', true, 'verified', 'mk.geometry::MK-B11-GEO-8'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-7', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 3, 'Evaluate: (-4)(-6).', '["-24","-10","10","24"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A negative times a negative is positive: 4 x 6 = 24. The choice -24 keeps a negative sign. The choice -10 adds the numbers with a sign error. The choice 10 adds the numbers. The correct value is 24.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B11-NP-7'),
  ('MK-B11-NP-8', 'MK', 'mk.number-properties', 4, 'Evaluate: 20 - 12 / 4 + 2.', '["4","9","19","20"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Divide first: 12 / 4 = 3. Then work left to right: 20 - 3 + 2 = 19. The choice 4 divides the running total. The choice 9 subtracts before dividing. The choice 20 mishandles the addition. The correct value is 19.', true, 'verified', 'mk.number-properties::MK-B11-NP-8'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-1', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 1, 'ABUNDANT most nearly means:', '["plentiful","expensive","fragile","hidden"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Abundant means present in large quantity, as in ''rain was abundant that spring.'' Plentiful is its direct synonym. Expensive describes high cost, a different idea, since something can be abundant and cheap. Fragile describes how easily a thing breaks, unrelated to quantity. Hidden describes something concealed, the opposite of the visible plenty abundant suggests.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::abundant'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-2', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 1, 'STURDY most nearly means:', '["quiet","strong","heavy","smooth"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sturdy means strongly and solidly built, as in ''a sturdy table.'' Strong is its direct synonym. Quiet describes low sound, unrelated to build. Heavy is a near miss because sturdy objects are often heavy, but sturdiness names durability, not weight, since light materials can also be sturdy. Smooth describes an even surface, a separate property.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::sturdy'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-3', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 1, 'CONCEAL most nearly means:', '["hide","repair","announce","carry"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Conceal means to keep from being seen or known, as in ''she concealed the gift.'' Hide is its direct synonym. Announce means to make publicly known, the opposite of conceal. Repair means to fix something broken, unrelated. Carry means to transport, a different action entirely.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::conceal'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-4', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 2, 'DILIGENT most nearly means:', '["wealthy","hardworking","cheerful","talented"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Diligent means showing steady, careful effort, as in ''a diligent student who reviews every night.'' Hardworking is its direct synonym. Talented is a near miss because a diligent person may also be talented, but diligence describes effort, not natural ability. Wealthy describes having money, unrelated. Cheerful describes a happy mood, which has nothing to do with the steady work diligent names.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::diligent'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-5', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 2, 'VITAL most nearly means:', '["essential","optional","temporary","expensive"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Vital means absolutely necessary, as in ''water is vital to survival.'' Essential is its direct synonym. Optional is the antonym, naming what can be left out. Temporary describes short duration, unrelated to importance. Expensive describes cost, a separate quality, since a vital thing can be cheap.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::vital'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-6', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 2, 'ABRUPT most nearly means:', '["gradual","sudden","polite","lengthy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Abrupt means happening suddenly and without warning, as in ''an abrupt stop.'' Sudden is its direct synonym. Gradual is the antonym, describing slow, steady change. Polite describes courteous manners; abrupt can mean curt, but its core sense here is suddenness, not rudeness. Lengthy describes long duration, the opposite of the quickness abrupt implies.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::abrupt'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-7', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 2, 'FERTILE most nearly means:', '["productive","barren","frozen","rocky"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Fertile means able to produce abundantly, as in ''fertile soil.'' Productive is its direct synonym. Barren is the antonym, naming land that produces nothing. Frozen describes temperature and rocky describes texture; both are conditions that can reduce fertility, but neither defines the word itself.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::fertile'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-8', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'VIGILANT most nearly means:', '["watchful","careless","cheerful","exhausted"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Vigilant means keeping careful watch for danger, as in ''a vigilant guard.'' Watchful is its direct synonym. Careless is the antonym, naming a failure to pay attention. Cheerful describes a happy mood, unrelated to alertness. Exhausted describes tiredness, which would undermine vigilance rather than define it.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::vigilant'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-9', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'NOVICE most nearly means:', '["expert","beginner","leader","rival"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Novice means a person new to an activity, as in ''a novice climber.'' Beginner is its direct synonym. Expert is the antonym, naming someone highly skilled. Leader describes someone who directs others, unrelated to experience level. Rival describes a competitor, a different relationship entirely.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::novice'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-10', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'LENIENT most nearly means:', '["strict","merciful","honest","wealthy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lenient means not strict, willing to forgive or go easy, as in ''a lenient judge.'' Merciful is its closest synonym. Strict is the direct antonym. Honest describes truthfulness, unrelated to how harshly someone enforces rules. Wealthy describes having money, a separate idea.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::lenient'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-11', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'TEDIOUS most nearly means:', '["dangerous","boring","expensive","complicated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Tedious means tiresome through dullness and length, as in ''a tedious lecture.'' Boring is its direct synonym. Complicated is a near miss because a tedious task can be hard, but tedium comes from monotony, not difficulty. Dangerous describes risk and expensive describes cost, neither of which is what tedious names.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::tedious'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-12', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 3, 'DOCILE most nearly means:', '["obedient","intelligent","stubborn","fragile"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Docile means easy to manage or teach, as in ''a docile horse.'' Obedient is its closest synonym. Stubborn is the antonym, naming resistance to control. Intelligent describes mental ability, which a docile animal may lack or possess. Fragile describes how easily something breaks, unrelated to temperament.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::docile'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-13', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 4, 'GARRULOUS most nearly means:', '["talkative","silent","forgetful","rude"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Garrulous means excessively talkative, especially about small matters, as in ''a garrulous neighbor.'' Talkative is its direct synonym. Silent is the antonym. Rude is a register trap, since a garrulous person can be perfectly polite, just long-winded. Forgetful describes poor memory, unrelated to how much one speaks.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::garrulous'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-14', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 4, 'FRUGAL most nearly means:', '["wasteful","thrifty","honest","fearful"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Frugal means careful and sparing with money or resources, as in ''a frugal budget.'' Thrifty is its direct synonym. Wasteful is the antonym, naming careless spending. Honest describes truthfulness and fearful describes anxiety; neither relates to economy with resources.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::frugal'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-15', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 4, 'RESOLUTE most nearly means:', '["determined","uncertain","exhausted","generous"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Resolute means firmly determined and unwavering, as in ''resolute in her decision.'' Determined is its direct synonym. Uncertain is the antonym, naming doubt. Exhausted describes tiredness, unrelated to firmness of purpose. Generous describes willingness to give, a different trait entirely.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::resolute'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-16', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 4, 'MEAGER most nearly means:', '["scanty","generous","filthy","ancient"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Meager means lacking in quantity, thin or scant, as in ''a meager portion.'' Scanty is its direct synonym. Generous, naming an ample amount, is the antonym. Filthy describes dirtiness and ancient describes age; neither has to do with how small or sparse a quantity is.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::meager'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-17', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'CACOPHONY most nearly means:', '["harsh noise","sweet melody","deep silence","bright color"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Cacophony means a harsh, jarring mixture of sounds, as in ''the cacophony of car horns.'' Harsh noise captures it directly. Sweet melody is its near opposite, naming pleasant sound. Deep silence is the absence of sound, the full opposite. Bright color belongs to sight, not hearing, so it is the wrong sense entirely.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::cacophony'),
  ('WK-B12-SYN-18', 'WK', 'wk.synonyms', 5, 'INDIGENT most nearly means:', '["impoverished","outraged","native","lazy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Indigent means very poor, lacking the means to live, as in ''aid for indigent families.'' Impoverished is its direct synonym. Outraged is a sound-alike trap, since indigent is easily confused with indignant, which means angry. Native is a separate confusion with indigenous. Lazy describes a lack of effort, not a lack of money.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::indigent'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-1', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''After the long march, the soldiers were WEARY and could barely lift their packs,'' the word WEARY most nearly means:', '["excited","tired","hungry","lost"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''could barely lift their packs'' after a long march points to exhaustion. Weary means tired or worn out. Hungry is plausible after a march, but the sentence ties the state to lifting packs, which signals fatigue, not appetite. Excited reverses the mood, since worn-out soldiers are not energized. Lost addresses direction, which the sentence never raises.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::weary'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-2', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 1, 'In the sentence ''The new recruit was so TIMID that he hesitated to ask even simple questions,'' the word TIMID most nearly means:', '["shy","clever","loud","strong"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The clue ''hesitated to ask even simple questions'' shows a lack of confidence. Timid means shy or easily frightened. Loud is the opposite, since a timid person tends to be quiet. Clever describes intelligence, which the sentence does not measure. Strong describes physical or emotional power, the reverse of the hesitation described.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::timid'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-3', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''The instructions were so VAGUE that no two students completed the task the same way,'' the word VAGUE most nearly means:', '["detailed","unclear","lengthy","strict"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''no two students completed the task the same way'' shows the instructions lacked precision. Vague means not clearly expressed. Detailed is the opposite, since detailed instructions would produce uniform results. Lengthy describes length, but long instructions can still be clear. Strict describes how firmly rules are enforced, which the sentence does not address.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::vague'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-4', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''The hikers were CAUTIOUS on the icy trail, testing each step before shifting their weight,'' the word CAUTIOUS most nearly means:', '["careless","careful","cheerful","exhausted"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''testing each step before shifting their weight'' shows deliberate care to avoid danger. Cautious means careful to avoid risk. Careless is the direct opposite. Cheerful describes mood, which the sentence does not raise. Exhausted describes fatigue, but the hikers'' slowness comes from caution on ice, not tiredness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::cautious'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-5', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 2, 'In the sentence ''The manager praised the report as THOROUGH because it answered every question the client had raised,'' the word THOROUGH most nearly means:', '["brief","complete","colorful","late"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''answered every question'' signals nothing was left out. Thorough means complete and careful, covering all details. Brief is the opposite, naming something short and partial. Colorful describes vivid style, not completeness. Late describes timing, which the sentence does not mention.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::thorough'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-6', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The report was BIASED, presenting only the facts that favored one side and ignoring the rest,'' the word BIASED most nearly means:', '["unfair","balanced","lengthy","outdated"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The clue ''presenting only the facts that favored one side and ignoring the rest'' signals a slanted, one-sided treatment. Biased means unfairly favoring one side. Balanced is the antonym, naming an even-handed account. Lengthy describes length, which the sentence does not measure. Outdated describes age, but the problem is selective fairness, not timeliness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::biased'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-7', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''Funding was so SCARCE that the program had to turn away qualified applicants,'' the word SCARCE most nearly means:', '["abundant","limited","delayed","complicated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''had to turn away qualified applicants'' shows there was not enough to go around. Scarce means available in short supply. Abundant is the antonym, naming plenty. Delayed addresses timing, but the problem is quantity, not lateness. Complicated describes difficulty of process, which the sentence does not raise.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::scarce'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-8', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 3, 'In the sentence ''The coach remained COMPOSED even as the score slipped away, calmly calling the next play,'' the word COMPOSED most nearly means:', '["panicked","calm","angry","confused"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The clue ''calmly calling the next play'' even under pressure shows self-control. Composed means calm and in control of one''s emotions. Panicked and angry both name strong reactions the coach is said to avoid. Confused describes mental disorder, but the coach acts with clear purpose, not bewilderment.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::composed'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-9', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''Her PRAGMATIC plan ignored grand theories and focused only on what would actually work by Friday,'' the word PRAGMATIC most nearly means:', '["practical","idealistic","expensive","secretive"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The contrast ''ignored grand theories and focused only on what would actually work'' defines the term. Pragmatic means dealing with things sensibly and realistically. Idealistic is the contrast the sentence sets up, naming the theory-driven approach she rejects. Expensive addresses cost and secretive addresses concealment, neither of which the sentence raises.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::pragmatic'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-10', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 4, 'In the sentence ''The new supervisor was ABRASIVE, snapping at staff and dismissing their concerns,'' the word ABRASIVE most nearly means:', '["harsh","gentle","humorous","patient"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The clue ''snapping at staff and dismissing their concerns'' shows a rough, irritating manner. Abrasive means harsh or grating in dealing with others. Gentle and patient are both opposites, naming a mild, tolerant manner. Humorous describes a comic style, which the unkind behavior in the sentence does not match.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::abrasive'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-11', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''The witness gave such a LUCID account that the jury followed every step without confusion,'' the word LUCID most nearly means:', '["clear","muddled","lengthy","false"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The clue ''the jury followed every step without confusion'' shows the account was easy to understand. Lucid means clear and easy to follow. Muddled is the antonym, naming something confusing. Lengthy describes length, but a long account can still be unclear. False describes untruth, which the sentence does not raise; lucidity is about clarity, not honesty.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::lucid'),
  ('WK-B12-CTX-12', 'WK', 'wk.context-clues', 5, 'In the sentence ''Rather than make a scene, she handled the insult with great EQUANIMITY and simply changed the subject,'' the word EQUANIMITY most nearly means:', '["composure","outrage","confusion","generosity"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The clue ''Rather than make a scene'' and ''simply changed the subject'' shows calm self-possession under provocation. Equanimity means evenness of temper, calmness. Outrage is the reaction she deliberately avoids. Confusion describes a muddled mind, but she responds with clear control. Generosity describes giving, unrelated to staying calm.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::equanimity'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-1', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The word SPECTATOR shares its root with INSPECT and SPECTACLE. The root SPECT- means:', '["to hear","to look","to build","to break"]'::jsonb, 1, 'SPECT- comes from Latin specere, meaning to look or watch. Cognates include spectator (one who watches), inspect (to look into), spectacle (a sight), and prospect (a view ahead). ''To hear'' would use AUD-, a different sense entirely. ''To build'' would use STRUCT- (structure, construct). ''To break'' would use FRACT- or RUPT-, unrelated roots.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::spectator'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-2', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The word MANUAL shares its root with MANUFACTURE and MANIPULATE. The root MAN- means:', '["hand","mind","water","fire"]'::jsonb, 0, 'MAN- comes from Latin manus, meaning hand. Cognates include manual (done by hand), manufacture (originally to make by hand), manipulate (to handle), and manuscript (written by hand). ''Mind'' would use MENT- (mental) or PSYCH-. ''Water'' would use AQUA- or HYDRO-. ''Fire'' would use IGN- or PYRO-, none of which is MAN-.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::manual'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-3', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 3, 'The word VOLUNTEER shares its root with VOLUNTARY and VOLITION. The root VOL- means:', '["to fly","to wish or will","to roll","to speak"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In these words VOL- comes from Latin velle, meaning to wish or will. Cognates include volunteer (one who acts by choice), voluntary (done by choice), and volition (the act of willing). ''To fly'' belongs to a separate Latin root volare, not the one in volition. ''To roll'' would use VOLV- (revolve), and ''to speak'' would use DICT- or LOQU-, different roots.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::volunteer'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-4', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The word BIOLOGY shares its root with BIOGRAPHY and ANTIBIOTIC. The root BIO- means:', '["earth","life","light","sound"]'::jsonb, 1, 'BIO- comes from Greek bios, meaning life. Cognates include biology (the study of life), biography (an account of a life), and antibiotic (acting against living microbes). ''Earth'' would use GEO- (geology). ''Light'' would use PHOTO- (photograph). ''Sound'' would use PHON- (telephone), none of which is BIO-.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::biology'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-5', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 4, 'The word TENABLE shares its root with RETAIN and TENACIOUS. The root TEN- means:', '["to hold","to throw","to cut","to lead"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TEN- comes from Latin tenere, meaning to hold. Cognates include tenable (able to be held or defended), retain (to keep holding), and tenacious (holding firmly). ''To throw'' would use JECT- (eject). ''To cut'' would use CIS- (incision). ''To lead'' would use DUCT- (conduct), separate roots.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::tenable'),
  ('WK-B12-ROOT-6', 'WK', 'wk.root-words', 5, 'The word FRACTURE shares its root with FRAGMENT and INFRACTION. The root FRACT- (also FRAG-) means:', '["to bend","to break","to join","to measure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'FRACT-, with the variant FRAG-, comes from Latin frangere, meaning to break. Cognates include fracture (a break), fragment (a broken piece), and infraction (a breaking of a rule). ''To bend'' would use FLEX- (flexible). ''To join'' would use JUNCT- (junction). ''To measure'' would use METER- or MENS-, unrelated roots.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::fracture'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-1', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The word PREVIEW contains the prefix PRE-. Based on that prefix, PRE- most nearly means:', '["before","after","against","again"]'::jsonb, 0, 'PRE- means before, so a preview is a viewing before the main event. Other examples include predict (say before) and prepare (get ready before). ''After'' would use POST- (postwar). ''Against'' would use ANTI- (antiwar). ''Again'' would use RE- (rewrite), each a different prefix.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::preview'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-2', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 2, 'The word SUBMERGE contains the prefix SUB-. Based on that prefix, SUB- most nearly means:', '["over","under","beside","around"]'::jsonb, 1, 'SUB- means under or below, so to submerge is to put under water. Other examples include submarine (under the sea) and subway (an under-ground line). ''Over'' would use SUPER- or SUPRA- (superscript). ''Beside'' would use JUXTA- or PARA-. ''Around'' would use CIRCUM- (circumnavigate), separate prefixes.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::submerge'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-3', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The word MALFUNCTION contains the prefix MAL-. Based on that prefix, MAL- most nearly means:', '["well","badly or wrongly","fully","partly"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MAL- means bad or wrong, so a malfunction is a faulty operation. Other examples include malnutrition (bad nutrition) and malevolent (wishing ill). ''Well'' is the opposite sense, carried by BENE- (benefit). ''Fully'' would use a different intensifier, and ''partly'' would use SEMI- or DEMI-, unrelated prefixes.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::malfunction'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-4', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 3, 'The word WASHABLE ends in the suffix -ABLE. Based on that suffix, -ABLE most nearly means:', '["capable of being","the state of","one who does","without"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The suffix -ABLE means capable of or able to be, so washable means able to be washed. Other examples include readable (able to be read) and breakable (able to be broken). ''The state of'' is carried by -NESS or -ITY. ''One who does'' is carried by -ER or -OR. ''Without'' is carried by -LESS, different suffixes.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::washable'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-5', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word OMNIPRESENT contains the prefix OMNI-. Based on that prefix, OMNI- most nearly means:', '["none","all","half","self"]'::jsonb, 1, 'OMNI- means all, so omnipresent means present everywhere. Other examples include omnivore (eating all kinds of food) and omnipotent (all-powerful). ''None'' would be carried by a negating prefix like NON- or A-. ''Half'' would use SEMI- or HEMI-. ''Self'' would use AUTO- (automatic), different prefixes.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::omnipresent'),
  ('WK-B12-PFX-6', 'WK', 'wk.prefixes-suffixes', 4, 'The word NARRATOR ends in the suffix -OR. Based on that suffix, -OR most nearly means:', '["one who does","the act of","capable of","before"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The suffix -OR names a person or thing that performs an action, so a narrator is one who narrates. Other examples include actor (one who acts) and inventor (one who invents). ''The act of'' is carried by -ION (action). ''Capable of'' is carried by -ABLE (readable). ''Before'' is carried by the prefix PRE-, not a suffix.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::narrator'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-1', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Honeybees do far more than make honey. As they move from flower to flower collecting nectar, they carry pollen with them, allowing plants to produce fruits and seeds. Many of the crops people eat every day depend on this pollination to grow. Without bees, grocery shelves would hold far less variety."

The main idea of this passage is that:', '["honey is the most important product bees make","bees are important because they pollinate the crops people eat","bees travel long distances between flowers","grocery stores should sell more honey"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage opens with ''Honeybees do far more than make honey'' and spends the rest explaining pollination and its effect on food crops. Choice B states that central point. Choice A is contradicted by the first sentence, which downplays honey. Choice C names a supporting detail, how bees move, not the main idea. Choice D adds a recommendation about stores the passage never makes.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-1'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-2', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Drinking enough water affects nearly every part of how the body works. It helps regulate temperature, keeps joints cushioned, and carries nutrients to cells. When a person does not drink enough, even mild dehydration can cause headaches and trouble concentrating. Staying hydrated is a simple habit with wide-reaching effects."

Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["Dehydration always causes severe headaches.","Water plays many important roles in keeping the body working well.","Joints are the most important part of the body.","People should drink water only when they feel thirsty."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage lists several functions of water and closes by calling hydration ''a simple habit with wide-reaching effects.'' Choice B captures that broad point. Choice A overstates the text, which says mild dehydration ''can cause headaches,'' not always severe ones. Choice C elevates one example, joints, above the rest. Choice D gives advice about thirst the passage never offers.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-2'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-3', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The first public libraries were not free. Early reading rooms charged membership fees, which kept books out of reach for most working families. It was only in the nineteenth century that towns began funding libraries through taxes, opening their shelves to everyone. That shift turned the library from a private club into a public service."

The main idea of this passage is that:', '["libraries have always been free to the public","libraries changed from paid clubs into free public services","working families never used early libraries","the nineteenth century was the best time for reading"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage traces a change: early libraries ''charged membership fees,'' then tax funding ''opened their shelves to everyone.'' Choice B names that transformation. Choice A contradicts the opening line that libraries ''were not free.'' Choice C overstates the text, which says fees kept books ''out of reach for most,'' not that families never used them. Choice D adds a value judgment about the century the passage does not make.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-3'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-4', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Sleep is often treated as wasted time, but the brain stays remarkably busy while we rest. During deep sleep, it sorts through the day''s events, strengthening memories worth keeping and clearing away clutter. Skipping sleep does not just leave a person tired; it weakens the very process that helps learning stick."

Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["The brain shuts down completely during sleep.","Sleep is wasted time that could be spent learning.","Sleep is active work that helps the brain store what it learns.","People who sleep more always perform better in school."]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage rejects the idea of sleep as ''wasted time'' and describes the brain ''remarkably busy'' sorting and storing memories. Choice C captures that point. Choice A contradicts the description of a busy brain. Choice B states the very view the passage argues against. Choice D makes a guaranteed-outcome claim about grades the passage does not support.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-4'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-5', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Supporters of the new bridge point to shorter commutes and easier access to the hospital across the river. Critics counter that the cost has doubled since the first estimate and that traffic studies relied on outdated data. Both sides agree the current ferry is unreliable, but they disagree sharply on whether a bridge is the right fix."

The main idea of this passage is that:', '["the bridge will definitely be built","people disagree about whether the bridge is the right solution","the ferry is the best way to cross the river","the hospital should be moved to the other side"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage presents supporters and critics and ends by noting they ''disagree sharply on whether a bridge is the right fix.'' Choice B states that the debate is the point. Choice A predicts an outcome the passage never settles. Choice C misreads the shared view that the ferry ''is unreliable.'' Choice D introduces moving the hospital, an idea the passage does not raise.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-5'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-6', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"For decades, doctors warned patients to avoid all fats. Newer research draws a sharper line: some fats, like those in olive oil and fish, support heart health, while others, found in fried and heavily processed foods, do the opposite. The lesson is not to fear fat itself, but to learn which kinds belong on the plate."

Which statement best expresses the main idea?', '["All fats are equally harmful to the heart.","The type of fat matters more than avoiding fat altogether.","Olive oil is the only healthy food.","Doctors no longer give any dietary advice."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage contrasts old blanket advice with newer findings that distinguish helpful from harmful fats, closing with ''learn which kinds belong on the plate.'' Choice B names that point. Choice A states the outdated view the passage corrects. Choice C overstates one example into the only option. Choice D makes a sweeping claim about doctors the passage does not support.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-6'),
  ('PC-B12-MI-7', 'PC', 'pc.main-idea', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The factory''s switch to solar power was praised as a green milestone, and on sunny days it does run almost entirely on the sun. Yet on cloudy stretches it still draws heavily from the regional grid, which burns natural gas. Calling the plant fully renewable, then, paints a cleaner picture than the daily numbers support."

The main idea of this passage is that:', '["the factory has completely stopped using fossil fuels","the factory''s renewable claim is more partial than it sounds","solar power never works for factories","natural gas is cheaper than solar power"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage credits the solar switch but notes the plant ''still draws heavily from the grid'' on cloudy days, concluding the renewable label ''paints a cleaner picture than the daily numbers support.'' Choice B captures that qualified judgment. Choice A is contradicted by the grid reliance described. Choice C overgeneralizes, since the plant does run on solar on sunny days. Choice D compares costs the passage never discusses.', true, 'verified', 'pc.main-idea::PC-B12-MI-7'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-1', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The aquarium''s new exhibit features three types of jellyfish. The moon jelly glows pale white, the sea nettle trails long orange tentacles, and the spotted jelly carries tiny algae inside its body. Visitors can view all three in a single darkened room near the main entrance."

According to the passage, which jellyfish carries algae inside its body?', '["the moon jelly","the sea nettle","the spotted jelly","all three jellyfish"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states directly that ''the spotted jelly carries tiny algae inside its body.'' Choice C matches that detail. The moon jelly is described only as glowing pale white, so Choice A is wrong. The sea nettle is described by its orange tentacles, not algae, so Choice B is wrong. The passage attributes algae to only one type, so Choice D contradicts the text.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-1'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-2', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The hiking club meets every Saturday at 7 a.m. in the north parking lot. Members are asked to bring at least two liters of water, a light snack, and sturdy shoes. The leader provides a first aid kit and a trail map for each outing."

According to the passage, what does the leader provide?', '["water and snacks","a first aid kit and a trail map","sturdy shoes","transportation to the trailhead"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states ''The leader provides a first aid kit and a trail map.'' Choice B matches that detail. Water and snacks are listed as items members bring, not the leader, so Choice A is wrong. Sturdy shoes are also a member responsibility, so Choice C is wrong. Transportation is never mentioned, so Choice D adds information not in the text.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-2'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-3', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The library extended its hours during exam week. From Monday through Thursday it now stays open until midnight, two hours later than usual. On Friday it closes at the regular time of 8 p.m., and on the weekend it keeps its normal schedule. Free coffee is offered after 9 p.m. on the late nights."

According to the passage, on which days does the library stay open until midnight?', '["every day of the week","Monday through Thursday","only on Friday","only on the weekend"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states the library stays open until midnight ''From Monday through Thursday.'' Choice B matches that detail exactly. Choice A is wrong because Friday closes at 8 p.m. and the weekend keeps its normal schedule. Choice C names Friday, which the passage gives the regular 8 p.m. closing. Choice D names the weekend, which the passage says follows the normal schedule.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-3'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-4', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The recipe makes two dozen muffins. It calls for two cups of flour, one cup of sugar, and three eggs, plus a half cup of blueberries folded in at the end. The batter bakes for eighteen minutes at 375 degrees. The author notes that frozen blueberries work just as well as fresh ones."

According to the passage, how long do the muffins bake?', '["eight minutes","fifteen minutes","eighteen minutes","twenty-four minutes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage states the batter ''bakes for eighteen minutes at 375 degrees.'' Choice C matches that detail. The other times are distractors built from nearby numbers: twenty-four echoes the two dozen muffins, and fifteen and eight resemble parts of eighteen but do not appear as the baking time.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-4'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-5', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The museum offers three membership levels. The basic tier costs forty dollars a year and includes unlimited general admission. The family tier, at seventy-five dollars, adds free entry for two children and discounts in the gift shop. The patron tier, at two hundred dollars, includes everything in the family tier plus invitations to private exhibit previews."

According to the passage, which benefit is unique to the patron tier?', '["unlimited general admission","gift shop discounts","invitations to private previews","free entry for two children"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage says the patron tier ''includes everything in the family tier plus invitations to private exhibit previews,'' so the previews are the added benefit. Choice C is correct. Unlimited admission is part of the basic tier and shared upward, so Choice A is not unique. Gift shop discounts and free entry for two children both belong to the family tier, so Choices B and D are shared, not exclusive to patrons.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-5'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-6', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The storm caused damage across the county in three stages. First, heavy rain flooded low-lying roads on Tuesday night. Then, high winds on Wednesday morning knocked down power lines, leaving thousands without electricity. Finally, falling temperatures Wednesday night froze the standing water, making travel dangerous well into Thursday."

According to the passage, what happened on Wednesday morning?', '["Heavy rain flooded the roads.","High winds knocked down power lines.","Falling temperatures froze the water.","Travel returned to normal."]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states that ''high winds on Wednesday morning knocked down power lines.'' Choice B matches that detail. The flooding happened Tuesday night, so Choice A is the wrong stage. The freezing happened Wednesday night, so Choice C is also the wrong time. The passage says travel stayed dangerous into Thursday, so Choice D contradicts the text.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-6'),
  ('PC-B12-DR-7', 'PC', 'pc.detail-recall', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The grant came with strict conditions. The funds could be spent only on lab equipment, not on salaries or travel. Any purchase over five thousand dollars required written approval from the review board. Unspent money had to be returned at the end of the year, and a final report was due within sixty days of the project''s close."

According to the passage, what required written approval from the review board?', '["any spending on salaries","purchases over five thousand dollars","the final report","all travel expenses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage states that ''Any purchase over five thousand dollars required written approval from the review board.'' Choice B matches that condition. Salaries and travel were not allowed at all, so they could not be approved purchases, ruling out Choices A and D. The final report had a sixty-day deadline but no approval requirement, so Choice C confuses two separate rules.', true, 'verified', 'pc.detail-recall::PC-B12-DR-7'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-1', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Maria checked the sky one more time, zipped her jacket to the chin, and tucked the umbrella into her bag before stepping out the door. Dark clouds had been gathering all morning."

It can be inferred from the passage that Maria expects:', '["a sunny afternoon","rain","a snowstorm","a long vacation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maria zips up, packs an umbrella, and notes the ''dark clouds gathering,'' all signs she anticipates wet weather. Choice B follows from those clues. Choice A contradicts the dark clouds. Choice C jumps to snow, which the passage does not signal; an umbrella suits rain, not snow. Choice D about a vacation has no support in the brief, weather-focused scene.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-1'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-2', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"By the time the new manager arrived, the office had gone three years without a single all-staff meeting. Within her first month, she scheduled one for every Monday and asked each team to share what it was working on."

It can be inferred that the new manager values:', '["cutting costs","open communication among staff","longer working hours","reducing the size of the staff"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The manager replaces a three-year silence with weekly meetings and asks teams to share their work, which signals she wants people informed and talking. Choice B follows from those actions. Choice A about costs has no support; meetings are not framed as a budget move. Choice C reads hours into a scheduling change that says nothing about workday length. Choice D about cutting staff contradicts the inclusive, all-staff tone.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-2'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-3', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The trail was empty except for fresh tire tracks in the mud and a still-warm campfire ring at the clearing. A water bottle sat upright on a log, its cap off."

It can be inferred from the passage that:', '["no one had visited the trail in weeks","someone had been at the clearing very recently","the trail was permanently closed","a storm had just passed through"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fresh tracks, a ''still-warm'' fire, and an open water bottle left upright all point to a recent presence. Choice B follows from those clues. Choice A contradicts the freshness of the signs. Choice C about a closure has no support, since the evidence shows recent use. Choice D imports a storm the passage never mentions; the clues describe people, not weather.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-3'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-4', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"When the small bakery first opened, it sold out of bread by noon and turned away a line of customers each afternoon. The owner has just signed a lease on the empty shop next door and hired two more bakers."

It can be inferred that the owner is expanding because:', '["the bakery is losing money","demand has been greater than the bakery can meet","the original shop is being torn down","bread has become unpopular"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The bakery sells out daily and turns customers away, then leases more space and hires bakers, which signals growth driven by strong demand. Choice B follows from those facts. Choice A contradicts the picture of a thriving shop. Choice C invents a teardown the passage never mentions. Choice D reverses the evident popularity, since the bread sells out by noon.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-4'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-5', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"James reread the email twice, set his phone face down, and stared out the window for several minutes before finally typing a short reply. He had been hoping for a different answer."

It can be inferred from the passage that James:', '["was pleased with the email''s news","was disappointed by the email''s news","had not yet read the email","was writing the email to himself"]'::jsonb, 1, 'James pauses, sets the phone down, stares out the window, and ''had been hoping for a different answer,'' all signs the news let him down. Choice B follows from those cues. Choice A reverses the disappointment the last sentence states. Choice C contradicts the fact that he reread the email twice. Choice D misreads the situation, since he is replying to a message someone sent him.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-5'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-6', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee released its report on a Friday evening before a holiday weekend, with no press conference and no summary for reporters. The full document ran four hundred pages, and the most significant findings appeared in an unlabeled appendix near the back."

It can be inferred from the passage that the committee:', '["wanted the findings to attract as much attention as possible","preferred that the findings draw little notice","had no significant findings to report","was required by law to hold a press conference"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Releasing the report before a holiday weekend, skipping a press conference, and burying key findings in an ''unlabeled appendix'' are all moves that reduce visibility. Choice B follows from that pattern. Choice A reverses it, since these are not attention-seeking tactics. Choice C contradicts the mention of ''the most significant findings.'' Choice D invents a legal requirement the passage never states.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-6'),
  ('PC-B12-INF-7', 'PC', 'pc.inference', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The coach kept the rookie on the bench for the entire first half, even as the starters fell further behind. In the second half she sent him in, and within minutes he had scored twice. Afterward she told reporters only that the timing had to be right."

It can be inferred that the coach delayed playing the rookie because:', '["she did not think he was any good","she was waiting for a moment she judged best","the rookie had refused to play earlier","the game had already been won"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The coach benches the rookie, then plays him to immediate effect and says ''the timing had to be right,'' which signals a deliberate choice about when to use him. Choice B follows from that statement. Choice A is contradicted by his quick success once he played. Choice C invents a refusal the passage never mentions. Choice D contradicts the fact that the starters were falling behind.', true, 'verified', 'pc.inference::PC-B12-INF-7'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-1', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To make a paper boat, start with a rectangular sheet and fold it in half lengthwise. Open it, then fold the top two corners down to meet the center crease. Fold the bottom edges up on each side, and gently pull the sides outward until the boat takes shape. With a little practice, the whole process takes under a minute."

The author''s primary purpose in this passage is to:', '["argue that paper boats are better than toys","explain how to make a paper boat","describe the history of paper folding","warn readers about a difficult craft"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage gives ordered steps, ''start with,'' ''open it,'' ''fold,'' ''pull,'' which is the structure of instructions. Choice B names that how-to purpose. Choice A invents an argument comparing boats to toys the passage never makes. Choice C adds history the passage does not provide. Choice D misreads the tone, since the author calls the task quick and easy rather than difficult.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-1'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-2', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Volunteering at the animal shelter changed how I see my weekends. I used to fill Saturdays with errands and screens, but now I spend the morning walking dogs that have no one else to walk them. I come home tired and covered in fur, and I would not trade it for anything."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["resentful","grateful","indifferent","alarmed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author frames the change as positive, ending with ''I would not trade it for anything,'' which signals warmth and appreciation. Choice B names that grateful tone. Choice A reverses the feeling, since the author embraces the new routine rather than resenting it. Choice C ignores the strong personal investment described. Choice D imports alarm the passage never expresses.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-2'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-3', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Notice to residents: The water main on Oak Street will be shut off Tuesday from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m. for repairs. Please store enough water for drinking and cooking during that window. Service will resume automatically once work is complete, and discolored water for the first few minutes afterward is normal and safe."

The author''s primary purpose in this notice is to:', '["apologize for poor water quality","inform residents of a planned shutoff and how to prepare","argue that the water main should be replaced","advertise a new water service"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The notice states the shutoff window, tells residents to store water, and explains what to expect afterward, which is straightforward notification. Choice B captures that inform-and-prepare purpose. Choice A reads apology into a routine repair notice. Choice C invents an argument for replacement the passage never makes. Choice D treats the notice as an advertisement, but nothing is being sold.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-3'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-4', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Every city council seems to chase the same shiny project while the basics fall apart. We get a new fountain downtown, but the buses still run late and the side streets still flood after every storm. Maybe before we cut another ribbon, we could fix the things people actually use."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["frustrated","delighted","neutral","fearful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author contrasts ''shiny'' projects with neglected basics and closes with the pointed ''before we cut another ribbon, we could fix the things people actually use.'' That complaint signals frustration. Choice A names it. Choice B reverses the mood, since the author is unhappy, not pleased. Choice C ignores the clear criticism. Choice D names fear, but the passage expresses irritation about priorities, not dread.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-4'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-5', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The report describes the rollout as a success, yet it leaves out the two regions where the program was canceled within a month. The figures it does include come only from the pilot sites that volunteered, which are likely the best-prepared. A fuller picture would need data the report quietly sets aside."

The author''s primary purpose in this passage is to:', '["celebrate the program''s clear success","question whether the report gives a complete picture","explain how to design a pilot program","praise the regions that volunteered"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author notes the report ''leaves out'' canceled regions and relies on self-selected sites, concluding a fuller picture needs data the report ''quietly sets aside.'' Choice B names that critical purpose. Choice A states the very success claim the author challenges. Choice C reads a how-to guide into a critique. Choice D misreads the mention of volunteer sites, which the author treats as a source of bias, not praise.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-5'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-6', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The brochure promises that the supplement ''melts away fat while you sleep,'' with no diet or exercise required. It offers no studies, names no ingredients by amount, and points only to glowing testimonials from unnamed customers. Claims this dramatic, backed this thinly, deserve a careful second look."

The author''s tone toward the supplement''s claims is best described as:', '["trusting","skeptical","enthusiastic","indifferent"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The author lists what the brochure lacks, ''no studies,'' no named amounts, only ''unnamed customers,'' and urges ''a careful second look.'' That doubt grounded in missing evidence is skepticism. Choice B names it. Choice A reverses the stance, since the author plainly does not trust the claims. Choice C matches the brochure''s tone, not the author''s. Choice D ignores the active warning the author gives.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-6'),
  ('PC-B12-ATP-7', 'PC', 'pc.author-tone-purpose', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The data on the program''s results are mixed. Test scores rose modestly at four schools and fell slightly at two others, while attendance held steady throughout. The sample is small and the follow-up brief, so the early gains are worth noting without being mistaken for proof."

The author''s tone is best described as:', '["measured","outraged","dismissive","triumphant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The author reports gains and losses evenly and warns the early results are ''worth noting without being mistaken for proof.'' That balanced caution is a measured tone. Choice A names it. Choice B overshoots into anger the passage never shows. Choice C dismisses the findings, but the author keeps them in view as worth noting. Choice D claims victory the careful hedging explicitly avoids.', true, 'verified', 'pc.author-tone-purpose::PC-B12-ATP-7'),
  ('GS-B13-001', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'Which planet is closest to the Sun?', '["Venus","Earth","Mercury","Mars"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mercury is the innermost planet, orbiting nearest the Sun. Venus is the second planet, often confused for first because it is the brightest. Earth is third. Mars is fourth.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::planet-order'),
  ('GS-B13-002', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What is the largest planet in the solar system?', '["Jupiter","Saturn","Neptune","Earth"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Jupiter is the largest planet by both diameter and mass. Saturn is the second largest and is often guessed because of its prominent rings. Neptune is the most distant gas giant but much smaller. Earth is a small terrestrial planet.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::planet-sizes'),
  ('GS-B13-003', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'Which layer of the atmosphere contains most of the weather we experience?', '["Troposphere","Stratosphere","Mesosphere","Thermosphere"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The troposphere is the lowest layer, where almost all weather and clouds occur. The stratosphere holds the ozone layer and is above the weather. The mesosphere is where meteors burn up. The thermosphere is the high layer where auroras and the ISS are found.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::atmosphere-layers'),
  ('GS-B13-004', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What process in the water cycle changes liquid water into water vapor?', '["Condensation","Precipitation","Evaporation","Collection"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Evaporation is the change from liquid to gas, driven by heat such as sunlight. Condensation is the reverse, vapor turning back into liquid to form clouds. Precipitation is water falling as rain or snow. Collection is water gathering in oceans and lakes.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::water-cycle'),
  ('GS-B13-005', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'Which type of rock forms when magma or lava cools and hardens?', '["Igneous","Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Mineral"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Igneous rock forms from cooled molten rock (magma or lava). Sedimentary rock forms from compacted sediments. Metamorphic rock forms when existing rock is changed by heat and pressure. A mineral is a building block of rocks, not a rock type.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::rock-types'),
  ('GS-B13-006', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What causes the phases of the Moon?', '["Earth''s shadow on the Moon","The Moon changing size","The amount of sunlit Moon we see as it orbits Earth","Clouds covering the Moon"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Moon phases result from seeing different amounts of the Moon''s sunlit half as it orbits Earth. Earth''s shadow on the Moon causes a lunar eclipse, not the regular phases. The Moon does not change size. Clouds only block our local view, not the phase itself.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::moon-phases'),
  ('GS-B13-007', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'The theory that Earth''s outer shell is broken into large moving pieces is called:', '["Plate tectonics","Continental erosion","The rock cycle","The water cycle"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Plate tectonics describes the movement of large plates of Earth''s lithosphere. Erosion is the wearing away of land, not a theory of plate motion. The rock cycle describes how rocks change form. The water cycle describes the movement of water.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::plate-tectonics'),
  ('GS-B13-008', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'Which planet is known as the Red Planet?', '["Jupiter","Venus","Mercury","Mars"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Mars appears red because of iron oxide (rust) on its surface. Jupiter is the largest planet with banded clouds. Venus is covered in thick yellowish clouds. Mercury is a gray, cratered world.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::planet-features'),
  ('GS-B13-009', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 1, 'What is the name for a scientist who studies the weather?', '["Geologist","Meteorologist","Astronomer","Biologist"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A meteorologist studies weather and the atmosphere. A geologist studies rocks and the solid Earth. An astronomer studies space and celestial objects. A biologist studies living things.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::science-disciplines'),
  ('GS-B13-010', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'A geologist finds a rock made of layers of sand and shell fragments cemented together. This rock is most likely:', '["Igneous","Sedimentary","Metamorphic","Volcanic"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Layered, cemented sediments such as sand and shells are the signature of sedimentary rock, which forms from deposited and compacted particles. Igneous and volcanic rock form from cooled molten material, not layered sediments. Metamorphic rock forms when existing rock is reshaped by heat and pressure, which would distort the layers rather than preserve sand and shells.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::rock-identify'),
  ('GS-B13-011', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'It is summer in the Southern Hemisphere when the Southern Hemisphere is:', '["Tilted toward the Sun","Closest to the Sun in distance","Tilted away from the Sun","Receiving no sunlight"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Seasons are caused by Earth''s axial tilt; a hemisphere has summer when it is tilted toward the Sun and receives more direct sunlight. Distance from the Sun does not cause the seasons, since Earth is actually slightly closer to the Sun during Northern winter. Tilting away from the Sun causes winter. A hemisphere always receives some sunlight except near the poles.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::seasons'),
  ('GS-B13-012', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'The gravitational pull of the Moon on Earth''s oceans is mainly responsible for:', '["Ocean currents","Tides","Waves","Hurricanes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The Moon''s gravity (with help from the Sun) creates the regular rise and fall of sea level called tides. Ocean currents are driven mostly by wind and temperature differences. Waves are produced chiefly by wind blowing across the surface. Hurricanes are storms powered by warm ocean water and air.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::tides'),
  ('GS-B13-013', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Why does the Sun appear much larger and brighter than other stars?', '["It is the largest star in the universe","It is much closer to Earth than other stars","It is the hottest star that exists","It is the only star with planets"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The Sun looks large and bright simply because it is far closer to Earth than any other star. The Sun is an average-sized star, not the largest in the universe. Many stars are hotter than the Sun. Other stars are now known to have planets, so that is not unique to the Sun.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::sun-stars'),
  ('GS-B13-014', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Which gas makes up the largest portion of Earth''s atmosphere?', '["Oxygen","Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen","Hydrogen"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Nitrogen makes up about 78 percent of the atmosphere, the largest share. Oxygen is second at about 21 percent and is often mistakenly chosen because it is the gas we breathe. Carbon dioxide is less than one percent. Hydrogen is only a trace gas in the atmosphere.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::atmosphere-composition'),
  ('GS-B13-015', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Earthquakes and volcanoes occur most often:', '["In the center of large continents","Along the boundaries between tectonic plates","Only at the equator","Only in the deep ocean"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Most earthquakes and volcanoes occur along plate boundaries, where plates collide, separate, or slide past one another. Continental interiors are far from active boundaries and are relatively stable. The equator is a line of latitude, unrelated to plate edges. Plate boundaries exist on both land and ocean, not only in the deep sea.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::plate-boundaries'),
  ('GS-B13-016', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Clouds form when water vapor rises, cools, and undergoes which process?', '["Evaporation","Precipitation","Melting","Condensation"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Clouds form by condensation, when rising water vapor cools enough to turn back into tiny liquid droplets. Evaporation is the opposite process, turning liquid into vapor. Precipitation is water falling from clouds after droplets grow heavy. Melting is a solid turning to liquid, not vapor turning to liquid.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::cloud-formation'),
  ('GS-B13-017', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'A full moon occurs when:', '["The Moon is between Earth and the Sun","Earth is between the Sun and the Moon","The Moon is closest to Earth","The Sun is directly behind the Moon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A full moon happens when Earth is positioned between the Sun and the Moon, so we see the Moon''s fully sunlit side. When the Moon is between Earth and the Sun, we get a new moon (dark side facing us). The Moon''s distance from Earth affects apparent size, not the phase. The Sun being behind the Moon from our view corresponds to a new moon, not a full moon.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::moon-phases'),
  ('GS-B13-018', 'GS', 'gs.earth-space-science', 2, 'Over many years, flowing water in a river slowly wears away and carries off rock and soil. This process is called:', '["Deposition","Erosion","Condensation","Crystallization"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Erosion is the wearing away and transport of rock and soil by agents such as water, wind, or ice. Deposition is the opposite, the dropping of sediment in a new location. Condensation is a phase change of water vapor to liquid. Crystallization is the forming of crystals as minerals solidify.', true, 'verified', 'gs.earth-space-science::erosion'),
  ('GS-B13-019', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which part of the cell controls its activities and contains DNA?', '["Mitochondria","Nucleus","Cell membrane","Ribosome"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The nucleus contains the cell''s DNA and directs its activities. Mitochondria produce energy and are sometimes confused as the control center. The cell membrane controls what enters and leaves the cell. Ribosomes build proteins.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::cell-organelles'),
  ('GS-B13-020', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which organelle is known as the powerhouse of the cell?', '["Mitochondria","Nucleus","Vacuole","Cell wall"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Mitochondria are called the powerhouse because they generate most of the cell''s energy (ATP). The nucleus stores genetic information. The vacuole stores water and waste. The cell wall provides structure in plant cells.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::cell-organelles'),
  ('GS-B13-021', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which body system is responsible for pumping blood throughout the body?', '["Respiratory system","Digestive system","Circulatory system","Nervous system"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The circulatory system, including the heart and blood vessels, pumps and transports blood. The respiratory system handles breathing and gas exchange. The digestive system breaks down food. The nervous system carries signals and controls the body.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::body-systems'),
  ('GS-B13-022', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'During photosynthesis, plants use sunlight, water, and carbon dioxide to produce:', '["Glucose and oxygen","Salt and water","Carbon dioxide and nitrogen","Protein and fat"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Photosynthesis converts carbon dioxide and water into glucose (sugar for energy) and oxygen, using sunlight. Salt and water are not products of photosynthesis. Carbon dioxide is a reactant taken in, not produced. Proteins and fats are not made directly by photosynthesis.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::photosynthesis'),
  ('GS-B13-023', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'In a food chain, organisms that make their own food using sunlight are called:', '["Consumers","Producers","Decomposers","Predators"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Producers, such as green plants, make their own food through photosynthesis. Consumers eat other organisms for energy. Decomposers break down dead material. Predators are a type of consumer that hunts other animals.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::food-chains'),
  ('GS-B13-024', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which part of the human body produces insulin to regulate blood sugar?', '["Liver","Kidney","Stomach","Pancreas"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The pancreas produces insulin, the hormone that controls blood sugar levels. The liver stores sugar as glycogen but does not make insulin. The kidneys filter waste from blood. The stomach digests food but does not produce insulin.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::organs-function'),
  ('GS-B13-025', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'The basic unit of heredity that carries traits from parents to offspring is the:', '["Gene","Cell","Tissue","Organ"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A gene is the basic unit of heredity, a segment of DNA that codes for a trait. A cell is the basic unit of life, not specifically of heredity. A tissue is a group of similar cells. An organ is a structure made of tissues.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::genetics-basics'),
  ('GS-B13-026', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which of these is found in plant cells but NOT in animal cells?', '["Nucleus","Cell membrane","Cell wall","Mitochondria"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The cell wall is a rigid outer layer found in plant cells but not animal cells. The nucleus is found in both plant and animal cells. The cell membrane is present in both. Mitochondria are also found in both plant and animal cells.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::plant-animal-cells'),
  ('GS-B13-027', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 1, 'Which body system includes the brain, spinal cord, and nerves?', '["Endocrine system","Nervous system","Muscular system","Skeletal system"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The nervous system is made up of the brain, spinal cord, and nerves, which carry signals throughout the body. The endocrine system uses hormones, not nerves, to send signals. The muscular system produces movement. The skeletal system provides the body''s framework of bones.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::body-systems'),
  ('GS-B13-028', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'In pea plants, the allele for tall (T) is dominant over short (t). A plant with the genotype Tt will be:', '["Short","Medium height","Unable to grow","Tall"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Because T (tall) is dominant, a Tt plant shows the tall trait, since one dominant allele is enough to express it. The plant is not short, because the recessive t is masked when a dominant T is present. Dominant and recessive alleles do not blend into a medium height. A Tt plant grows normally.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::dominant-recessive'),
  ('GS-B13-029', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Cellular respiration in your cells uses oxygen and glucose to release energy and produce:', '["Sunlight and water","Carbon dioxide and water","Glucose and oxygen","Nitrogen and salt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cellular respiration breaks down glucose with oxygen to release energy, producing carbon dioxide and water as byproducts. Sunlight is an input for photosynthesis, not a product of respiration. Glucose and oxygen are the reactants used up, not the products. Nitrogen and salt are not involved in respiration.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::respiration'),
  ('GS-B13-030', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'In a food chain, a hawk eats a snake that ate a mouse that ate grass. The hawk is best described as a:', '["Producer","Primary consumer","Decomposer","Consumer"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The hawk eats other animals, so it is a consumer (specifically a top consumer in this chain). A producer makes its own food, which describes the grass, not the hawk. A primary consumer eats producers directly, which fits the mouse, not the hawk. A decomposer breaks down dead matter, which the hawk does not do.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::food-chains'),
  ('GS-B13-031', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Which gas do humans take in from the air and pass into the blood in the lungs?', '["Carbon dioxide","Nitrogen","Oxygen","Hydrogen"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In the lungs, oxygen from inhaled air passes into the blood to be carried to cells. Carbon dioxide moves the other way, from blood into the lungs to be exhaled. Nitrogen is the most abundant air gas but is not absorbed for use this way. Hydrogen is only a trace gas and is not taken in for respiration.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::gas-exchange'),
  ('GS-B13-032', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'A scientist classifies a living thing as a mammal. Which feature would support this classification?', '["It has scales and lays eggs in water","It has feathers and a beak","It has hair and feeds milk to its young","It breathes only through gills"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mammals are defined by having hair or fur and feeding their young with milk from mammary glands. Scales and laying eggs in water describe many fish and amphibians, not mammals. Feathers and a beak describe birds. Breathing only through gills describes fish, while mammals breathe with lungs.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::classification'),
  ('GS-B13-033', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Red blood cells carry oxygen because they contain a protein called:', '["Insulin","Collagen","Chlorophyll","Hemoglobin"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Hemoglobin is the iron-containing protein in red blood cells that binds and carries oxygen. Insulin is a hormone that regulates blood sugar, not oxygen transport. Collagen is a structural protein in skin and connective tissue. Chlorophyll is the light-absorbing pigment in plants, not in human blood.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::blood'),
  ('GS-B13-034', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'Two brown-eyed parents each carry one allele for blue eyes. If brown (B) is dominant and blue (b) is recessive, a child can have blue eyes only with the genotype:', '["BB","Bb","bb","Bb or BB"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Blue eyes are recessive, so the trait appears only when both alleles are recessive, giving the genotype bb. BB is homozygous dominant and produces brown eyes. Bb is heterozygous and still shows the dominant brown because one B masks the b. The combined choice Bb or BB lists only brown-eyed genotypes.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::dominant-recessive'),
  ('GS-B13-035', 'GS', 'gs.life-science', 2, 'What is the green pigment in plant leaves that absorbs sunlight for photosynthesis?', '["Hemoglobin","Keratin","Chlorophyll","Melanin"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Chlorophyll is the green pigment in plant leaves that captures light energy used in photosynthesis. Hemoglobin carries oxygen in animal blood. Keratin is a structural protein in hair and nails. Melanin is the pigment that colors skin and hair.', true, 'verified', 'gs.life-science::photosynthesis'),
  ('GS-B13-036', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'What are the three common states of matter?', '["Solid, liquid, gas","Hot, warm, cold","Hard, soft, liquid","Atom, molecule, compound"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The three common states of matter are solid, liquid, and gas. Hot, warm, and cold describe temperature, not states of matter. Hard and soft describe texture, not states. Atom, molecule, and compound describe units of matter, not its physical states.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::states-of-matter'),
  ('GS-B13-037', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'What is the center of an atom called?', '["Electron","Nucleus","Proton","Orbit"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The nucleus is the dense center of an atom, containing protons and neutrons. Electrons move around the nucleus and are not the center. A proton is one type of particle inside the nucleus, not the nucleus itself. An orbit is the path electrons travel, not a part of the atom''s center.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::atomic-structure'),
  ('GS-B13-038', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which subatomic particle carries a negative charge?', '["Proton","Neutron","Electron","Nucleus"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The electron carries a negative charge. The proton carries a positive charge. The neutron has no charge. The nucleus, made of protons and neutrons, has an overall positive charge, not negative.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::atomic-charge'),
  ('GS-B13-039', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Water (H2O) is an example of a:', '["Element","Compound","Mixture","Single atom"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Water is a compound because it is made of two different elements (hydrogen and oxygen) chemically bonded in a fixed ratio. An element contains only one kind of atom, which water does not. A mixture can be separated physically and has no fixed ratio, unlike a compound. A single atom is just one particle, not a substance like water.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::elements-compounds-mixtures'),
  ('GS-B13-040', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'On the pH scale, a substance with a pH of 7 is considered:', '["Acidic","Basic","Neutral","Salty"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A pH of 7 is neutral, like pure water. Values below 7 are acidic. Values above 7 are basic (alkaline). Saltiness is a taste, not a pH value.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::acids-bases'),
  ('GS-B13-041', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Which of the following is a chemical change?', '["Ice melting into water","Tearing a sheet of paper","Wood burning into ash","Dissolving sugar in water"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Burning wood is a chemical change because it forms new substances such as ash, smoke, and gases. Melting ice is a physical change, since it is still water. Tearing paper changes shape only, a physical change. Dissolving sugar is a physical change because the sugar can be recovered by evaporating the water.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::chemical-physical-change'),
  ('GS-B13-042', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'The change of a liquid into a solid is called:', '["Melting","Evaporation","Condensation","Freezing"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Freezing is the change from liquid to solid, as when water turns to ice. Melting is the reverse, solid to liquid. Evaporation is liquid to gas. Condensation is gas to liquid.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::phase-changes'),
  ('GS-B13-043', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Density is best described as the amount of:', '["Mass in a given volume","Heat in an object","Force on an object","Speed of an object"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Density is mass per unit volume, calculated as mass divided by volume. Heat is a form of energy, not density. Force is a push or pull, not a measure of how packed matter is. Speed describes motion, unrelated to density.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::density'),
  ('GS-B13-044', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 1, 'Salad dressing made of oil and vinegar that can be separated by settling is an example of a:', '["Compound","Element","Mixture","Pure substance"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Oil and vinegar form a mixture because the substances are combined but not chemically bonded and can separate physically. A compound has elements chemically bonded in a fixed ratio, which oil and vinegar are not. An element is a single type of atom. A pure substance has a single, fixed composition, unlike this blend.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::elements-compounds-mixtures'),
  ('GS-B13-045', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'An object has a mass of 60 grams and a volume of 20 cubic centimeters. What is its density?', '["3 g/cm3","40 g/cm3","1200 g/cm3","0.33 g/cm3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Density equals mass divided by volume: 60 g divided by 20 cm3 equals 3 g/cm3. The value 40 comes from subtracting volume from mass, which is the wrong operation. The value 1200 comes from multiplying mass by volume. The value 0.33 comes from dividing volume by mass, inverting the formula.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::density-calc'),
  ('GS-B13-046', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'A liquid with a pH of 2 compared to a liquid with a pH of 6 is:', '["More basic","More acidic","More neutral","The same acidity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Lower pH values are more acidic, so a pH of 2 is more acidic than a pH of 6. It is not more basic, because basic substances have pH values above 7. It is not more neutral, since neutral is pH 7 and pH 2 is far from it. The two are not the same acidity because their pH values differ.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::acids-bases'),
  ('GS-B13-047', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'When water boils and turns into steam, what happens to its particles?', '["They move faster and spread far apart","They stop moving completely","They lock into a fixed pattern","They lose all their energy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Boiling adds heat energy, so particles move faster and spread far apart as the liquid becomes a gas. Particles never stop moving completely except at absolute zero. Locking into a fixed pattern describes freezing into a solid, the opposite change. Gaining heat means particles gain energy, not lose it.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::phase-changes-particles'),
  ('GS-B13-048', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'Which of these is a physical change rather than a chemical change?', '["Iron rusting","Milk turning sour","Crushing a can","Baking a cake"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Crushing a can changes only its shape, with no new substance formed, so it is a physical change. Iron rusting forms a new compound (iron oxide), a chemical change. Milk turning sour produces new acidic substances, a chemical change. Baking a cake forms new substances through chemical reactions.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::chemical-physical-change'),
  ('GS-B13-049', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'The atomic number of an element tells you the number of:', '["Neutrons in the nucleus","Protons in the nucleus","Electron shells","Total particles in the atom"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The atomic number equals the number of protons in the nucleus, which defines the element. It is not the number of neutrons, which can vary among isotopes. It is not the number of electron shells. It is not the total particle count, which would also include neutrons and electrons.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::atomic-number'),
  ('GS-B13-050', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'A solid object is placed in water and it floats. This tells you the object is:', '["More dense than water","Less dense than water","The same density as water","Made of metal"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An object floats when it is less dense than the liquid it is placed in, so this object is less dense than water. If it were more dense than water, it would sink. If it had the same density, it would hover suspended rather than float at the top. The material alone, such as metal, does not determine floating; some metal shapes float and many metals sink.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::density'),
  ('GS-B13-051', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'A substance turns red litmus paper blue. The substance is most likely a(n):', '["Acid","Base","Neutral salt","Pure water"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Bases turn red litmus paper blue, so the substance is most likely a base. Acids do the opposite, turning blue litmus paper red. A neutral salt solution generally does not change litmus color. Pure water is neutral and would not turn red litmus blue.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::acids-bases-litmus'),
  ('GS-B13-052', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Newton''s First Law of Motion states that an object at rest will:', '["Always start moving on its own","Stay at rest unless acted on by a force","Speed up over time","Turn into energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Newton''s First Law (inertia) says an object at rest stays at rest unless an outside force acts on it. Objects do not start moving on their own without a force. They do not spontaneously speed up. Matter at rest does not turn into energy under this law.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::newtons-first-law'),
  ('GS-B13-053', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Energy that an object has because of its motion is called:', '["Kinetic energy","Potential energy","Chemical energy","Stored energy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Kinetic energy is the energy of motion. Potential energy is stored energy due to position, not motion. Chemical energy is stored in bonds, such as in fuel or food. Stored energy is another way to describe potential energy, the opposite of motion energy.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::energy-types'),
  ('GS-B13-054', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'The transfer of heat through direct contact between two objects is called:', '["Convection","Radiation","Conduction","Insulation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Conduction is heat transfer through direct contact, such as a metal spoon heating in hot soup. Convection transfers heat through moving fluids like air or water. Radiation transfers heat as waves through space, like the Sun''s warmth. Insulation slows heat transfer rather than performing it.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::heat-transfer-define'),
  ('GS-B13-055', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Newton''s Third Law of Motion is often summarized as:', '["Objects always fall down","Force equals mass times acceleration","Energy cannot be created or destroyed","For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Newton''s Third Law states that for every action force there is an equal and opposite reaction force. Objects falling down describes gravity, not the Third Law. Force equals mass times acceleration is Newton''s Second Law. Energy cannot be created or destroyed is the law of conservation of energy, not a Newton law of motion.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::newtons-third-law'),
  ('GS-B13-056', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Speed is best defined as:', '["The distance traveled in a given time","The force pushing an object","The mass of a moving object","The direction of motion only"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Speed is how much distance is covered in a given amount of time, such as miles per hour. Force is a push or pull, not speed. Mass is the amount of matter in an object, unrelated to how fast it moves. Direction alone is not speed; speed combined with direction is velocity.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::speed-define'),
  ('GS-B13-057', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Which of the following is an example of potential energy?', '["A car driving down the road","A ball held high above the ground","Wind blowing through trees","A spinning fan"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A ball held high has gravitational potential energy stored because of its position. A car driving has kinetic energy because it is moving. Wind blowing is moving air, which is kinetic energy. A spinning fan is in motion, also kinetic energy.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::energy-types'),
  ('GS-B13-058', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 1, 'Acceleration refers to the rate at which an object''s ____ changes.', '["Mass","Temperature","Velocity","Weight"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity over time, including speeding up, slowing down, or changing direction. Mass is the amount of matter and does not change with acceleration. Temperature is a measure of heat, unrelated to acceleration. Weight is the force of gravity on mass, not what acceleration measures.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::acceleration'),
  ('GS-B13-059', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'A car travels 150 miles in 3 hours. What is its average speed?', '["50 miles per hour","450 miles per hour","153 miles per hour","30 miles per hour"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Average speed equals distance divided by time: 150 miles divided by 3 hours equals 50 miles per hour. The value 450 comes from multiplying distance by time. The value 153 comes from adding distance and time. The value 30 does not match dividing 150 by 3 and reflects an arithmetic error.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::speed-calc'),
  ('GS-B13-060', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'Newton''s Second Law states that force equals mass times acceleration. A 10 kg object accelerating at 5 m/s2 experiences a force of:', '["2 newtons","15 newtons","50 newtons","0.5 newtons"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Force equals mass times acceleration: 10 kg times 5 m/s2 equals 50 newtons. The value 2 comes from dividing mass by acceleration. The value 15 comes from adding mass and acceleration. The value 0.5 comes from dividing acceleration by mass, inverting the relationship.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::force-calc'),
  ('GS-B13-061', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'Heat from the Sun reaches Earth through empty space mainly by:', '["Conduction","Convection","Radiation","Insulation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Radiation transfers heat as electromagnetic waves and can travel through the vacuum of space, which is how the Sun''s heat reaches Earth. Conduction requires direct contact between materials, impossible across empty space. Convection requires a moving fluid like air or water, also absent in space. Insulation blocks heat transfer rather than carrying it.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::heat-transfer-apply'),
  ('GS-B13-062', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'When you push a heavy box and it does not move, you are still applying a force. According to Newton''s First Law, the box stays still because:', '["Your force is balanced by friction and other forces","Forces do not affect heavy objects","The box has no mass","Heavy objects cannot be moved by any force"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The box stays at rest because your push is balanced by opposing forces such as friction, giving a net force of zero. Forces do affect heavy objects; they just require more force to move. The box clearly has mass, since it is heavy. Heavy objects can be moved with enough unbalanced force, so they are not unmovable.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::newtons-first-law'),
  ('GS-B13-063', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'Two cars travel the same distance. Car A takes 2 hours and Car B takes 4 hours. Which statement is true?', '["Car B is faster","They have the same speed","Car A has more mass","Car A is faster"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Covering the same distance in less time means a higher speed, so Car A (2 hours) is faster than Car B (4 hours). Car B is slower because it took more time for the same distance. Their speeds are not equal because their times differ. Travel time tells us nothing about mass.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::speed-compare'),
  ('GS-B13-064', 'GS', 'gs.physics-mechanics', 2, 'A ball is held at the top of a hill and then released to roll down. As it rolls down, its energy mainly changes from:', '["Kinetic energy to potential energy","Potential energy to kinetic energy","Chemical energy to heat energy","Heat energy to light energy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At the top the ball has stored potential energy due to its height; as it rolls down, that converts into kinetic energy of motion. The reverse, kinetic to potential, happens when something rises, not falls. Chemical energy is not the main energy stored by simply lifting a ball. Heat and light are not the primary energies involved in a ball rolling downhill.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physics-mechanics::energy-conversion'),
  ('GS-B13-065', 'GS', 'gs.physical-science', 2, 'Equal volumes of two liquids are weighed. Liquid X has more mass than Liquid Y. Which liquid has the greater density?', '["Liquid X, because more mass in the same volume means greater density","Liquid Y, because it is lighter","They have equal density because the volumes are equal","Density cannot be compared from this information"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Density is mass divided by volume, so with equal volumes the liquid with more mass (Liquid X) has the greater density. Liquid Y is less dense, not more, because it has less mass for the same volume. Equal volume does not make density equal when the masses differ. Density can be compared here precisely because the volumes are the same and only mass differs.', true, 'verified', 'gs.physical-science::density-compare'),
  ('EI-B14-001', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a series circuit, the components are connected so that the current has how many paths to flow through?', '["One path","Two paths","Three paths","As many paths as there are components"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A series circuit provides a single path for current, so the same current flows through every component in turn. Two paths and three paths describe parallel arrangements, where current splits among branches. The choice of one path per component also describes a parallel circuit, not a series circuit. A series circuit has exactly one path.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-current-path'),
  ('EI-B14-002', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a parallel circuit, each component is connected across the same two points, so each branch receives what?', '["A smaller current than the source","Half the source voltage","No voltage until the next branch closes","The same voltage as the source"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In a parallel circuit every branch connects across the same two nodes, so each branch sees the full source voltage. Branch current can differ between branches, but that is current, not voltage. Half the source voltage describes a series voltage divider, not parallel branches. Branches are independent, so one does not have to close before another gets voltage. Each parallel branch receives the same voltage as the source.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::parallel-voltage-same'),
  ('EI-B14-003', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'A circuit in which the path is complete and current can flow is called what?', '["An open circuit","A short circuit","A broken circuit","A closed circuit"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A closed circuit has a complete, unbroken path, so current flows. An open circuit has a break in the path and stops current. A short circuit is an unintended low-resistance path that bypasses the load; it allows current but is a fault, not the normal complete circuit described. A broken circuit is just another name for an open circuit. The complete, current-carrying circuit is a closed circuit.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::open-closed-define'),
  ('EI-B14-004', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'What is an open circuit?', '["A circuit with a break that stops current flow","A circuit with a complete path for current","A circuit with two or more current paths","A circuit with an unintended low-resistance path"]'::jsonb, 0, 'An open circuit has a break in the path, so current cannot flow. A complete path describes a closed circuit. Two or more paths describes a parallel circuit. An unintended low-resistance path describes a short circuit. An open circuit is defined by the break that stops current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::open-closed-define'),
  ('EI-B14-005', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'A short circuit is best described as which of the following?', '["An unintended low-resistance path that lets current bypass the load","A break that stops all current","A circuit that uses less wire than normal","A circuit with the switch turned off"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A short circuit is an unintended low-resistance path that lets current bypass the intended load, causing a large current. A break that stops current describes an open circuit. A short has nothing to do with using less wire. A switch turned off creates an open circuit, not a short. A short is the unintended low-resistance path.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::short-define'),
  ('EI-B14-006', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'Two light bulbs are wired in series. If one bulb burns out, what happens to the other bulb?', '["It glows brighter","It is unaffected","It glows dimmer but stays on","It also goes out"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In a series circuit there is only one path, so a burned-out bulb breaks that path and the other bulb also goes out. It cannot glow brighter or stay on because no current can flow. Staying lit (unaffected or dimmer) would only happen in a parallel circuit. In series, both bulbs go out.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::bulb-fails-series'),
  ('EI-B14-007', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'Two light bulbs are wired in parallel. If one bulb burns out, what happens to the other bulb?', '["It also goes out","It glows much brighter","The whole circuit shorts out","It stays lit"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In a parallel circuit each bulb has its own path, so one bulb burning out does not break the path of the other; it stays lit. It would only go out if they were in series. The remaining bulb does not change brightness much because it still sees the same source voltage. A burned-out bulb is an open, not a short. The other bulb stays lit.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::bulb-fails-parallel'),
  ('EI-B14-008', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'In a simple series circuit, the current measured at any point in the circuit is which of the following?', '["The same everywhere","Largest near the battery","Different in each component","Zero at the last component"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Because a series circuit has only one path, the same current flows through every part of it, so current is the same everywhere. It does not get larger near the battery or shrink along the way. Current would differ between branches only in a parallel circuit. It is not zero at the last component. Series current is the same everywhere.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-current-same'),
  ('EI-B14-009', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 1, 'Christmas lights where every bulb goes dark when a single bulb fails are most likely wired in what configuration?', '["Parallel","Series","Short circuit","Open by design"]'::jsonb, 1, 'If one failed bulb darkens the whole string, the bulbs share a single path, which is a series circuit. In a parallel string, one failure would leave the rest lit. A short circuit is a wiring fault, not a normal lighting layout. Open by design is not a real circuit type. The all-or-nothing behavior indicates a series circuit.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::bulb-fails-series'),
  ('EI-B14-010', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'Two resistors are connected in series across a battery. Compared with the current through the first resistor, the current through the second resistor is which of the following?', '["Twice as large","Half as large","The same","Zero"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Series components share one path, so the same current flows through both resistors. It is not doubled or halved between them because current is not used up. It is not zero, since the circuit is complete. The current through the second resistor is the same as through the first.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-current-same'),
  ('EI-B14-011', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'A circuit has three lamps connected so that switching off one lamp leaves the other two lit at full brightness. This circuit is wired in which way?', '["Series","A single loop","A short circuit","Parallel"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Because turning off one lamp leaves the others at full brightness, each lamp must have its own path across the source, which is a parallel circuit. In a series single loop, opening one lamp would break the whole circuit and the others would go dark. A short circuit is a fault, not a lamp arrangement. The independent operation indicates a parallel circuit.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::parallel-independent'),
  ('EI-B14-012', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'Household outlets are wired in parallel mainly so that which of the following is true?', '["Total resistance increases with each device added","Current is the same in every branch","Devices must all be turned on together","Each device gets the same full voltage and can run independently"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Parallel wiring gives every outlet the same full line voltage and lets each device run independently. Adding parallel branches decreases total resistance, not increases it. Branch currents can differ, so current is not the same in every branch. Devices do not have to be on together, which is the whole advantage. Parallel wiring gives full voltage and independent operation.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::parallel-independent'),
  ('EI-B14-013', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'When identical resistors are added in series, the total resistance of the circuit does what?', '["Decreases","Stays the same","Increases","Drops to zero"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In a series circuit, resistances add, so adding more resistors increases the total resistance. Total resistance decreases only when resistors are added in parallel. It does not stay the same or fall to zero. Adding series resistors increases total resistance.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-vs-parallel-resistance'),
  ('EI-B14-014', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'When identical resistors are added in parallel, the total resistance of the circuit does what?', '["Increases","Stays exactly the same","Decreases","Becomes infinite"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Adding parallel branches gives current more paths, so the total resistance decreases. Resistance increases only when resistors are added in series. It does not stay the same. Infinite resistance describes an open circuit, the opposite of adding paths. Adding parallel resistors decreases total resistance.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-vs-parallel-resistance'),
  ('EI-B14-015', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'A wire accidentally connects the two battery terminals directly with almost no resistance in between. This condition is called what, and it produces what?', '["An open circuit, producing no current","A short circuit, producing a very large current","A parallel circuit, producing equal branch voltages","A series circuit, producing reduced current"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A direct, near-zero-resistance connection across the source is a short circuit, and by Ohm''s law a tiny resistance produces a very large current. An open circuit is a break with no current, the opposite of this. This is a fault, not a normal parallel or series arrangement. The condition is a short circuit producing a very large current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::short-define'),
  ('EI-B14-016', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'In a parallel circuit, how does the total current drawn from the source compare with the current in any single branch?', '["It equals the current in one branch","It is always less than any branch current","It is zero","It is the sum of all the branch currents"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The current leaving the source splits among the branches, so the total source current equals the sum of all the branch currents. It is not equal to just one branch, since several branches draw current. It cannot be less than a single branch when several branches draw from the same source. It is not zero in a working circuit. Total current is the sum of the branch currents.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::parallel-current-sums'),
  ('EI-B14-017', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'A switch is placed in the single loop of a series circuit. When the switch is opened, what happens to the circuit?', '["Current increases","The circuit becomes open and current stops","Voltage doubles","The circuit becomes a short"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Opening the switch breaks the single path, making the circuit open so current stops. Breaking the path cannot increase current or double voltage. An open is the opposite of a short, which is an unintended low-resistance path. Opening the switch creates an open circuit and stops the current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::open-switch'),
  ('EI-B14-018', 'EI', 'ei.circuit-types', 2, 'Two resistors in series are connected to a 12-volt battery. The voltage measured across the first resistor is 5 volts. What is the voltage across the second resistor?', '["5 volts","7 volts","12 volts","17 volts"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In a series circuit the source voltage divides among the components and the drops add up to the source: 12 - 5 = 7 volts across the second resistor. The choice 5 volts wrongly assumes both drops are equal. The choice 12 volts ignores the first drop, as if the second resistor got the whole source. The choice 17 volts adds instead of subtracting. The second resistor drops 7 volts.', true, 'verified', 'ei.circuit-types::series-voltage-divides'),
  ('EI-B14-019', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'What is the main function of a resistor in a circuit?', '["To store electric charge","To allow current in only one direction","To increase voltage","To limit or control the flow of current"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A resistor opposes current, so it limits or controls how much current flows. Storing charge is the job of a capacitor. Allowing current in only one direction is the job of a diode. Increasing voltage is done by a transformer or step-up circuit. A resistor limits current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::resistor-function'),
  ('EI-B14-020', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'What is the main function of a capacitor?', '["To store electrical energy in an electric field","To convert AC to DC","To amplify a signal","To resist the flow of current"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A capacitor stores electrical energy in an electric field between its plates. Converting AC to DC is the job of a diode in a rectifier. Amplifying a signal is the job of a transistor. Resisting current is the job of a resistor. A capacitor stores energy in an electric field.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::capacitor-function'),
  ('EI-B14-021', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A diode is a component that does what?', '["Allows current to flow in only one direction","Stores charge between two plates","Steps voltage up or down","Splits current into branches"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A diode allows current to flow in only one direction, acting like a one-way valve. Storing charge between plates describes a capacitor. Stepping voltage up or down is done by a transformer. Splitting current into branches is what a parallel junction does, not a single component. A diode permits one-way current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::diode-function'),
  ('EI-B14-022', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A transistor is commonly used to do which of the following?', '["Store energy in a magnetic field","Convert AC to DC only","Provide a fixed resistance","Switch or amplify electrical signals"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A transistor is used to switch or amplify electrical signals, which makes it a building block of electronics. Storing energy in a magnetic field describes an inductor. Converting AC to DC is done by a diode rectifier. Providing a fixed resistance is the job of a resistor. A transistor switches or amplifies.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::transistor-function'),
  ('EI-B14-023', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'What is the purpose of a fuse in an electrical circuit?', '["To store charge for later use","To step the voltage up","To smooth out a signal","To protect the circuit by breaking it if current gets too high"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A fuse protects a circuit by melting and breaking the path when current exceeds a safe level. Storing charge is the job of a capacitor. Stepping voltage up is the job of a transformer. Smoothing a signal is done by capacitors or filters. A fuse protects against excess current by breaking the circuit.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::fuse-function'),
  ('EI-B14-024', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A transformer is a device that primarily does what?', '["Steps AC voltage up or down","Allows current in one direction only","Stores energy in an electric field","Converts light into electricity"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A transformer uses two coils to step an AC voltage up or down. Allowing current in one direction is the job of a diode. Storing energy in an electric field describes a capacitor. Converting light into electricity is what a photocell or solar cell does. A transformer steps AC voltage up or down.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::transformer-function'),
  ('EI-B14-025', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'What does LED stand for?', '["Low Energy Device","Light Emitting Diode","Linear Electric Detector","Load Energy Director"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LED stands for Light Emitting Diode, a diode that gives off light when current flows through it. The other options are invented phrases that do not match the standard term. LED means Light Emitting Diode.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::led-define'),
  ('EI-B14-026', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'What is the function of a switch in a circuit?', '["To store electrical charge","To increase current automatically","To convert AC to DC","To open or close the circuit path"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A switch opens or closes the circuit path to turn current on or off. Storing charge is the job of a capacitor. A switch does not increase current on its own. Converting AC to DC is done by a diode. A switch opens or closes the path.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::switch-function'),
  ('EI-B14-027', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 1, 'A battery is a source that supplies which of the following to a circuit?', '["Magnetic force only","Electrical energy through chemical reactions","Resistance to limit current","Light when current flows"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A battery converts stored chemical energy into electrical energy to drive current through a circuit. It does not supply magnetic force as its purpose. Limiting current is the job of a resistor. Emitting light when current flows describes an LED. A battery supplies electrical energy from chemical reactions.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::battery-function'),
  ('EI-B14-028', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'An inductor stores energy in which form?', '["An electric field between plates","A magnetic field around a coil","Chemical bonds","Heat in a resistive element"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An inductor is a coil that stores energy in the magnetic field created around it when current flows. Storing energy in an electric field between plates describes a capacitor. Chemical bonds describe a battery. Heat in a resistive element describes a resistor dissipating power, not storing it. An inductor stores energy in a magnetic field.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::inductor-function'),
  ('EI-B14-029', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'Which component would you use to convert alternating current (AC) into direct current (DC)?', '["Resistor","Capacitor","Diode","Switch"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A diode passes current in only one direction, so it can rectify AC into DC. A resistor only limits current and cannot change AC to DC. A capacitor can smooth DC but does not perform the conversion. A switch only opens or closes the path. A diode converts AC to DC by rectification.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::diode-function'),
  ('EI-B14-030', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'A transformer has more turns of wire on its secondary coil than on its primary coil. This transformer will do what to the voltage?', '["Step it up","Step it down","Leave it unchanged","Convert it to DC"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A transformer''s output voltage rises with more secondary turns, so more secondary turns than primary turns steps the voltage up. Fewer secondary turns would step it down. Equal turns would leave it unchanged. A transformer works only with AC and does not convert to DC. More secondary turns steps the voltage up.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::transformer-turns'),
  ('EI-B14-031', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'A device that protects a circuit from excess current and can be reset by flipping a switch instead of being replaced is called what?', '["A fuse","A capacitor","A resistor","A circuit breaker"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A circuit breaker trips to stop excess current and can be reset by flipping it back on. A fuse also stops excess current but melts and must be replaced, not reset. A capacitor stores charge and offers no overcurrent protection. A resistor only limits current and does not trip. A resettable overcurrent protector is a circuit breaker.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::breaker-vs-fuse'),
  ('EI-B14-032', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'Which component, when correctly biased, lets current flow forward but blocks it in the reverse direction?', '["Capacitor","Diode","Resistor","Inductor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A diode conducts when forward biased and blocks current when reverse biased, acting as a one-way valve. A capacitor blocks steady DC but passes changing signals in both directions; it is not a one-way valve. A resistor passes current both ways. An inductor passes current both ways while opposing changes. The one-way component is a diode.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::diode-bias'),
  ('EI-B14-033', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'A schematic symbol drawn as a zigzag line (or a plain rectangle in newer drawings) represents which component?', '["Capacitor","Resistor","Battery","Inductor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The zigzag line, or a rectangle in newer standards, is the schematic symbol for a resistor. A capacitor is drawn as two parallel lines. A battery is drawn as alternating long and short parallel lines. An inductor is drawn as a series of loops or coils. The zigzag or rectangle is a resistor.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::symbol-resistor'),
  ('EI-B14-034', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'A schematic symbol drawn as a series of coils or loops in the wire represents which component?', '["Resistor","Inductor","Capacitor","Diode"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A series of coils or loops is the schematic symbol for an inductor, reflecting its coil of wire. A resistor is a zigzag or rectangle. A capacitor is two parallel lines. A diode is a triangle pointing into a bar. The coiled symbol is an inductor.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::symbol-inductor'),
  ('EI-B14-035', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'On a schematic, a battery is usually shown using which of the following?', '["A triangle touching a straight bar","Alternating long and short parallel lines","A zigzag line","Two equal-length parallel plates"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A battery symbol uses alternating long and short parallel lines, with the long line as the positive terminal. A triangle touching a bar is a diode. A zigzag line is a resistor. Two equal-length parallel plates form a capacitor. A battery is shown with alternating long and short lines.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::symbol-battery'),
  ('EI-B14-036', 'EI', 'ei.components-devices', 2, 'Which component would you choose to amplify a weak audio signal into a stronger one?', '["Transistor","Fuse","Capacitor","Resistor"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A transistor can amplify, using a small input signal to control a larger output, so it boosts a weak audio signal. A fuse only protects against overcurrent. A capacitor stores charge and can couple signals but does not provide gain. A resistor only limits current. Amplification is done by a transistor.', true, 'verified', 'ei.components-devices::transistor-function'),
  ('EI-B14-037', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which of the following materials is the best conductor of electricity?', '["Rubber","Copper","Glass","Dry wood"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Copper is a metal with many free electrons, making it an excellent conductor, which is why it is used in most wiring. Rubber, glass, and dry wood are insulators that strongly resist current. The best conductor listed is copper.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::pick-conductor'),
  ('EI-B14-038', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which material is commonly used as an insulator around electrical wires?', '["Copper","Aluminum","Silver","Rubber"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Rubber resists the flow of current, so it is used as insulation around wires to keep electricity contained and safe. Copper, aluminum, and silver are all metals and good conductors, which is why they form the wire itself rather than the insulation. The insulator is rubber.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::pick-insulator'),
  ('EI-B14-039', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Metals are good conductors of electricity mainly because they have what?', '["Very tightly bound electrons","No electrons at all","Many free electrons that can move","A hard, shiny surface"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Metals conduct well because they have many free electrons that move easily and carry current. Tightly bound electrons describe insulators, where charges cannot move. All materials have electrons, so having none is incorrect. A shiny surface is unrelated to electrical conduction. Metals conduct because of their free electrons.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::why-conduct'),
  ('EI-B14-040', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which of the following is the best example of an electrical insulator?', '["Gold","Aluminum","Glass","Copper"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Glass holds its electrons tightly and resists current, so it is a good insulator. Gold, aluminum, and copper are all metals and good conductors. The insulator is glass.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::pick-insulator'),
  ('EI-B14-041', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'A material whose ability to conduct electricity falls between that of a conductor and an insulator is called a what?', '["Superconductor","Semiconductor","Resistor","Dielectric"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A semiconductor, such as silicon, conducts more than an insulator but less than a metal, putting it between the two. A superconductor conducts with essentially no resistance, beyond a normal conductor. A resistor is a component, not a material class. A dielectric is an insulating material used in capacitors. The in-between material is a semiconductor.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::semiconductor-define'),
  ('EI-B14-042', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'The purpose of grounding an electrical system is mainly to do what?', '["Increase the voltage","Store extra energy","Provide a safe path for stray current to the earth","Speed up the current"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Grounding gives stray or fault current a safe, low-resistance path to the earth, protecting people and equipment. It does not raise voltage or store energy. It does not speed up current. Grounding provides a safe path to earth for stray current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::grounding-purpose'),
  ('EI-B14-043', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 1, 'Which common material is the most widely used conductor in household electrical wiring?', '["Plastic","Copper","Rubber","Wood"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Copper is the most widely used wiring conductor because it conducts well and is reasonably affordable. Plastic, rubber, and wood are insulators and do not carry current. The common wiring conductor is copper.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::pick-conductor'),
  ('EI-B14-044', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Silicon is the base material for most modern transistors and chips because it is what kind of material?', '["A perfect conductor","A semiconductor","A perfect insulator","A magnetic metal"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Silicon is a semiconductor, so its conductivity can be controlled, which is exactly what transistors and chips need. A perfect conductor would carry current uncontrollably. A perfect insulator would block current entirely. Silicon is not a magnetic metal. Silicon is a semiconductor.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::semiconductor-define'),
  ('EI-B14-045', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'In the American Wire Gauge (AWG) system, as the gauge number gets larger, the wire diameter does what?', '["Gets larger","Gets smaller","Stays the same","Becomes a better conductor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'In AWG, a larger gauge number means a thinner wire, so the diameter gets smaller. It does not get larger or stay the same. A thinner wire actually carries less current safely, so it does not become a better conductor. Larger AWG numbers mean smaller wire diameter.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::awg-gauge'),
  ('EI-B14-046', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Which wire can safely carry more current: a thick 10-gauge wire or a thin 18-gauge wire?', '["The 18-gauge wire","Both carry the same current","Neither can carry current","The 10-gauge wire"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In AWG a smaller number is a thicker wire, and thicker wire carries more current, so the 10-gauge wire carries more than the 18-gauge. The 18-gauge wire is thinner and carries less. They are different sizes, so they do not carry the same. Both are conductors and can carry current. The 10-gauge wire carries more current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::awg-gauge'),
  ('EI-B14-047', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Why is rubber or plastic used to coat electrical cords rather than leaving the metal bare?', '["To make the wire conduct better","To insulate the wire and prevent shocks or shorts","To increase the voltage","To make the wire heavier"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rubber and plastic are insulators, so coating the wire prevents accidental shocks and short circuits. They do not improve conduction; only the metal inside conducts. They do not change the voltage. Adding weight is not the goal. The coating insulates the wire for safety.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::why-insulate'),
  ('EI-B14-048', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'A three-prong plug includes a grounding prong. What is the main job of that grounding prong?', '["To deliver more power to the device","To store charge for the device","To carry fault current safely away if a wire touches the metal case","To convert AC to DC"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The grounding prong gives fault current a safe path to ground if a hot wire contacts the device''s metal case, preventing shock. It does not deliver more power or store charge. It does not convert AC to DC. The grounding prong safely carries away fault current.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::grounding-purpose'),
  ('EI-B14-049', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Of the following metals, which is generally the best electrical conductor?', '["Iron","Silver","Lead","Tin"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Silver has the lowest resistance of common metals, making it the best electrical conductor of the choices listed. Iron, lead, and tin all conduct but have noticeably higher resistance than silver. The best conductor here is silver.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::best-conductor-metal'),
  ('EI-B14-050', 'EI', 'ei.conductors-insulators', 2, 'Dry wood is generally considered an insulator, but wet wood can conduct electricity. Why does adding water change this?', '["Water has dissolved ions that can carry current","Water turns wood into a metal","Water removes all electrons from the wood","Water lowers the wood''s temperature"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ordinary water contains dissolved ions that can carry charge, so wetting the wood gives current a path it lacks when dry. Water does not turn wood into a metal or strip out its electrons. Temperature change is not the reason it conducts. Wet wood conducts because water carries dissolved ions.', true, 'verified', 'ei.conductors-insulators::why-conduct'),
  ('EI-B14-051', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'Ohm''s law states the relationship among voltage, current, and resistance. Which equation is correct?', '["V = I / R","V = R / I","V = I + R","V = I x R"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Ohm''s law is V = I x R, where voltage equals current times resistance. V = I / R and V = R / I divide instead of multiply, which is incorrect. V = I + R adds two quantities with different units, which is meaningless. The correct form is V = I x R.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::ohms-law-form'),
  ('EI-B14-052', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'Electrical power in a simple circuit can be found using which formula?', '["P = V / I","P = V + I","P = V - I","P = V x I"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Power equals voltage times current: P = V x I. Dividing voltage by current (P = V / I) is incorrect. Adding or subtracting voltage and current mixes different units and is meaningless. The correct power formula is P = V x I.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::power-form'),
  ('EI-B14-053', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'A 12-volt source drives a current of 3 amperes through a resistor. What is the voltage already given, and what does Ohm''s law let you find using R = V / I?', '["2 ohms","4 ohms","6 ohms","36 ohms"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Using R = V / I, divide voltage by current: 12 / 3 = 4 ohms. The choice 2 ohms divides incorrectly. The choice 6 ohms comes from using 12 / 2. The choice 36 ohms multiplies 12 x 3 instead of dividing. The resistance is 4 ohms.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::ohms-law-solve-R'),
  ('EI-B14-054', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'A 9-volt battery is connected across a 3-ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law (I = V / R), how much current flows?', '["3 amperes","6 amperes","12 amperes","27 amperes"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Using I = V / R, divide voltage by resistance: 9 / 3 = 3 amperes. The choice 6 amperes divides incorrectly. The choice 12 amperes adds 9 + 3. The choice 27 amperes multiplies 9 x 3 instead of dividing. The current is 3 amperes.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::ohms-law-solve-I'),
  ('EI-B14-055', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'A current of 2 amperes flows through a 5-ohm resistor. Using Ohm''s law (V = I x R), what is the voltage across the resistor?', '["2.5 volts","7 volts","10 volts","20 volts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Using V = I x R, multiply current by resistance: 2 x 5 = 10 volts. The choice 2.5 volts divides 5 / 2 instead of multiplying. The choice 7 volts adds 2 + 5. The choice 20 volts doubles the correct answer. The voltage is 10 volts.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::ohms-law-solve-V'),
  ('EI-B14-056', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 1, 'How many milliamperes (mA) are in 1 ampere?', '["10 mA","100 mA","1,000 mA","1,000,000 mA"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The prefix milli means one-thousandth, so 1 ampere equals 1,000 milliamperes. The choices 10 and 100 mA are too small by factors of 100 and 10. The choice 1,000,000 mA would equal 1,000 amperes, confusing milli with micro. One ampere is 1,000 milliamperes.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::unit-prefix'),
  ('EI-B14-057', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'A device uses 4 amperes at 120 volts. Using P = V x I, what is its power consumption?', '["30 watts","124 watts","480 watts","480 amperes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Using P = V x I, multiply: 120 x 4 = 480 watts. The choice 30 watts divides 120 / 4 instead of multiplying. The choice 124 watts adds 120 + 4. The value 480 amperes uses the wrong unit; power is measured in watts. The power is 480 watts.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::power-solve'),
  ('EI-B14-058', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'Two resistors, 3 ohms and 5 ohms, are connected in series. What is their total resistance?', '["8 ohms","1.875 ohms","15 ohms","2 ohms"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Series resistances add: 3 + 5 = 8 ohms. The choice 1.875 ohms is the parallel result, which does not apply to series. The choice 15 ohms multiplies 3 x 5 instead of adding. The choice 2 ohms subtracts 5 - 3. The series total is 8 ohms.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::series-resistance-add'),
  ('EI-B14-059', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'Two equal 10-ohm resistors are connected in parallel. What is their total resistance?', '["5 ohms","10 ohms","20 ohms","100 ohms"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Two equal resistors in parallel give half of one resistor''s value: 10 / 2 = 5 ohms. The choice 10 ohms ignores the parallel effect. The choice 20 ohms adds them as if in series. The choice 100 ohms multiplies 10 x 10. The parallel total is 5 ohms.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::parallel-resistance'),
  ('EI-B14-060', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'A resistor carries 2 amperes and has a resistance of 4 ohms. Using P = I squared x R, what power does it dissipate?', '["8 watts","16 watts","32 watts","64 watts"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Using P = I squared x R: 2 squared is 4, then 4 x 4 = 16 watts. The choice 8 watts forgets to square the current, doing 2 x 4. The choice 32 watts doubles the correct answer. The choice 64 watts squares the whole product incorrectly. The power dissipated is 16 watts.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::power-i2r'),
  ('EI-B14-061', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'A 2-kilohm (kΩ) resistor is the same as how many ohms?', '["20 ohms","200 ohms","2,000 ohms","200,000 ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The prefix kilo means one thousand, so 2 kilohms equals 2 x 1,000 = 2,000 ohms. The choices 20 and 200 ohms are too small by factors of 100 and 10. The choice 200,000 ohms confuses kilo with a larger prefix. Two kilohms is 2,000 ohms.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::unit-prefix'),
  ('EI-B14-062', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'A 24-volt source is connected across a 6-ohm resistor. Using P = V squared / R, what is the power dissipated?', '["4 watts","48 watts","96 watts","144 watts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Using P = V squared / R: 24 squared is 576, then 576 / 6 = 96 watts. The choice 4 watts divides 24 / 6 without squaring. The choice 48 watts comes from 24 x 6 / 3, an incorrect setup. The choice 144 watts multiplies 24 x 6. The power dissipated is 96 watts.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::power-v2r'),
  ('EI-B14-063', 'EI', 'ei.ohms-law-power', 2, 'A circuit draws 0.5 ampere from a 12-volt battery. Using Ohm''s law (R = V / I), what is the circuit''s resistance?', '["6 ohms","12 ohms","24 ohms","0.5 ohm"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Using R = V / I, divide voltage by current: 12 / 0.5 = 24 ohms. The choice 6 ohms multiplies 12 x 0.5 instead of dividing. The choice 12 ohms ignores the current. The choice 0.5 ohm just repeats the current value. The resistance is 24 ohms.', true, 'verified', 'ei.ohms-law-power::ohms-law-solve-R'),
  ('AS-B15-001', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which type of screwdriver fits a screw with a single straight slot across its head?', '["Phillips","Allen","Torx","Flathead"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A flathead (slotted) screwdriver has a single flat blade that fits the straight slot of a slotted screw. A Phillips screwdriver has a cross- or plus-shaped tip for cross-recess screws. Torx has a six-point star tip. An Allen (hex) key fits hexagonal socket screws. Only the flathead matches a single straight slot.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::screwdriver-types'),
  ('AS-B15-002', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which hand tool is specifically designed to apply a measured, exact amount of tightening force to a fastener?', '["Pipe wrench","Open-end wrench","Torque wrench","Box-end wrench"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A torque wrench measures and limits the rotational force (torque) applied so a bolt is tightened to an exact specification. An open-end wrench grips two flats of a fastener but cannot measure force. A pipe wrench grips round pipe and applies no measured torque. A box-end wrench surrounds the fastener fully but also does not measure force. Only the torque wrench applies a specified amount of force.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::torque-wrench'),
  ('AS-B15-003', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which pliers have long, thin, tapered jaws for gripping small objects in tight spaces?', '["Channel-lock pliers","Slip-joint pliers","Needle-nose pliers","Locking pliers"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Needle-nose pliers have long, narrow, tapered jaws ideal for reaching into tight spaces and holding small wires or parts. Channel-lock (tongue-and-groove) pliers have wide, adjustable jaws for large objects. Slip-joint pliers have a movable pivot for two jaw widths but blunt jaws. Locking pliers clamp and lock onto a part. Only needle-nose pliers have the long tapered jaws described.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::pliers-types'),
  ('AS-B15-004', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which hammer has one flat striking face and one rounded face used for shaping metal and striking punches?', '["Ball-peen hammer","Claw hammer","Sledgehammer","Rubber mallet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A ball-peen hammer has a flat face for striking and a rounded (ball) peen for shaping metal and setting rivets, making it standard for metalwork. A claw hammer has a flat face and a curved claw for pulling nails. A sledgehammer is a heavy two-faced hammer for demolition. A rubber mallet has a soft head to avoid marring surfaces. Only the ball-peen has a rounded peen for shaping metal.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::hammer-types'),
  ('AS-B15-005', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'An Allen wrench (hex key) is used to drive fasteners that have what kind of recess?', '["A six-sided (hexagonal) recess","A cross-shaped recess","A single straight slot","A square recess"]'::jsonb, 0, 'An Allen wrench, or hex key, is an L-shaped tool with six flat sides that fits a hexagonal socket recess in the fastener head. A cross-shaped recess is driven by a Phillips screwdriver. A single straight slot is driven by a flathead. A square recess is driven by a Robertson driver. Only a hexagonal recess matches the Allen wrench.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::allen-wrench'),
  ('AS-B15-006', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which tool is used to cut internal threads inside a drilled hole?', '["Tap","Die","Reamer","File"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A tap cuts internal threads inside a hole so a bolt or screw can be threaded into it. A die cuts external threads onto a rod or bolt. A reamer enlarges and smooths a hole to an exact size but does not cut threads. A file removes material to smooth or shape surfaces. Only a tap cuts internal threads.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::taps-dies'),
  ('AS-B15-007', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which measuring tool uses a thin blade of a known thickness to measure the gap between two parts?', '["Tape measure","Micrometer","Feeler gauge","Caliper"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A feeler gauge is a set of thin metal blades, each a known thickness, that are slipped into a gap to measure its width, such as a spark plug or valve clearance. A micrometer measures the outside thickness of an object very precisely. A tape measure measures longer lengths. A caliper measures inside, outside, and depth dimensions. Only the feeler gauge is built to measure a gap with set-thickness blades.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::feeler-gauge'),
  ('AS-B15-008', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'Which wrench completely surrounds a nut or bolt head on all six points for the strongest grip?', '["Open-end wrench","Pipe wrench","Box-end wrench","Adjustable wrench"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A box-end wrench fully encloses the fastener and contacts all six points of a hex head, giving the best grip with the least chance of slipping or rounding. An open-end wrench grips only two flats and can slip. A pipe wrench is for round pipe, not hex fasteners. An adjustable wrench grips two flats with movable jaws that can slip. Only the box-end wrench surrounds the head completely.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::wrench-types'),
  ('AS-B15-009', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 1, 'A cold chisel is a striking tool used mainly to do what?', '["Tighten bolts","Measure thread pitch","Cut and shape metal","Drill round holes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A cold chisel is a hardened steel tool struck with a hammer to cut, chip, or shape cold metal such as removing rivet heads or cutting bar stock. Measuring thread pitch is done with a thread pitch gauge. Tightening bolts is done with a wrench. Drilling round holes is done with a drill bit. Only cutting and shaping metal describes the cold chisel.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::chisel'),
  ('AS-B15-010', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A mechanic must loosen a bolt that is recessed deep inside a tube where only a straight-down approach is possible. Which tool is best?', '["Socket with an extension and ratchet","Open-end wrench","Channel-lock pliers","Box-end wrench"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A socket on an extension bar driven by a ratchet reaches straight down into a recessed area and turns the bolt fully enclosed, which is exactly what a deep, narrow space requires. An open-end wrench needs side clearance to swing and grips only two flats. Channel-lock pliers would round the bolt and cannot reach deep. A box-end wrench needs swing room and cannot reach down a tube. The socket-and-extension setup is designed for this access.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::socket-access'),
  ('AS-B15-011', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A technician needs to measure the diameter of a bolt shaft to the nearest thousandth of an inch. Which tool gives that precision?', '["Outside micrometer","Tape measure","Yardstick","Carpenter''s square"]'::jsonb, 0, 'An outside micrometer measures small outside dimensions to within a thousandth of an inch using a precise threaded spindle, ideal for a bolt shaft diameter. A tape measure reads only to about a sixteenth of an inch. A yardstick is even less precise. A carpenter''s square checks right angles, not diameters. Only the micrometer offers thousandth-inch precision.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::micrometer'),
  ('AS-B15-012', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A bolt head is rounded off and a wrench will no longer grip it. Which tool is the best choice to remove it?', '["Phillips screwdriver","Open-end wrench","Locking pliers (vise-grips)","Feeler gauge"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Locking pliers clamp down hard and lock onto a damaged, rounded fastener, biting into what remains so it can be turned out. An open-end wrench needs clean flats and will keep slipping on a rounded head. A Phillips screwdriver drives cross-recess screws, not a rounded bolt. A feeler gauge only measures gaps. Locking pliers are the right tool for a stripped fastener.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::locking-pliers'),
  ('AS-B15-013', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A worker needs to cut new external threads onto the end of a metal rod. Which tool does the job?', '["Die","Tap","Hacksaw","Center punch"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A die cuts external (male) threads onto the outside of a rod or bolt blank. A tap cuts internal threads inside a hole, the opposite job. A hacksaw cuts a rod to length but cannot make threads. A center punch marks a starting dimple for drilling. Only a die produces external threads.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::taps-dies'),
  ('AS-B15-014', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'Before drilling a hole in flat steel, a machinist wants to keep the drill bit from wandering off the mark. Which tool should be used first?', '["Torque wrench","Cold chisel","Center punch","File"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A center punch is struck to make a small dimple at the mark, giving the drill bit a starting point so it does not slide across the surface. A cold chisel cuts metal, not a precise starting dimple. A torque wrench applies measured force to fasteners. A file smooths surfaces. Only the center punch makes the locating dimple for drilling.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::center-punch'),
  ('AS-B15-015', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A mechanic must hold two pieces of glued wood firmly together while the adhesive sets. Which tool is best?', '["C-clamp","Pry bar","Ratchet","Hacksaw"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A C-clamp tightens a screw to apply steady pressure and hold parts together while glue or weld sets. A pry bar applies leverage to separate or lift, the opposite action. A ratchet turns sockets on fasteners. A hacksaw cuts material. Only the C-clamp holds parts together under pressure.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::clamps'),
  ('AS-B15-016', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A technician needs to make a long, straight cut through a sheet of plywood. Which saw is best suited?', '["Circular saw","Hacksaw","Coping saw","Keyhole saw"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A circular saw uses a large spinning blade to make fast, long, straight cuts through plywood and lumber. A hacksaw has a fine blade for cutting metal, not large wood panels. A coping saw cuts tight curves in thin wood. A keyhole saw cuts small openings in tight spots. Only the circular saw is built for long straight cuts in plywood.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::saw-selection'),
  ('AS-B15-017', 'AS', 'as.hand-tools', 2, 'A worker must smooth and round a rough metal edge after cutting. Which tool is designed for this?', '["File","Wood chisel","Tap","Soldering iron"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A file has rows of hardened teeth that shave off small amounts of metal to smooth and shape a rough edge. A wood chisel is for cutting wood, not finishing metal edges. A tap cuts internal threads. A soldering iron melts solder to join parts, not remove metal. Only the file smooths and shapes the metal edge.', true, 'verified', 'as.hand-tools::file-use'),
  ('AS-B15-018', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'During an oil change, what component is normally replaced along with the oil?', '["Brake pad","Spark plug","Oil filter","Serpentine belt"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The oil filter is replaced with the oil because it traps contaminants and becomes clogged over time. A spark plug is part of the ignition system and is changed on its own schedule. A brake pad is a braking component, unrelated to oil changes. A serpentine belt drives accessories and is replaced when worn. Only the oil filter is routinely changed with the oil.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::oil-change'),
  ('AS-B15-019', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'Rotating tires means doing what?', '["Moving tires to different positions on the vehicle","Balancing each tire on a machine","Adding air to each tire","Replacing the valve stems"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Tire rotation moves tires from one position to another (such as front to back) so they wear more evenly and last longer. Balancing adds weights to correct vibration but is a separate service. Adding air sets tire pressure, not rotation. Replacing valve stems is its own repair. Only moving tires between positions describes a rotation.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::tire-rotation'),
  ('AS-B15-020', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'The gap on a spark plug is measured and set using which tool?', '["Feeler or gap gauge","Torque wrench","Tire pressure gauge","Compression tester"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A spark plug gap is the small space between the center and ground electrodes, set precisely with a feeler or gap gauge. A torque wrench tightens the plug to spec but does not measure the gap. A tire pressure gauge reads air pressure in tires. A compression tester checks cylinder pressure. Only a feeler or gap gauge sets the spark plug gap.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::spark-plug-gap'),
  ('AS-B15-021', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'Which fluid should be checked using the engine''s dipstick?', '["Refrigerant","Window washer fluid","Engine oil","Tire sealant"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The dipstick is pulled out, wiped, reinserted, and read to check the engine oil level and condition. Window washer fluid is checked at its own reservoir, which has no dipstick. Refrigerant is measured with gauges on the air-conditioning system. Tire sealant is not a checked fluid. Only engine oil is measured with the dipstick.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::fluid-checks'),
  ('AS-B15-022', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'When jump-starting a dead battery, which cable color is connected to the positive terminal?', '["Black","Green","Red","White"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The red jumper cable connects to the positive (+) terminal of both batteries. Black is the negative cable, connected to the negative terminal or an unpainted ground point. Green and white are not standard jumper cable colors. Only red is the positive cable.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::battery-service'),
  ('AS-B15-023', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 1, 'In a typical disc brake system, what part squeezes against the rotor to slow the wheel?', '["Tie rods","Spark plugs","Brake pads","Lug nuts"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Brake pads are pressed against the spinning rotor by the caliper, and the resulting friction slows the wheel. Spark plugs ignite the fuel mixture and have nothing to do with braking. Tie rods are steering parts. Lug nuts hold the wheel onto the hub. Only the brake pads create the friction that slows the rotor.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::brake-service'),
  ('AS-B15-024', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A car''s engine overheats and the temperature gauge climbs into the red. Which of these is a likely cause to check first?', '["Low engine coolant","A worn brake pad","A loose gas cap","A burned-out headlight"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Low coolant reduces the cooling system''s ability to carry heat away from the engine, so it is a leading cause of overheating and the first thing to check. A worn brake pad affects braking, not engine temperature. A loose gas cap may trigger an emissions light but not overheating. A burned-out headlight is an electrical issue unrelated to engine heat. Low coolant is the relevant cause.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::overheat-diagnosis'),
  ('AS-B15-025', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A driver hears a squealing noise from the front wheels that goes away when the brakes are pressed. What does this most likely indicate?', '["The brake pads are worn and need replacement","The transmission needs fluid","The tires are overinflated","The battery is low"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Many brake pads have a wear indicator that squeals when the pad material is thin; the noise often changes or stops as the brakes are applied, signaling the pads need replacement. Transmission fluid affects shifting, not a wheel squeal. Overinflated tires cause a rougher ride, not a brake squeal. A low battery affects starting and electronics. Worn brake pads best explain the squeal.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::brake-symptom'),
  ('AS-B15-026', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'An engine cranks but will not start, and there is no spark at the plugs. Which system should be checked first?', '["Ignition system","Cooling system","Exhaust system","Suspension system"]'::jsonb, 0, 'No spark points to the ignition system, which produces and delivers the spark needed for combustion, so it is the first system to check. The cooling system controls engine temperature, not spark. The exhaust system carries away burned gases. The suspension system handles ride and handling. The ignition system is responsible for spark.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::no-start-diagnosis'),
  ('AS-B15-027', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'A serpentine belt that drives the alternator and water pump is cracked and frayed. What is the correct action?', '["Replace the belt before it breaks","Add belt dressing and ignore it","Tighten the lug nuts","Top off the brake fluid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A cracked, frayed serpentine belt is failing and should be replaced before it snaps and shuts down the alternator, water pump, and other accessories. Belt dressing only masks noise and does not fix a worn belt. Tightening lug nuts addresses the wheels, not the belt. Topping off brake fluid is unrelated to the belt. Replacing the worn belt is the correct repair.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::belt-replacement'),
  ('AS-B15-028', 'AS', 'as.maintenance-repair', 2, 'Before removing a wheel to service the brakes, when should the lug nuts be loosened?', '["While the vehicle''s weight is still on the tire","After the wheel is fully off the ground","Only after the brake job is finished","They should never be loosened by hand"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Lug nuts should be broken loose while the tire still rests on the ground because the ground keeps the wheel from spinning, letting you apply force safely. If the wheel is already lifted, it spins freely and can rock the vehicle off the jack. Waiting until after the job makes no sense, since the wheel must come off first. Lug nuts are routinely loosened with a lug wrench. Loosening while weight is on the tire is correct.', true, 'verified', 'as.maintenance-repair::wheel-removal'),
  ('AS-B15-029', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'Which piece of personal protective equipment protects the eyes from flying debris while grinding?', '["Steel-toe boots","Work gloves","Safety glasses","Ear plugs"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Safety glasses (or goggles) shield the eyes from sparks and flying particles produced while grinding. Work gloves protect the hands but not the eyes. Steel-toe boots protect the feet from falling objects. Ear plugs protect hearing from loud noise. Only safety glasses protect the eyes from debris.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::eye-ppe'),
  ('AS-B15-030', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'After raising a vehicle with a jack, what must be placed under it before anyone works underneath?', '["Wheel chocks only","Jack stands","A floor mat","More jacks of the same type"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Jack stands are rigid supports placed under the vehicle to hold it safely once it is raised, because a hydraulic jack alone can leak down or fail. Wheel chocks block the wheels from rolling but do not support a raised vehicle. A floor mat offers no structural support. Relying only on jacks is unsafe because a jack can fail. Jack stands are required for working underneath.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::jack-stands'),
  ('AS-B15-031', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'Which class of fire extinguisher is intended for electrical fires?', '["Class A","Class B","Class C","Class D"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A Class C extinguisher is rated for fires in energized electrical equipment, using an agent that does not conduct electricity. Class A is for ordinary combustibles like wood and paper. Class B is for flammable liquids such as gasoline and oil. Class D is for combustible metals. Only Class C is for electrical fires.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::fire-classes'),
  ('AS-B15-032', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'Why should an engine never be run inside a closed garage without ventilation?', '["It uses too much electricity","The engine will run too cold","The exhaust contains deadly carbon monoxide","The tires will lose air"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Engine exhaust contains carbon monoxide, a colorless, odorless gas that can be deadly when it builds up in an enclosed space, so ventilation is essential. Running an engine warms it, it does not run too cold. An engine burns fuel, not building electricity. Tire pressure is not affected by running the engine indoors. The carbon monoxide hazard is the reason.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::ventilation'),
  ('AS-B15-033', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'Flammable liquids such as gasoline should be stored in what?', '["An open bucket","An approved, sealed safety container","A glass jar near a heater","A cardboard box"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Flammable liquids must be kept in an approved, sealed safety container designed to contain vapors and resist ignition. An open bucket lets vapors escape and can ignite easily. A glass jar near a heater is dangerous because heat and a fragile container invite fire. A cardboard box cannot hold liquid or contain vapor. Only an approved safety container is correct.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::flammables'),
  ('AS-B15-034', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'What does an SDS (Safety Data Sheet) provide information about?', '["The price of a part","The horsepower of an engine","The hazards and safe handling of a chemical","A vehicle''s fuel economy"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A Safety Data Sheet lists a chemical''s hazards, safe handling, storage, first-aid, and emergency information. Engine horsepower is found in vehicle specifications, not an SDS. Part prices come from a catalog or invoice. Fuel economy is a vehicle rating. Only chemical hazard and handling information comes from an SDS.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::sds'),
  ('AS-B15-035', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'Which PPE protects your hearing from loud shop equipment like air tools and grinders?', '["A respirator","Ear muffs or ear plugs","Safety glasses","A face shield"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Ear muffs or ear plugs block harmful noise and protect hearing around loud equipment. A respirator protects the lungs from dust and fumes. Safety glasses protect the eyes. A face shield protects the face from flying debris and splashes. Only ear protection guards hearing.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::hearing-ppe'),
  ('AS-B15-036', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'When lifting a heavy object from the floor, what is the correct technique?', '["Bend at the waist and lift with the back","Bend the knees and lift with the legs","Twist the body while lifting","Hold the object far from your body"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Proper lifting means bending the knees and using the strong leg muscles while keeping the back straight, which protects the spine. Bending at the waist and lifting with the back strains and can injure it. Twisting while lifting risks back injury. Holding a load far from the body increases strain. Lifting with the legs is the safe technique.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::lifting'),
  ('AS-B15-037', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 1, 'What is the purpose of a machine guard on a bench grinder or saw?', '["To make the tool quieter","To keep the operator away from moving parts","To increase the tool''s speed","To store extra blades"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A machine guard is a barrier that keeps the operator''s hands and clothing away from rotating wheels, blades, or belts to prevent injury. It is not designed to reduce noise. It does not increase speed. It is not a storage compartment. Protecting the operator from moving parts is its purpose.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::machine-guarding'),
  ('AS-B15-038', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A small gasoline fire starts in a drip pan under a car. Which fire extinguisher class should be used?', '["Class A","Class B","Class K","No extinguisher; pour water on it"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gasoline is a flammable liquid, so a Class B extinguisher is the correct choice. Class A is for ordinary solids like wood and paper, not liquids. Class K is for cooking-oil and grease fires in kitchens. Pouring water on burning gasoline spreads the fuel and the fire. Class B is the right choice for a gasoline fire.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::extinguisher-selection'),
  ('AS-B15-039', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A worker is about to repair a machine that could start unexpectedly. Which safety procedure prevents accidental start-up during the repair?', '["Wheel balancing","Tire rotation","Lockout/tagout","Oil change"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Lockout/tagout shuts off and locks the energy source, then tags it, so the machine cannot be powered on while someone is working on it. Tire rotation, wheel balancing, and oil changes are maintenance tasks that do nothing to prevent unexpected start-up. Only lockout/tagout controls the energy source during a repair.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::lockout-tagout'),
  ('AS-B15-040', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A mechanic will be spraying paint in an enclosed booth with strong fumes. Which PPE is most important to add?', '["A back brace","Steel-toe boots","Ear plugs","A respirator"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A respirator filters harmful paint fumes and vapors so they are not breathed into the lungs, which is the main hazard when spraying paint. Steel-toe boots protect the feet from impacts, not fumes. Ear plugs protect hearing. A back brace supports the back during lifting. A respirator addresses the breathing hazard.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::respirator'),
  ('AS-B15-041', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'Why should oily shop rags be kept in a closed metal container rather than piled in a corner?', '["They are easier to count","They will dry out too quickly","They take up less floor space","They can spontaneously combust"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Oily rags can heat up on their own as the oils oxidize, and piled together this heat can build until they catch fire, so a closed metal container limits oxygen and contains any fire. Keeping them dry is not the safety reason. Saving floor space and counting them are conveniences, not the hazard being controlled. Preventing spontaneous combustion is the reason.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::oily-rags'),
  ('AS-B15-042', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'Before working under a vehicle on a slope, what should be done to keep it from rolling?', '["Leave it in neutral with no brake","Place wheel chocks against the tires","Open all the doors","Remove the wheels first"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Wheel chocks are wedges placed against the tires to keep the vehicle from rolling, which is essential on a slope. Leaving it in neutral with no brake invites it to roll. Opening the doors does nothing to stop motion. Removing the wheels before securing the vehicle is dangerous. Wheel chocks prevent rolling.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::wheel-chocks'),
  ('AS-B15-043', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A label says a cleaning solvent is corrosive. What is the best practice when handling it?', '["Use bare hands for better grip","Wear chemical-resistant gloves and eye protection","Pour it down the storm drain when done","Mix it with other cleaners for strength"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A corrosive solvent can burn skin and eyes, so chemical-resistant gloves and eye protection are required when handling it. Using bare hands exposes the skin to chemical burns. Pouring it down a storm drain is illegal and pollutes the environment. Mixing cleaners can create dangerous fumes or reactions. Wearing proper PPE is the best practice.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::chemical-handling'),
  ('AS-B15-044', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'A grinding wheel must be operated. Which combination of PPE is most appropriate?', '["Sandals and shorts","Safety glasses and a face shield","A back brace only","Loose long sleeves and a necktie"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Grinding throws sparks and particles, so safety glasses with a face shield protect the eyes and face, the parts most at risk. Sandals and shorts leave skin and feet exposed. A back brace alone protects nothing from sparks. Loose sleeves and a necktie can be caught by the spinning wheel and pull the worker in. Eye and face protection is the appropriate PPE.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::grinder-ppe'),
  ('AS-B15-045', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'An air compressor tank shows rust and a small leak at a weld. What is the safest action?', '["Keep using it at higher pressure","Take it out of service and have it inspected or replaced","Patch it with tape and keep working","Paint over the rust"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A rusted, leaking pressure tank can rupture violently, so it should be taken out of service and inspected or replaced. Raising the pressure makes a rupture more likely. Tape cannot safely hold pressurized air at a weld. Painting over rust hides the problem without fixing the weakened metal. Removing it from service is the safe action.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::compressor-safety'),
  ('AS-B15-046', 'AS', 'as.shop-safety', 2, 'Why is it important to keep shop floors free of oil and clutter?', '["To improve the building''s resale value","To prevent slips, trips, and falls","To make tools last longer","To reduce the electric bill"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Oil spills and clutter create slip, trip, and fall hazards, the most common cause of shop injuries, so keeping floors clean prevents those accidents. Resale value is not a safety concern. Floor cleanliness does not directly extend tool life. It does not affect the electric bill. Preventing slips, trips, and falls is the reason.', true, 'verified', 'as.shop-safety::housekeeping'),
  ('AS-B15-047', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What is the correct order of the four strokes in a four-stroke gasoline engine?', '["Compression, intake, exhaust, power","Intake, compression, power, exhaust","Power, exhaust, intake, compression","Exhaust, power, compression, intake"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A four-stroke engine runs intake (draws in air and fuel), compression (squeezes the mixture), power (ignition pushes the piston down), then exhaust (pushes out burned gases). The other sequences scramble these steps out of order. Only intake, compression, power, exhaust is the correct cycle.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::four-stroke-cycle'),
  ('AS-B15-048', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What is the main job of the radiator in a cooling system?', '["To filter the fuel","To store engine oil","To generate electricity","To release heat from the coolant to the air"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The radiator passes hot coolant through thin tubes and fins so air flowing across them carries the heat away, cooling the coolant before it returns to the engine. Engine oil is stored in the oil pan, not the radiator. Electricity is generated by the alternator. Fuel is cleaned by the fuel filter. Only releasing heat to the air describes the radiator.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::cooling-system'),
  ('AS-B15-049', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'Which component charges the battery and powers the electrical system while the engine runs?', '["Starter","Alternator","Radiator","Catalytic converter"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The alternator is driven by the engine and produces electricity to recharge the battery and run the electrical system while the engine runs. The starter uses battery power to crank the engine and then stops. The radiator cools the engine. The catalytic converter cleans exhaust gases. Only the alternator charges the battery while running.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::charging-system'),
  ('AS-B15-050', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What part transfers engine power to the drive wheels and lets the driver change gear ratios?', '["Water pump","Muffler","Alternator","Transmission"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The transmission takes power from the engine and, through different gear ratios, sends it to the drive wheels for a range of speeds and torque. The muffler quiets exhaust noise. The alternator generates electricity. The water pump circulates coolant. Only the transmission changes gear ratios to drive the wheels.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::drivetrain'),
  ('AS-B15-051', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What is the main purpose of engine oil in the lubrication system?', '["To ignite the fuel","To reduce friction between moving parts","To cool the cabin","To inflate the tires"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Engine oil coats moving parts with a film that reduces friction and wear, and also helps carry away heat. Igniting the fuel is the job of the spark plug. Cabin cooling is handled by the air-conditioning system. Tire inflation comes from compressed air. Only reducing friction describes the role of engine oil.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::lubrication'),
  ('AS-B15-052', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What does the catalytic converter in the exhaust system do?', '["Increases engine horsepower","Reduces harmful emissions in the exhaust","Cools the engine coolant","Charges the battery"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The catalytic converter uses a catalyst to change harmful exhaust gases into less harmful ones, reducing emissions. It does not add horsepower; it is part of the emissions system. Coolant is cooled by the radiator. The battery is charged by the alternator. Only reducing harmful emissions describes the catalytic converter.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::exhaust-system'),
  ('AS-B15-053', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'In a manual-transmission vehicle, what does the clutch do?', '["Filters the engine oil","Stores brake fluid","Cools the exhaust","Connects and disconnects the engine from the transmission"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The clutch engages and disengages the connection between the engine and the transmission, allowing the driver to shift gears and stop without stalling. Brake fluid is held in the master cylinder and reservoir. The exhaust is cooled by airflow, not the clutch. Oil is cleaned by the oil filter. Only connecting and disconnecting the engine and transmission describes the clutch.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::clutch'),
  ('AS-B15-054', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'What does the thermostat in a cooling system control?', '["The air pressure in the tires","The amount of fuel injected","The brightness of the headlights","The flow of coolant based on engine temperature"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The thermostat is a temperature-sensitive valve that stays closed until the engine warms up, then opens to let coolant flow to the radiator, keeping the engine at the right temperature. Fuel delivery is managed by the injection system. Headlight brightness is an electrical function. Tire pressure comes from compressed air. Only controlling coolant flow by temperature describes the thermostat.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::thermostat'),
  ('AS-B15-055', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 1, 'Which part uses electrical power from the battery to crank the engine when starting the vehicle?', '["Radiator","Muffler","Differential","Starter motor"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The starter motor draws power from the battery to spin the engine fast enough to begin the combustion cycle when the key is turned. The muffler quiets exhaust noise. The differential splits power between drive wheels. The radiator cools the engine. Only the starter motor cranks the engine.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::starter'),
  ('AS-B15-056', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'During which stroke of a four-stroke engine does the spark plug fire to ignite the fuel mixture?', '["At the start of the intake stroke","Near the end of the compression stroke","During the exhaust stroke","While the engine is off"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The spark plug fires near the end of the compression stroke, when the mixture is fully compressed, so the burning gases drive the piston down on the power stroke. Firing at the start of intake would ignite an incomplete charge. Firing during exhaust would waste the spark on burned gases. The engine off means no combustion at all. Ignition near the end of compression is correct.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::ignition-timing'),
  ('AS-B15-057', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'A car''s headlights dim and the battery keeps dying even after a recharge. Which component is the most likely cause?', '["A leaking radiator","A clogged air filter","A worn brake pad","A faulty alternator"]'::jsonb, 3, 'If the alternator fails, the battery is not recharged while the engine runs, so it drains and the lights dim. A clogged air filter affects engine breathing and power, not charging. A worn brake pad affects braking. A leaking radiator causes overheating. A faulty alternator best explains a battery that will not stay charged.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::charging-diagnosis'),
  ('AS-B15-058', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'What is the main purpose of the differential in a vehicle''s drivetrain?', '["To boost radio signal","To store engine coolant","To filter the cabin air","To let the drive wheels turn at different speeds in a turn"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The differential lets the two drive wheels rotate at different speeds, which is needed in a turn because the outside wheel travels farther than the inside wheel. It does not store coolant, which the radiator and reservoir handle. It does not filter cabin air. It has nothing to do with radio signal. Allowing different wheel speeds in a turn is its purpose.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::differential'),
  ('AS-B15-059', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'Why do most vehicles use hydraulic fluid in the brake system?', '["It increases fuel economy","It makes the engine run cooler","It charges the battery","Liquid transmits the pedal force to the brakes at each wheel"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Brake fluid is nearly incompressible, so pressing the pedal pushes the fluid and transmits that force evenly through the lines to the brakes at each wheel. Brake fluid does not cool the engine, which the coolant does. It does not charge the battery, which is the alternator''s job. It does not affect fuel economy. Transmitting pedal force to the wheels is why hydraulic fluid is used.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::hydraulic-brakes'),
  ('AS-B15-060', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'What does an ABS (anti-lock braking system) do during hard braking?', '["Charges the battery faster","Increases engine horsepower","Cools the brake fluid","Keeps the wheels from locking up so the driver can steer"]'::jsonb, 3, 'ABS rapidly pulses brake pressure to keep the wheels from locking and skidding during hard braking, letting the driver keep steering control. It does not change engine horsepower. It does not cool brake fluid. It has no role in charging the battery. Preventing wheel lockup so the driver can steer is what ABS does.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::abs'),
  ('AS-B15-061', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'A driver notices the engine temperature rising and the coolant level is fine, but the water pump belt is broken. Why would that cause overheating?', '["The transmission will not shift","The fuel will not ignite","The headlights stop working","The water pump can no longer circulate coolant through the engine"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The water pump circulates coolant through the engine and radiator; if its drive belt is broken, the pump stops and coolant no longer moves, so heat builds and the engine overheats. A broken pump belt does not stop the spark that ignites fuel. It does not control the headlights. It does not affect transmission shifting. Loss of coolant circulation is why it overheats.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::water-pump'),
  ('AS-B15-062', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'On the power stroke of a four-stroke engine, what produces the force that pushes the piston down?', '["The coolant flowing past the cylinder","The exhaust leaving the cylinder","Fresh air being drawn in","The burning, expanding fuel-air mixture"]'::jsonb, 3, 'On the power stroke, the ignited fuel-air mixture burns and expands rapidly, and that high pressure forces the piston down to turn the crankshaft. Exhaust leaving happens on the exhaust stroke, after power. Fresh air drawn in occurs on the intake stroke. Coolant flowing only carries away heat and does not move the piston. The expanding burning mixture produces the power.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::four-stroke-cycle'),
  ('AS-B15-063', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'A vehicle''s brakes feel spongy and the pedal sinks toward the floor. Which is the most likely cause?', '["Low tire pressure","A dead battery","A clogged air filter","Air trapped in the brake lines"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Air in the brake lines compresses when the pedal is pressed, giving a soft, spongy feel and a sinking pedal, which is fixed by bleeding the brakes. A dead battery affects starting and electronics, not pedal feel. A clogged air filter affects engine breathing. Low tire pressure changes handling, not the brake pedal. Air in the lines best explains a spongy pedal.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::brake-symptom'),
  ('AS-B15-064', 'AS', 'as.vehicle-systems', 2, 'What is the primary job of the suspension system, including the shock absorbers and springs?', '["To charge the battery","To ignite the fuel mixture","To cool the engine","To smooth the ride and keep the tires in contact with the road"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The suspension, using springs and shock absorbers, absorbs bumps to smooth the ride and keeps the tires pressed against the road for traction and control. Igniting the fuel is the ignition system''s job. Cooling the engine is the cooling system''s role. Charging the battery is done by the alternator. Smoothing the ride and maintaining tire contact is the suspension''s primary job.', true, 'verified', 'as.vehicle-systems::suspension'),
  ('MC-B16-001', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Which type of friction is generally GREATER for the same two surfaces?', '["Kinetic (sliding) friction","Static (starting) friction","They are always exactly equal","Rolling friction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Static friction (the friction that must be overcome to START an object moving) is generally greater than kinetic friction (the friction once it is already sliding). That is why it takes more force to begin pushing a heavy box than to keep it moving. Choice A is the smaller of the two. Choice C is false; the two values differ for most surfaces. Choice D, rolling friction, is typically smaller than both static and kinetic sliding friction.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::static-vs-kinetic'),
  ('MC-B16-002', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Adding oil between two metal surfaces that rub together will MOST directly:', '["Increase friction","Have no effect on friction","Increase the weight of the object","Reduce friction"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A lubricant such as oil reduces friction by separating the surfaces so they slide more easily. Choice A is the opposite of what a lubricant does. Choice C is wrong because adding a thin film of oil does not meaningfully change the object''s weight, and weight is not the point of lubrication. Choice B is wrong because lubrication clearly changes (lowers) the friction.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::reducing-friction'),
  ('MC-B16-003', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'When an object rests on a table and is not moving, the forces acting on it are:', '["Unbalanced, with a net downward force","Balanced, with a net upward force","Balanced, so the net force is zero","Always zero, since nothing is touching it"]'::jsonb, 2, 'An object at rest is in equilibrium: the downward weight is balanced by the upward support (normal) force from the table, so the net force is zero. Choice A is wrong because a net downward force would make it accelerate down. Choice B is contradictory; balanced forces give a net of zero, not a net upward force. Choice D is wrong because real forces (weight and the table''s support) are present and acting.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::equilibrium'),
  ('MC-B16-004', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'What is the difference between an object''s weight and its mass?', '["They are the same thing","Weight measures the amount of matter; mass is the pull of gravity","Mass measures the amount of matter; weight is the force of gravity on that matter","Mass changes with location but weight never does"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Mass is the amount of matter in an object and stays the same everywhere. Weight is the force of gravity acting on that mass, so weight changes if gravity changes (for example, on the Moon). Choice A is wrong because they are distinct quantities. Choice B reverses the definitions. Choice D is backward: mass stays constant while weight changes with location.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::weight-vs-mass'),
  ('MC-B16-005', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Pressure is defined as:', '["Force multiplied by area","Area divided by force","Force divided by area","Force multiplied by distance"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Pressure equals force divided by area (P = F/A). The same force spread over a smaller area produces greater pressure. Choice A multiplies instead of divides. Choice B inverts the correct ratio. Choice D describes work (force times distance), not pressure.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::pressure-basics'),
  ('MC-B16-006', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Replacing a sliding contact with ball bearings reduces friction mainly because:', '["Rolling friction is generally less than sliding friction","Bearings increase the weight on the surface","Bearings increase the contact area","Rolling friction is always larger than sliding friction"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ball bearings let parts roll rather than slide, and rolling friction is generally much less than sliding friction, so the parts move more freely. Choice B is wrong because adding bearings does not meaningfully add weight, and more weight would raise friction anyway. Choice C is wrong because bearings reduce, not increase, effective contact. Choice D states the opposite of the true relationship.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::reducing-friction'),
  ('MC-B16-007', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Which surface pairing would produce the GREATEST friction?', '["Ice on ice","Rubber on dry concrete","Oiled steel on steel","Wet tile on smooth plastic"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rubber on dry concrete has a high friction (high traction), which is why tires grip the road. Choice A (ice on ice) is very slippery, with low friction. Choice C is lubricated, lowering friction. Choice D involves wet, smooth surfaces, which also reduce friction.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::factors-surface'),
  ('MC-B16-008', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Two people push on a stationary crate from opposite sides with equal force. The crate:', '["Accelerates toward the stronger pusher","Stays still because the forces are balanced","Moves at constant speed forever","Lifts off the floor"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Equal and opposite pushes cancel, producing a net force of zero, so the crate remains in equilibrium and does not move. Choice A is wrong because the forces are equal, so neither pusher wins. Choice C describes motion that would require an existing velocity, but the crate starts at rest. Choice D is wrong because horizontal pushes do not lift the crate vertically.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::equilibrium'),
  ('MC-B16-009', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 1, 'Friction between two surfaces acts in a direction that:', '["Helps the motion along","Opposes the motion or attempted motion","Is always straight down","Is always straight up"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Friction always acts opposite to the direction of motion (or attempted motion), resisting sliding. Choice A is wrong because friction resists rather than aids motion. Choices C and D are wrong because friction acts along the contact surface, not strictly vertically; the surface could be horizontal, vertical, or sloped.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::friction-direction'),
  ('MC-B16-010', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A box weighs 200 newtons and sits on a flat floor. The coefficient of static friction is 0.4. About how much horizontal force is needed to JUST start it sliding?', '["50 N","80 N","200 N","500 N"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Maximum static friction equals the coefficient times the normal force. On a flat floor the normal force equals the weight (200 N), so friction = 0.4 x 200 = 80 N, and you must apply just over 80 N to start sliding. Choice A divides instead of using the right product. Choice C mistakes the weight for the friction force. Choice D divides weight by the coefficient (200 / 0.4) instead of multiplying.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::friction-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-011', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A force of 300 N is spread evenly over an area of 6 square meters. What is the pressure?', '["50 pascals","300 pascals","1,800 pascals","0.02 pascals"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Pressure = force / area = 300 N / 6 m^2 = 50 pascals. Choice B simply repeats the force without dividing. Choice C multiplies force by area (300 x 6) instead of dividing. Choice D divides area by force (6 / 300), inverting the formula.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::pressure-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-012', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A sharp knife cuts more easily than a dull one because the sharp edge:', '["Applies less total force","Concentrates the force over a smaller area, raising pressure","Reduces the friction of the food","Has more mass behind it"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Because pressure = force / area, a thin sharp edge has a tiny contact area, so the same force produces much higher pressure and cuts more easily. Choice A is wrong because the total force can be the same; only the area changes. Choice C confuses cutting with friction reduction. Choice D is wrong because mass is not what makes a sharp edge cut better than a dull one.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::pressure-basics'),
  ('MC-B16-013', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'If the same crate is pushed onto a surface with a higher coefficient of friction (everything else equal), the force needed to slide it will:', '["Decrease","Stay exactly the same","Increase","Drop to zero"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Friction force equals the coefficient of friction times the normal force, so a higher coefficient means more friction and a larger push is required. Choice A is the opposite. Choice B is wrong because changing the coefficient changes the friction. Choice D is wrong because friction does not disappear; it grows.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::factors-normal'),
  ('MC-B16-014', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'A wide tractor tire and a narrow bicycle tire carry the same load. The wide tire exerts LESS pressure on the ground because:', '["It carries less weight","The same force is spread over a larger contact area","Wide tires reduce the force of gravity","Pressure increases with contact area"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Pressure = force / area. Spreading the same load over a larger contact area lowers the pressure, which is why wide tires sink less into soft ground. Choice A is wrong because the load is stated to be the same. Choice C is wrong because tire width does not change gravity. Choice D states the relationship backward; larger area means lower pressure, not higher.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::pressure-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-015', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'An object hangs motionless from a single rope. If the object weighs 150 N, the tension in the rope is:', '["0 N","75 N","150 N","300 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Because the object is in equilibrium (not accelerating), the upward rope tension must exactly balance the 150 N downward weight, so tension = 150 N. Choice A would mean no support at all, and the object would fall. Choice B halves the weight without reason. Choice D doubles it, which would accelerate the object upward.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::tension-equilibrium'),
  ('MC-B16-016', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'On Earth a wrench has a mass of 2 kg and a weight of about 20 N. Taken to the Moon, where gravity is weaker, the wrench''s:', '["Mass and weight both stay 2 kg and 20 N","Mass stays 2 kg but its weight becomes less than 20 N","Mass becomes less than 2 kg but weight stays 20 N","Mass and weight both increase"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mass is the amount of matter and does not change with location, so it stays 2 kg. Weight is the force of gravity, and the Moon''s weaker gravity makes the wrench weigh less than 20 N. Choice A is wrong because weight decreases on the Moon. Choice C is wrong because mass does not change. Choice D is wrong because the weaker Moon gravity lowers weight, not raises it.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::weight-vs-mass'),
  ('MC-B16-017', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'Two equal forces of 40 N each pull on a ring, one to the east and one to the west. The net force on the ring is:', '["0 N","40 N east","40 N west","80 N"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Equal forces in opposite directions cancel, so the net force is zero and the ring stays in equilibrium. Choice B and Choice C wrongly pick one direction as if it dominates, but the forces are equal. Choice D adds the magnitudes as if they pointed the same way; opposite directions subtract to zero.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::net-force'),
  ('MC-B16-018', 'MC', 'mc.forces-friction', 2, 'For a given pair of dry, hard surfaces, the friction force is best described as depending on:', '["The size of the contact area","How hard the surfaces press together (the normal force) and how rough they are","The color of the surfaces","Only the speed of sliding"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For ideal dry surfaces, friction depends on the normal force pressing the surfaces together and on the roughness of the surfaces (the coefficient of friction), not on the apparent contact area. Choice A is a common misconception; contact area does not change ideal friction. Choice C has no effect on friction. Choice D is wrong because friction does not depend mainly on speed for these surfaces.', true, 'verified', 'mc.forces-friction::factors-normal'),
  ('MC-B16-019', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'When two gears are meshed together (their teeth interlock directly), they turn:', '["In the same direction","Without turning at all","At the same speed always","In opposite directions"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two directly meshed gears always rotate in opposite directions, because where the teeth touch they push each other in opposite ways. Choice A describes belt or chain drives, not directly meshed gears. Choice C is wrong because meshed gears of different sizes turn at different speeds. Choice B is wrong because meshed gears do turn each other.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::direction'),
  ('MC-B16-020', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'In a gear system, the gear that supplies the power and starts the motion is called the:', '["Driven gear","Idler gear","Driver gear","Free gear"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The driver gear is the one connected to the power source that turns first and drives the rest of the system. Choice A, the driven gear, is the output gear that receives motion. Choice B, an idler gear, sits between others mainly to change direction. Choice D is not a standard gear term.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::driver-driven'),
  ('MC-B16-021', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'Two pulleys connected by a belt (not crossed) will rotate:', '["In opposite directions","Only if they are the same size","At the same speed regardless of size","In the same direction"]'::jsonb, 3, 'An open (uncrossed) belt or chain drive makes both pulleys turn in the same direction, since the belt pulls the same way around each. Choice A describes directly meshed gears, not a belt drive. Choice C is wrong because different-sized pulleys spin at different speeds. Choice B is wrong because a belt connects pulleys of any sizes.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::belt-chain'),
  ('MC-B16-022', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'A small gear driving a large gear will cause the large gear to turn:', '["Faster than the small gear, with less torque","At exactly the same speed","Slower than the small gear, with more torque","In the same direction as the small gear"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A small gear driving a larger gear trades speed for torque: the large gear turns more slowly but with greater turning force (torque). Choice A reverses the tradeoff. Choice B is wrong because different sizes give different speeds. Choice D is wrong because directly meshed gears turn in opposite directions.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::speed-torque'),
  ('MC-B16-023', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'What is the main purpose of an idler gear placed between a driver and a driven gear?', '["To change the gear ratio dramatically","To stop the system from turning","To remove all friction","To make the driven gear turn the same direction as the driver"]'::jsonb, 3, 'An idler gear reverses direction once more, so the driven gear ends up turning the same direction as the driver; it does not change the overall speed ratio. Choice A is wrong because an idler does not change the final speed ratio between driver and driven. Choice C is false; gears cannot remove all friction. Choice B is wrong because an idler still transmits motion.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::idler'),
  ('MC-B16-024', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'A wheel-and-axle works as a simple machine. Turning the large wheel to rotate the small axle gives you:', '["A reduction in distance moved by the wheel","Less force than you put in","No change in force or speed","A mechanical advantage (more output force)"]'::jsonb, 3, 'When effort is applied to the large wheel and the load is on the small axle, the wheel-and-axle multiplies force, giving a mechanical advantage (like a doorknob or steering wheel). Choice B is wrong; this arrangement increases output force. Choice C is wrong because a force/speed tradeoff does occur. Choice A is wrong because the large wheel moves a greater distance, which is the trade for more force.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::wheel-axle'),
  ('MC-B16-025', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'Three gears are meshed in a row: A drives B, and B drives C. If gear A turns clockwise, gear C turns:', '["Clockwise","Counterclockwise","It does not turn","At the same speed as B"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Each meshed pair reverses direction. A clockwise reverses B to counterclockwise, and B counterclockwise reverses C back to clockwise. With an odd number of gears in a line, the last gear turns the same way as the first. Choice B would be correct only with an even number of gears. Choice C is wrong because the gears do transmit motion. Choice D is about speed, not direction, and need not match.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::direction'),
  ('MC-B16-026', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'A large gear driving a small gear makes the small gear turn:', '["Slower, with more torque","At the same speed","Faster, with less torque","Backward then forward repeatedly"]'::jsonb, 2, 'When a large gear drives a small one, the small gear spins faster but delivers less torque. This is the speed-for-torque tradeoff in reverse from a small-driving-large setup. Choice A describes a small gear driving a large one. Choice B is wrong because different sizes give different speeds. Choice D is not how steadily meshed gears behave.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::speed-torque'),
  ('MC-B16-027', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 1, 'On a bicycle, the chain connects the front sprocket to the rear sprocket. The two sprockets turn:', '["In opposite directions","At identical speeds always","Only when coasting","In the same direction"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A chain drive, like a belt drive, makes both sprockets rotate in the same direction. Choice A describes directly meshed gears, not a chain. Choice C is wrong because the sprockets turn together while pedaling, not only when coasting. Choice B is wrong because different-sized sprockets turn at different speeds.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::belt-chain'),
  ('MC-B16-028', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A driver gear has 10 teeth and the driven gear has 30 teeth. For every one full turn of the driven gear, the driver gear makes:', '["3 turns","1 turn","30 turns","10 turns"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The number of turns is inversely proportional to teeth. The driven gear (30 teeth) is three times bigger, so the small driver (10 teeth) makes 30/10 = 3 turns for each single turn of the driven gear. Choice B would be true only for equal-size gears. Choice C and Choice D simply copy a tooth count rather than computing the ratio.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::turns-ratio'),
  ('MC-B16-029', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A driver gear with 12 teeth turns at 60 revolutions per minute and meshes with a driven gear of 24 teeth. The driven gear turns at:', '["120 rpm","48 rpm","60 rpm","30 rpm"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Speed is inversely proportional to teeth: driven speed = driver speed x (driver teeth / driven teeth) = 60 x (12/24) = 30 rpm. The larger driven gear turns slower. Choice A doubles the speed, which would be the case if the driven gear were smaller. Choice C ignores the size difference. Choice B uses an incorrect ratio.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::rpm-ratio'),
  ('MC-B16-030', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'Two meshed gears have a gear ratio of 4 to 1 (driven to driver). Compared with the input, the output provides:', '["More speed and less torque","The same torque and speed","More speed and more torque","More torque and less speed"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A 4-to-1 reduction (large driven gear) multiplies torque about four times while cutting output speed to one quarter. You trade speed for force. Choice A describes a speed-increasing (overdrive) setup, the opposite. Choice C is impossible; you cannot gain both speed and torque for free. Choice B ignores the gear ratio entirely.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::ratio-tradeoff'),
  ('MC-B16-031', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A driver gear has 20 teeth and the driven gear has 40 teeth. For every two full turns of the driver gear, the driven gear makes:', '["Half a turn","2 turns","4 turns","1 turn"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The driven gear (40 teeth) is twice as large, so it turns half as fast as the driver. Two turns of the driver produce 2 x (20/40) = 1 turn of the driven gear. Choice B ignores the size difference. Choice C inverts the ratio. Choice A is the result for only one turn of the driver, not two.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::turns-ratio'),
  ('MC-B16-032', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'A wheel-and-axle has a wheel of radius 20 cm and an axle of radius 4 cm. Applying effort at the wheel to lift a load on the axle gives an ideal mechanical advantage of:', '["5","0.2","16","24"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The ideal mechanical advantage of a wheel-and-axle is the wheel radius divided by the axle radius: 20 / 4 = 5. Choice B inverts the ratio (axle over wheel). Choice C multiplies the radii (20 x 4 is not even 16; this is just a distractor value). Choice D adds the radii (20 + 4) instead of dividing.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::wheel-axle'),
  ('MC-B16-033', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'An engineer wants a fan to spin FASTER than the motor. The motor''s gear should be:', '["Larger than the fan''s gear","Smaller than the fan''s gear","The same size as the fan''s gear","Connected with an idler only"]'::jsonb, 0, 'To make the driven (fan) gear spin faster, the driver (motor) gear must be larger so the smaller fan gear turns more times per motor revolution. Choice B would make the fan turn slower. Choice C would give equal speeds. Choice D, an idler, changes direction but not the overall speed ratio.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::ratio-tradeoff'),
  ('MC-B16-034', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'Gear A (driver, 15 teeth) meshes with Gear B (driven, 45 teeth). What is the gear ratio of driven to driver?', '["1 to 3","1 to 1","3 to 1","45 to 1"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The gear ratio of driven to driver is 45 to 15, which simplifies to 3 to 1. Choice A is the inverse (driver to driven). Choice B would require equal teeth. Choice D uses the raw tooth count without simplifying against the 15-tooth driver.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::teeth-ratio'),
  ('MC-B16-035', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'An inclined plane (ramp) makes it easier to raise a load because it:', '["Removes the weight of the load","Reduces the load''s mass","Increases gravity in your favor","Lets you apply a smaller force over a longer distance"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A ramp trades distance for force: you push with a smaller force but over a longer path, doing the same total work to raise the load. Choice A is wrong because the weight is unchanged. Choice C is wrong because gravity is constant. Choice B is wrong because mass does not change on a ramp.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::ramp-concept'),
  ('MC-B16-036', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'A wedge (such as an axe head or doorstop) is essentially:', '["A type of lever","An inclined plane that moves","A wheel-and-axle","A fixed pulley"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A wedge is a moving inclined plane (often two inclined planes back to back) used to split or hold; the user moves it into the work. Choice A confuses it with a lever. Choice C and Choice D are entirely different simple machines, not wedges.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::wedge-screw'),
  ('MC-B16-037', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'A screw can be thought of as which simple machine wrapped around a cylinder?', '["A lever","A pulley","An inclined plane","A wheel-and-axle"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A screw is an inclined plane wrapped in a spiral around a shaft; its threads are the slope. Choice A, a lever, pivots on a fulcrum and is unrelated. Choice B, a pulley, uses a rope over a wheel. Choice D, a wheel-and-axle, is a different machine, though a screwdriver handle uses that principle to turn the screw.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::wedge-screw'),
  ('MC-B16-038', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'Pascal''s principle states that pressure applied to a confined fluid is:', '["Lost as heat","Reduced as it travels","Only felt at the point of contact","Transmitted equally throughout the fluid"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Pascal''s principle says pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted undiminished and equally to every part of the fluid and the container walls. This is the basis of hydraulic systems. Choice A is wrong; the pressure is transmitted, not lost to heat. Choice C is wrong because the pressure spreads throughout. Choice B is wrong because the pressure is not reduced in transmission.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::pascal'),
  ('MC-B16-039', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'A hydraulic system can multiply force because:', '["The output piston is always smaller","Liquids weigh less than solids","The fluid removes friction completely","The output piston has a larger area than the input piston"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In a hydraulic press the same pressure acts on a larger output piston, and since force equals pressure times area, the bigger area produces a bigger force. Choice B is irrelevant to force multiplication. Choice C is false; hydraulics do not remove friction. Choice A is backward; the output piston is larger, not smaller, to gain force.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::hydraulic-concept'),
  ('MC-B16-040', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 1, 'Compared with lifting a load straight up, a longer, more gradual ramp requires:', '["More force","No force at all","Exactly the same force","Less force"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A longer, gentler ramp has a higher mechanical advantage (length divided by height), so it requires less force to move the same load up, though over a greater distance. Choice A is the opposite. Choice C ignores the benefit of the ramp. Choice B is impossible; some force is always needed against gravity and friction.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::ramp-concept'),
  ('MC-B16-041', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'In a hydraulic car lift, you press a small piston and a large piston rises to lift the car. The large piston moves:', '["A greater distance than the small piston","Exactly the same distance","A shorter distance than the small piston","Backward"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Hydraulics multiply force but trade off distance: the large output piston moves a shorter distance than the small input piston, just as a ramp trades force for distance. Choice A reverses the tradeoff. Choice B ignores the area difference. Choice D is wrong because both pistons move in coordinated directions, not backward.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::hydraulic-concept'),
  ('MC-B16-042', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A ramp is 12 meters long and rises to a height of 3 meters. Its ideal mechanical advantage is:', '["9","3","4","0.25"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The ideal mechanical advantage of an inclined plane is its length divided by its height: 12 / 3 = 4. Choice B just repeats the height. Choice A subtracts (12 - 3) instead of dividing. Choice D inverts the ratio (height over length).', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::ramp-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-043', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'A 600 N barrel is rolled up a frictionless ramp with a mechanical advantage of 3. The effort force needed is about:', '["200 N","300 N","600 N","1,800 N"]'::jsonb, 0, 'With a mechanical advantage of 3, the required effort equals the load divided by the MA: 600 / 3 = 200 N. Choice B halves the load instead of dividing by 3. Choice C ignores the ramp''s advantage. Choice D multiplies the load by 3 instead of dividing.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::ramp-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-044', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'In a hydraulic press, the input piston has an area of 2 square cm and the output piston has an area of 20 square cm. A 50 N push on the input produces an output force of:', '["5 N","50 N","500 N","1,000 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The hydraulic mechanical advantage is the area ratio: 20 / 2 = 10. The output force is 50 N x 10 = 500 N. Choice A divides instead of multiplies. Choice B ignores the area difference. Choice D multiplies by the output area (50 x 20) instead of by the area ratio.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::hydraulic-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-045', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'Two ramps reach the same loading dock height. Ramp X is short and steep; Ramp Y is long and gradual. Pushing the same crate up Ramp Y requires:', '["More force than Ramp X","The same force as Ramp X","Less force than Ramp X","No force"]'::jsonb, 2, 'For the same height, the longer ramp (Y) has a larger length-to-height ratio, so it has more mechanical advantage and needs less force. Choice A reverses this. Choice B ignores that the ramps differ in length. Choice D is impossible because gravity still must be overcome.', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::ramp-compare'),
  ('MC-B16-046', 'MC', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics', 2, 'In a hydraulic system, the output piston has 4 times the area of the input piston. To raise the output piston 1 cm, the input piston must move:', '["1 cm","2 cm","4 cm","0.25 cm"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Because the fluid volume pushed equals the volume that rises, distance is inversely proportional to area. The output force is multiplied by 4, so the input must move 4 times as far: 4 cm. Choice A ignores the volume tradeoff. Choice B uses the wrong factor. Choice D applies the ratio backward (it would mean the output piston moved farther, which is impossible here).', true, 'verified', 'mc.inclined-plane-hydraulics::hydraulic-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-047', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A seesaw, with the pivot in the middle and a person on each end, is an example of which lever class?', '["First-class lever","Second-class lever","Third-class lever","It is not a lever"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A seesaw is a first-class lever because the fulcrum (pivot) is between the effort and the load. Choice B (second-class) puts the load between fulcrum and effort, like a wheelbarrow. Choice C (third-class) puts the effort in the middle, like tweezers. Choice D is wrong because a seesaw clearly is a lever.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-classes'),
  ('MC-B16-048', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A wheelbarrow, where the load sits between the wheel (fulcrum) and your hands (effort), is which class of lever?', '["First-class lever","Second-class lever","Third-class lever","Fourth-class lever"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A wheelbarrow is a second-class lever because the load is positioned between the fulcrum (the wheel) and the effort (your hands). Choice A puts the fulcrum in the middle, like a seesaw. Choice C puts the effort in the middle, like tweezers. Choice D does not exist; there are only three lever classes.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-class-second'),
  ('MC-B16-049', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A pair of tweezers, where you squeeze in the middle to move the tips, is which class of lever?', '["First-class lever","Second-class lever","Third-class lever","It has no fulcrum"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Tweezers are a third-class lever because the effort (your fingers) is applied between the fulcrum (the joined end) and the load (the tips). Choice A puts the fulcrum in the middle. Choice B puts the load in the middle. Choice D is wrong because the joined end acts as the fulcrum.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-class-third'),
  ('MC-B16-050', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A single FIXED pulley (attached overhead) gives a mechanical advantage of:', '["1","2","3","0"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A single fixed pulley only changes the direction of the force; it has a mechanical advantage of 1, so you still pull with a force equal to the load. Choice B is the value for a single movable pulley, not a fixed one. Choice C is too high for any single pulley. Choice D would mean it provides no support, which is false.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::pulley-types'),
  ('MC-B16-051', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'The main advantage of a single fixed pulley is that it:', '["Multiplies your force by two","Has a mechanical advantage of 4","Removes the weight of the load","Lets you pull down to lift a load up (changes direction)"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A fixed pulley changes the direction of the applied force, letting you pull down to raise a load, which is more convenient even though it does not multiply force. Choice A describes a movable pulley. Choice C is impossible; the load''s weight remains. Choice B is far too high for a single pulley.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::fixed-pulley'),
  ('MC-B16-052', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'A single MOVABLE pulley (one that rises with the load) gives an ideal mechanical advantage of:', '["1","2","3","4"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A single movable pulley has two rope segments supporting the load, giving an ideal mechanical advantage of 2, so you lift with about half the force. Choice A is the value for a fixed pulley. Choices C and D are too high for a single movable pulley.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::pulley-types'),
  ('MC-B16-053', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'In a block-and-tackle pulley system, the ideal mechanical advantage equals:', '["The number of pulleys you can see","Always exactly 2","The length of the rope","The number of rope segments supporting the load"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The ideal mechanical advantage of a block and tackle equals the number of rope segments actually supporting the moving load (the load block). Choice A is a common error; not every pulley adds a supporting segment. Choice C confuses rope length with advantage. Choice B is wrong because the advantage depends on the rigging, not a fixed value of 2.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::block-tackle-concept'),
  ('MC-B16-054', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'The lever law for balance states that:', '["Effort plus effort-arm equals load plus load-arm","Effort always equals the load","Effort divided by load equals zero","Effort times effort-arm equals load times load-arm"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A lever balances when the effort multiplied by its distance from the fulcrum equals the load multiplied by its distance: effort x effort-arm = load x load-arm. Choice A adds instead of multiplies. Choice C is meaningless for balance. Choice B is only true when the arms are equal, not in general.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-law'),
  ('MC-B16-055', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 1, 'Which everyday tool is a clear example of a first-class lever?', '["A wheelbarrow","A pair of scissors (or a seesaw)","A pair of tweezers","A ramp"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Scissors (and a seesaw) are first-class levers because the fulcrum sits between the effort and the load. Choice A, a wheelbarrow, is a second-class lever. Choice C, tweezers, is a third-class lever. Choice D, a ramp, is an inclined plane, not a lever at all.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-classes'),
  ('MC-B16-056', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'On a seesaw, a 60 lb child sits 4 ft from the pivot. To balance, an 80 lb child must sit how far from the pivot?', '["3 ft","4 ft","5 ft","6 ft"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Balance requires effort x arm = load x arm: 60 x 4 = 240, so 80 x distance = 240, giving distance = 240 / 80 = 3 ft. The heavier child sits closer. Choice B would only balance equal weights. Choice C and Choice D place the heavier child too far, which would tip the seesaw toward that child.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-balance'),
  ('MC-B16-057', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A lever is used to lift a 500 N rock. The effort arm is 5 times longer than the load arm. The effort force needed (ideally) is:', '["100 N","500 N","2,500 N","50 N"]'::jsonb, 0, 'With an effort arm 5 times the load arm, the mechanical advantage is 5, so effort = load / 5 = 500 / 5 = 100 N. Choice B ignores the lever advantage. Choice C multiplies by 5 instead of dividing. Choice D divides by 10 instead of 5.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-law'),
  ('MC-B16-058', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A worker lifts a 400 N load using a single movable pulley (ideal). The force the worker must apply is about:', '["100 N","400 N","200 N","800 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A single movable pulley has a mechanical advantage of 2, so the effort is half the load: 400 / 2 = 200 N. Choice A divides by 4, as if there were two movable pulleys. Choice B ignores the pulley advantage. Choice D doubles the load instead of halving it.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::movable-pulley'),
  ('MC-B16-059', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A block-and-tackle has 4 rope segments supporting the load. To lift a 600 N load (ideally), the effort needed is:', '["600 N","200 N","150 N","2,400 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mechanical advantage equals the 4 supporting segments, so effort = load / 4 = 600 / 4 = 150 N. Choice B divides by 3 instead of 4. Choice A ignores the mechanical advantage. Choice D multiplies by 4 instead of dividing.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::block-tackle'),
  ('MC-B16-060', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'Two weights balance on a lever. A 30 N weight is 6 cm from the fulcrum. A second weight is 9 cm from the fulcrum on the other side. The second weight is:', '["20 N","30 N","45 N","180 N"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Balance means 30 x 6 = weight x 9, so 180 = weight x 9, giving weight = 180 / 9 = 20 N. The weight farther from the fulcrum is lighter. Choice B would balance only at equal arms. Choice C reverses the relationship. Choice D is the moment value (180), not the weight.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-balance'),
  ('MC-B16-061', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'Which lever class always provides a mechanical advantage GREATER than 1 (output force larger than input)?', '["First-class lever","All lever classes equally","Third-class lever","Second-class lever"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A second-class lever always has the load between the fulcrum and effort, so the effort arm is always longer than the load arm, giving a mechanical advantage greater than 1 (more force out). Choice A, a first-class lever, can be greater or less than 1 depending on placement. Choice C, a third-class lever, always has MA less than 1 (it trades force for speed/distance). Choice B is false because the classes differ.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::lever-class-advantage'),
  ('MC-B16-062', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'A pulley system lifts a load using an effort of 50 N to move a 250 N load. Its mechanical advantage is:', '["5","0.2","200","300"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Mechanical advantage equals load divided by effort: 250 / 50 = 5. Choice B inverts the ratio (effort over load). Choice C subtracts the forces (250 - 50). Choice D adds them (250 + 50).', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::block-tackle'),
  ('MC-B16-063', 'MC', 'mc.levers-pulleys', 2, 'Adding a single fixed pulley at the top of a block-and-tackle, in addition to the movable pulleys, mainly serves to:', '["Double the mechanical advantage by itself","Cut the rope length in half","Remove the load''s weight","Let the operator pull downward instead of upward"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A fixed pulley redirects the rope so the operator can pull down (a more natural, gravity-assisted direction); by itself it adds no mechanical advantage. Choice A is wrong because a fixed pulley alone does not double the advantage. Choice C is impossible. Choice B misstates the effect; rope length relates to the number of supporting segments, not to adding a single redirect.', true, 'verified', 'mc.levers-pulleys::fixed-pulley'),
  ('MC-B16-064', 'MC', 'mc.gears-wheels', 2, 'Gear A drives gear B, which drives gear C, all directly meshed in a line. If gear A turns clockwise, what direction does gear B turn?', '["Clockwise, like A","It does not turn","The same direction as C","Counterclockwise"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Each pair of directly meshed gears turns in opposite directions, so if A turns clockwise, the gear next to it (B) must turn counterclockwise. Choice A is wrong because meshed neighbors cannot turn the same way. Choice B is wrong because B is driven by A and does turn. Choice C is wrong because C (two reversals from A) turns clockwise, opposite to B.', true, 'verified', 'mc.gears-wheels::direction-chain'),
  ('MC-B16-065', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'What is the difference between speed and velocity?', '["They are identical terms","Speed has direction; velocity does not","Velocity includes direction; speed does not","Velocity is always larger than speed"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Velocity is speed in a specific direction (a vector), while speed is just how fast (a magnitude with no direction). Choice A is wrong because they differ in the direction aspect. Choice B reverses the definitions. Choice D is wrong because their magnitudes are the same; velocity simply adds direction.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::speed-velocity'),
  ('MC-B16-066', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'Acceleration is best defined as:', '["The distance an object travels","The total speed of an object","A force pushing an object","The rate at which velocity changes"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity over time, including speeding up, slowing down, or changing direction. Choice A describes distance. Choice C describes a force, which causes acceleration but is not the same thing. Choice B confuses acceleration with speed.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::acceleration'),
  ('MC-B16-067', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'Ignoring air resistance, if a heavy ball and a light ball are dropped from the same height at the same time, they will:', '["Hit the ground at the same time","The heavy ball lands first","The light ball lands first","Neither one falls"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ignoring air resistance, all objects fall with the same gravitational acceleration, so both balls hit the ground at the same time regardless of mass. Choice B is a common misconception; heavier does not mean faster falling without air resistance. Choice C is also wrong for the same reason. Choice D is wrong because gravity makes both fall.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::falling'),
  ('MC-B16-068', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'Momentum of a moving object depends on its:', '["Color and shape","Height above the ground","Temperature only","Mass and velocity"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Momentum equals mass times velocity, so a heavier or faster object has more momentum. Choice A has nothing to do with momentum. Choice C, temperature, does not determine momentum. Choice B, height, relates to potential energy, not momentum.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::momentum'),
  ('MC-B16-069', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'An object moving in a circle at constant speed is accelerating because:', '["Its speed keeps increasing","Its direction keeps changing","It has stopped moving","Its mass is changing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Even at constant speed, an object moving in a circle constantly changes direction, and any change in velocity (which includes direction) is acceleration, directed toward the center. Choice A is wrong because the speed is stated as constant. Choice C contradicts that it is moving. Choice D is wrong because mass does not change.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::centripetal'),
  ('MC-B16-070', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'When a ball is thrown horizontally off a cliff, the force of gravity acts:', '["Forward, in the direction of the throw","Straight down","Backward, opposing the throw","Upward"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gravity always acts straight down, pulling the ball toward the ground while it continues moving forward, producing a curved (projectile) path. Choice A is wrong because gravity does not act in the throwing direction. Choice C describes air resistance, not gravity. Choice D is wrong because gravity pulls down, not up.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::projectile'),
  ('MC-B16-071', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 1, 'An object moving at a steady, unchanging velocity has an acceleration of:', '["A negative value","A large positive value","Zero","Equal to its speed"]'::jsonb, 2, 'If velocity is not changing (steady speed and direction), there is no acceleration, so acceleration is zero. Choice B and Choice A would require the velocity to be changing. Choice D confuses acceleration with speed; they are different quantities.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::zero-acceleration'),
  ('MC-B16-072', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A car travels 150 miles in 3 hours. Its average speed is:', '["50 miles per hour","45 miles per hour","450 miles per hour","153 miles per hour"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Average speed equals distance divided by time: 150 / 3 = 50 miles per hour. Choice B is an incorrect division. Choice C multiplies distance by time (150 x 3). Choice D adds distance and time (150 + 3), which mixes units and is meaningless.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::speed-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-073', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A car speeds up from 10 m/s to 30 m/s in 5 seconds. Its average acceleration is:', '["4 m/s squared","20 m/s squared","6 m/s squared","40 m/s squared"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Acceleration equals the change in velocity divided by time: (30 - 10) / 5 = 20 / 5 = 4 m/s squared. Choice B is the change in velocity (20) without dividing by time. Choice C divides the final speed by 5 incorrectly. Choice D multiplies instead of dividing.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::acceleration-calc'),
  ('MC-B16-074', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A 4 kg object moves at 5 m/s. Its momentum is:', '["9 kg m/s","0.8 kg m/s","1.25 kg m/s","20 kg m/s"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Momentum equals mass times velocity: 4 x 5 = 20 kg m/s. Choice A adds mass and velocity (4 + 5) instead of multiplying. Choice C divides velocity by mass (5 / 4). Choice B divides mass by velocity (4 / 5).', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::momentum'),
  ('MC-B16-075', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'Ignoring air resistance, an object dropped from rest falls about 10 m/s faster each second (gravity is about 10 m/s squared). After 3 seconds, its downward speed is about:', '["10 m/s","30 m/s","3 m/s","300 m/s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Speed gained equals acceleration times time: 10 x 3 = 30 m/s. Choice A is the speed after only 1 second. Choice C uses the time alone without multiplying by gravity. Choice D multiplies by 100 instead of by 3 seconds.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::falling'),
  ('MC-B16-076', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A runner completes a 400 m lap and returns to the exact starting line. Her total distance and her displacement are:', '["Distance 400 m, displacement 0 m","Distance 0 m, displacement 400 m","Both 400 m","Both 0 m"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Distance is the total path traveled (400 m), but displacement is the straight-line change in position from start to finish; since she returns to the start, displacement is 0 m. Choice B reverses the two. Choice C wrongly treats displacement as the full path. Choice D wrongly zeros out the distance, but she did travel 400 m.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::speed-velocity'),
  ('MC-B16-077', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'On level ground, a ball is thrown horizontally and at the same instant an identical ball is simply dropped from the same height. Ignoring air resistance, they hit the ground:', '["At the same time","The thrown ball lands much sooner","The dropped ball lands much sooner","Neither ball lands"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Horizontal motion does not affect the time to fall; both balls have the same downward acceleration from the same height, so they land at the same time. Choice B and Choice C are common misconceptions; horizontal speed does not change fall time. Choice D is wrong because gravity brings both down.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::projectile'),
  ('MC-B16-078', 'MC', 'mc.motion-projectile', 2, 'A cyclist rides 60 km in 2 hours, then 30 km in 1 hour. Her average speed for the whole trip is:', '["30 km/h","45 km/h","90 km/h","20 km/h"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Average speed is total distance divided by total time: (60 + 30) / (2 + 1) = 90 / 3 = 30 km/h. Choice B averages the two leg speeds (30 and 30... actually each leg is 30 km/h) incorrectly as if weighting differently. Choice C uses total distance without dividing by time. Choice D divides incorrectly. Note both legs are 30 km/h, so the trip average is also 30 km/h.', true, 'verified', 'mc.motion-projectile::speed-calc'),
  ('AO-B17-001', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube has colored stickers: top = red, bottom = yellow, front = blue, back = green, left = white, right = black. The cube is rotated 90 degrees to the left around the vertical axis (the left face swings to the front). What color is now facing you (the front)?', '["Blue","Green","Black","White"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Rotating 90 degrees to the left around the vertical axis swings the left face forward to become the new front. The left face is white, so white now faces you. ''Blue'' is the trap of forgetting the cube moved at all (blue was the original front). ''Black'' confuses left rotation with right rotation, which would bring the right face (black) forward. ''Green'' jumps to the opposite face, which would need a 180 degree turn, not 90.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::vertical-axis-spin'),
  ('AO-B17-002', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube has colored stickers: top = red, bottom = yellow, front = blue, back = green, left = white, right = black. The cube is rotated 90 degrees to the left around the vertical axis (the left face swings to the front). The top and bottom faces sit on the axis of rotation. What color is now on top?', '["White","Black","Red","Yellow"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A rotation around the vertical axis only moves the four side faces; the top and bottom faces lie on the axis and stay put. The top was red and remains red. ''White'' and ''Black'' grab side faces, which would only reach the top if the cube were tilted (a horizontal-axis rotation), not spun. ''Yellow'' would require flipping the cube upside down.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::vertical-axis-spin'),
  ('AO-B17-003', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube rests on a table. Its top face is marked with a star. The cube is tipped over to the right, rotating 90 degrees around its bottom-right edge (the top tilts toward the right side). After this single quarter turn, where is the star face now pointing?', '["Still on top","Facing left","Facing right","On the bottom"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Tipping the cube 90 degrees over its bottom-right edge swings the top face down toward the right, so the star ends up on the right-facing side. The original right face rotates down to the table (new bottom), the original bottom swings up to the left side, and the original left face moves to the top. ''Still on top'' ignores the rotation. ''Facing left'' reverses the tip direction. ''On the bottom'' would require a 180 degree flip, not a single 90 degree tip.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::single-tip'),
  ('AO-B17-004', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A tall rectangular box stands upright with its longest dimension vertical, like a refrigerator. You walk around and view it from directly above (a bird''s-eye view looking straight down). What shape do you see?', '["A rectangle that is wider than it is tall (the footprint)","A tall rectangle","A square only if the box is a cube","A triangle"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Looking straight down at any box shows only its top face, which is the footprint of the box. For a fridge-shaped box standing upright, the footprint is a flat rectangle (its base outline), generally wider than deep. The tall vertical dimension is hidden because you are looking down its length. ''A tall rectangle'' describes the front view, not the top view. The square option is a distractor about a special case that the stem does not state. A box never projects as a triangle from a face-on overhead view.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::viewing-direction'),
  ('AO-B17-005', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 1, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. The cube is flipped forward 90 degrees, pivoting around its front-bottom edge (the top tilts toward you and the front goes down to the table). What color is now on the bottom (touching the table)?', '["Black","White","Green","Red"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Pivoting forward around the front-bottom edge sends the front face straight down onto the table, so the red front becomes the new bottom. The top (white) swings forward to become the new front, the bottom (black) swings up and back to become the new back, and the back (green) rises to the top. ''Black'' is the trap of assuming the old bottom stays on the bottom. ''White'' was the top, which becomes the front. ''Green'' becomes the top, not the bottom.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::single-tip'),
  ('AO-B17-006', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. The cube is rotated 90 degrees to the right around the vertical axis (right face swings to the front), and then tipped forward 90 degrees around its new front-bottom edge (the new top tilts toward you, the new front goes down). What color is now on top?', '["Blue","Red","White","Green"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Step 1, spin right around the vertical axis: top stays white, bottom stays black, and the sides cycle so the new front is yellow (old right), new right is green (old back), new back is blue (old left), new left is red (old front). Step 2, tip forward around the new front-bottom edge: the new front (yellow) goes to the bottom, the top (white) swings to the front, the bottom (black) swings to the back, and the back face (blue) rises to the top. So blue is now on top. ''White'' forgets the second tip moves the top to the front. ''Red'' and ''Green'' are side faces that end up left and right, not on top.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::two-step-rotation'),
  ('AO-B17-007', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. The cube is tipped to the left 90 degrees (around its bottom-left edge, the top tilting toward the left), then tipped to the left 90 degrees again the same way. What color is now on top?', '["Black","White","Yellow","Blue"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Each left tip is a 90 degree rotation around the front-to-back horizontal axis. One tip: top (white) goes to the left, left (blue) goes to the bottom, bottom (black) goes to the right, right (yellow) goes to the top. Second identical tip: the current top (yellow) goes to the left, current left (white) goes to the bottom, current bottom (blue) goes to the right, current right (black) goes to the top. Two left tips equal a 180 degree roll, so the original top and bottom swap: black is now on top. ''White'' ignores that 180 degrees flips top and bottom. ''Yellow'' stops after only one tip. ''Blue'' is a side face, not the top.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::two-step-rotation'),
  ('AO-B17-008', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cylinder (like a soup can) is lying on its side on a table so it can roll. You view it from directly above, looking straight down. What shape do you see?', '["A circle","A triangle","An oval that is taller than it is wide","A rectangle"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A can lying on its side shows its curved body to an overhead viewer. Looking straight down, the outline of that curved surface projects as a rectangle: the can''s length in one direction and its diameter in the other. The circular ends point sideways, not up, so you do not see a circle from above. ''A circle'' is the view you would get looking down a standing can. ''An oval'' confuses a tilted perspective with a straight overhead projection. A cylinder never projects as a triangle.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::viewing-direction'),
  ('AO-B17-009', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A cube has top = white, bottom = black, front = red, back = green, left = blue, right = yellow. It is rotated 180 degrees around the vertical axis (spun halfway around so the front and back swap). What color is now facing you (the front), and is the top color changed?', '["Front = green, top still white","Front = blue, top now black","Front = green, top now black","Front = red, top still white"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A 180 degree spin around the vertical axis swaps front with back and swaps left with right, but leaves top and bottom fixed because they sit on the axis. So the back (green) comes around to the front, and the top stays white. ''Front = blue, top now black'' wrongly moves a side to the front and flips the top. ''Front = green, top now black'' is right about the front but wrongly flips the top. ''Front = red'' forgets the cube turned at all.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::half-turn-spin'),
  ('AO-B17-010', 'AO', 'ao.3d-visualization', 2, 'A square-based pyramid (four triangular sides meeting at a point on top, sitting on its square base) is viewed from directly above, looking straight down at the apex. What shape outline do you see?', '["A triangle","A square with diagonal lines from each corner to the center","A circle","A single point only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Viewed straight down, the outer outline of the pyramid is its square base. The apex sits directly above the center, and the four sloping edges from the base corners to the apex project as four diagonal lines running from each corner inward to the center point. So you see a square with an X-like set of diagonals to the middle. ''A triangle'' is a side view, not an overhead view. ''A circle'' would be a cone, not a square pyramid. ''A single point only'' ignores the visible base outline.', true, 'verified', 'ao.3d-visualization::pyramid-projection'),
  ('AO-B17-011', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net is shaped like a plus sign (cross): one square in the center, plus one square attached to each of the center square''s four edges (top, bottom, left, right), and one more square attached to the outer edge of the top arm. That is 6 squares total. When folded along all the shared edges, what 3D shape is formed?', '["An open-top box","A cube","A rectangular prism that is not a cube","A triangular prism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Six identical squares is exactly the number needed for a cube, and this layout is a classic valid cube net: the central square plus its four neighbors wrap around to form four sides, a top, and a bottom, while the sixth square (on the top arm) folds over to close the remaining open face. ''An open-top box'' uses only 5 squares; here there are 6, so no face is left open. A ''rectangular prism that is not a cube'' requires non-square faces. A ''triangular prism'' needs triangles, not squares.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::cube-net-id'),
  ('AO-B17-012', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net consists of five identical squares: one center square with one square attached to each of its four edges (a plus sign with no extra squares). When folded up along the shared edges, what 3D shape is formed?', '["A cube","A pyramid","A rectangular prism","An open-top box (five faces, one face missing)"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Five squares fold into a box with a bottom and four upright sides but no lid, because a cube needs six faces and only five are present. The center square becomes the bottom and the four attached squares fold up to become the walls, leaving the top open. ''A cube'' needs all six faces. ''A rectangular prism'' would still be six faces. ''A pyramid'' would require triangular sides meeting at a point, not four squares.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::cube-net-id'),
  ('AO-B17-013', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net is made of one square base with four identical triangles attached, one to each edge of the square, all pointing outward. When the four triangles are folded upward so their tips meet at a single point above the center, what 3D shape is formed?', '["A cube","A triangular prism","A square-based pyramid","A cone"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A square base with four triangles that fold up to meet at one apex point is the definition of a square-based pyramid (think of the great pyramids). ''A cube'' would need six square faces. ''A triangular prism'' has two triangular ends and three rectangular sides, not four triangles around a square. ''A cone'' has a circular base and a curved surface, not flat triangles.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::solid-from-net'),
  ('AO-B17-014', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A flat net has two identical triangles and three rectangles. The three rectangles are joined edge to edge in a row, and one triangle is attached to the top edge of the middle rectangle while the other triangle is attached to the bottom edge of that same middle rectangle. When folded, what 3D shape is formed?', '["A triangular prism","A square-based pyramid","A cube","A cylinder"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A triangular prism has two triangular ends and three rectangular sides. The three rectangles wrap around to form the three side walls, and the two triangles fold to cap the two open ends, exactly matching this net. ''A square-based pyramid'' has one base and four triangles meeting at a point, not two triangles plus three rectangles. ''A cube'' has six squares. ''A cylinder'' has curved surfaces and circular ends, which flat rectangles and triangles cannot form.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::solid-from-net'),
  ('AO-B17-015', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A cube net is laid out as a vertical column of three squares (top, middle, bottom) with one extra square attached to the right edge of the middle square and one extra square attached to the left edge of the middle square. That is 5 squares forming a plus-like shape. How many squares must be added, and where, to make a complete cube net?', '["No squares needed; it already folds into a cube","Three squares","Two squares","One square, on the far (outer) edge of any one of the four arms"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A cube has six faces and this net has only five, so exactly one more is needed. The five squares form a plus shape: the middle square is the base and the four arms fold up as the four walls, leaving the top open. Adding one square to the free outer edge of any one of those four arms supplies the lid and closes the cube. Adding two or three squares would exceed six faces. Saying none are needed ignores that five squares fold into an open box, not a closed cube.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::complete-the-net'),
  ('AO-B17-016', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 1, 'A cube net is drawn as a row of four squares left to right (labeled 1, 2, 3, 4) with one square attached above square 2 and one square attached below square 2. When folded into a cube, which face ends up directly opposite square 2?', '["Square 1","Square 3","Square 4","The square above square 2"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In a row of four squares, opposite faces are two apart in the chain: square 2 folds opposite square 4, and square 1 folds opposite square 3. The squares attached above and below square 2 become the top and bottom faces, opposite each other. So square 4 is directly opposite square 2. ''Square 1'' is adjacent to square 2, not opposite. ''Square 3'' is opposite square 1. The square above square 2 becomes a top/bottom face, opposite the square below it, not opposite square 2.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::opposite-faces'),
  ('AO-B17-017', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A cube net is a row of four squares left to right labeled A, B, C, D, with one square labeled E attached above square B and one square labeled F attached below square C. When folded into a cube, which face is opposite square E?', '["Square F","Square A","Square B","Square D"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Trace the fold: the four-square row A-B-C-D wraps around as the four side faces (A opposite C, B opposite D). E (above B) and F (below C) become the remaining two faces, the top and the bottom, which are opposite each other. So E is opposite F. ''Square B'' is the face E folds onto and shares an edge with, so it is adjacent, not opposite. ''Square A'' and ''Square D'' are side faces adjacent to the top and bottom, not opposite E.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::opposite-faces'),
  ('AO-B17-018', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A standard six-sided die is folded from a cube net. On a real die, the numbers on opposite faces always add up to 7. If one face shows 2 and the face that will fold to be directly opposite it must follow that rule, what number is on the opposite face?', '["3","4","5","6"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Opposite faces of a standard die sum to 7. The face opposite 2 must be 7 minus 2, which equals 5. ''The 3'' pairs with 4, ''the 4'' pairs with 3, and ''the 6'' pairs with 1, so none of those are opposite the 2.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::die-opposite-sum'),
  ('AO-B17-019', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A cube net is shaped like a capital T: a vertical column of four squares (top to bottom: P, Q, R, S) with one square attached to the left edge of the top square P and one square attached to the right edge of the top square P. When folded into a cube, which square is opposite square R?', '["Square P","Square Q","Square S","The square left of P"]'::jsonb, 0, 'In the vertical chain P-Q-R-S, faces two apart in the chain are opposite: P is opposite R, and Q is opposite S. The two squares attached to the left and right of P become opposite each other (the remaining pair). So square R is opposite square P. ''Square Q'' shares an edge with R, making it adjacent. ''Square S'' is opposite Q, not R. The square left of P is part of the other opposite pair.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::opposite-faces-tnet'),
  ('AO-B17-020', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A flat net is made of six identical squares arranged in a single straight row of all six in a line, attached edge to edge. If you try to fold this along the shared edges, what happens?', '["It folds into a perfect cube","It cannot form a cube; two faces overlap and one face is left missing","It folds into an open-top box","It folds into a rectangular prism"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A straight strip of six squares wraps around like a tube, but four squares already complete the loop around the four sides; the fifth and sixth squares wrap back over faces that are already covered, causing overlap, while no squares are positioned to cap the two open ends. So it cannot form a closed cube. A valid cube net must have squares branching off to reach the top and bottom faces, which a straight line never provides. ''A cube,'' ''an open-top box,'' and ''a rectangular prism'' all require faces in positions the straight strip does not offer.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::invalid-net'),
  ('AO-B17-021', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two identical right triangles are given. Each has two legs of equal length (a 45-45-90 triangle). The two triangles are joined edge to edge along their hypotenuses (the longest side), with one flipped so the right-angle corners end up on opposite ends. What single shape results?', '["A larger triangle","A square","A parallelogram","A pentagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Two identical 45-45-90 right triangles joined along their hypotenuses, with one reflected, place the two right-angle corners diagonally opposite and line the equal legs up edge to edge. Because both legs are equal, the four outer edges are all the same length and meet at right angles, forming a square. ''A larger triangle'' would come from joining along a leg, not the hypotenuse. ''A parallelogram'' results from sliding (translating) one triangle rather than flipping it. ''A pentagon'' has five sides; this figure has four.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::two-triangles'),
  ('AO-B17-022', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two identical right triangles, each with legs of different lengths (one short leg, one long leg, and a hypotenuse), are joined edge to edge along their matching long legs, with one triangle flipped so the right angles sit at opposite ends of that shared leg. What shape results?', '["A larger triangle (isosceles)","A rectangle","A square","A parallelogram"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Joining two identical right triangles along a shared leg, with one reflected so the right angles are at opposite ends of that leg, makes the two short legs point outward in opposite directions and the two hypotenuses form the two equal slanted sides. The result is a larger isosceles triangle whose base equals twice the short leg and whose height equals the shared long leg. ''A rectangle'' or ''square'' would require joining along the hypotenuse with right angles preserved. ''A parallelogram'' comes from sliding the second triangle rather than flipping it.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::two-triangles'),
  ('AO-B17-023', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two identical squares are placed edge to edge, sharing one full side, lying flat in the same plane. What single shape results?', '["A larger square","An L-shape","A triangle","A rectangle twice as long as it is tall"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Two identical squares sharing one full edge span twice the width but only one square of height, giving a rectangle that is twice as long as it is tall (a 2:1 rectangle). ''A larger square'' would require four squares (a 2-by-2 block) to double both dimensions. ''A triangle'' cannot be made from two squares meeting on a full edge. ''An L-shape'' would require offsetting the squares, but they share a full side here, keeping the outline a clean rectangle.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::squares'),
  ('AO-B17-024', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two identical equilateral triangles are joined edge to edge along one full side, with the second triangle flipped to point the opposite direction (one apex up, one apex down). What shape results?', '["A larger equilateral triangle","A square","A rhombus (diamond)","A regular hexagon"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Two equilateral triangles sharing a full edge, oriented in opposite directions, form a rhombus (a four-sided diamond) because all four outer sides equal the triangle''s side length and opposite angles match. ''A larger equilateral triangle'' would require a small triangle to also fill a corner notch, not just two triangles base to base. ''A square'' needs right angles, which equilateral triangles (60-degree angles) do not produce. ''A regular hexagon'' needs six triangles around a center, not two.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::triangles-other'),
  ('AO-B17-025', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Two identical half-circles (semicircles) are joined along their flat straight edges (the diameters), with the curved sides bulging in opposite directions. What shape results?', '["An oval (ellipse)","A full circle","A crescent","A square"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each semicircle is exactly half of a circle. Joining two identical semicircles along their straight diameter edges, with the curves bulging outward in opposite directions, reassembles the two halves into one complete circle. ''An oval'' would require stretching the halves apart, but they share the full diameter edge here. ''A crescent'' is one curve subtracted from another, not two halves joined. ''A square'' has straight sides only.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::curved-pieces'),
  ('AO-B17-026', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'A square has a smaller square notch cut out of one corner, leaving an L-shaped piece. You are given that L-shaped piece plus the small square that was removed. When the small square is placed back into the notch, what shape results?', '["A rectangle","A complete square","A larger L-shape","A triangle"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The L-shape is simply a square missing one corner square. Returning that exact small square to the notch fills the missing corner and restores the original complete square. ''A rectangle'' would require the pieces to have different dimensions than described. ''A larger L-shape'' would mean adding outside the outline rather than filling the notch. ''A triangle'' cannot result from fitting two rectangular pieces together.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::notch-fit'),
  ('AO-B17-027', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'Four identical small squares are arranged in a 2-by-2 block, each sharing full edges with its neighbors. What single shape results?', '["A rectangle twice as long as it is tall","A triangle","A plus sign","A larger square"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A 2-by-2 block of identical squares is two squares wide and two squares tall, doubling both dimensions equally, which produces a larger square. ''A rectangle twice as long as tall'' would be a 1-by-2 (only two squares) or 1-by-4 strip, not a 2-by-2 block. ''A plus sign'' needs five squares arranged in a cross. ''A triangle'' cannot be tiled from four full squares meeting on edges.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::squares'),
  ('AO-B17-028', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 1, 'A right triangle and a rectangle are given. The rectangle''s height equals the triangle''s vertical leg, and the rectangle is placed so the triangle''s vertical leg lines up flush against the rectangle''s left side, with the triangle''s right angle at the bottom-left and its slanted hypotenuse rising to the right. What is the outline of the combined figure?', '["A larger rectangle","A right trapezoid (a four-sided shape with one slanted side)","A larger triangle","A pentagon with five equal sides"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The rectangle gives a flat bottom, a flat vertical side, and a flat top; attaching the right triangle along the matching vertical side, with its hypotenuse slanting, replaces one straight edge with a slanted one. The result has a bottom, a vertical side, a top, and one slanted side: a right trapezoid (four sides, one slanted). ''A larger rectangle'' would need the added piece to keep all right angles. ''A larger triangle'' would require removing the rectangle''s flat top. The figure has four sides, not five, so it is not a pentagon.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::triangle-plus-rect'),
  ('AO-B17-029', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'You have four identical right triangles, each with two equal legs (45-45-90). They are arranged with all four right-angle corners pointing inward to meet at a single center point, and the hypotenuses forming the outer boundary. What shape does the outer boundary form?', '["A larger right triangle","A square","A rectangle that is not a square","A regular hexagon"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Four identical 45-45-90 triangles with right angles meeting at the center each contribute one hypotenuse to the outer edge. The four right-angle vertices total 360 degrees, exactly filling the center with no gap, and the four equal hypotenuses become four equal outer sides meeting at right angles, forming a square. ''A larger right triangle'' has only three sides, but four hypotenuses make four sides. ''A rectangle that is not a square'' would need unequal sides, but all hypotenuses are equal. ''A regular hexagon'' needs six outer edges, not four.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::four-triangles'),
  ('AO-B17-030', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Six identical equilateral triangles are arranged around a single shared center point, each sharing one edge with the next, all pointing outward from the center. What shape does the combined figure form?', '["A regular hexagon","A circle","A six-pointed star","A pentagon"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Each equilateral triangle has a 60-degree angle at its tip. Six tips meeting at the center sum to 6 times 60, which equals exactly 360 degrees, filling the area with no gaps or overlaps. The six outer edges (one base per triangle) form a closed boundary of six equal sides and six equal angles: a regular hexagon. ''A circle'' would need infinitely many pieces. ''A six-pointed star'' results when triangles point alternately in and out, not all from a shared center. ''A pentagon'' has only five sides.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::triangles-other'),
  ('AO-B17-031', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Two identical right triangles, each with legs of different lengths, are joined along their hypotenuses with one triangle flipped (reflected) so the right-angle corners land at opposite ends of the shared hypotenuse. What shape results?', '["A square","A rectangle","An isosceles triangle","A kite"]'::jsonb, 1, 'When two congruent right triangles are joined along the hypotenuse with one reflected, the two right-angle corners sit at opposite ends, and the matching legs align to form four sides meeting at right angles. Because the original legs have different lengths, the result is a rectangle (a square only if the legs were equal). ''A square'' requires equal legs, which the stem rules out. ''An isosceles triangle'' comes from joining along a leg, not the hypotenuse. ''A kite'' would require the triangles joined without reflection along two adjacent unequal sides.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::two-triangles-rectangle'),
  ('AO-B17-032', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'You have three pieces: two identical right trapezoids (each a four-sided shape with one slanted side, parallel top and bottom) and they are mirror images when one is flipped. If the two trapezoids are joined along their slanted sides, with one flipped so the slants match, what shape results?', '["A rectangle","A larger trapezoid","A triangle","A hexagon"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Each right trapezoid has one vertical side, one slanted side, and parallel top and bottom. Flipping one and joining the two slanted sides cancels the slants against each other, leaving the two vertical sides on the outer left and right and the parallel tops and bottoms aligning into a flat top and bottom. The outline becomes a rectangle. ''A larger trapezoid'' would keep a slanted side, but the slants were joined internally. ''A triangle'' has three sides. ''A hexagon'' would require six sides, but matching the slants removes them, leaving four.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::trapezoids'),
  ('AO-B17-033', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'A large square is divided by one diagonal line into two triangles. You are given those two triangle pieces. If you take one triangle and flip it over, then slide it next to the other so they share a leg (not the hypotenuse) and form a shape with the two hypotenuses on the outside, what is the resulting shape?', '["The original square again","A smaller square","A parallelogram","A larger triangle"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Cutting a square along its diagonal yields two identical 45-45-90 right triangles. Joining them along a leg (with one flipped so the right angles sit at opposite ends of that shared leg) makes the two hypotenuses become the two equal slanted outer sides, producing a larger isosceles triangle. ''The original square'' would come from rejoining along the diagonal (hypotenuse). ''A parallelogram'' comes from sliding without flipping. ''A smaller square'' is impossible because the combined area equals the original square''s area, not less.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::two-triangles-leg'),
  ('AO-B17-034', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'A jigsaw piece is a square with a rounded tab sticking out of its right edge. A second jigsaw piece is a square with a matching rounded notch (a cavity) cut into its left edge, identical in size and shape to the first piece''s tab. When the tab is inserted into the notch and the two squares are pushed together flush, what is the outline of the combined shape?', '["A square with a bump on the right","A rectangle twice as wide as one square","An hourglass shape","A circle"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Because the tab on the first piece exactly matches the notch on the second, the tab fills the notch perfectly and the two square bodies sit flush side by side. The interlocking detail disappears into the seam, so the outer outline is just two squares in a row, a rectangle twice as wide as one square. ''A square with a bump'' would mean the tab still protrudes, but it is buried in the matching notch. ''An hourglass'' implies pinched middle, which flush squares do not create. ''A circle'' has no straight edges.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::notch-fit'),
  ('AO-B17-035', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'Two identical right triangles, each with legs of different lengths, are joined along their matching SHORT legs, with one triangle slid (translated, not flipped) so both right angles point the same direction. The two hypotenuses end up parallel. What shape results?', '["A rectangle","An isosceles triangle","A parallelogram","A square"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sliding (translating) one triangle and joining short legs without reflecting it keeps both right angles pointing the same way, so the two hypotenuses come out parallel and the two long legs become the other pair of parallel sides. Opposite sides parallel and equal but no right angles at the joined corner makes a parallelogram. ''A rectangle'' would require flipping one triangle so a straight rectangular boundary forms. ''An isosceles triangle'' comes from reflecting along a leg. ''A square'' needs equal sides and right angles, which differing legs and the slide do not give.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::two-triangles-parallelogram'),
  ('AO-B17-036', 'AO', 'ao.pattern-assembly', 2, 'You have one square and four identical right triangles, each triangle''s longest leg equal to the square''s side. The square is placed in the center, and one triangle is attached to each of the square''s four sides, with each triangle''s right angle at the square''s corner and the hypotenuse pointing outward. What is the outer outline of the whole figure?', '["A regular octagon","A larger tilted square (a diamond shape)","A circle","A plus sign"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Placing a right triangle on each side of the square with the hypotenuses facing outward turns the four flat sides into four slanted edges. With four identical triangles, those four hypotenuses are equal and meet at right angles at the outer tips, so the outline is a larger square tilted relative to the original (a diamond). ''A regular octagon'' would need eight outer edges, but there are only four hypotenuses. ''A circle'' has no straight edges. ''A plus sign'' would result if the triangles pointed inward as notches, not outward as added points.', true, 'verified', 'ao.pattern-assembly::triangle-plus-rect'),
  ('AO-B17-037', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A solid block is built from small identical cubes arranged 3 cubes long, 2 cubes wide, and 2 cubes tall, with no gaps. How many small cubes are in the block?', '["7","10","12","14"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Multiply the three dimensions: 3 times 2 times 2 equals 12 cubes. ''7'' adds the dimensions instead of multiplying (3+2+2). ''10'' is a miscount. ''14'' over-counts. The block is full and solid, so every position is filled.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::block-volume'),
  ('AO-B17-038', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A standard cube (like a box) has how many faces, edges, and vertices (corners)?', '["6 faces, 12 edges, 8 vertices","8 faces, 12 edges, 6 vertices","6 faces, 8 edges, 12 vertices","4 faces, 8 edges, 8 vertices"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A cube has 6 flat square faces, 12 straight edges where faces meet, and 8 corner vertices. The other options swap the numbers around: 8 faces and 6 vertices reverses faces and corners, and 8 edges or 4 faces simply undercount the standard cube.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::solid-features'),
  ('AO-B17-039', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'Cubes are stacked into three columns standing side by side in a row: the left column is 2 cubes tall, the middle column is 4 cubes tall, and the right column is 1 cube tall. Each column is 1 cube wide and 1 cube deep. How many cubes are there in total?', '["6","9","8","7"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Add the heights of the columns: 2 plus 4 plus 1 equals 7 cubes. ''6'' drops one cube, ''8'' adds one, and ''9'' over-counts. Since each column is one cube wide and deep, the count is simply the sum of the heights.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::column-stack'),
  ('AO-B17-040', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A square-based pyramid (a square bottom with four triangular sides meeting at one apex point) has how many vertices (corners)?', '["4","8","6","5"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A square base has 4 corners, and the single apex point on top adds 1 more, for a total of 5 vertices. ''4'' counts only the base and forgets the apex. ''6'' and ''8'' over-count, perhaps confusing the pyramid with a prism or cube.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::solid-features'),
  ('AO-B17-041', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 1, 'A solid cube measuring 2 cubes by 2 cubes by 2 cubes is built from 8 small cubes. The whole outside surface is painted. How many of the small cubes have at least one painted face?', '["4","6","8","0"]'::jsonb, 2, 'In a 2x2x2 cube, every one of the 8 small cubes sits on a corner of the big cube, so each touches the outside surface and gets paint on at least one face. There is no hidden interior cube in a 2x2x2 block (an interior would first appear at 3x3x3). So all 8 are painted. ''4'' and ''6'' assume some cubes are hidden, but none are. ''0'' is the opposite error.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::painted-cube-2x2'),
  ('AO-B17-042', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A solid block is 3 cubes long, 3 cubes wide, and 2 cubes tall, made of small identical cubes with no gaps. It sits on a table. Looking at the block from any outside angle, how many small cubes are completely hidden from view (touching no outside surface, including the bottom that rests on the table)?', '["0","1","2","3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A small cube is fully hidden only if it is surrounded on all six faces by other cubes, meaning it must have at least one cube on every side: left, right, front, back, top, and bottom. That requires the block to be at least 3 cubes in every dimension. Here the height is only 2, so every cube touches either the top face or the bottom face (the table side counts as an exposed bottom). Therefore zero cubes are fully interior. ''1'', ''2'', and ''3'' assume an interior layer that a 2-tall block cannot have.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::hidden-cubes'),
  ('AO-B17-043', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A solid 3-by-3-by-3 cube is built from 27 small cubes. The entire outer surface is painted, then the cube is taken apart. How many of the small cubes have NO paint at all (were completely inside)?', '["0","8","6","1"]'::jsonb, 3, 'In a 3x3x3 cube, exactly one small cube sits in the very center, surrounded on all six sides by other cubes, so it never touches the painted surface. That single center cube is the only one with no paint. ''8'' is the count of corner cubes (which have THREE painted faces, the opposite of unpainted). ''6'' is the count of face-center cubes (one painted face each). ''0'' wrongly assumes no interior cube exists.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::painted-cube'),
  ('AO-B17-044', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A solid 3-by-3-by-3 cube is built from 27 small cubes and the whole outside is painted. How many of the small cubes have exactly THREE painted faces?', '["6","8","12","1"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A small cube gets three painted faces only at the corners of the big cube, where three outer surfaces meet. A cube has exactly 8 corners, so 8 small cubes have three painted faces. ''12'' is the count of edge cubes (two painted faces each, one on each of the 12 edges). ''6'' is the count of face-center cubes (one painted face). ''1'' is the single hidden center cube (zero painted faces).', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::painted-cube'),
  ('AO-B17-045', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'Cubes are stacked to form a pyramid-style staircase. The bottom layer is a 3-by-3 square of cubes, the middle layer is a 2-by-2 square of cubes centered on top, and the top layer is a single 1 cube centered on that. How many cubes are used in total?', '["12","13","14","9"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Count each layer and add: bottom 3x3 equals 9 cubes, middle 2x2 equals 4 cubes, top equals 1 cube. 9 plus 4 plus 1 equals 14. ''9'' counts only the bottom layer. ''12'' misses two cubes. ''13'' is off by one. Each layer is solid, so no positions are empty.', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::column-stack'),
  ('AO-B17-046', 'AO', 'ao.paper-folding-nets', 2, 'A flat net is folded into a triangular prism (two triangular ends and three rectangular sides). Once folded, how many total edges does the prism have?', '["6","5","12","9"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Count the edges of the folded prism: each triangular end contributes 3 edges (3 plus 3 equals 6), and 3 more edges run lengthwise where the rectangular sides meet, joining the two triangles. That gives 6 plus 3 equals 9 edges. ''6'' counts only the two triangle outlines and forgets the connecting edges. ''12'' is the edge count of a cube, not a triangular prism. ''5'' is the number of faces, not edges.', true, 'verified', 'ao.paper-folding-nets::folded-solid-features'),
  ('AO-B17-047', 'AO', 'ao.spatial-counting', 2, 'A solid 3-by-3-by-3 cube is built from 27 small cubes and the entire outside is painted. How many of the small cubes have exactly ONE painted face?', '["8","12","6","1"]'::jsonb, 2, 'A small cube has exactly one painted face only when it sits in the center of one of the big cube''s faces, touching just that single outer surface. A cube has 6 faces, and each face has exactly one center small cube, so 6 small cubes have exactly one painted face. ''8'' is the count of corner cubes (three painted faces each). ''12'' is the count of edge cubes (two painted faces each). ''1'' is the single hidden center cube (zero painted faces).', true, 'verified', 'ao.spatial-counting::painted-cube-faces'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-1', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'What is the average of 4, 8, and 12?', '["6","8","12","24"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add the values and divide by how many there are: (4 + 8 + 12) / 3 = 24 / 3 = 8. The choice 6 mishandles the division. The choice 24 is the sum, not the average. The choice 12 is the largest value, not the mean. The correct average is 8.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-1'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-2', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'A recruit runs 2 miles on Monday, 3 miles on Tuesday, and 4 miles on Wednesday. What is the average distance per day?', '["2","3","4","9"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the miles and divide by the number of days: (2 + 3 + 4) / 3 = 9 / 3 = 3. The choice 9 is the total miles, not the average. The choices 2 and 4 are individual days, not the mean. The correct average is 3 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-2'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-3', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'What is the average of 10, 20, 30, and 40?', '["20","25","30","100"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add the four values and divide by 4: (10 + 20 + 30 + 40) / 4 = 100 / 4 = 25. The choice 100 is the sum, not the average. The choices 20 and 30 are middle values but not the mean. The correct average is 25.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-3'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-4', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'A soldier scores 85, 90, and 95 on three PT events. What is the average score?', '["88","90","92","270"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the scores and divide by 3: (85 + 90 + 95) / 3 = 270 / 3 = 90. The choice 270 is the total, not the average. The choices 88 and 92 miscompute the division. The correct average is 90.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-4'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-5', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'The average of 5 numbers is 12. What is the sum of all 5 numbers?', '["12","17","60","2.4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sum equals average times count: 12 x 5 = 60. The choice 12 restates the average. The choice 17 adds 12 and 5. The choice 2.4 divides 12 by 5 instead of multiplying. The correct sum is 60.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-5'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-6', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'Find the median of these test scores: 70, 95, 80, 60, 85.', '["78","80","85","95"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Put the scores in order: 60, 70, 80, 85, 95. The middle value is 80. The choice 78 is the mean, not the median. The choice 95 is the highest value. The choice 85 is the fourth value, not the middle. The correct median is 80.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-6'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-7', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'A supply clerk counts boxes for 4 days: 12, 15, 11, and 14 boxes. What is the average number of boxes per day?', '["12","13","14","52"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the counts and divide by 4: (12 + 15 + 11 + 14) / 4 = 52 / 4 = 13. The choice 52 is the total, not the average. The choices 12 and 14 are individual days. The correct average is 13 boxes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-7'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-8', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A recruit has scores of 78, 84, and 90 on three tests. What must the recruit score on a fourth test to average 85?', '["85","86","88","340"]'::jsonb, 2, 'To average 85 over 4 tests the total must be 85 x 4 = 340. The three scores so far total 78 + 84 + 90 = 252, so the fourth must be 340 - 252 = 88. The choice 85 is the target average, not the needed score. The choice 86 averages the existing three scores. The choice 340 is the required total, not a single score. The correct score is 88.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-8'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-9', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A truck drives 120 miles out at 40 mph and the same 120 miles back at 60 mph. What is the average speed for the round trip?', '["48","50","52","100"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Time out is 120 / 40 = 3 hours and time back is 120 / 60 = 2 hours, so total distance is 240 miles over 5 hours: 240 / 5 = 48 mph. The choice 50 averages the two speeds, which is the wrong method because more time is spent on the slow leg. The choice 100 adds the two speeds. The choice 52 miscomputes the total time. The correct average speed is 48 mph.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-9'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-10', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A platoon of 10 soldiers averages 70 push-ups and a platoon of 30 soldiers averages 90 push-ups. What is the average for all 40 soldiers combined?', '["80","82","85","88"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use a weighted average: (10 x 70) + (30 x 90) = 700 + 2,700 = 3,400 total push-ups over 40 soldiers, so 3,400 / 40 = 85. The choice 80 averages the two group averages, which is wrong because the groups are different sizes. The choices 82 and 88 misweight the groups. The correct average is 85.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-10'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-11', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 4, 'After 4 tests a recruit has an average of 82. One more test of 92 is added. What is the new average over all 5 tests?', '["84","85","87","82"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The first 4 tests total 82 x 4 = 328. Adding 92 gives 328 + 92 = 420 over 5 tests: 420 / 5 = 84. The choice 85 mishandles the new total. The choice 87 averages 82 and 92 directly, ignoring that the 82 represents 4 tests. The choice 82 ignores the new score. The correct new average is 84.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-11'),
  ('AR-B18-AVG-12', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 4, 'The average weight of 6 rucksacks is 38 pounds. When one more rucksack is added, the average drops to 36 pounds. How much does the added rucksack weigh?', '["24","30","36","38"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Six rucksacks total 38 x 6 = 228 pounds. Seven rucksacks at the new average total 36 x 7 = 252 pounds. The added rucksack is 252 - 228 = 24 pounds. The choice 36 is the new average, not the added weight. The choice 38 is the old average. The choice 30 splits the difference incorrectly. The correct weight is 24 pounds.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B18-AVG-12'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-1', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A soldier can clean a barracks in 5 hours. What fraction of the barracks does the soldier clean in 1 hour?', '["1/2","1/5","5","1/10"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rate equals one job divided by the time to finish: 1 / 5 = 1/5 of the barracks per hour. The choice 5 is the number of hours, not the hourly rate. The choice 1/2 ignores the 5 hours. The choice 1/10 halves the rate. The correct rate is 1/5.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-1'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-2', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A machine produces 50 parts per hour. How many parts does it produce in 4 hours?', '["54","150","200","250"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Output equals rate times time: 50 x 4 = 200 parts. The choice 54 adds 50 + 4. The choice 150 uses 3 hours. The choice 250 uses 5 hours. The correct output is 200 parts.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-2'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-3', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A worker earns 15 dollars per hour. How much does the worker earn in 6 hours?', '["21","75","90","96"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Pay equals rate times time: 15 x 6 = 90 dollars. The choice 21 adds 15 + 6. The choice 75 uses 5 hours. The choice 96 mishandles the product. The correct pay is 90 dollars.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-3'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-4', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A pump moves 8 gallons per minute. How many minutes does it take to move 96 gallons?', '["10","12","14","88"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals total divided by rate: 96 / 8 = 12 minutes. The choice 10 mishandles the division. The choice 14 uses about 7 gallons per minute. The choice 88 subtracts 8 from 96. The correct time is 12 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-4'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-5', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'Worker A loads a truck in 6 hours and Worker B loads the same truck in 6 hours. Working together, how long does it take?', '["2 hours","3 hours","6 hours","12 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each works at 1/6 per hour, so together they do 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3 of the job per hour, finishing in 3 hours. The choice 12 hours wrongly adds the two times. The choice 6 hours ignores the help from the second worker. The choice 2 hours overstates the speedup. The correct time is 3 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-5'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-6', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A copier prints 1,200 pages in 4 hours at a steady rate. How many pages does it print per hour?', '["250","300","350","4,800"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rate equals total divided by time: 1,200 / 4 = 300 pages per hour. The choice 250 mishandles the division. The choice 350 overstates the rate. The choice 4,800 multiplies instead of dividing. The correct rate is 300 pages per hour.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-6'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-7', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A soldier digs 18 feet of trench per hour. At that rate, how long does it take to dig 90 feet?', '["4 hours","5 hours","6 hours","72 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals total divided by rate: 90 / 18 = 5 hours. The choice 4 hours uses about 22 feet per hour. The choice 6 hours uses 15 feet per hour. The choice 72 hours subtracts 18 from 90. The correct time is 5 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-7'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-8', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'Worker A paints a wall in 4 hours and Worker B paints the same wall in 12 hours. Working together, how long does it take?', '["3 hours","4 hours","8 hours","16 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Combined rate is 1/4 + 1/12 = 3/12 + 1/12 = 4/12 = 1/3 of the job per hour, so the time is 3 hours. The choice 8 hours averages the two times. The choice 16 hours adds the two times. The choice 4 hours ignores the help from Worker B. The correct time is 3 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-8'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-9', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'A pipe fills a fuel tank in 6 hours. A drain empties the full tank in 12 hours. With both open, how long does it take to fill the empty tank?', '["4 hours","8 hours","12 hours","18 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The net rate is the fill rate minus the drain rate: 1/6 - 1/12 = 2/12 - 1/12 = 1/12 of the tank per hour, so it takes 12 hours. The choice 4 hours adds the rates instead of subtracting. The choice 18 hours adds the two times. The choice 8 hours miscombines the rates. The correct time is 12 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-9'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-10', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'Two soldiers fill sandbags together. One alone fills a pallet in 3 hours, the other in 6 hours. How long does it take both working together?', '["1.5 hours","2 hours","4.5 hours","9 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Combined rate is 1/3 + 1/6 = 2/6 + 1/6 = 3/6 = 1/2 of a pallet per hour, so the time is 2 hours. The choice 4.5 hours averages the two times. The choice 9 hours adds the two times. The choice 1.5 hours overstates the speedup. The correct time is 2 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-10'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-11', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 4, 'A team must pack 600 ration kits. Three packers each do 40 kits per hour and work for 4 hours. How many kits still need to be packed?', '["120","160","480","0"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The three packers together do 3 x 40 = 120 kits per hour, so in 4 hours they pack 120 x 4 = 480 kits. Remaining is 600 - 480 = 120. The choice 480 is the number packed, not remaining. The choice 160 uses only 2 packers. The choice 0 assumes the job is finished. The correct remaining count is 120 kits.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-11'),
  ('AR-B18-WR-12', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 4, 'Two pumps drain a flooded bunker. The first removes 1/8 of the water per hour and the second removes 1/24 per hour. Running together, how long to empty the bunker?', '["4 hours","6 hours","12 hours","16 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Combined rate is 1/8 + 1/24 = 3/24 + 1/24 = 4/24 = 1/6 of the water per hour, so it takes 6 hours. The choice 16 hours adds the two times of 8 and 24 incorrectly. The choice 12 hours averages the two rates. The choice 4 hours overstates the combined rate. The correct time is 6 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B18-WR-12'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-1', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: 2 + 3 x 4', '["14","20","24","9"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiplication comes before addition: 3 x 4 = 12, then 2 + 12 = 14. The choice 20 comes from adding first (2 + 3 = 5, then 5 x 4 = 20), which ignores order of operations. The choice 24 multiplies all three numbers. The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-1'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-2', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: 10 - 6 / 2', '["2","7","8","5"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Division comes before subtraction: 6 / 2 = 3, then 10 - 3 = 7. The choice 2 comes from subtracting first (10 - 6 = 4, then 4 / 2 = 2), which ignores order of operations. The choice 5 divides the whole left side. The correct value is 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-2'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-3', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: (4 + 5) x 2', '["18","14","13","11"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 4 + 5 = 9, then 9 x 2 = 18. The choice 14 comes from multiplying only the 5 by 2 first (5 x 2 = 10, then 4 + 10 = 14), which ignores the grouping. The choice 13 adds without multiplying. The correct value is 18.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-3'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-4', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 24 / 4 x 2', '["3","12","48","6"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Division and multiplication are equal rank, so go left to right: 24 / 4 = 6, then 6 x 2 = 12. The choice 3 comes from multiplying first (4 x 2 = 8, then 24 / 8 = 3), which breaks the left-to-right rule. The choice 6 stops after the division. The correct value is 12.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-4'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-5', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 2 x 3^2', '["36","12","18","64"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Exponents come before multiplication: 3^2 = 9, then 2 x 9 = 18. The choice 36 comes from multiplying first (2 x 3 = 6, then 6^2 = 36), which applies the exponent in the wrong order. The choice 12 multiplies 2 x 3 x 2. The correct value is 18.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-5'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-6', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 8 - (3 - 5)', '["0","6","10","-10"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Parentheses first: 3 - 5 = -2, then 8 - (-2) = 8 + 2 = 10. The choice 0 comes from dropping the parentheses sign (8 - 3 - 5 = 0). The choice 6 comes from 8 - 2 without flipping the subtracted negative. The correct value is 10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-6'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-7', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 5 + 2 x 3 - 4', '["7","13","17","9"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiplication first: 2 x 3 = 6, then 5 + 6 - 4 = 7. The choice 13 comes from working strictly left to right (5 + 2 = 7, 7 x 3 = 21, 21 - 4 = 17 or other misorderings) instead of multiplying first. The choice 9 forgets to subtract the 4. The correct value is 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-7'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-8', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 5 x (2 + 3)^2', '["55","125","625","100"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Parentheses first: 2 + 3 = 5. Then exponent: 5^2 = 25. Then multiply: 5 x 25 = 125. The choice 55 squares only part or skips the exponent. The choice 625 squares the 5 outside as well (5 x 5)^2. The correct value is 125.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-8'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-9', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 3 + 2[4 + (6 - 2)]', '["19","21","27","17"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Work from the inside out: 6 - 2 = 4, then 4 + 4 = 8, then 2 x 8 = 16, then 3 + 16 = 19. The choice 21 adds the 3 inside the brackets before multiplying. The choice 27 comes from multiplying (3 + 2) x ... after ignoring order. The correct value is 19.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-9'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-10', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: (6 - 2)^2 / 4 + 1', '["5","4","2","9"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 6 - 2 = 4. Exponent: 4^2 = 16. Then left to right for equal ranks: 16 / 4 = 4, then 4 + 1 = 5. The choice 4 stops before adding 1. The choice 2 divides by (4 + 1) = 5 first, ignoring left-to-right order. The correct value is 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-10'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-11', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 4, 'Evaluate: 4 + 3 x 2^3 - 10 / 5', '["26","30","12","22"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Exponent first: 2^3 = 8. Then multiplication and division: 3 x 8 = 24 and 10 / 5 = 2. Then add and subtract left to right: 4 + 24 - 2 = 26. The choice 30 forgets to subtract the 2. The choice 12 mishandles the exponent as 2 x 3. The correct value is 26.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-11'),
  ('MK-B19-OOP-12', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 4, 'Evaluate: 2[18 / (3 + 6) + 5^2] - 4', '["50","54","29","58"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Innermost parentheses: 3 + 6 = 9. Inside the brackets, exponent first: 5^2 = 25, and 18 / 9 = 2, so the bracket is 2 + 25 = 27. Then 2 x 27 = 54, then 54 - 4 = 50. The choice 54 forgets to subtract 4. The choice 29 forgets the outer multiplier of 2. The correct value is 50.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B19-OOP-12'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-1', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: x + 5 < 12', '["x < 7","x > 7","x < 17","x > 17"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 5 from both sides: x < 7. The symbol stays the same because subtraction never flips an inequality. The choice x > 7 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x < 17 adds 5 instead of subtracting. The correct answer is x < 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-1'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-2', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: 2x > 10', '["x > 5","x < 5","x > 20","x > 8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide both sides by 2, a positive number, so the symbol stays: x > 5. The choice x < 5 wrongly flips the symbol even though 2 is positive. The choice x > 20 multiplies by 2 instead of dividing. The correct answer is x > 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-2'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-3', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: x - 3 >= 4', '["x >= 7","x <= 7","x >= 1","x >= 12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Add 3 to both sides: x >= 7. Adding never flips the symbol. The choice x <= 7 wrongly flips it. The choice x >= 1 subtracts 3 instead of adding. The correct answer is x >= 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-3'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-4', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: -2x > 8', '["x < -4","x > -4","x < 4","x > 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide both sides by -2 and flip the symbol because the divisor is negative: x < -4. The choice x > -4 forgets to flip. The choice x > 4 drops the negative sign as well. The correct answer is x < -4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-4'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-5', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: 3x + 4 < 19', '["x < 5","x > 5","x < 7","x < 23"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 4: 3x < 15. Divide by 3, a positive number, so no flip: x < 5. The choice x > 5 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x < 7 skips dividing by 3 (subtracts 4 then divides only the right by... ) or mishandles the steps. The correct answer is x < 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-5'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-6', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: 5 - x <= 2', '["x >= 3","x <= 3","x >= 7","x <= 7"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 5: -x <= -3. Divide by -1 and flip the symbol: x >= 3. The choice x <= 3 forgets to flip when dividing by the negative. The choice x >= 7 adds 5 instead of subtracting. The correct answer is x >= 3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-6'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-7', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'A delivery truck can carry at most 1,200 pounds. It already holds 750 pounds. What is the most additional weight w it can carry?', '["w <= 450","w >= 450","w <= 1,950","w < 450"]'::jsonb, 0, 'At most means <=, so 750 + w <= 1,200. Subtract 750: w <= 450. The choice w >= 450 reverses the constraint. The choice w <= 1,950 adds 750 instead of subtracting. ''At most'' includes the endpoint, so w < 450 is wrong. The correct answer is w <= 450.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-7'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-8', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve for x: -3x + 7 <= 22', '["x >= -5","x <= -5","x >= 5","x <= 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 7: -3x <= 15. Divide by -3 and flip the symbol: x >= -5. The choice x <= -5 forgets to flip. The choice x >= 5 drops the negative sign on the result. The correct answer is x >= -5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-8'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-9', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve the compound inequality: -3 < 2x - 1 <= 5', '["-1 < x <= 3","-2 < x <= 6","-1 <= x < 3","1 < x <= 3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Add 1 to all three parts: -2 < 2x <= 6. Divide all parts by 2: -1 < x <= 3. The choice -2 < x <= 6 forgets to divide by 2. The choice -1 <= x < 3 swaps which endpoints are included. The correct answer is -1 < x <= 3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-9'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-10', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve for x: 4x - 9 > 2x + 5', '["x > 7","x < 7","x > 2","x > 14"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 2x from both sides: 2x - 9 > 5. Add 9: 2x > 14. Divide by 2, a positive number, so no flip: x > 7. The choice x < 7 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x > 14 forgets to divide by 2. The correct answer is x > 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-10'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-11', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 4, 'Solve for x: (x / -4) + 3 >= 5', '["x <= -8","x >= -8","x <= 8","x >= 8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 3: x / -4 >= 2. Multiply both sides by -4 and flip the symbol because the multiplier is negative: x <= -8. The choice x >= -8 forgets to flip. The choice x <= 8 drops the negative on the result. The correct answer is x <= -8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-11'),
  ('MK-B19-INEQ-12', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 4, 'Solve for x: 2(3 - x) > x + 12', '["x < -2","x > -2","x < 2","x > -6"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Distribute: 6 - 2x > x + 12. Subtract x: 6 - 3x > 12. Subtract 6: -3x > 6. Divide by -3 and flip the symbol: x < -2. The choice x > -2 forgets to flip after dividing by the negative. The choice x < 2 drops the negative sign. The correct answer is x < -2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B19-INEQ-12'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-1', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'EXPAND is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["contract","grow","measure","paint"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Expand means to grow larger or take up more space. Its opposite is contract, to grow smaller. ''Grow'' is the synonym trap, since it means the same as expand, not the opposite. Measure and paint are unrelated actions.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::expand'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-2', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'ANCIENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["modern","old","heavy","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ancient means very old, from long ago. Its opposite is modern, belonging to the present. ''Old'' is the synonym trap, a close match for ancient rather than its opposite. Heavy describes weight and distant describes space, neither related to age.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ancient'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-3', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'ASCEND is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["descend","climb","hurry","arrive"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ascend is a verb meaning to move upward. Its opposite is descend, to move downward. ''Climb'' is the synonym trap, since climbing also means going up. Hurry and arrive describe speed and reaching a place, not direction of movement.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ascend'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-4', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'GENEROUS is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["stingy","giving","wealthy","friendly"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Generous means free in giving and sharing. Its opposite is stingy, unwilling to give or spend. ''Giving'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for generous. Wealthy is merely related, since a rich person can still be stingy, and friendly names a different trait.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::generous'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-5', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'TRANQUIL is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["turbulent","calm","distant","honest"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Tranquil means calm and peaceful. Its opposite is turbulent, marked by disturbance and agitation. ''Calm'' is the synonym trap, since it means the same as tranquil. Distant describes space and honest describes truthfulness, neither tied to calmness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::tranquil'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-6', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'ABUNDANT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["scarce","plentiful","expensive","fragile"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Abundant means present in large quantity. Its opposite is scarce, available in short supply. ''Plentiful'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for abundant. Expensive describes cost and fragile describes how easily something breaks, neither related to quantity.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::abundant'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-7', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'CONCEAL is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["reveal","hide","repair","carry"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Conceal is a verb meaning to keep from being seen. Its opposite is reveal, to make visible or known. ''Hide'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for conceal. Repair means to fix and carry means to transport, both unrelated actions.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::conceal'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-8', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'PRUDENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["reckless","cautious","wealthy","quiet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Prudent means careful and sensible, acting with good judgment. Its opposite is reckless, acting without care for consequences. ''Cautious'' is the synonym trap, since it means the same as prudent. Wealthy and quiet describe money and sound, neither related to judgment.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::prudent'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-9', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'TRANSPARENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["opaque","clear","fragile","colorful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Transparent means able to be seen through, like clear glass. Its opposite is opaque, not allowing light through. ''Clear'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for transparent. Fragile describes breakability and colorful describes hue, neither the opposite of see-through.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::transparent'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-10', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'AMPLE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["meager","plentiful","rapid","honest"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ample means more than enough, generous in amount. Its opposite is meager, lacking in quantity. ''Plentiful'' is the synonym trap, a close match for ample rather than its opposite. Rapid describes speed and honest describes truthfulness, neither related to amount.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ample'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-11', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 4, 'BENEVOLENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["malicious","kind","wealthy","talkative"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Benevolent means kind and wishing others well, sharing the BENE- root meaning good. Its opposite is malicious, intending to do harm. ''Kind'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for benevolent. Wealthy and talkative describe money and speech, neither tied to goodwill.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::benevolent'),
  ('WK-B20-ANT-12', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 4, 'CANDID is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["evasive","frank","cheerful","wealthy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Candid means open and honest, speaking frankly. Its opposite is evasive, avoiding a direct answer. ''Frank'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for candid. Cheerful describes mood and wealthy describes money, neither related to openness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::candid'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-1', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''The carpenter built a new TABLE for the kitchen,'' the word TABLE most nearly means:', '["a piece of furniture","to postpone a decision","a chart of numbers","a flat plateau"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Table has several meanings: a piece of furniture, a chart of data, or, as a verb, to set a motion aside. Here a carpenter ''built'' it ''for the kitchen,'' so it is the furniture meaning. To postpone is the verb meaning, which does not fit a thing that is built. The chart and plateau meanings do not match a kitchen object.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::table'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-2', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''Please TURN off the lights before you leave,'' the word TURN most nearly means:', '["to switch by moving a control","a chance to play in a game","to become sour","a bend in the road"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Turn can mean to rotate or operate a control, a chance in a game, to spoil (''the milk turned''), or a curve in a road. Paired with ''off the lights,'' it means to switch by moving a control. A chance to play and a bend in the road are noun meanings that do not fit. Going sour does not apply to lights.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::turn'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-3', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''The nurse will CHECK the patient''s temperature,'' the word CHECK most nearly means:', '["to examine","a written order for money","a pattern of squares","to stop suddenly"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Check can mean a bank draft, a pattern of squares, to halt, or to examine or test. Taking a temperature means to examine, so that meaning fits. A written order for money and a pattern of squares are noun meanings unrelated to a nurse''s action. To stop suddenly does not match measuring a temperature.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::check'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-4', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The strong CURRENT pulled the swimmer away from shore,'' the word CURRENT most nearly means:', '["a flow of moving water","up to date","a strong opinion","a unit of money"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Current can be a noun meaning a flow of water or electricity, or an adjective meaning present and up to date. Pulling a swimmer ''away from shore'' points to the flowing-water meaning. ''Up to date'' is the adjective meaning and does not fit a thing that pulls. A strong opinion and a unit of money are not meanings of current.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::current'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-5', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The roof beams must BEAR the weight of the heavy snow,'' the word BEAR most nearly means:', '["to support","a large wild animal","to give birth","to turn to one side"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Bear can mean the animal, or as a verb to carry or support, to endure, to produce, or to veer (''bear left''). With beams holding up ''the weight,'' it means to support. The animal is a noun meaning that does not fit. To give birth and to turn to one side are real meanings of bear but do not match holding weight.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::bear'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-6', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The judge ruled the contract was FAIR to both sides,'' the word FAIR most nearly means:', '["just and even-handed","a public event with rides","light in color","only average in quality"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Fair can mean just and even, a public event, light in color, or merely acceptable. A judge ruling it ''fair to both sides'' points to just and even-handed. A public event is a noun meaning that does not fit a contract. Light in color and only average are real senses of fair but do not match a ruling about fairness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::fair'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-7', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''They built the camp on the grassy BANK of the river,'' the word BANK most nearly means:', '["the raised ground along the water","a place that holds money","to tilt while turning","a row of switches"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Bank can mean a financial institution, the side of a river, to tilt in flight, or a row of things. ''On the grassy bank of the river'' points to the raised ground along the water. A place that holds money does not fit a riverside camp. To tilt while turning is a verb meaning, and a row of switches is a separate sense.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::bank'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-8', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''The senator moved to TABLE the motion until the next session,'' the word TABLE most nearly means:', '["to set aside for later","a piece of furniture","a chart of figures","to serve a meal"]'::jsonb, 0, 'In legislative use, to table a motion means to postpone it or set it aside. Here table is a verb, so the noun meanings of furniture and a chart of figures do not fit. To serve a meal is not a meaning of table. The wording ''until the next session'' confirms the postponing sense.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::table'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-9', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''Adding more debt will only COMPOUND the problem,'' the word COMPOUND most nearly means:', '["to make worse","a chemical mixture","an enclosed group of buildings","to pay in full"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Compound can be a noun meaning a chemical mixture or an enclosed set of buildings, or a verb meaning to increase or make worse. ''Will only compound the problem'' uses the verb meaning, to make worse. The two noun meanings do not fit a sentence about a worsening problem. To pay in full is not a meaning of compound.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::compound'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-10', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''She was hired to RUN the new factory,'' the word RUN most nearly means:', '["to manage or operate","to move quickly on foot","to flow steadily","to spread when wet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Run has many senses: to jog, to flow, to bleed or spread, or to manage. Being ''hired to run the new factory'' uses the manage-or-operate meaning. To move quickly on foot does not fit running a business. To flow steadily and to spread when wet (as dye runs) are real meanings of run but do not match managing a factory.', true, 'verified', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words::WK-B20-MM-10'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-11', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 4, 'The word ARTICULATE is used the same way in ''She gave an ARTICULATE answer to the hard question'' as it is in:', '["His clear, articulate speech impressed the panel.","She could articulate her plan in a single sentence.","The arm has an articulate joint at the elbow.","He failed to articulate why he was upset."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Articulate can be an adjective meaning clearly expressed or a verb meaning to put into words (and a separate sense meaning jointed). In the prompt, ''an articulate answer'' is the adjective meaning clearly expressed. Choice A, ''clear, articulate speech,'' uses that same adjective sense. Choices B and D use the verb ''to articulate,'' and choice C uses the jointed sense, so their parts of speech and meanings differ.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::articulate'),
  ('WK-B20-MM-12', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 4, 'The word TEMPER is used the same way in ''The blacksmith had to TEMPER the steel blade'' as it is in:', '["Engineers temper the glass to make it stronger.","She lost her temper during the argument.","Time can temper even the deepest grief.","Try to keep your temper in check."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Temper can be a noun meaning a state of mind or mood, or a verb meaning to harden metal or glass by heating, or to soften or moderate. In the prompt, ''temper the steel blade'' is the verb meaning to harden metal. Choice A, ''temper the glass to make it stronger,'' uses that same hardening sense. ''Lost her temper'' and ''keep your temper in check'' are the noun meaning, and ''temper even the deepest grief'' is the soften-or-moderate sense.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::temper'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-1', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The hikers found a level clearing and decided to camp there. After a steep climb all afternoon, the flat ground was a welcome change."

In this passage, the word "level" most nearly means:', '["even and flat","a stage or rank","to aim a weapon","honest and fair"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The next sentence calls the clearing ''flat ground,'' so ''level'' here means even and flat. ''A stage or rank'' and ''to aim a weapon'' are real meanings of level but neither fits a place to camp. ''Honest and fair'' (as in ''level with me'') does not match the description of the ground.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-1'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-2', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The coach kept a firm grip on the rope as the students climbed. He would not let it slip, no matter how hard they pulled."

As used in the passage, the word "firm" most nearly means:', '["a business company","tight and steady","a final decision","strict and harsh"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage says he ''would not let it slip,'' so a ''firm grip'' is a tight, steady hold. ''A business company'' is a common meaning of firm but makes no sense for holding a rope. ''Strict and harsh'' describes a person, not a grip on a rope. ''A final decision'' does not fit the sentence.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-2'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-3', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The store will stock the new boots next week. Until then, the shelves where they belong sit empty."

In this passage, the word "stock" most nearly means:', '["a share of a company","soup base","supply with goods","a wooden frame"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage talks about empty shelves that will hold boots next week, so ''stock'' means to supply the shelves with goods. ''A share of a company'' and ''soup base'' are other meanings of stock that do not fit a store filling its shelves. ''A wooden frame'' is unrelated to the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-3'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-4', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The drill instructor''s praise was rare, so the recruits prized it. A single nod from him meant more than a long speech from anyone else."

As used in the passage, the word "prized" most nearly means:', '["valued highly","won as an award","forced open with a tool","measured carefully"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Because the praise was ''rare'' and a single nod ''meant more'' than a long speech, the recruits valued it highly. ''Won as an award'' connects to the noun ''prize'' but does not fit how the recruits treated the praise. ''Forced open with a tool'' (pried) and ''measured carefully'' are not supported by the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-4'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-5', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee decided to table the proposal until more data arrived. There was no point voting on numbers they did not yet have."

In this passage, the word "table" most nearly means:', '["a piece of furniture","a chart of numbers","set aside for later","bring up for a vote"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The committee waited ''until more data arrived'' and saw ''no point voting'' yet, so to ''table'' the proposal is to set it aside for later. ''A piece of furniture'' and ''a chart of numbers'' are common meanings of table that do not fit the action described. ''Bring up for a vote'' is the opposite of what the committee did.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-5'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-6', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Everyone expected the speech to be tedious, but the speaker proved sharp and lively. People who had planned to leave early stayed until the very end."

As used in the passage, the word "sharp" most nearly means:', '["having a fine edge","quick and clever","a sudden pain","exactly on time"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The signal word ''but'' contrasts ''tedious'' with ''sharp and lively,'' and the audience stayed, so ''sharp'' means quick and clever. ''Having a fine edge'' is the most literal meaning of sharp but a speech does not have an edge. ''A sudden pain'' and ''exactly on time'' (as in ''two o''clock sharp'') are other meanings that do not fit the contrast.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-6'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-7', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The new rule was designed to curb wasteful spending. Within a year, the department''s budget overruns had shrunk by half."

In this passage, the word "curb" most nearly means:', '["the edge of a sidewalk","a strap on a horse''s bit","restrain or reduce","encourage to grow"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The next sentence says overruns ''had shrunk by half,'' so the rule was meant to restrain or reduce wasteful spending. ''The edge of a sidewalk'' and ''a strap on a horse''s bit'' are real meanings of curb but neither fits a rule about budgets. ''Encourage to grow'' is the opposite of what the rule did.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-7'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-8', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Witnesses described the suspect as anything but bold. He was a retiring man who avoided crowds and spoke only when spoken to."

As used in the passage, the word "retiring" most nearly means:', '["leaving a job for good","going to bed","shy and withdrawn","wealthy from savings"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The man is contrasted with ''bold'' and described as avoiding crowds and rarely speaking, so ''retiring'' means shy and withdrawn. ''Leaving a job for good'' is the most common meaning of retiring but the passage describes a personality, not a career move. ''Going to bed'' and ''wealthy from savings'' are not supported by the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-8'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-9', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The treaty did little to temper the rivalry between the two nations. If anything, the forced handshake left both sides more bitter than before."

In this passage, the word "temper" most nearly means:', '["a state of anger","soften or ease","harden steel by heating","a musical tuning"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage says the treaty ''did little to temper the rivalry'' and left both sides ''more bitter,'' so ''temper'' here means to soften or ease the rivalry. ''A state of anger'' uses temper as a noun, which does not fit the verb form in the sentence. ''Harden steel by heating'' and ''a musical tuning'' are real meanings of temper but neither fits a rivalry between nations.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-9'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-10', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The veteran sergeant had a wealth of stories from his years overseas, though he rarely had wealth of any other kind. His richest possessions were his memories."

As used in the first sentence, the word "wealth" most nearly means:', '["a large amount","money and property","good health","a famous reputation"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A ''wealth of stories'' means a large amount of stories, and the passage even contrasts it with ''wealth of any other kind,'' meaning money. ''Money and property'' is the most common meaning of wealth, but the passage uses that sense only in the second half to set up the contrast; the first sentence is about a large supply. ''Good health'' and ''a famous reputation'' are not meanings the passage supports.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-10'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-11', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The negotiator was known for her tact. Even when delivering bad news, she chose her words so carefully that no one left the room feeling insulted."

In this passage, the word "tact" most nearly means:', '["a plan of attack","a sense of touch","skill in handling people gently","a small nail"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage explains tact by showing she chose words ''so carefully that no one left the room feeling insulted,'' which is skill in handling people gently. ''A plan of attack'' confuses tact with the similar word ''tactic.'' ''A sense of touch'' and ''a small nail'' (tack) are sound-alikes the passage gives no support for.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-11'),
  ('PC-B21-VIC-12', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The report praised the program in glowing terms, yet a close reader could detect a current of doubt running beneath the compliments. The author seemed unconvinced by his own praise."

As used in the passage, the word "current" most nearly means:', '["happening now","flow of electricity","an underlying movement of feeling","a small dried fruit"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage describes ''a current of doubt running beneath the compliments,'' an undercurrent of feeling the author tries to hide. ''Happening now'' is the most common meaning of current (as an adjective) but does not fit ''a current of doubt.'' ''Flow of electricity'' is too literal here, and ''a small dried fruit'' (currant) is a sound-alike with no support in the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B21-VIC-12'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-1', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To make toast, first place the bread in the toaster. Next, push down the lever to start it. Then wait for the toast to pop up. Finally, spread butter on the warm slice."

According to the passage, what is the first step in making toast?', '["Push down the lever","Place the bread in the toaster","Spread butter on the slice","Wait for the toast to pop up"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The word ''first'' marks the opening step: ''place the bread in the toaster.'' Pushing the lever is signaled by ''next,'' spreading butter by ''finally,'' and waiting by ''then,'' so they are later steps, not the first.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-1'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-2', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The forecast warned of a hard freeze overnight. Because the gardener covered her plants with cloth, they survived the cold. The neighbors who did not cover theirs lost most of their garden."

The passage is organized mainly by:', '["listing items in alphabetical order","comparing two seasons","showing cause and effect","describing a place"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The word ''because'' links covering the plants to their survival, and not covering them to the loss, which is a cause-effect structure. There is no alphabetical list and no comparison of two seasons, so those choices do not match the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-2'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-3', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"First, the recruits woke at dawn and ate breakfast. After that, they ran the morning course. Then they cleaned their barracks before lunch."

According to the passage, which activity came last?', '["Eating breakfast","Running the morning course","Cleaning the barracks","Waking at dawn"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The transition words set the order: ''first'' breakfast, ''after that'' the run, ''then'' cleaning the barracks before lunch. Cleaning the barracks is the last activity named. Waking and eating happen ''first,'' and the run comes before the cleaning.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-3'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-4', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"Gas cars burn fuel and release exhaust as they drive. Electric cars, on the other hand, run on batteries and produce no tailpipe emissions. However, electric cars take longer to refuel than it takes to fill a gas tank."

How is this passage organized?', '["Steps in time order","Compare and contrast","Problem and solution","A single cause with many effects"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage sets gas cars against electric cars using ''on the other hand'' and ''however,'' which is a compare-and-contrast structure. There is no time sequence of steps, and no problem is stated and then solved, so those choices do not fit.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-4'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-5', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To change a flat tire, loosen the lug nuts first while the car is still on the ground. Next, raise the car with the jack. Then remove the nuts the rest of the way and pull off the wheel. Finally, mount the spare and tighten the nuts."

According to the passage, what should you do right after raising the car with the jack?', '["Loosen the lug nuts while the car is on the ground","Remove the nuts the rest of the way and pull off the wheel","Mount the spare tire","Tighten the nuts fully"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage uses ''then'' right after raising the car: ''remove the nuts the rest of the way and pull off the wheel.'' Loosening the nuts on the ground happens ''first,'' before the jack. Mounting and the final tightening are signaled by ''finally,'' so they come last.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-5'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-6', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"For years the town''s only bridge was too narrow for two cars to pass, causing daily backups. To fix this, the county built a second lane beside the old one. Traffic now flows in both directions without delay."

How is this passage organized?', '["Compare and contrast","A list of unrelated facts","Problem followed by a solution","Events in reverse time order"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage names a problem (a narrow bridge causing backups), then signals a fix with ''to fix this'' and describes the new lane that solved it. That is a problem-solution structure. Nothing is being compared, and the facts are clearly related, so those choices do not fit.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-6'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-7', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The factory dumped waste into the river for years. As a result, fish populations downstream collapsed. Because the fish vanished, the local fishing businesses soon closed."

Which choice best describes the order of causes and effects in the passage?', '["Fishing businesses closed, which caused the factory to dump waste","Dumping waste led to fish dying, which led to businesses closing","Fish died first, which caused the factory to start dumping","Businesses closing caused the fish to vanish"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The signal words trace the chain: dumping waste, then ''as a result'' fish collapsed, then ''because the fish vanished'' the businesses closed. Choice B follows that order. The other choices reverse cause and effect, putting the result before the thing that caused it.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-7'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-8', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The road was washed out by morning. It had collapsed during the night, after a week of rain soaked the soil beneath it. By the time crews arrived, the gap was twenty feet wide."

Which event happened first?', '["The road was washed out by morning","Crews arrived at the gap","A week of rain soaked the soil","The gap grew to twenty feet wide"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Although the washed-out road is mentioned first, the passage explains it collapsed ''after a week of rain soaked the soil,'' so the rain happened earliest. The collapse and washout came next, and the crews arriving ''by the time'' the gap was wide came last. The order of telling is not the order of events.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-8'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-9', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"New employees first complete safety orientation. Once that is done, they shadow an experienced worker for a week. After the shadowing period, they handle tasks on their own under light supervision. The handbook ends its onboarding chapter at this point."

Based on the passage''s pattern, what would most likely come next after light supervision?', '["Repeating the safety orientation","Working fully on their own","Quitting the company","Starting the shadowing week again"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage moves forward through stages of growing independence: orientation, shadowing, then light supervision. The next step in that pattern is working fully on their own. Repeating orientation or restarting shadowing reverses the forward progression, and quitting breaks the pattern of advancing toward independence.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-9'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-10', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The new alarm system was meant to deter break-ins. However, thieves quickly learned to cut the outdoor wires before entering. To counter this, the company moved to a wireless system that cannot be disabled from outside."

How is this passage organized?', '["A simple list of security products","Compare and contrast of two companies","A problem, a complication, and a new solution","Events told in reverse order"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The passage sets up a solution (the alarm), introduces a complication with ''however'' (thieves cut the wires), then offers a new fix with ''to counter this'' (the wireless system). That problem-complication-solution flow matches choice C. It is not a plain list, and only one company is involved, so those choices do not fit.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-10'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-11', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"By the time the medics reached him, the soldier was already stable. They had been delayed because the radio call came in garbled, so the location had to be confirmed twice before anyone moved."

According to the passage, which event happened earliest?', '["The medics reached the soldier","The radio call came in garbled","The soldier became stable","The location was confirmed twice"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage explains the delay started ''because the radio call came in garbled,'' which then forced the location to be confirmed twice before the medics moved and finally reached the soldier. So the garbled call is the earliest event. The medics reaching him is described first but happened last, a trap of telling order versus event order.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-11'),
  ('PC-B21-TS-12', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The essay opens by describing how cities flooded as sea levels rose. It then steps back to trace the cause: decades of warming had melted distant glaciers. Only in its final lines does the essay turn to what coastal towns might do about it."

How is the essay organized, according to the passage?', '["Strict step-by-step time order from start to finish","Effect first, then cause, then a turn toward solutions","A side-by-side comparison of two cities","A list of definitions with examples"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage says the essay ''opens by describing'' the flooding (an effect), ''then steps back to trace the cause'' (warming and melting glaciers), and only at the end ''turn[s] to what coastal towns might do'' (solutions). That effect-cause-solution order matches choice B. It is not strict forward time order, because the cause is given after its effect. No two cities are compared and no list of definitions appears.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B21-TS-12'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-1', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'What is the average of 6, 9, and 15?', '["9","10","15","30"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add the values and divide by how many there are: (6 + 9 + 15) / 3 = 30 / 3 = 10. The choice 30 is the sum, not the average. The choice 15 is the largest value, not the mean. The correct average is 10.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-1'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-2', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'A guard records the overnight low for three nights: 30, 34, and 38 degrees. What is the average low?', '["32","34","36","102"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the temperatures and divide by 3: (30 + 34 + 38) / 3 = 102 / 3 = 34. The choice 102 is the total, not the average. The choice 36 misadds the values. The correct average is 34 degrees.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-2'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-3', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'What is the average of 14, 16, 18, and 20?', '["16","17","18","68"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Add the four values and divide by 4: (14 + 16 + 18 + 20) / 4 = 68 / 4 = 17. The choice 68 is the sum, not the average. The choices 16 and 18 are middle values but not the mean. The correct average is 17.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-3'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-4', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 1, 'A recruit fires 5 shots scoring 7, 8, 9, 10, and 6 points. What is the average points per shot?', '["7","8","9","40"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the points and divide by 5: (7 + 8 + 9 + 10 + 6) / 5 = 40 / 5 = 8. The choice 40 is the total points, not the average. The choice 9 misdivides. The correct average is 8 points.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-4'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-5', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'The average of 8 numbers is 15. What is the sum of all 8 numbers?', '["23","60","120","1.875"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Sum equals average times count: 15 x 8 = 120. The choice 23 adds 15 and 8. The choice 1.875 divides 15 by 8 instead of multiplying. The choice 60 multiplies by 4 instead of 8. The correct sum is 120.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-5'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-6', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'Find the median of these inspection scores: 88, 72, 95, 81.', '["81","84","84.5","88"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Put the scores in order: 72, 81, 88, 95. With an even count, average the two middle values: (81 + 88) / 2 = 169 / 2 = 84.5. The choice 84 is the mean of all four, not the median. The choices 81 and 88 are single middle values, but the median averages both. The correct median is 84.5.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-6'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-7', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'A medic logs patients seen over 5 shifts: 9, 12, 7, 10, and 12. What is the average per shift?', '["9","10","12","50"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sum the counts and divide by 5: (9 + 12 + 7 + 10 + 12) / 5 = 50 / 5 = 10. The choice 50 is the total, not the average. The choice 12 is the most frequent value, not the mean. The correct average is 10 patients.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-7'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-8', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'Over 6 days a soldier averages 3 hours of training per day. How many total hours did the soldier train?', '["9","12","18","2"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Total equals average times count: 3 x 6 = 18 hours. The choice 9 adds 3 and 6. The choice 2 divides 6 by 3. The choice 12 uses 4 days. The correct total is 18 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-8'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-9', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'A class of 6 recruits has an average height of 70 inches. A 76-inch recruit and a 68-inch recruit join. What is the new average height of all 8?', '["70","71","72","73"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The first 6 total 70 x 6 = 420 inches. Adding 76 and 68 gives 420 + 76 + 68 = 564 over 8 recruits: 564 / 8 = 70.5, which rounds to 71. The choice 70 ignores the two new recruits. The choice 72 averages just the two newcomers. The choice 73 overcounts. The correct new average is about 71 inches.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-9'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-10', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A recruit scores 72, 80, and 76 on three tests. What must the recruit score on a fourth test to average 79?', '["79","82","88","316"]'::jsonb, 2, 'To average 79 over 4 tests the total must be 79 x 4 = 316. The three scores so far total 72 + 80 + 76 = 228, so the fourth must be 316 - 228 = 88. The choice 79 is the target average, not the needed score. The choice 316 is the required total, not a single score. The choice 82 underestimates the needed catch-up. The correct score is 88.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-10'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-11', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A convoy drives 100 miles at 50 mph, then the same 100 miles at 25 mph. What is the average speed for the whole trip?', '["33.3","37.5","40","75"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Time for the fast leg is 100 / 50 = 2 hours and the slow leg is 100 / 25 = 4 hours, so total distance is 200 miles over 6 hours: 200 / 6 = 33.3 mph. The choice 37.5 averages the two speeds, which is wrong because more time is spent on the slow leg. The choice 75 adds the two speeds. The choice 40 miscomputes the total time. The correct average speed is about 33.3 mph.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-11'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-12', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A squad of 4 soldiers averages 80 on a quiz and a squad of 6 soldiers averages 90. What is the combined average for all 10?', '["84","85","86","88"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Use a weighted average: (4 x 80) + (6 x 90) = 320 + 540 = 860 total points over 10 soldiers, so 860 / 10 = 86. The choice 85 averages the two group averages, which is wrong because the groups are different sizes. The choices 84 and 88 misweight the groups. The correct average is 86.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-12'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-13', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'A recruit earns grades on a weighted scale: a homework grade of 90 counts once and a final exam grade of 70 counts three times. What is the weighted average?', '["75","78","80","82"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiply each grade by its weight and divide by the total weight: (90 x 1 + 70 x 3) / (1 + 3) = (90 + 210) / 4 = 300 / 4 = 75. The choice 80 is the simple average of 90 and 70, which ignores the weights. The choice 82 underweights the exam. The choice 78 miscombines the weights. The correct weighted average is 75.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-13'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-14', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 3, 'Compare the mean and median of these mileage logs: 4, 5, 6, 7, 28. By how much does the mean exceed the median?', '["0","2","4","6"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The mean is (4 + 5 + 6 + 7 + 28) / 5 = 50 / 5 = 10. The median is the middle value of the sorted list, which is 6. The mean exceeds the median by 10 - 6 = 4. The choice 0 assumes mean and median match, but the large 28 pulls the mean up. The choice 6 is the median itself. The correct difference is 4.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-14'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-15', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 4, 'After 3 tests a recruit averages 76. To raise the average to exactly 80 after a fourth test, what must the recruit score?', '["80","84","88","92"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The first 3 tests total 76 x 3 = 228. To average 80 over 4 tests the total must be 80 x 4 = 320, so the fourth score must be 320 - 228 = 92. The choice 80 is the target average, not the needed score. The choice 84 only adds the gap once instead of covering all three prior shortfalls. The choice 88 undercounts. The correct score is 92.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-15'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-16', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 2, 'The average weight of 5 crates is 40 pounds. After the heaviest crate is removed, the average of the remaining 4 is 35 pounds. How much did the removed crate weigh?', '["45","55","60","75"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Five crates total 40 x 5 = 200 pounds. Four crates total 35 x 4 = 140 pounds. The removed crate is 200 - 140 = 60 pounds. The choice 45 is the old average plus 5, not the difference of totals. The choice 75 doubles the gap incorrectly. The choice 55 undercounts. The correct weight is 60 pounds.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-16'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-17', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 4, 'A drone flies a triangle route: 60 miles at 60 mph, 60 miles at 30 mph, and 60 miles at 20 mph. What is the average speed for the full route?', '["30","33.3","36.7","40"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Leg times are 60 / 60 = 1 hour, 60 / 30 = 2 hours, and 60 / 20 = 3 hours, totaling 6 hours for 180 miles: 180 / 6 = 30 mph. The choice 36.7 averages the three speeds, which is wrong because slower legs take more time. The choice 40 ignores the slowest leg''s weight. The choice 33.3 miscomputes total time. The correct average speed is 30 mph.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-17'),
  ('AR-B22-AVG-18', 'AR', 'ar.averages', 4, 'A unit of 20 soldiers has an average run time of 24 minutes. If 5 soldiers averaging 30 minutes are reassigned out, what is the new average of the 15 who remain?', '["20","22","23","24"]'::jsonb, 1, 'All 20 total 24 x 20 = 480 minutes. The 5 leaving total 30 x 5 = 150 minutes, so the 15 who remain total 480 - 150 = 330 minutes: 330 / 15 = 22 minutes. The choice 24 ignores that the slower soldiers left. The choice 20 subtracts too much. The choice 23 miscomputes the remaining total. The correct new average is 22 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.averages::AR-B22-AVG-18'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-1', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A mechanic can service a truck in 3 hours. What fraction of the truck does the mechanic service in 1 hour?', '["1/2","1/3","3","1/6"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rate equals one job divided by the time to finish: 1 / 3 = 1/3 of the truck per hour. The choice 3 is the number of hours, not the hourly rate. The choice 1/6 halves the rate. The correct rate is 1/3.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-1'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-2', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A press stamps 70 dog tags per hour. How many does it stamp in 5 hours?', '["75","280","350","420"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Output equals rate times time: 70 x 5 = 350 tags. The choice 75 adds 70 + 5. The choice 280 uses 4 hours. The choice 420 uses 6 hours. The correct output is 350 tags.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-2'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-3', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A contractor earns 22 dollars per hour. How much does the contractor earn in 8 hours?', '["30","154","176","198"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Pay equals rate times time: 22 x 8 = 176 dollars. The choice 30 adds 22 + 8. The choice 154 uses 7 hours. The choice 198 uses 9 hours. The correct pay is 176 dollars.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-3'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-4', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 1, 'A generator burns 4 gallons of fuel per hour. How long can it run on 32 gallons?', '["6 hours","8 hours","10 hours","28 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals total divided by rate: 32 / 4 = 8 hours. The choice 6 hours uses about 5 gallons per hour. The choice 10 hours uses about 3 gallons per hour. The choice 28 hours subtracts 4 from 32. The correct time is 8 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-4'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-5', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A loader earns 96 dollars for a 6-hour shift. What is the hourly pay rate?', '["14","16","18","90"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rate equals total pay divided by time: 96 / 6 = 16 dollars per hour. The choice 14 mishandles the division. The choice 18 overstates the rate. The choice 90 subtracts 6 from 96. The correct rate is 16 dollars per hour.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-5'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-6', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'Two soldiers each fold a stack of laundry in 8 hours alone. Working together, how long does it take?', '["2 hours","4 hours","8 hours","16 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Each works at 1/8 per hour, so together they do 1/8 + 1/8 = 2/8 = 1/4 of the job per hour, finishing in 4 hours. The choice 16 hours wrongly adds the two times. The choice 8 hours ignores the help from the second worker. The choice 2 hours overstates the speedup. The correct time is 4 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-6'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-7', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A hose fills a water buffalo at 12 gallons per minute. How long to fill a 540-gallon tank?', '["40 minutes","45 minutes","50 minutes","528 minutes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Time equals total divided by rate: 540 / 12 = 45 minutes. The choice 40 minutes uses about 13.5 gallons per minute. The choice 50 minutes uses about 10.8 gallons per minute. The choice 528 minutes subtracts 12 from 540. The correct time is 45 minutes.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-7'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-8', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A welder completes 6 brackets per hour. A second welder completes 9 brackets per hour. Working together, how many brackets do they finish in 4 hours?', '["15","36","60","72"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Combined rate is 6 + 9 = 15 brackets per hour, so in 4 hours they finish 15 x 4 = 60 brackets. The choice 15 is the hourly combined rate, not the 4-hour total. The choice 36 uses only the faster welder. The choice 72 double-counts an hour. The correct total is 60 brackets.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-8'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-9', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'Worker A assembles a kit in 5 hours and Worker B assembles the same kit in 20 hours. Working together, how long does it take?', '["4 hours","10 hours","12.5 hours","25 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Combined rate is 1/5 + 1/20 = 4/20 + 1/20 = 5/20 = 1/4 of the job per hour, so the time is 4 hours. The choice 12.5 hours averages the two times. The choice 25 hours adds the two times. The choice 10 hours miscombines the rates. The correct time is 4 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-9'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-10', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'A pipe fills a reservoir in 4 hours. A drain empties the full reservoir in 6 hours. With both open, how long to fill the empty reservoir?', '["2 hours","5 hours","10 hours","12 hours"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The net rate is the fill rate minus the drain rate: 1/4 - 1/6 = 3/12 - 2/12 = 1/12 of the reservoir per hour, so it takes 12 hours. The choice 2 hours adds the rates instead of subtracting. The choice 10 hours adds the two times. The choice 5 hours miscombines the rates. The correct time is 12 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-10'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-11', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'Three soldiers clean a motor pool together. Alone they would take 6, 6, and 3 hours. How long does it take all three working together?', '["1.5 hours","2 hours","3 hours","5 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Combined rate is 1/6 + 1/6 + 1/3 = 1/6 + 1/6 + 2/6 = 4/6 = 2/3 of the job per hour, so the time is 1 divided by 2/3 = 1.5 hours. The choice 5 hours averages the three times. The choice 3 hours ignores two of the workers. The choice 2 hours uses only two of the rates. The correct time is 1.5 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-11'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-12', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'A job needs 240 sandbags filled. One crew fills 30 per hour and works 5 hours, then a second crew filling 25 per hour finishes the rest. How many hours does the second crew work?', '["3 hours","3.6 hours","4 hours","6 hours"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The first crew fills 30 x 5 = 150 bags, leaving 240 - 150 = 90 bags. At 25 per hour the second crew needs 90 / 25 = 3.6 hours. The choice 4 hours rounds up incorrectly. The choice 6 hours uses the wrong remaining count. The choice 3 hours undercounts. The correct time is 3.6 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-12'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-13', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 3, 'A soldier paints 2/5 of a fence in 4 hours at a steady rate. How long to paint the entire fence?', '["6 hours","8 hours","10 hours","20 hours"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The rate is (2/5 of the job) / 4 hours = 1/10 of the job per hour, so the whole fence takes 1 divided by 1/10 = 10 hours. The choice 8 hours assumes a linear guess instead of using the rate. The choice 20 hours doubles the rate''s denominator incorrectly. The choice 6 hours undercounts. The correct time is 10 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-13'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-14', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 4, 'A tank has two fill pipes and one drain. The pipes fill in 6 and 12 hours; the drain empties in 8 hours. With all three open on an empty tank, how long to fill it?', '["8 hours","6 hours","4.8 hours","10 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Net rate is 1/6 + 1/12 - 1/8. Using 24ths: 4/24 + 2/24 - 3/24 = 3/24 = 1/8 of the tank per hour, so the time is 1 divided by 1/8 = 8 hours. The choice 6 hours uses only the faster fill pipe and ignores the drain. The choice 10 hours adds the drain rate instead of subtracting it. The choice 4.8 hours uses a wrong numerator of 5/24. The correct time is 8 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-14'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-15', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 4, 'Worker A digs a foundation in 10 hours. With Worker B helping, they finish in 4 hours. How long would Worker B take alone?', '["20/3 hours","6 hours","14 hours","20 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Together the rate is 1/4. Worker A alone is 1/10, so Worker B alone is 1/4 - 1/10 = 5/20 - 2/20 = 3/20 of the job per hour, giving a solo time of 20/3 hours, about 6.67 hours. The choice 6 hours wrongly subtracts times instead of rates. The choice 14 hours adds the times. The choice 20 hours doubles the denominator incorrectly. The correct time is 20/3 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-15'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-16', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 4, 'A bottling line runs at 90 bottles per hour for the first 3 hours, then speeds up to 120 bottles per hour. How long in total to fill an order of 870 bottles?', '["8 hours","7 hours","9.7 hours","5 hours"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The first 3 hours produce 90 x 3 = 270 bottles, leaving 870 - 270 = 600 bottles. At 120 per hour that takes 600 / 120 = 5 more hours, for a total of 3 + 5 = 8 hours. The choice 5 hours is only the second phase, forgetting the first 3 hours. The choice 9.7 hours wrongly uses 90 per hour for the whole order. The choice 7 hours undercounts the remaining bottles. The correct total is 8 hours.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-16'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-17', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A copier finishes a print job in 40 minutes. What fraction of the job does it complete in 20 minutes?', '["1/4","1/3","1/2","2/3"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The copier finishes the whole job in 40 minutes, so its rate is 1/40 per minute. In 20 minutes it completes 20 x 1/40 = 20/40 = 1/2 of the job. The choice 1/3 treats 20 as a third of an assumed 60 minutes. The choice 1/4 halves the correct fraction. The choice 2/3 overstates it. The correct fraction is 1/2.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-17'),
  ('AR-B22-WR-18', 'AR', 'ar.work-rate', 2, 'A soldier marches at a steady 4 miles per hour. How far does the soldier march in 3 hours?', '["7 miles","12 miles","1.3 miles","16 miles"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Distance equals rate times time: 4 x 3 = 12 miles. The choice 7 miles adds 4 + 3. The choice 1.3 miles divides 4 by 3. The choice 16 miles uses 4 hours. The correct distance is 12 miles.', true, 'verified', 'ar.work-rate::AR-B22-WR-18'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-1', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: 7 + 6 / 3', '["9","4","5","13"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Division comes before addition: 6 / 3 = 2, then 7 + 2 = 9. The choice 4 comes from adding first (7 + 6 = 13, then 13 / 3 is not clean) or from dividing 6 by 3 after wrongly using 6 / 3 then subtracting; either way it ignores order. The choice 13 forgets to divide entirely and just adds 7 + 6. The correct value is 9.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-1'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-2', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: 20 - 4 x 3', '["8","48","16","12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiplication comes before subtraction: 4 x 3 = 12, then 20 - 12 = 8. The choice 48 comes from subtracting first (20 - 4 = 16, then 16 x 3 = 48), which ignores order of operations. The choice 12 stops at 4 x 3 and forgets to subtract from 20. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-2'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-3', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: (12 - 3) / 3', '["3","11","9","4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 12 - 3 = 9, then 9 / 3 = 3. The choice 11 comes from dividing 3 by 3 first (12 - 1 = 11), which ignores the grouping. The choice 9 stops at the parentheses and forgets to divide. The correct value is 3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-3'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-4', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 1, 'Evaluate: 4^2 - 6', '["10","2","26","14"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Exponents come before subtraction: 4^2 = 16, then 16 - 6 = 10. The choice 2 comes from subtracting first (4 - 6 = -2) then misreading the exponent. The choice 26 comes from doing 4 x (something) or adding instead of subtracting. The correct value is 10.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-4'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-5', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 36 / 6 / 3', '["2","18","12","6"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Two divisions are equal rank, so go left to right: 36 / 6 = 6, then 6 / 3 = 2. The choice 18 comes from dividing 6 / 3 = 2 first, then 36 / 2 = 18, which breaks the left-to-right rule. The choice 6 stops after the first division. The correct value is 2.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-5'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-6', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 3 x 2^2 + 1', '["13","37","49","25"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Exponent first: 2^2 = 4. Then multiply: 3 x 4 = 12. Then add: 12 + 1 = 13. The choice 37 comes from multiplying before squaring (3 x 2 = 6, then 6^2 = 36, then + 1 = 37), which applies the exponent in the wrong order. The choice 49 squares the whole (3 x 2 + 1) = 7. The correct value is 13.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-6'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-7', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 9 - (2 - 7)', '["14","4","0","-14"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 2 - 7 = -5, then 9 - (-5) = 9 + 5 = 14. The choice 4 comes from 9 - 5 without flipping the subtracted negative. The choice 0 comes from dropping the parentheses sign entirely (9 - 2 - 7 = 0). The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-7'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-8', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 10 + 12 / 4 - 5', '["8","0.5","10","3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Division first: 12 / 4 = 3. Then add and subtract left to right: 10 + 3 - 5 = 8. The choice 0.5 comes from adding before dividing (10 + 12 = 22, then 22 / 4 = 5.5, then - 5 = 0.5), which does addition before division. The choice 10 forgets to subtract the 5. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-8'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-9', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: -3(4 - 9)', '["15","-15","-21","3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 4 - 9 = -5, then -3 x (-5) = 15. The choice -15 keeps the wrong sign, forgetting that a negative times a negative is positive. The choice -21 distributes only partly (-3 x 4 = -12, then -12 - 9), mishandling the negative distribution. The correct value is 15.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-9'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-10', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 2 + 3[10 - (4 + 2)]', '["14","26","50","12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Work inside out: 4 + 2 = 6, then 10 - 6 = 4, then 3 x 4 = 12, then 2 + 12 = 14. The choice 26 comes from adding the 2 inside the bracket before multiplying ((2 + 3) misuse or 3 x (10 - 6 + 2)). The choice 50 comes from treating (2 + 3) = 5 and multiplying by 10, ignoring the nested parentheses. The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-10'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-11', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: (8 - 3)^2 - 4 x 2', '["17","33","2","42"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 8 - 3 = 5. Exponent: 5^2 = 25. Multiplication: 4 x 2 = 8. Then subtract: 25 - 8 = 17. The choice 33 comes from adding instead of subtracting (25 + 8). The choice 2 comes from subtracting before multiplying (25 - 4 = 21, then x 2 wrong) or doing 25 - 4 x 2 as (25 - 4) x 2 then misstep. The correct value is 17.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-11'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-12', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 48 / (2^2 x 3)', '["4","16","72","8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Inside the parentheses, exponent first: 2^2 = 4, then 4 x 3 = 12. Then divide: 48 / 12 = 4. The choice 16 comes from squaring then dividing before multiplying (48 / 4 = 12, then a misstep) or ignoring the grouping. The choice 72 divides 48 by 2 then multiplies (24 x 3), mishandling the parentheses and exponent. The correct value is 4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-12'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-13', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 5 - 2 x (3 - 8)', '["15","-15","5","11"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Parentheses first: 3 - 8 = -5. Then multiply: 2 x (-5) = -10. Then subtract: 5 - (-10) = 5 + 10 = 15. The choice -15 comes from doing (5 - 2) x (3 - 8) = 3 x (-5) = -15, ignoring that multiplication binds before the leftmost subtraction. The choice 5 forgets to flip the subtracted negative (5 - 10 then mishandled). The correct value is 15.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-13'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-14', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 3, 'Evaluate: 100 / 5^2 x 2', '["8","2","200","10"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Exponent first: 5^2 = 25. Then division and multiplication left to right: 100 / 25 = 4, then 4 x 2 = 8. The choice 2 comes from multiplying 25 x 2 = 50 before dividing (100 / 50), breaking the left-to-right rule. The choice 200 multiplies 100 x 2 then divides, mishandling order. The correct value is 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-14'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-15', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 2, 'Evaluate: 6 + 2[3^2 - (8 / 4)]', '["20","26","16","32"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Inside the brackets: exponent 3^2 = 9, and the inner parentheses 8 / 4 = 2, so 9 - 2 = 7. Then 2 x 7 = 14, then 6 + 14 = 20. The choice 26 comes from adding the 6 inside the multiplier ((6 + 2) x ...) instead of multiplying first. The choice 16 mishandles the exponent as 3 x 2 = 6 (6 - 2 = 4, 2 x 4 = 8, 6 + 8 = 14, then off). The correct value is 20.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-15'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-16', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 4, 'Evaluate: (10 - 4)^2 / [2 x (1 + 2)]', '["6","3","18","12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Numerator group: 10 - 4 = 6, then 6^2 = 36. Denominator group inside out: 1 + 2 = 3, then 2 x 3 = 6. Then divide: 36 / 6 = 6. The choice 3 comes from squaring after dividing or dividing by only the 2 then mishandling. The choice 18 divides 36 by 2 first, ignoring that the full bracket is the divisor. The correct value is 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-16'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-17', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 4, 'Evaluate: 50 - 3[2 + (4^2 - 10)]', '["26","24","44","8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Innermost: 4^2 = 16, then 16 - 10 = 6. Brackets: 2 + 6 = 8. Multiply: 3 x 8 = 24. Subtract: 50 - 24 = 26. The choice 24 stops at the product and forgets to subtract from 50. The choice 44 comes from squaring as 4 x 2 = 8 inside (8 - 10 = -2, 2 + (-2) = 0, ... ) mishandling the exponent. The correct value is 26.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-17'),
  ('MK-B23-OOP-18', 'MK', 'mk.order-of-operations', 4, 'Evaluate: 2^3 + 4 x [15 / (1 + 4)] - 6', '["14","20","10","26"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Exponent: 2^3 = 8. Inner parentheses: 1 + 4 = 5, then 15 / 5 = 3, then 4 x 3 = 12. Now combine left to right: 8 + 12 - 6 = 14. The choice 20 forgets to subtract the 6. The choice 10 mishandles the exponent as 2 x 3 = 6 (6 + 12 - 6 = 12, then off) or subtracts before multiplying. The correct value is 14.', true, 'verified', 'mk.order-of-operations::MK-B23-OOP-18'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-1', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: x + 8 > 11', '["x > 3","x < 3","x > 19","x > 8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 8 from both sides: x > 3. Subtraction never flips an inequality. The choice x < 3 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x > 19 adds 8 instead of subtracting. The correct answer is x > 3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-1'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-2', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: 4x <= 20', '["x <= 5","x >= 5","x <= 80","x <= 16"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide both sides by 4, a positive number, so the symbol stays: x <= 5. The choice x >= 5 wrongly flips the symbol even though 4 is positive. The choice x <= 80 multiplies by 4 instead of dividing. The correct answer is x <= 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-2'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-3', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Solve for x: x - 6 < 2', '["x < 8","x > 8","x < -4","x < 12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Add 6 to both sides: x < 8. Adding never flips the symbol. The choice x > 8 wrongly flips it. The choice x < -4 subtracts 6 instead of adding. The correct answer is x < 8.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-3'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-4', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 1, 'Which inequality means ''x is at least 9''?', '["x >= 9","x > 9","x <= 9","x < 9"]'::jsonb, 0, '''At least 9'' means 9 is allowed and anything bigger, so x >= 9. The choice x > 9 excludes 9, which ''more than'' would mean, not ''at least''. The choice x <= 9 reverses the direction. The correct answer is x >= 9.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-4'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-5', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: -5x < 15', '["x > -3","x < -3","x < 3","x > 3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Divide both sides by -5 and flip the symbol because the divisor is negative: x > -3. The choice x < -3 forgets to flip. The choice x < 3 drops the negative sign on the result as well. The correct answer is x > -3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-5'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-6', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: 2x - 7 >= 3', '["x >= 5","x <= 5","x >= -2","x >= 10"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Add 7: 2x >= 10. Divide by 2, a positive number, so no flip: x >= 5. The choice x <= 5 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x >= -2 subtracts 7 instead of adding it. The correct answer is x >= 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-6'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-7', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: 8 - x > 1', '["x < 7","x > 7","x < 9","x > -7"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 8: -x > -7. Divide by -1 and flip the symbol: x < 7. The choice x > 7 forgets to flip when dividing by the negative. The choice x < 9 adds 8 instead of subtracting. The correct answer is x < 7.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-7'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-8', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'A student needs at least 360 points across 4 equally weighted tests to pass. She has 255 points after 3 tests. What score s on the last test passes?', '["s >= 105","s <= 105","s >= 615","s > 105"]'::jsonb, 0, '''At least 360'' means the total must be >= 360, so 255 + s >= 360. Subtract 255: s >= 105. The choice s <= 105 reverses the constraint. The choice s >= 615 adds 255 instead of subtracting. ''At least'' includes the endpoint, so s > 105 is wrong. The correct answer is s >= 105.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-8'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-9', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'The number line shows a closed dot at 4 with shading to the left. Which inequality matches?', '["x <= 4","x < 4","x >= 4","x > 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Shading to the left means values less than 4, and a closed dot means 4 is included, so x <= 4. The choice x < 4 uses an open dot and excludes 4, which contradicts the closed dot. The choice x >= 4 shades the wrong direction. The correct answer is x <= 4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-9'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-10', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve for x: -4x + 6 < 18', '["x > -3","x < -3","x > 3","x < 3"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 6: -4x < 12. Divide by -4 and flip the symbol: x > -3. The choice x < -3 forgets to flip after dividing by the negative. The choice x > 3 drops the negative sign on the result. The correct answer is x > -3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-10'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-11', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve the compound inequality: 1 <= 3x + 4 < 16', '["-1 <= x < 4","-1 < x <= 4","1 <= x < 4","-3 <= x < 12"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 4 from all three parts: -3 <= 3x < 12. Divide all parts by 3: -1 <= x < 4. The choice -3 <= x < 12 forgets to divide by 3. The choice -1 < x <= 4 swaps which endpoints are included. The correct answer is -1 <= x < 4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-11'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-12', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve for x: 5x + 2 < 3x - 6', '["x < -4","x > -4","x < -2","x < 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 3x from both sides: 2x + 2 < -6. Subtract 2: 2x < -8. Divide by 2, a positive number, so no flip: x < -4. The choice x > -4 wrongly flips the symbol. The choice x < -2 forgets to divide by 2 after reaching 2x < -8 (or stops early). The correct answer is x < -4.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-12'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-13', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'Solve for x: 7 - 2x <= 13', '["x >= -3","x <= -3","x >= 3","x <= 10"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 7: -2x <= 6. Divide by -2 and flip the symbol: x >= -3. The choice x <= -3 forgets to flip when dividing by the negative. The choice x >= 3 drops the negative on the result. The correct answer is x >= -3.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-13'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-14', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 3, 'A parking garage charges a $3 entry fee plus $2 per hour. With $15, how many whole hours h can a driver park?', '["h <= 6","h >= 6","h <= 9","h <= 7.5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Total cost must be no more than 15: 3 + 2h <= 15. Subtract 3: 2h <= 12. Divide by 2: h <= 6. The choice h <= 9 forgets the per-hour rate and just does 15 - 3 - 3. The choice h <= 7.5 ignores the entry fee (15 / 2) and also is not a whole hour. The correct answer is h <= 6.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-14'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-15', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 4, 'Solve for x: 3(x - 2) > 5x + 4', '["x < -5","x > -5","x < 5","x > 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Distribute: 3x - 6 > 5x + 4. Subtract 5x: -2x - 6 > 4. Add 6: -2x > 10. Divide by -2 and flip the symbol: x < -5. The choice x > -5 forgets to flip after dividing by the negative. The choice x < 5 drops the negative sign. The correct answer is x < -5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-15'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-16', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 2, 'Solve for x: (2x + 1) / -3 >= 3', '["x <= -5","x >= -5","x <= 4","x >= 5"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Multiply both sides by -3 and flip the symbol: 2x + 1 <= -9. Subtract 1: 2x <= -10. Divide by 2 (positive, no flip): x <= -5. The choice x >= -5 forgets to flip when multiplying by the negative. The choice x <= 4 mishandles the sign and arithmetic. The correct answer is x <= -5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-16'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-17', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 4, 'Solve the compound inequality: -8 <= 2 - 2x < 6', '["-2 < x <= 5","-2 <= x < 5","5 < x <= -2","-5 < x <= 2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Subtract 2 from all parts: -10 <= -2x < 4. Divide all parts by -2 and flip BOTH symbols, which also swaps the order: 5 >= x > -2, written as -2 < x <= 5. The choice -2 <= x < 5 forgets to flip the symbols when dividing by the negative. The choice -5 < x <= 2 divides only the wrong numbers. The correct answer is -2 < x <= 5.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-17'),
  ('MK-B23-INEQ-18', 'MK', 'mk.inequalities', 4, 'A crate weighs 12 pounds empty. Books weigh 3 pounds each. To keep the loaded crate under 50 pounds, how many books b can it hold?', '["b < 12.67, so at most 12 books","b <= 12","b < 16.67, so at most 16 books","b > 12.67"]'::jsonb, 0, '''Under 50'' means strictly less than: 12 + 3b < 50. Subtract 12: 3b < 38. Divide by 3: b < 12.67, so the most whole books is 12. The choice b <= 12 wrongly uses <= when ''under'' excludes the endpoint; here 12 books gives 48 pounds which is fine, but the inequality itself should be strict. The choice b < 16.67 forgets the empty crate weight (50 / 3). The choice b > 12.67 reverses the direction. The correct answer is b < 12.67, so at most 12 books.', true, 'verified', 'mk.inequalities::MK-B23-INEQ-18'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-1', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'RAPID is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["slow","quick","loud","narrow"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Rapid means moving or happening fast. Its opposite is slow, moving at low speed. ''Quick'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for rapid. Loud describes sound and narrow describes width, neither related to speed.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::rapid'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-2', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'ARRIVE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["depart","reach","build","answer"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Arrive is a verb meaning to reach a place. Its opposite is depart, to leave a place. ''Reach'' is the synonym trap, since reaching a destination is the same as arriving. Build and answer are unrelated actions.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::arrive'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-3', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'PERMANENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["temporary","lasting","heavy","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Permanent means lasting without end. Its opposite is temporary, lasting only a short time. ''Lasting'' is the synonym trap, a close match for permanent. Heavy describes weight and distant describes space, neither related to duration.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::permanent'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-4', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 1, 'ACCEPT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["reject","receive","repair","follow"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Accept is a verb meaning to take or agree to something offered. Its opposite is reject, to refuse it. ''Receive'' is the synonym trap, since receiving is close to accepting. Repair and follow are unrelated actions.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::accept'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-5', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'HUMBLE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["arrogant","modest","wealthy","quiet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Humble means modest and not proud. Its opposite is arrogant, full of self-importance. ''Modest'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for humble. Wealthy and quiet describe money and sound, neither related to pride.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::humble'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-6', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'RIGID is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["flexible","stiff","bright","honest"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Rigid means stiff and not able to bend. Its opposite is flexible, able to bend easily. ''Stiff'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for rigid. Bright describes light and honest describes truthfulness, neither related to stiffness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::rigid'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-7', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'VACANT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["occupied","empty","fragile","rapid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Vacant means empty or not in use. Its opposite is occupied, filled or in use. ''Empty'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for vacant. Fragile describes breakability and rapid describes speed, neither related to whether a space is filled.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::vacant'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-8', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'DEFEND is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["attack","protect","measure","gather"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Defend is a verb meaning to protect from harm. Its opposite is attack, to act against with force. ''Protect'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for defend. Measure and gather are unrelated actions.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::defend'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-9', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'FERTILE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["barren","productive","distant","noisy"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Fertile means able to produce abundantly, as rich soil does. Its opposite is barren, unable to produce. ''Productive'' is the synonym trap, a close match for fertile. Distant describes space and noisy describes sound, neither related to productivity.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::fertile'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-10', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'DILIGENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["lazy","hardworking","wealthy","cheerful"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Diligent means careful and hardworking. Its opposite is lazy, unwilling to work or make effort. ''Hardworking'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for diligent. Wealthy and cheerful describe money and mood, neither related to effort.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::diligent'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-11', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'OBSCURE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["clear","unclear","heavy","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Obscure means not clearly understood or hard to see. Its opposite is clear, easily seen or understood. ''Unclear'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for obscure. Heavy describes weight and distant describes space, neither related to clarity.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::obscure'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-12', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'HOSTILE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["friendly","unfriendly","expensive","rapid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Hostile means unfriendly and ready to oppose. Its opposite is friendly, warm and welcoming. ''Unfriendly'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for hostile. Expensive describes cost and rapid describes speed, neither related to attitude.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::hostile'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-13', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'FEEBLE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["strong","weak","bright","honest"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Feeble means lacking strength, weak. Its opposite is strong, having great power or force. ''Weak'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for feeble. Bright describes light and honest describes truthfulness, neither related to strength.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::feeble'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-14', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 3, 'LENIENT is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["strict","merciful","wealthy","quiet"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Lenient means not harsh, willing to forgive or go easy. Its opposite is strict, demanding and firm in rules. ''Merciful'' is the synonym trap, a close match for lenient. Wealthy and quiet describe money and sound, neither related to how firmly rules are enforced.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::lenient'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-15', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 2, 'FRUGAL is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["wasteful","thrifty","cheerful","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Frugal means careful with money, thrifty. Its opposite is wasteful, spending or using carelessly. ''Thrifty'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for frugal. Cheerful describes mood and distant describes space, neither related to spending habits.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::frugal'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-16', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 4, 'VERBOSE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["concise","wordy","honest","rapid"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Verbose means using too many words, wordy. Its opposite is concise, expressing much in few words. ''Wordy'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for verbose. Honest describes truthfulness and rapid describes speed, neither related to length of speech.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::verbose'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-17', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 4, 'AMIABLE is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["disagreeable","friendly","wealthy","talkative"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Amiable means good-natured and pleasant, easy to like. Its opposite is disagreeable, unpleasant and hard to get along with. ''Friendly'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for amiable. Wealthy and talkative describe money and speech, neither related to pleasantness.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::amiable'),
  ('WK-B24-ANT-18', 'WK', 'wk.antonyms', 4, 'ARDUOUS is most nearly OPPOSITE in meaning to:', '["effortless","difficult","honest","distant"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Arduous means hard to do, requiring great effort. Its opposite is effortless, requiring little or no effort. ''Difficult'' is the synonym trap, a direct match for arduous. Honest describes truthfulness and distant describes space, neither related to how hard a task is.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::arduous'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-1', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''She put a stamp on the LETTER before mailing it,'' the word LETTER most nearly means:', '["a written message sent by mail","a symbol of the alphabet","a person who lets property","an award worn on a jacket"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Letter can mean a piece of mail, a character of the alphabet, an athletic award, or one who lets out property. ''Put a stamp on it before mailing'' points to a written message sent by mail. A symbol of the alphabet and the other senses do not fit something you stamp and mail.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::letter'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-2', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''He used a sharp knife to PARE the apple,'' the word PARE most nearly means:', '["to trim off the outer layer","two of a kind","a sweet fruit","to join together"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Pare is a verb meaning to cut away an outer layer or peel. With ''a sharp knife'' and ''the apple,'' it means to trim off the skin. ''Two of a kind'' (pair) and ''a sweet fruit'' (pear) are different words that only sound the same. To join together is not a meaning of pare.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::pare'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-3', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''The lamp gave off a soft LIGHT,'' the word LIGHT most nearly means:', '["brightness that lets us see","not heavy","to set on fire","pale in color"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Light can mean brightness, not heavy, to ignite, or pale in color. A lamp that ''gave off a soft light'' uses the brightness meaning. Not heavy and pale in color are adjective senses that do not fit something a lamp gives off, and to set on fire is a verb that does not match.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::light'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-4', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 1, 'In the sentence ''The runner came in LAST in the race,'' the word LAST most nearly means:', '["final, after all others","to continue over time","a mold for shaping a shoe","most recent"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Last can mean final in order, to endure, a shoemaker''s mold, or most recent. ''Came in last in the race'' means final, after all others. To continue over time is a verb meaning, a shoe mold is a separate noun, and most recent (as in ''last week'') does not fit a finishing position.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::last'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-5', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The hikers reached the highest POINT on the trail,'' the word POINT most nearly means:', '["a specific place or spot","the sharp end of an object","a unit of score","the main idea"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Point can mean a place or spot, a sharp tip, a unit of score, or the main idea. ''The highest point on the trail'' means a specific place or spot. The sharp end of an object, a unit of score, and the main idea are real senses of point but do not fit a location on a trail.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::point'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-6', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The factory will SHIP the order on Friday,'' the word SHIP most nearly means:', '["to send goods to a destination","a large boat","a crew of sailors","to take on water"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Ship can be a noun meaning a large boat or, as a verb, to send goods. ''Will ship the order on Friday'' uses the verb meaning, to send goods to a destination. A large boat and a crew of sailors are noun meanings that do not fit sending an order. To take on water is a separate nautical sense that does not match.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::ship'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-7', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''A heavy SPRING holds the door shut,'' the word SPRING most nearly means:', '["a coiled piece of metal","the season after winter","a source of water","to leap suddenly"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Spring can mean a coil, a season, a water source, or to leap. A ''heavy spring'' that ''holds the door shut'' is a coiled piece of metal. The season after winter, a source of water, and to leap suddenly are real meanings of spring but do not fit a part that holds a door closed.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::spring'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-8', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The hostess showed us to our SEAT,'' the word SEAT most nearly means:', '["a place to sit","to install a part firmly","the center of authority","a share in an organization"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Seat can mean a place to sit, to set firmly in place, a center of power, or membership in a body. ''Showed us to our seat'' means a place to sit. To install a part firmly is a verb meaning, while the center of authority and a share in an organization are figurative senses that do not fit being shown where to sit.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::seat'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-9', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'In the sentence ''The team will DRILL the new play until they master it,'' the word DRILL most nearly means:', '["to practice by repetition","a tool that bores holes","to make a hole","a coarse cotton fabric"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Drill can mean a boring tool, to bore a hole, to train by repetition, or a heavy fabric. ''Will drill the new play until they master it'' means to practice by repetition. A tool that bores holes and a coarse cotton fabric are noun meanings, and to make a hole does not fit practicing a play.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::drill'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-10', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''The two nations agreed to forge a lasting BOND,'' the word BOND most nearly means:', '["a connection between people or groups","money paid to release a prisoner","a certificate of debt","a glue that holds things together"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Bond can mean a tie between people, bail money, a financial certificate, or an adhesive. ''A lasting bond'' between two nations means a connection between people or groups. Money paid to release a prisoner, a certificate of debt, and a glue are real meanings of bond but do not fit a relationship between nations.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::bond'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-11', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''Cooks STRAIN the broth to remove the bones,'' the word STRAIN most nearly means:', '["to pass through a filter","to injure by overuse","great pressure or stress","a particular variety of plant or germ"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Strain can mean to filter, to injure by overuse, stress or pressure, or a variety of organism. ''Strain the broth to remove the bones'' means to pass through a filter. To injure by overuse and great pressure are real senses of strain, and a particular variety of plant or germ does not fit filtering broth.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::strain'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-12', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''The general decided to MOUNT a surprise attack at dawn,'' the word MOUNT most nearly means:', '["to organize and launch","to climb up onto","a tall hill or peak","a support that holds something in place"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Mount can mean to climb onto, to organize and carry out, a peak, or a support for an object. ''Mount a surprise attack'' means to organize and launch. To climb up onto is a different verb sense, while a tall hill and a support are noun meanings that do not fit launching an attack.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::mount'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-13', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''The witness gave a clear ACCOUNT of what happened,'' the word ACCOUNT most nearly means:', '["a description of events","a record of money at a bank","to consider or regard","a reason or explanation"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Account can mean a description, a bank record, to consider, or a reason. A witness who ''gave a clear account of what happened'' means a description of events. A record of money is a noun meaning that does not fit, to consider is a verb sense, and a reason or explanation does not match telling what happened.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::account'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-14', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 3, 'In the sentence ''The senator holds a great deal of WEIGHT in the committee,'' the word WEIGHT most nearly means:', '["influence or importance","how heavy something is","a heavy object used for lifting","a burden of worry"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Weight can mean heaviness, a lifting object, a worry, or influence. ''Holds a great deal of weight in the committee'' means influence or importance. How heavy something is and a heavy object are literal senses that do not fit, and a burden of worry does not match having power in a committee.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::weight'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-15', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 4, 'The word SOUND is used the same way in ''The bridge was still SOUND after the storm'' as it is in:', '["After the repairs, the engine was sound again.","The sound of the bell carried across the valley.","We could sound the depth of the lake with a rope.","She gave him sound advice about the job."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Sound can be a noun (a noise), a verb (to measure depth), or an adjective meaning either in good condition or sensible. In the prompt, a bridge ''still sound after the storm'' means in good condition. Choice A, an engine ''sound again'' after repairs, uses that same meaning. Choice B is the noun, choice C is the verb, and choice D means sensible, a different adjective sense.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::sound'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-16', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 2, 'The word KEEN is used the same way in ''The hawk has KEEN eyesight'' as it is in:', '["The dog has a keen sense of smell.","She was keen to start the new project.","The mourners began to keen at the grave.","He felt a keen disappointment at the news."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Keen can mean sharp or acute (of senses), eager, intense (of feeling), or, as a verb, to wail in grief. In the prompt, ''keen eyesight'' means sharp or acute. Choice A, a ''keen sense of smell,'' uses that same meaning. Choice B means eager, choice C is the verb to wail, and choice D means intense in feeling, which are different senses.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::keen'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-17', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 4, 'The word RELIEVE is used the same way in ''These pills RELIEVE the pain quickly'' as it is in:', '["A warm bath will relieve sore muscles.","The next shift came to relieve the guards.","Tall hedges relieve the plain brick wall.","The general was relieved of his command."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Relieve can mean to ease pain or distress, to take over a duty from someone, to break up monotony, or to remove from a position. In the prompt, pills that ''relieve the pain'' means to ease distress. Choice A, a bath that will ''relieve sore muscles,'' uses that same meaning. Choice B means to take over a duty, choice C means to break up monotony, and choice D means to remove from a position.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::relieve'),
  ('WK-B24-MM-18', 'WK', 'wk.multiple-meaning-words', 4, 'The word EXECUTE is used the same way in ''The pilot will EXECUTE the landing carefully'' as it is in:', '["The dancer can execute the difficult turn flawlessly.","The state did not execute the prisoner.","Both parties must execute the contract today.","The program failed to execute on the old computer."]'::jsonb, 0, 'Execute can mean to carry out an action, to put to death, to sign a legal document, or, of software, to run. In the prompt, a pilot who will ''execute the landing'' means to carry out an action. Choice A, a dancer who can ''execute the difficult turn,'' uses that same meaning. Choice B means to put to death, choice C means to sign a contract, and choice D means to run a program.', true, 'verified', 'wk.headword::execute'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-1', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The mechanic told us to mind the wet floor near the entrance. He had just mopped it and did not want anyone to slip."

In this passage, the word "mind" most nearly means:', '["the part of you that thinks","watch out for","obey an order","object to something"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The mechanic warns about a slippery floor so no one will slip, so ''mind'' means watch out for. ''The part of you that thinks'' is the most common meaning of mind as a noun but does not fit a warning about a floor. ''Obey an order'' and ''object to something'' are other senses of mind that the passage does not support.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-1'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-2', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"After the storm, the river began to rise. By nightfall the water had climbed over the lowest bank."

As used in the passage, the word "rise" most nearly means:', '["get out of bed","a small hill","go up in level","a pay raise"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The next sentence says the water ''had climbed over the lowest bank,'' so ''rise'' means to go up in level. ''Get out of bed'' is a common meaning of rise but a river does not get out of bed. ''A small hill'' and ''a pay raise'' are noun meanings that do not fit a river after a storm.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-2'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-3', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The nurse asked the patient to be still while she listened to his heart. Any movement would make it harder to hear."

In this passage, the word "still" most nearly means:', '["even now","not moving","a device for making liquor","even more"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The nurse warns that ''any movement'' would make listening harder, so ''still'' means not moving. ''Even now'' and ''even more'' are adverb meanings of still that do not fit the request to hold a position. ''A device for making liquor'' is a noun meaning the passage gives no support for.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-3'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-4', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The sergeant told the squad to fall in before the inspection. Within seconds the recruits formed a neat line."

As used in the passage, the phrase "fall in" most nearly means:', '["drop into a hole","get into formation","begin to like someone","collapse from exhaustion"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The next sentence says the recruits ''formed a neat line,'' so ''fall in'' means to get into formation. ''Drop into a hole'' and ''collapse from exhaustion'' take the word ''fall'' too literally. ''Begin to like someone'' (fall for) is unrelated to lining up for inspection.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-4'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-5', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The witness gave a sound account of the accident. The judge noted that every detail held up under questioning."

In this passage, the word "sound" most nearly means:', '["a noise you hear","reliable and solid","a narrow body of water","to measure depth"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The judge notes that every detail ''held up under questioning,'' so a ''sound account'' is one that is reliable and solid. ''A noise you hear'' is the most common meaning of sound but a noise cannot hold up under questioning. ''A narrow body of water'' and ''to measure depth'' are other meanings of sound that do not fit a witness''s account.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-5'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-6', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The manager liked to keep her plans close, sharing them with no one until the day they were announced. Even her assistant was often surprised."

As used in the passage, the word "close" most nearly means:', '["near in distance","kept private","to shut","the end of something"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage says she shared her plans ''with no one'' and even her assistant was surprised, so to keep them ''close'' means to keep them private. ''Near in distance'' is a common meaning of close but does not fit hiding plans. ''To shut'' and ''the end of something'' are other meanings that the passage does not support.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-6'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-7', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The supply officer had to ration the water carefully once the convoy was stranded. Each soldier received only a single cup per day until rescue arrived."

In this passage, the word "ration" most nearly means:', '["a reason or logic","limit to a fixed amount","a daily food packet","to give freely"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The passage says each soldier got ''only a single cup per day,'' so to ''ration'' the water is to limit it to a fixed amount. ''A daily food packet'' is the noun sense of ration but here the word is a verb describing the act of limiting. ''A reason or logic'' confuses ration with ''rationale,'' and ''to give freely'' is the opposite of what the officer did.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-7'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-8', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The coach delivered a stinging critique after the loss, but he ended on a note of hope. He reminded the team that the season was far from over."

As used in the passage, the word "note" most nearly means:', '["a short written message","a musical tone","a tone or quality of feeling","paper money"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The coach ''ended on a note of hope'' and reminded the team of better days ahead, so ''note'' means a tone or quality of feeling. ''A short written message'' is the most common meaning of note but the coach is speaking, not writing. ''A musical tone'' and ''paper money'' are other meanings that do not fit a hopeful ending to a speech.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-8'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-9', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The instructor warned that the rope was frayed and might not bear the climber''s weight. He replaced it before letting anyone use it."

In this passage, the word "bear" most nearly means:', '["a large wild animal","support or hold up","to give birth","to carry away"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The worry is that the rope ''might not bear the climber''s weight,'' so ''bear'' means to support or hold up. ''A large wild animal'' is a common meaning of bear but is unrelated to a rope holding weight. ''To give birth'' and ''to carry away'' are other senses of bear that do not fit the sentence.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-9'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-10', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The captain''s orders were anything but rigid. He gave each squad leader latitude to adjust the plan as conditions on the ground changed."

As used in the passage, the word "latitude" most nearly means:', '["distance north or south of the equator","freedom to make choices","a line on a map","the width of an object"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The orders were ''anything but rigid'' and squad leaders could ''adjust the plan,'' so ''latitude'' means freedom to make choices. ''Distance north or south of the equator'' and ''a line on a map'' are the geographic meanings of latitude but neither fits orders that leaders can change. ''The width of an object'' is not a standard meaning the passage supports.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-10'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-11', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The crowd''s mood was volatile that night. One moment they cheered, and the next they were ready to riot, with no warning of which way they would turn."

In this passage, the word "volatile" most nearly means:', '["quick to evaporate","easily changing and unstable","explosive when lit","high in value"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The crowd swung from cheering to near-rioting ''with no warning,'' so ''volatile'' means easily changing and unstable. ''Quick to evaporate'' and ''explosive when lit'' are the chemical meanings of volatile that do not describe a crowd''s mood. ''High in value'' is not a meaning of volatile the passage supports.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-11'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-12', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The lecture was so dry that several students nodded off. Even the professor seemed bored by his own delivery."

As used in the passage, the word "dry" most nearly means:', '["free of moisture","dull and boring","lacking rain","served without ice"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Students ''nodded off'' and even the professor ''seemed bored,'' so a ''dry'' lecture is dull and boring. ''Free of moisture'' is the most common meaning of dry but a lecture has no moisture to lose. ''Lacking rain'' and ''served without ice'' are other senses of dry that do not fit a tedious lecture.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-12'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-13', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The new lieutenant tried to assert himself, but his weak commands only invited mutiny. The seasoned troops sensed his uncertainty at once."

In this passage, the word "invited" most nearly means:', '["asked someone to an event","made more likely to happen","welcomed warmly","requested politely"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The lieutenant''s ''weak commands'' caused the risk of mutiny, so ''invited'' means made more likely to happen. ''Asked someone to an event'' is the most common meaning of invited but no one is being asked to an event. ''Welcomed warmly'' and ''requested politely'' suggest he wanted the mutiny, which contradicts the passage.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-13'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-14', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 3, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The senator''s apology was hollow. He said the right words, but his actions the next day showed he meant none of them."

As used in the passage, the word "hollow" most nearly means:', '["empty on the inside","insincere and meaningless","a small valley","echoing in sound"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The apology used ''the right words'' but his actions ''showed he meant none of them,'' so ''hollow'' means insincere and meaningless. ''Empty on the inside'' is the most literal meaning of hollow but an apology is not a physical object. ''A small valley'' and ''echoing in sound'' are other meanings that do not fit a false apology.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-14'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-15', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The general''s reputation for caution was the very thing that lent weight to his sudden call for attack. When a careful man urges boldness, others listen."

In this passage, the word "lent" most nearly means:', '["loaned for a time","gave or added","bent slightly","the season before Easter"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The general''s reputation ''lent weight'' to his call, meaning it gave or added authority to it. ''Loaned for a time'' is the most common meaning of lent but the weight is not being borrowed and returned. ''Bent slightly'' (leant) is a sound-alike, and ''the season before Easter'' (Lent) is a homophone the passage gives no support for.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-15'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-16', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 2, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The editor pruned the manuscript without mercy, cutting whole chapters that slowed the story. What remained was lean and fast."

As used in the passage, the word "pruned" most nearly means:', '["a dried plum","trimmed away the excess","wrinkled with age","watered carefully"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The editor cut ''whole chapters'' until what remained was ''lean and fast,'' so ''pruned'' means trimmed away the excess. ''A dried plum'' is the noun prune but the passage uses the word as a verb. ''Wrinkled with age'' (pruney) and ''watered carefully'' are other associations that do not fit the act of cutting a manuscript.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-16'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-17', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"For all his bluster, the colonel had a temperate streak. He rarely drank, kept regular hours, and avoided every excess his rank allowed him."

In this passage, the word "temperate" most nearly means:', '["having mild weather","self-restrained and moderate","quick to lose one''s temper","warm and friendly"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The colonel ''rarely drank,'' ''kept regular hours,'' and ''avoided every excess,'' so ''temperate'' means self-restrained and moderate. ''Having mild weather'' is a common meaning of temperate (as in a climate) but a person is not a climate. ''Quick to lose one''s temper'' confuses temperate with ''temper,'' and the passage describes the opposite. ''Warm and friendly'' is not supported by the description of restraint.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-17'),
  ('PC-B25-VIC-18', 'PC', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context', 4, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"The committee''s praise was qualified at best. They admired the design, yet noted that it would fail the moment the budget tightened."

As used in the passage, the word "qualified" most nearly means:', '["having the right skills","limited by conditions","having earned a degree","entered into a contest"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The praise came with a ''yet'' that warned the design would fail under a tight budget, so ''qualified'' means limited by conditions. ''Having the right skills'' is the most common meaning of qualified but it describes a person, not praise. ''Having earned a degree'' and ''entered into a contest'' are other meanings that do not fit praise hedged by a warning.', true, 'verified', 'pc.vocabulary-in-context::PC-B25-VIC-18'),
  ('PC-B25-TS-1', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

"To send a letter, first write the address on the envelope. Next, place a stamp in the top right corner. Then drop the envelope in the mailbox."

According to the passage, what is the second step in sending a letter?', '["Write the address on the envelope","Place a stamp in the corner","Drop the envelope in the mailbox","Open the mailbox door"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The transition words map the order: ''first'' write the address, ''next'' place a stamp. So the second step is placing the stamp. Writing the address is ''first,'' dropping it in the mailbox is signaled by ''then,'' and opening the door is never mentioned.', true, 'verified', 'pc.text-structure::PC-B25-TS-1'),
  ('PC-B25-TS-2', 'PC', 'pc.text-structure', 1, 'Read the passage below and answer the question.

